<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-22 00:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5515 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s BC-SPT-ATHLETES-IMMORTAL     08-22 1613
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPT-ATHLETES-IMMORTAL-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE RULES DON'T APPLY TO US'  
 INVINCIBLE MIND-SET CAN LEAD ATHLETES INTO TROUBLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By LES POLK  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - You're younger, stronger and tougher than the average
person.
</P>
<P>
   You're a star athlete and you're allowed to cut corners.
Parents, coaches and counselors bend the rules for you.
</P>
<P>
   It's easy to think the rules don't apply to you. After all,
you're invincible.
</P>
<P>
   Then you break an ankle or tear a ligament and don't
rehabilitate properly, leading to further damage. You get caught
with drugs or drinking and driving. You don't wear a seat belt and
are injured in a crash. You're suspended from the team for academic
problems.
</P>
<P>
   It happens often, and it may never change as long as young
athletes continue to grow up in that cocoon of security that can
lead to recklessness and danger.
</P>
<P>
   But is that the whole story? Or are young athletes no different
from typical teenagers who can't fathom that their world could come
crashing down in an instant of bad judgment?
</P>
<P>
   Cardinals starting strong safety Tommy Bennett, 26, who made the
team as an undrafted rookie three seasons ago out of UCLA, has seen
it all.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see that in society in general, just young people in general
thinking they're invincible. From junior high to high school to
college, and even in my professional career, I've seen many, many
young people just live their lives kind of recklessly,'' said
Bennett, who had three teammates, including two who weren't wearing
seat belts, injured last week in a nasty car crash.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not saying the guys in question that were in the accident
Monday necessarily had that attitude, but I've seen it a lot (in
society) _ driving without seat belts, maybe speeding when they
don't have to, just doing really, really silly things when they
don't have to, and it's just because they think they're
invincible.''
</P>
<P>
   Ernest Dye, Lester Holmes and Carl Simpson were hurt in the
crash south of Flagstaff. Dye and Simpson weren't wearing seat
belts, and the Department of Public Safety said Holmes would be
ticketed for driving at a speed not reasonable and prudent in the
rainstorm, although he was not above the 75 mph speed limit.
</P>
<P>
   At the high school level, coaches and kids see the invincibility
factor as more of a teenage thing than anything else.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been through it with my own kids,'' said Washington High
football Coach Steve Chisman. ``One of my big concerns is the
lunchtime situation (when open-campus policies allow students to
leave during lunch, often leading to car accidents).
</P>
<P>
   ``My teenage daughter makes the same comment, `That's somebody
else.' She's an athlete, but everybody thinks they are
invincible.''
</P>
<P>
   Bennett says high-level athletes may be more prone to
recklessness because they've come to believe they're immune.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously professional athletes are some of the most
conditioned people on the planet. They think they're never going to
get hurt,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ASU cornerback Courtney Jackson says athletes have to make a
distinction between invincibility on the field and in their
personal life.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's an invincibility that most athletes have _ and need _
on the football field,'' he said. ``But what they have to
understand is what happens between these lines isn't necessarily
how things are in the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``A bullet ``can'' hurt you _ I don't care how good a football
player you are.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Gary Beale, a sports psychology consultant at the Sierra
Center for Peak Performance in Reno, Nev., says elite athletes can
be prone to getting in trouble because of their background.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have in general not been people who have had to live by
the rules while growing up,'' he said. ``They're treated with
favoritism, and nothing is their fault. If you grow up not being
required to live by the rules . . . it can lead to a general
subculture that `the rules don't apply to us.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Bennett says experience is the best teacher, and he's outgrown
whatever streak of recklessness he may have had.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wear my seat belt. I put on my helmet even when I ride my
bike. I tie my shoes. I've experienced that, honestly, in high
school and college. I got a few speeding tickets, things of that
nature, because I didn't think I was going to get caught,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's just from having that young mental attitude. A lot of
young people, we see it every year, somebody gets in trouble for
speeding, maybe DUI, something like that. They all do it because
they think they're not going to get caught.''
</P>
<P>
   The bad decisions often get more attention than the good, said
Joe Corte, Scottsdale Coronado athletic director and football
coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this age, athletes and non-athletes are liable to make some
poor judgments. It's just 17-year-olds making 50 good decisions and
one bad decision,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Mesa Westwood senior volleyball player Brittney Bingham knows
well the impact one bad decision can make, in her case not wearing
a seat belt.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago she was in an accident near Winslow, thrown
through the window of a car and pinned under the wheels for an hour
while waiting for help.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until you experience something, you never think it's going to
happen to you,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Bingham sat out a whole season and isn't yet fully recovered
from leg injuries.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember thinking `Is this really happening?' '' she said.
``You never actually think anything like that is going to happen to
you until it does. Now I wear my seat belt. It was a horrible
experience, and I never want to go through that again. Kids don't
think about what might happen afterward.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike Baston, directory of physical therapy at St. Joseph's
Hospital Center for Sports Medicine, says he deals regularly with
the ``invincibility factor.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You find them maybe taking for granted their injury, thinking
it's not serious,'' he said of some athletes. ``Many think it's not
that important to follow their rehabilitation. It's part of the
immaturity level, thinking `It's not going to happen to me.' ''
</P>
<P>
   And when it happens, it can be difficult to deal with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``High-profile athletes have a hard time with these injuries,''
Baston said. ``The guys that know what to expect are more mature
about it, but for the first-timer it can be very difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   Baston has clients as young as 8 years old.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's amazing what parents are doing to their kids,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And what kids do to themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see a lot of people doing dangerous stuff, stupid stuff just
to say I'm cool or I'm tough or whatever,'' said Westwood
volleyball player Wa'Nami Allen, a junior.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're jumping off cliffs, drinking while they're driving,
stupid stuff just for the thrill so they can say, `Look what we did
this weekend.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Mike Devlin, veteran backup center on the Cardinals, says age
plays a bigger role than invincibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you go through college without an injury, maybe that's the
attitude, but how many guys can say that? If the injury occurs,
it's kind of a humbling thing. Then you know that you're not
invincible,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's just what I think. I think it has more to do with being
young than being an athlete. When you're young, you can go all
day.''
</P>
<P>
   Devlin, in his seventh training camp, said rookie Yusuf Scott, a
University of Arizona product, had asked him about the age issue
the other day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `Well, you know, I used to feel like I could go 50
years. Then as you get a little bit older, you find it takes longer
to recuperate. Wear and tear.' He was saying, `Well, I feel pretty
good,' and I said, `Well, so did I back then.' All young men think
they're something, I guess,'' Devlin said.
</P>
<P>
   Anthony Clement of the Cardinals knows what it's like to see
your invincibility come to an end.
</P>
<P>
   After starting 33 games in college and never being hurt, he
suffered a season-ending injury his first month in Cardinals camp
last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the worst thing you can imagine,'' he said. ``I'd never
experienced it before. I didn't know how to deal with it. I never
spent any time in the training room in college. Never missed a
play. You start to think it can never happen to you, and then it
did.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was something I never thought about and something, really,
that I wasn't prepared to deal with.''
</P>
<P>
   Sergio Rodriguez, a senior starting right tackle at Tempe Marcos
de Niza high school, has faced the same struggle, though not as
severe.
</P>
<P>
   He was injured three weeks ago in a chain-reaction accident and
is undergoing back therapy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I definitely don't consider myself invincible,'' he said.
``When you hear that (Dye) almost lost his arm, that's pretty
severe. My accident could've been worse.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was hard to go through, right before my senior year that
I'm supposed to start. It can happen to anybody, not just the
average person.''
</P>
<P>
   Beale, the sports psychology consultant, says coaches at all
levels have to pay more attention to the psychological and
sociological welfare of athletes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coaches really control that,'' he said. ``They can either be
advocates for or barriers to involvement in psychology. It's an ego
thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson, the ASU cornerback, perhaps best summed up the impact
of the Cardinals players' crash.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bad thing about what happened to those players is that
people got hurt,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The good thing is that you're going to see a lot more people
put their seat belts on because of that. It's sad how things
work.'' &QL; 
Republic writers Paola Boivin, Paul Coro, Craig Morgan and Lee
Shappell contributed to this article. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
