A5516 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-MONTINICOL-AZR &LR;      08-22 0681
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONTINI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A NOT-SO COLORFUL RAPE
 HOAX 
</HEADLINE>
 COL-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service
 clients)  
 By E.J. MONTINI  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
Sometime after she'd bashed herself on the head, dug ugly scratches
into her neck and upper thighs, and used a pair of scissors to
slice apart her shirt and bra, Kari Rae Bodenski had to invent a
rapist.
<TEXT>
<P>
   She has a storyteller's gift, it turns out, and made her
attacker believ able, frightful and, in ways she hadn't planned,
useful.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of condemning the poor woman, we should praise her
creativ ity and her insight.
</P>
<P>
   Sprawled on the floor of the girls restroom at Mendoza Middle
School in Mesa, waiting to be discovered by one of the 500 or so
people on the grounds for ``Meet Your Teacher'' day, the troubled
Bodenski pictured a man with dirty fingernails who smelled of
cigarettes.
</P>
<P>
   He would have carried something sharp and held it to her neck,
she decided. She visualized herself fight ing back, but of course
he was too strong. He'd knock her unconscious, take advantage of
her and leave her there, bruised, scratched, dishevelled.
</P>
<P>
   That was the rough sketch, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   She had time to fine-tune the look of her make-believe felon
after the paramedics lifted her onto a stretcher and wheeled her to
an ambulance. The description she later gave the police appeared in
all the local papers and on TV. &QL; 
`TAKING NO CHANCES'
</P>
<P>
   The rapist was said to be about 6 feet tall and 160 pounds. He
had messy brown collar-length hair and was wearing blue jeans and a
black T-shirt.
</P>
<P>
   And oh, yeah, he was White.
</P>
<P>
   Police departments throughout the area were alerted. A manhunt
was launched. School districts, not only in Mesa but all over the
Valley, hurriedly re-evaluated their security measures.
</P>
<P>
   Worried parents telephoned local talk radio programs. Special
meet ings were called at schools. Anxious education officials said
things like, ``We're not taking chances anymore. The world is such
a crazy place that there doesn't seem to be any places left where
students are not in dan ger.''
</P>
<P>
   It didn't take long, however, before police detectives began
unraveling Bodenski's twisted fairy tale.
</P>
<P>
   Three days after the incident, Mesa officials called a press
conference to announce that no rape had taken place and that
Bodenski, a 31-year-old mother of two, may only have been trying to
get her husband's attention.
</P>
<P>
   Even more public meetings were called during which even more par
ents vented even more anger and frustration, all of it aimed at a
scissor-toting mom with a pitiably overactive imagination. &QL; 
UNDISTURBED GROUP
</P>
<P>
   Strangely enough, the one group who seemed completely
undisturbed by the hoax was the only group with a claim to having
been wronged _ White guys.
</P>
<P>
   Bodenski said she'd been sexually assaulted by a White man and
everyone _ the police, the public, the media _ was eager to believe
her.
</P>
<P>
   They reacted with anger and outrage, but not surprise.
</P>
<P>
   Not because we have some special prejudice against White men,
but because we hate rapists no matter what the pigmentation.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, there have been other cases of false crime
reporting in which an invented assailant was described as Black or
Hispanic or some other minority.
</P>
<P>
   Always, afterward, leaders from these communities hold press
confer ences to say the public's frantic reaction to the ruse only
proves that deep-seated prejudice still exists.
</P>
<P>
   And perhaps it does _ but not about rape.
</P>
<P>
   Kari Rae Bodenski proved it.
</P>
<P>
   When her story broke, it wasn't the image of a White man or a
Black man people saw in their heads, only an evil man.
</P>
<P>
   It caused a lot of trouble for us and will cause even more for
Bodenski and her family. But in the end, it isn't anger we should
feel toward her, only gratitude.
</P>
<P>
   Bodenski shuffled the deck of imagi nary assaulters and tossed
out the race card.
</P>
<P>
   She did us a favor. She proved that, sometimes, color really
doesn't mat ter. It's all there in black and (now) white. &QL; 
E.J. Montini can be reached at (602) 444-8978 or at
ed.montini &LR; pni.com. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
