A5517 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s BC-FBN-CARDINALS-CASSTEV     08-22 0716
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDINALS-CASSTEVENS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLUMMER'S LUCK HOLDS IN INJURY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID CASSTEVENS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. - The morning after, he placed his thumbs together.
He compared their size.
</P>
<P>
   One was swollen, stiff, sore.
</P>
<P>
   When the pain pills wore off during the night, his right thumb,
the one a Tennessee defender grabbed and yanked backward _ ``I
heard him go ``Grrrrrrrrr,'''' Jake said, sounding like a masked
wrestling villain applying a torturous hold _ stirred him from
sleep.
</P>
<P>
   In the darkness his aching thumb spoke.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jake,'' it said, telling him nothing he doesn't know, ``you're
one lucky'' ``guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Jake Plummer was born under a lucky star. He is remarkably
resilient. Although he is not sure how, he manages to sidestep the
most precarious and dangerous situations, dodging trouble, escaping
happy and unharmed. Jake Plummer is as irrepressible as Brer
Rabbit.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals $25 million quarterback can't remember sitting out
of a football game because he was hurt. Not in the briar patch of
the NFL. Not at ASU. Not in high school.
</P>
<P>
   `'I can't remember missing a ``practice,'' '' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Jake can't grip a football. His thumb is sprained. But he
flashed a smile Saturday morning on the way to the training room.
The same easy smile he gave teammates who won their first preseason
game with their quarterback on the sideline, blowing pink bubbles
with his gum.
</P>
<P>
   It was the same smile he gave Larry Wilson in the upbeat locker
room.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know about these things,'' Jake said of his bandaged hand.
It was Jake's way of acknowledging the tough-as-nails former
Cardinals defensive back who sustained and played with worse
injuries than a sprained thumb during his Hall of Fame career.
</P>
<P>
   Plummer is _ knock on wood _ the opposite of injury prone. After
games, like the seven-sack pounding he took last year in Seattle,
No. 16 peels off his jersey. Usually his elbows are scabbed, or
oozing fresh blood. Otherwise, he is fine.
</P>
<P>
   Plummer took a fierce blind-side hit in last year's opener
against Dallas. Detroit sacked him on three consecutive third-down
plays, one time after 370-pound guard Jerome Daniels stepped on his
foot. In Jake's rookie season, the Steelers sacked him 10 times. He
must have a guardian angel.
</P>
<P>
   Plummer brings to mind a sleepwalker in a cartoon, arms
outstretched as he crosses a busy intersection unscratched. Up an
elevator he goes, to the top of a construction site where he steps
sightlessly from one narrow girder to the next, oblivious to the
dizzying height and the danger.
</P>
<P>
   NFL defenders would love to break him in half. In two seasons,
they've sacked him 101 times. So far, thankfully, he has kept on
ticking, durable as a Timex.
</P>
<P>
   Plummer doesn't need to be reminded of the risks of his
occupation. At ASU he moved into the starting job after Grady
Benton was injured. A freshman, playing on a sore ankle, Plummer
threw for 253 yards in the second half against Washington State.
</P>
<P>
   As a Cardinals rookie, Jake saw Kent Graham go down under a heap
of Giants jerseys. Some fans at Sun Devil Stadium cheered Graham's
injury that day. Graham's misfortune meant that Plummer, hometown
hero, had moved up from third-team to No. 2.
</P>
<P>
   Injuries happen. The 1999 Cardinals are Exhibit A. In the first
quarter Friday night, Plummer left the field holding his thumb. He
walked toward the tunnel behind a cart carrying defensive tackle
Mike Moten, who had sprained a knee. The cart disappeared beneath a
sign that read ``Godspeed, Ernest Dye.'' Dye is scheduled to
undergo more surgery today on his right arm, which was almost
severed in a recent car accident.
</P>
<P>
   The way the Cardinals' luck is running, a sprained thumb is
almost good news.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's luck involved,'' Plummer said, referring to his
health. ``It's also a matter of playing hard, not thinking about
getting hurt. Just playing ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at me _ at my size,'' he said, inviting inspection. He
stood there, a slender frame in a T-shirt and shorts and sandals, a
cap pulled down low on his head. He held up his hand. ``I've been
lucky. All I've got is this thumb.'' &QL; 
David Casstevens can be reached at 602-444-8635 or at
david.casstevens(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
