<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-22 00:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5518 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s BC-FBN-CARDS-TILLMAN-AZR     08-22 1188
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDS-TILLMAN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHORN, BUT NOT REBORN, TILLMAN AS TOUGH AS EVER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By TIM TYERS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. - The body has been remolded from that of an
undersized collegiate linebacker turned bulked-up rookie NFL free
safety, to that of a sleeker, quicker strong safety.
</P>
<P>
   The Samsonesque hairdo that once flowed to the shoulders, making
him look like a 1960s flower child, has given way to a traditional
cut. A white-sidewalled look.
</P>
<P>
   Ask most anybody and they'll tell you it's a product of Pat
Tillman's maturation, especially as a football player.
</P>
<P>
   Just don't tell it to Pat Tillman, the Pac-10 Conference's
defensive player of the year two years ago as an Arizona State
senior, who's seeking to someday regain a starting role with the
Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm no different than I was a year ago,'' said Tillman, who
often would climb the light towers at Sun Devil Stadium to study
and meditate while at ASU. ``I`m a year older and, I guess, a year
wiser. I don't think I'm a much different person than I have been.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anything I did back then I can see myself doing today.''
</P>
<P>
   College teammate Jake Plummer, the Cardinals quarterback,
concurs.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's still Pat to me,'' he said. ``He still throws my tight
end down in practice too often. It's just tougher to identify him
nowadays.''
</P>
<P>
   Exactly. What about that new ``do?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I got sick of it, there's really no reason,'' said Tillman,
who dropped 15 pounds to 192 in the off-season, while reshaping his
frame and improving his footwork through arduous workout sessions,
including martial arts, to better suit his role as backup strong
safety to Tommy Bennett. ``It got old.''
</P>
<P>
   But Cardinals head Coach Vince Tobin, defensive coordinator Dave
McGinnis and secondary coach Larry Marmie each agree that there is
a difference between Tillman today and the rookie who won the
starting free safety job only to lose it at midseason last year to
Kwamie Lassiter. Lassiter ended the season tied for the NFL lead in
interceptions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen a lot of maturation in him,'' Tobin said. `'I still
see things you'd rather he not do, but he has matured quite a lot.
He's learning the defensive back position and he seems more
comfortable in what he's doing. He changed his body style to the
effect that he looks more like a defensive back now, rather than a
linebacker.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has done a lot of things, both mentally and physically, to
improve his game. He's going to be a big part of our defense this
year, whether he starts or not. If he continues to play like he has
been, we've got to design some things to get him into the ball game
where he can make plays. Because that's what he is. He's a play
maker.''
</P>
<P>
   The book on Tillman, who was graduated from ASU ``summa cum
laude'' (3.84 grade average) in 3{ years with a degree in
marketing, has been that of a hitter. Point him toward a brick wall
and he'll run through it and then take on the bus sitting behind
the wall.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, too often last year he exercised that trait in practice
drills conducted without pads, pleasing few but Tillman. And, least
of all, Tobin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, he's not hitting guys without pads on as much,'' Tobin
said, shaking his head. ``Once in a while you can see the wheels
turning in there that he wants to do it. But he's practicing more
within himself. He still leaves his feet a little bit more in
practice than I'd like to see, where you have a chance to leg-whip
somebody. But he's getting better at that, too.
</P>
<P>
   Don't get the idea that adding a year, losing 15 pounds and a
pound of hair has turned a gladiator into Caspar Milquetoast.
</P>
<P>
   Witness the first preseason game in Denver, when his memory was
knocked from Mile High Stadium into the upper regions of Montana
after he was blindsided covering a punt.
</P>
<P>
   ``He came to the sidelines and I asked him if he was OK,''
McGinnis said. ``He said, `My (stuff) is kinda scrambled, coach.' I
asked him if he could go back in and he said, `Don't know, my
(stuff) is kinda scrambled.' ''
</P>
<P>
   In the halftime locker room, Tillman was asked if he knew his
current location, or the game score. He failed both tests. But he
also refused to shower and walk the second half sidelines in
civvies, staying in uniform.
</P>
<P>
   Bottom line? Cardinals equipment manager Jim Shearer wisely hid
Tillman's helmet in the locker room to ensure he wouldn't sneak
back onto the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't remember any of it. I have no idea,'' Tillman said.
``If coach said it, I guess I did. I'd like to think I'd have
gotten my butt in there. I must have been scrambled.''
</P>
<P>
   After digesting the story during lunch, Tillman hunted down his
interviewer and said, ``Like I said, I don't remember it. But if I
did it, then I'm a (expletive). I don't take myself out of football
games.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He was really (upset),'' McGinnis said, laughing. ``He came to
talk to me about it, asking if it was true. Pat Tillman is a
helluva football. He's the kind of nut you want to have.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maturity really wasn't a problem with him. He was mature as a
rookie. The thing he has done is to focus in on what he's doing.
Instead of trying to do everything, he does his job full out and
then gets in the flow of what's going on. When he first came he
tried to do everything at once and couldn't do anything, and every
once in awhile would make the lucky hit.''
</P>
<P>
   Which partly explains why he's making the conversion to strong
safety and finds himself in a backup role behind Bennett, for whom
he harbors deep respect.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like strong safety a lot,'' Tillman said. `'I feel like I'm
more a part of the defense. I'm closer to the line of scrimmage and
I'm moving around a little more, as opposed to just getting back
into the deep third or something. I still have a lot of work to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm progressing as well as I can. We've got two real good
safeties right now in Tommy and Kwamie. I just have to keep working
and maybe I'll get in there to play. Maybe I won't, but I have to
keep fighting.''
</P>
<P>
   While he will see considerable playing time _ even if schemes
must be developed to get him on the field as Tobin and McGinnis
suggest _ holding an NFL starting job remains Tillman's special
goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously it's my goal,'' he said. ``It should be for anybody
who is out here. If it happens or not, who knows? I'm going to work
for it, but, like I said, Tommy has been playing very good.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's never easy when you lose your job. I knew I had things I
had to improve. I tried to come back out and tried to do the best I
could on special teams, and Kwamie played great.''
</P>
<P>
   Plummer, for one, thinks the disappointment of losing his
starting job has aided his development as a player.
</P>
<P>
   ``His starting early helped because he was thrust right into it
and had to learn quickly,'' Plummer said. ``Getting benched in
turn, he had to sit there and watch even more. Watching really
helps a rookie.
</P>
<P>
   ``He would have given anything to not watch and be out there
playing, but he looks a lot better now. He's quicker and faster and
he's reading plays better.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
