<HEADLINE>
ANDERSON SETTLING IN TO BULLPEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DON KETCHUM  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH _ Now that right-hander  &UR; Todd Stottlemyre is on his
way to re-establishing himself as a member of the starting
rotation, it's time for left-hander  &UR; Brian Anderson to settle into
his bullpen role.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson began the season in the bullpen, then rejoined the
rotation after Stottlemyre went down. Anderson has pitched in 23
games, starting 15, and has one save.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mechanically and mentally, I'm more prepared this go-round
than the first time,'' said Anderson, who was 5-1 and allowed only
seven earned runs over his past five starts with a 2.15 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was down there and didn't get in a lot of games and
there was a long period in between when I pitched, I started to
doubt myself. But I don't doubt myself now. I have confidence. I'm
ready whenever I'm needed.'' &QL; 
Rookie debut &QL; 
Rookie outfielder  &UR; Rob Ryan got a souvenir from his major league
debut on Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   It was a Pittsburgh Pirates batting helmet,supposedly sent over
to the Arizona clubhouse on Saturday and signed by Pirates catcher
 &UR; Joe Oliver, congratulating him on his first major league ``hit.''
</P>
<P>
   Ryan, pinch-hitting in the seventh inning, hit Oliver in the
head with his back swing when he fouled off the first pitch, giving
Oliver a concussion. The helmet sent to Ryan had a dent in the side
of it.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan was a bit skeptical as to its authenticity.
</P>
<P>
   ``The size of it seems awful small,'' he said. ``It was a nice
gesture, though. A nice thought.''
</P>
<P>
   After being up with the big club for about a week, Ryan was glad
to get his first at-bat (he grounded out to second base) out of the
way.
</P>
<P>
   ``''Now, hopefully I can settle in and concentrate better on
what I'm supposed to be doing.'' &QL; 
Old friend &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When the Diamondbacks move on to Florida Tuesday night to begin
their next series against the Marlins, their first pitching
opponent will be right-hander  &UR; Vladimir Nunez, who was part of the
July 9 trade with Arizona that also sent right-hander  &UR; Brad Penny
to the Marlins in exchange for right-handed closer  &UR; Matt  &UR; Mantei.
</P>
<P>
   During a recent trip by the Marlins to the West Coast, Nunez
stopped in Phoenix to tend to some personal matters, including the
sale of his house. Nunez also stopped by to visit Manager  &UR; Buck
 &UR; Showalter after Wednesday night's final game of a homestand.
</P>
<P>
   `Sac' attack &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Left-handed middle reliever  &UR; Dan Plesac had an ice pack to cut
the swelling in his right eye after receiving a shiner during
batting practice. He went to field a low line drive that bounced
off the artificial turf and off his glove and struck him above the
eye. The injury is not expected to affect his pitching status. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
