<HEADLINE>
GIANTS INSIST RACE NOT OVER IN NL WEST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PEDRO GOMEZ  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The San Francisco Giants believe they are capable of pulling off
a miracle and overtaking the Diamondbacks for the National League
West crown. Most of that belief comes from their leader, Manager
 &UR; Dusty
 &UR; Baker, the optimist's optimist.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still believe in miracles,'' Baker said. ``I still dream,
like when I was a kid. I hope I remain that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Although they have a 7{-game lead over the Giants, the
Diamondbacks remained respectful of their closest competitor in the
NL West. Manager  &UR; Buck Showalter fully believes the Giants have at
least two runs to make at his club.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants, after all, have a recent history of overcoming
nearly impossible odds. Last year, they trailed the Chicago Cubs by
five games with 10 remaining and managed to force a one-game
playoff for the wild card by winning eight of their last 10 games.
</P>
<P>
   The year before, the Giants suffered a four-game losing streak
that left them trailing Los Angeles by two games with 11 to play.
They won eight of their next 10, including a key two-game series
against the Dodgers, and wound up NL West champions.
</P>
<P>
   ``To say the Giants are out of it or soon out of it, we believe
it's unfair and unjust because this team has capabilities to do
something,'' All-Star second baseman  &UR; Jeff Kent said. ``I'm not
saying we're going to do it, but this is a team that's been there
and done it before.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a non-panic situation. Right now, our confidence is
low. We've been beaten up. We've played better games and we know we
can play better. It helps when you have experience in that regard.
You still have hope.''
</P>
<P>
   Baker added: ``The more recent the miracle is, the more you
think it could happen again.''
</P>
<P>
   The Giants still have 40 games remaining, starting with today's
game in Milwaukee, which will be followed a four-game visit to
Chicago. With six weeks of the season remaining, the Giants
collectively believe they have the club to pull out yet another
miraculous finish.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think what we need is a miracle,'' Pitcher  &UR; Russ Ortiz
said. ``What happened to us last year, maybe that was a miracle _ I
mean, in baseball terms. But we're nowhere near that point yet. We
won't need something like that. Then again, you never know. God
works in mysterious ways.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't talk for anyone else, but I think it's a real good
possibility. If we get hot and Arizona gets cold, great things can
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   A look at the NL West standings and the wild card standings
shows the Giants' best chance of reaching the postseason is by
winning the division. After all, they would only have to catch one
club, the Diamondbacks. For the wild card, San Francisco would have
to leapfrog four clubs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see how at this stage we can qualify for the
wild-card,'' said  &UR; Peter Magowan, managing general partner. ``We've
got to figure out how to beat Arizona. We play them (Sept. 24-26 at
3Com Park), and we've got to get to a position where those games
mean something.'' &QL; 
Trivial question &QL; 
 &UR; Dale Sveum recently became the second Pittsburgh Pirates player in
the 112-year history of that franchise to hit home runs from both
sides of the plate in the same game, joining  &UR; Bobby Bonilla. Who
holds the major league records for accomplishing the feat most in a
season and career? &QL; 
If you had wings &QL; 
 &UR; Carlos Baerga was so eager to get back to Cleveland that he left
San Diego before he was told his trade back to the Indians was
completed. Baerga was informed late Sunday night that a trade was
possible. There was a 6:30 a.m. flight out of San Diego on Sunday
and he was on it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I called to tell Carlos that the deal was finalized (just
before noon), and he was already en route,'' Padres General Manager
 &UR; Kevin
 &UR; Towers said.
</P>
<P>
   Baerga was so excited to return to the club where he enjoyed his
greatest success that he easily agreed to waive the clause in his
contract that called for his 1999 salary to be hiked from $500,000
to $1.5 million in the event of a trade.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Carlos would have run across the country to get
here,'' Cleveland General Manager  &UR; John Hart said.
</P>
<P>
   Baerga said: ``This is my house. I'm in the place where I always
wanted to be all my life. This changes everything. I'm happy
again.'' &QL; 
More on Mondesi &QL; 
Dodgers right fielder  &UR; Raul Mondesi, who inexplicably and without
provocation railed into club officials last week, had a meeting
with GM  &UR; Kevin Malone and several other Dodgers officials last
week. Mondesi's agent,  &UR; Jeff Moorad, also sat in as the sides all
try to mend fences.
</P>
<P>
   Mondesi declined to comment on the meeting, while Moorad said it
was a ``productive session.'' Malone, who is getting blasted on
local radio in Los Angeles, insists the club will keep this matter,
and any disciplinary measures, within the club.
</P>
<P>
   The fans, however, are speaking loudly, enthusiastically booing
Mondesi every time he steps up to the plate. &QL; 
D-Backs alumni report &QL; 
It's not going so well for former Diamondbacks right fielder
 &UR; Karim &UR; Garcia in Detroit. Garcia was on first base during a game
against Tampa Bay on Monday with no outs and another runner on
third in the fifth inning.
</P>
<P>
   Detroit trailed, 8-0, at the time and shortstop  &UR; Deivi Cruz
slapped a single to right-center. Garcia decided to make it to
third base and was thrown out, breaking one of the game's cardinal
rules of not making the first or last out of an inning at third
base.
</P>
<P>
   ``How do you get thrown out in a situation like that?'' Tigers
Manager  &UR; Larry Parrish asked. ``There's a time to be aggressive,
but that's not it _ not when you're down, 8-0. You've got to learn
how to think when you're playing.''
</P>
<P>
   In other news, former catcher  &UR; Jorge Fabregas is batting .086 (3
for 35) when batting after the sixth inning in games either tied or
within one run. It's the worst such mark in the majors. &QL; 
The Toy Dept. &QL; 
Chicago Cubs reliever  &UR; Rod Beck, one of our favorites at
``Baseball'' ``Insider,'' had a unique way of looking at the Cubs'
collapse:
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm embarrassed at where we are at. It's sad to see we folded
at a time we had everything going for us. It's no one's fault but
the guys in here. I think everybody, including myself, played a
part. . . . We're stuck in the middle of trying to save some
respect for ourselves, but we now live in the land of misfit
toys.'' &QL; 
Trivial answer &QL; 
Baltimore hitting coach  &UR; Eddie Murray holds the record for a
career, having hit home runs from both the right and left side of
the plate 11 times. Houston third baseman  &UR; Ken Caminiti holds the
single-season record with four, a feat he accomplished during his
MVP season in 1996. &QL; 
THE HIT LIST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Let's make it official and just get the guys red capes: After
it's all said and done, maybe  &UR; Mark McGwire and  &UR; Sammy Sosa truly
are the closest thing to  &UR; Superman in this game. Amazingly, they
are both on a better home run pace than last year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The push to raid the border begins in earnest: Something
calling itself the Virginia Baseball Stadium Authority recently
mailed out flashy books to expound the virtues of the
Washington/northern Virginia metro area. These folks are serious
about wanting to take away the Expos from Montreal.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Flashback: Lee Lacy.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; What, like it could have
 &UR; possibly been Charlie Hayes?: The San Francisco Giants announced
their all-1990s team last week and, no surprise here,  &UR; Matt
Williams was elected at third base.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Wonder how much a Johnny Damon jock strap could have
 &UR; fetched?: The Kansas City Royals charities recently auctioned off
the futuristic jerseys worn by Royals players. Rookie  &UR; Carlos
Febles' went for $975 while  &UR; Chad Kreuter's (yes, Chad Kreuter)
brought in $325. &QL; 
EXTRA BASES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Texas outfielder  &UR; Juan Gonzalez's lingering hamstring problems
have placed  &UR; Rafael Palmeiro in a tough spot. Because of the
hamstring injury, Gonzalez has required more time as the designated
hitter. In the meantime, Palmeiro, who twice had surgery on his
right knee during spring training, has been forced to move to first
base.
</P>
<P>
   St. Louis pitcher  &UR; Kent Bottenfield, enjoying the finest season
of his life, entered the weekend series with a 16-5 record.
Amazingly, he entered the season with an 18-27 career record.
</P>
<P>
   Cincinnati relievers  &UR; Scott Sullivan (85 innings before the
weekend series),  &UR; Danny Graves (84) and  &UR; Scott Williamson (77) all
have a legitimate shot at pitching at least 100 innings. The last
time three relievers from the same club did that was the 1992
Astros, who had  &UR; Doug Jones,  &UR; Joe Boever and  &UR; Xavier Hernandez.
</P>
<P>
   In 1968, the last year the pitcher's mound was 15 inches high,
only one player ( &UR; Frank Howard, 44) hit 40 home runs and only three
(Howard,  &UR; Ken Harrelson and  &UR; Willie McCovey) had 100 RBIs. Last
year, the 30th since the mound was lowered to 10 inches, 11 players
hit 40 home runs and 41 had 100 RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland's  &UR; Steve Karsay, who has overcome tremendous arm
injuries, won his 10th consecutive game Thursday night, becoming
the first Indians pitcher to do so since
 &UR; Fritz Peterson, he of wife-swapping fame, did so in 1975.
</P>
<P>
   It became official last week that the New York Mets and Chicago
Cubs will open the 2000 season with a pair of games in Japan on
March 29 and 30. They will play a pair of exhibition games the two
days prior. For their troubles, players and coaches each will
receive $25,000 and $8,000 in expense money.
</P>
<P>
   There were signs of Colorado GM  &UR; Bob Gebhard's departure before
he resigned Friday. Owner  &UR; Jerry McMorris' statement after the
``Denver Post'' reported Gebhard's ouster is imminent last week:
``It's all pure speculation and it's premature.'' Premature,
according to ``Webster's Dictionar''y: ``Before happening. Before
the proper or usual time.'' &QL; 
THE RUMOR MILL &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Expect Milwaukee to hire one or two minorities for their vacant
general manager and manager openings. With dad  &UR; Bud Selig in the
commissioner's chair and a strong desire to move minorities into
decisionmaking positions, daughter and Brewers CEO  &UR; Wendy
Selig-Preib must follow dad's mandates. Otherwise, Bud could lose
all credibility.
</P>
<P>
   With  &UR; Billy Taylor now pitching for the Mets, Oakland relied on
 &UR; Doug Jones to take over as closer after the July 31 trading
deadline. But Jones has faltered and there is growing talk that
onetime Mets phenom  &UR; Jason Isringhausen could take over the role,
if not now, then certainly in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   When Atlanta traded for shortstop  &UR; Jose Hernandez, GM
 &UR; John Schuerholz said the former Cub would provide insurance against
 &UR; Walt Weiss' leg injuries. In his first 16 games with the Braves,
Hernandez has started 13 times. Weiss has lost his job.
</P>
<P>
   Houston was initially counting on injured left fielder  &UR; Moises
Alou to make a dramatic return to the lineup right around Sept. 1.
That's looking impossible now. Alou has no other target date to
return but insists he will be ready for the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Cincinnati acquired pitcher  &UR; Juan Guzman from Baltimore strictly
for the stretch run. After his first three starts, Guzman, who was
2-1 with a 2.05 ERA before Saturday's start, says he wants to
remain with the Reds. GM  &UR; Jim Bowden may try to work out something.
</P>
<P>
   The wonderful world of Walt Disney hasn't been so kind to its
stockholders recently. In fact, there is growing talk that
 &UR; Mickey Mouse and his pals may sell off part or all of their stake
in the Angels and/or the NHL's Mighty Ducks. &QL; 
THE RANKINGS &QL; 
 &UR; TOP OF THE ORDER &QL; 
