Walker at all. ON THE RISE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Seattle Mariners: Fresh off a three-game sweep in Toronto,
their record reached the .500 mark. More important, Mariners
players are starting to talk (and act) as if they still have a
chance to jump into the wild card race. ``I see the confidence
coming in everyone, and I think the new stadium (Safeco Field) has
had a lot to do with that,''  &UR; Jay Buhner said. The Mariners are no
longer concentrating on home runs and doing little things to
produce runs. In turn, they have become a better balanced club,
especially in the bullpen, where relievers finally are gaining
confidence. &QL; 
GOING SOUTH &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Toronto Blue Jays: One week earlier, the praises of the Blue
Jays were being heralded from coast to coast. Entering their
weekend series in Oakland, Toronto had lost seven in a row and was
beginning to fade in the AL wild card race. The starting pitching
has not been able to keep its share of the burden. Losing all six
games of last week's homestand tied the worst in franchise history
as they were outscored, 51-24. Manager  &UR; Jim Fregosi, not wanting to
wait until it's too late, yanked the struggling  &UR; Kelvim Escobar
from the rotation. The recent loss of ace  &UR; David Wells due to a
back injury has only compounded the weakness. &QL; 
OVERHEARD &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Oakland took a terrible hit when the versatile  &UR; Tony
 &UR; Phillips suffered a broken leg during a game last weekend, an
injury that will keep him out for the remainder of the season. From
his hospital bed in Toronto, Phillips had this to say about the
surprising and surging Athletics: ``They're young, but they can
play. When I came here, they were eating baby food. Now, they've
moved on to meat and potatoes.'' &QL; 
OUT OF LEFT FIELD &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By now, most have heard of Boston first baseman  &UR; Brian
 &UR; Daubach, signed by the Red Sox over the winter as a six-year minor
league free agent out of the Florida Marlins system. Daubach has
taken New England by storm, becoming a phenom overnight. He has
filled in to the point where hardly any Red Sox fan even mentions
 &UR; Mo Vaughn's name anymore. Daubach had a five-game stretch in which
he drove in a head-shaking 15 runs. His legend grows by the day. &QL; 
