<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-22 00:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5535 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s BC-BKL-MERCURY-SEASON-OB     08-22 1196
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKL-MERCURY-SEASON-OBIT-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MERCURY LEADERS FIGHT 2 FOES  
 COMPETITION, AGE ARE WORTHY ADVERSARIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF METCALFE  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Once in Italy, Michele Timms played for a team that
lost all 18 of its games. Only that season was a bigger
disappointment to her than this one with the Mercury.
</P>
<P>
   But going 0-for-Firenze at age 28 is different than 15-17 at age
34 in the vastly superior Western Conference of what undeniably is
the best women's professional basketball league ever assembled.
</P>
<P>
   It's easier to rationalize because of the competition. Yet
tougher to accept because of the physiological clock.
</P>
<P>
   The ticking was loud enough for Timms and Jennifer Gillom, 35,
after the Mercury's 1998 WNBA Finals shortfall that both committed
to major off-season conditioning. It was work that in the short
term proved futile, but still might pay off before the
rest-of-their-life phase begins.
</P>
<P>
   ``The dedication they made to staying in such good shape, almost
reinventing themselves, has added at least one to two years of
high-level play'' for both, said Seth Sulka, Mercury vice
president.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Jen Gillom could play for three to five years, not at
this level, but I think she can play at this level next year. She's
just so smooth, and I don't see a point her game is going to suffer
from age.''
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line is that Timms at point guard and Gillom at power
forward have a place in Phoenix for 2000 and are virtually certain
to be among whatever number of players are allowed to be shielded
from the third expansion draft.
</P>
<P>
   That draft is part of the reason Sulka believes the Mercury
needs tweaking, not an overhaul.
</P>
<P>
   Stocking four new teams (Seattle, Portland, Indianapolis, Miami)
instead of two during an Olympic year will be disruptive enough for
the 12 existing teams, none more than three years old.
</P>
<P>
   Will teams be allowed to protect four, five or, as in the past,
six of its 11 players? And after losing a player, can a team pull
back one or two others from the unprotected list if it is at risk
of losing more than one for the first time?
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of different ways the league can go,'' Sulka
said. ``They really need to consider the fact the existing teams
need to try to maintain some continuity.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's as big a factor and as important as making the four new
teams competitive. It needs to be looked at just as much.
Competitiveness is what's going to make this work.''
</P>
<P>
   Gillom is convinced that because of how the Mercury finished,
going 12-7 after a 3-10 start, less is more when it comes to
change.
</P>
<P>
   ``We definitely don't need a lot of changes. We found that
out,'' she said. ``We need to try to keep this team together as
much as possible because we've gone through enough this year to
realize a lot of the mistakes we've made.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've learned a lesson, that with the new faces coming in,
they didn't experience the excitement of the playoffs, so they
didn't know what it was like. But now they've gone through it and
seen how we've suffered from it. By keeping this team together,
we'll have a much better start.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the expansion and regular draft rules _ will existing
teams with sub-.500 records still pick ahead of the new teams? _
the Mercury's best-case scenario is to return seven of its top nine
players, including soon-to-be mother Michelle Griffiths.
</P>
<P>
   If the 2000 season tips off with three of the four main posts
(Gillom, Griffiths, Maria Stepanova, Marlies Askamp) and four of
five from the perimeter (Timms, Lisa Harrison, Kristi Harrower,
Edna Campbell, Bridget Pettis) still here, consider the off-season
a rousing success.
</P>
<P>
   But Sulka's best guess is that one of his four Olympic-bound
players will not return. The prime candidates are Australians
Griffiths and Harrower, although both say their preference is to be
back.
</P>
<P>
   Timms, the Australian national team captain, must make the most,
financially, of the end of her career and will play in the WNBA
before the Sydney Olympics, which begin Sept. 15, 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'll be a very individual thing with the players and the
coach (Carrie Graf, a Mercury and Australian national team
assistant) whether they come back or not,'' Timms said. ``There are
a lot of tough decisions to be made, and everyone's situation is
different.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't sit at home and not get paid, but these other kids
who have got 10 years left to play in this league, they should
possibly stay at home. They've got to look out for themselves
financially, too, so it'll be an interesting decision for everyone
to make.''
</P>
<P>
   Stepanova, the 6-foot-8 center who fell nine rebounds shy of
finishing the season with nine consecutive double-doubles, likely
has earned a promotion off the Russian national team bench.
</P>
<P>
   But the 20-year-old seems determined not only to return for a
third Mercury season but for the majority of training camp,
something Sulka said he desperately wants.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's her preference to come back and play here,'' Stepanova
said through her interpreter. ``They can't order me to go
somewhere. If everything works out fine, I feel I will play here.''
</P>
<P>
   Stepanova said she and her agent have discussed the need to be
in training camp, which she missed in 1998 because of the World
Championships and this year due to the European Championships, to
``get in shape really fast and get ready to play the season
straightaway.''
</P>
<P>
   Because Germany did not qualify for the Olympics, Askamp does
not have a conflict, although she must re-sign with the league.
</P>
<P>
   Harrower and former American Basketball League players Harrison
and Campbell, who signed for only one year to be eligible for the
veteran pay scale in 2000, also must be re-signed.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, the Mercury reached agreement with Coach Cheryl
Miller on a three-year contract extension. The 35-year-old has a
53-44 pro coaching record in three years, including playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Miller did not receive a technical foul in the final 17 games of
the season after being assessed nine, with three ejections, in the
first 15.
</P>
<P>
   Of the eight original WNBA coaches, only Houston's Van
Chancellor, the two-time Coach of the Year, and Miller remain.
Cleveland's Linda Hill-MacDonald was fired on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The Mercury's early-season chemistry problems and inability to
win on the road (3-13), where it played 10 of its first 14 games,
are well documented.
</P>
<P>
   The team shooting was 39.9 percent, second-worst in the league,
falling to 37.7 percent excluding Stepanova and Askamp, 11th and
12th in league field goal percentage.
</P>
<P>
   But Harrison shot better than her ABL career average (47.6
percent to 44.3) and Campbell, in what she admits was a subpar
season, finished ninth in 3-point shooting (37.6).
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone wishes they could pull out a better player at some
position,'' Sulka said. ``But the way we played down the stretch, I
think we were solid. We could get another shooter, but I certainly
don't say we have any voids to fill that are unfillable.''
</P>
<P>
   Although attendance dropped 11.2 percent, the average of 12,219
still was third-best in the league. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
