<SLUG> BC-OUT-ARIZONA-OUTDOORS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOT WEATHER HALTS CATFISH STOCKING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BARRY BURKHART  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Catfish stockings in Phoenix's urban lakes ceased on
July 15. It will begin again on Sept. 6.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Swanson, head of the Arizona Game and Fish Department's
urban program, said the department has learned that the low
survival rate of stocked fish during the hottest monsoon months is
counterproductive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Water conditions are pressing the threshold for stocking,'' he
said. ``It just isn't feasible to keep stocking catfish during
those times.''
</P>
<P>
   The state's urban program, allowing adults and children to fish
near home in city lakes, keeps growing and it considered a
universal success. The latest survey on anglers at the lake is
1996, when 168,100 anglers days were spent at the five Valley urban
lakes during the year.
</P>
<P>
   Poor periods are expected a certain times of the year.
</P>
<P>
   First, there's the problem of the pH factor. This measures the
contrast between the alkaline and acid contents of the water. In
this state, the alkaline reading is of the most concern. A perfect
pH reading is 5. But as the pH factor rises (alkaline), fish become
more stressed. At 10, they die. Swanson said the pH levels
sometimes rise to 9 to 9.5 in urban lakes. Then, stocking is a
useless proposition.
</P>
<P>
   Water temperature is another consideration. These are small,
shallow lakes. There's no cool, deep water to seek in summer
months. Fish become sluggish and quit feeding.
</P>
<P>
   The warm water and intense sunlight lead to an explosion of
growth by water plants. The water is robbed of oxygen. That's the
cause of many fish kills.
</P>
<P>
   The third most highly used urban lake in the Valley is Cortez
Park Lake north of 35th Avenue and Dunlap Road, with 23,900 angler
days a year. Alvord Lake in south Phoenix is the most used, with
23,900 angler days.
</P>
<P>
   But Alvord dwarfs Cortez in size. There are many more acres to
fish. Considering the acreages of the two lakes, Cortez dwarfs
Alford in the number of angler hours per acre _ 21,500 to 9,800.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, Cortez is a sick lake now and is getting help
from Game and Fish and the city of Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   ``These artificial lakes are like a giant fish bowls,'' Swanson
said. ``Every so often, they need cleaning like a fish bowl.''
</P>
<P>
   That also means adding more water since the lakes tend to get
stagnant.
</P>
<P>
   Water weeds and siltation cause problems and must be removed.
</P>
<P>
   Cortez has a unique problem. The canal that feeds it water has a
Phoenix water treatment plant located upstream.
</P>
<P>
   Alum, a chemical, is used at the water plant to cause minerals
and other particles to settle out of the water. It is flushed into
the canal. The chemical no longer is active, but it produces silt
that enters Cortez and settles to the bottom.
</P>
<P>
   Salt River Project is trying to stop that process, Swanson said.
It would require enlarging the area around the water plant so that
settling basins could be built. The sediment would be dredged
occasionally so the almu wouldn't be discharged into the canal.
</P>
<P>
   Fixing Cortez would be easier if it could be purged and cleaned
with incoming water. But there's a problem with that, too.
</P>
<P>
   SRP used to be able to fill Cortez with water and then take it
back without losing its water allowance. The state's Ground Water
and Management Act fixed that, according to Swanson.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were three phases to the law,'' Swanson said. ``In one,
water allocations to lakes and parks were reduced.'' And SRP now
longer receives credit for water it takes back from the lake.
</P>
<P>
   For now. the remedy for Cortez is to remove water weeds from
Cortez and dredge for silt.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix will have to allocate money for most of the work.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really encouraging that the city has been enthusiastic
about rejuvenating its urban lakes,'' Swanson said. ``Some cities
don't want to spend much on their lakes.'' &QL; 
Barry Burkhart can be reached at (602) 444-8454 or at
barry.burkhart(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
