<SLUG> BC-FBC-ARIZONA-DEFENSE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STANDARD HIGH FOR UA DEFENSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By NORM FRAUENHEIM  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TUCSON, Ariz. - The attention has swirled around Trung Canidate,
Heisman candidates and a double-barreled attack at quarterback.
There's even a $2.9 million, state-of-the-art scoreboard under
construction at the north end of Arizona Stadium. The dim bulbs are
gone. Soon, they'll be replaced by the bright lights of cyberspace.
</P>
<P>
   Ding-ding-ding, the Wildcats are prepared to make some points.
But make no mistake about one of them:
</P>
<P>
   The potential for another dynamic season on offense is not the
radical new face of Arizona football. If the fourth-ranked Wildcats
can stage an encore of last year's offensive strike force, they
won't be changing so much as evolving.
</P>
<P>
   In Coach Dick Tomey's 12-year regime, Arizona was built with an
emphasis on defense. Since 1994, the Wildcats have been identified
by ``Desert Swarm.'' It's a catchy nickname, but it stuck because
defense is an Arizona tradition. It remains to be seen whether the
new-look offense is a passing fashion or something substantial
enough to merit its own nickname. Stayed tuned on that one.
</P>
<P>
   But there doesn't appear to be much doubt that much of the
Arizona tradition endures. There was evidence throughout the
Wildcats camp at Cochise College near Douglas that plenty of sting
is left in the old swarm. However, one potentially fatal, question
lingers.
</P>
<P>
   Is there life after Chris McAlister?
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got life without Chris, and what life without Chris is
like, we'll see,'' Tomey said.
</P>
<P>
   McAlister, the Baltimore Ravens' first-round pick in April's NFL
draft, was such a dominant presence at cornerback last year that
the Wildcats were able to hide whatever other weaknesses they might
have had in the secondary. McAlister virtually shut down his side
of the field.
</P>
<P>
   His departure has created inevitable doubts about the Wildcats
secondary. Arizona's defensive backs are short. McAlister's
designated successor, 5-foot-9 Leland Gayles, is returning after
missing most of last season after a devastating collision at
Washington that left him with a cervical sprain. The doubts have
been heard.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody has their opinions,'' said 5-9 Kelvin Hunter, who is
projected to start at the corner opposite Gayles. ``But we know in
our hearts that we can cover anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   If the secondary has a weakness, it might not become evident
immediately, anyway. The Wildcats open Saturday at Penn State,
which has never been known for a strong passing attack.
Nonetheless, the Nittany Lions might be tempted by well-circulated
suspicions of a weak Arizona secondary. However, that also could be
a point at which they fall into a trap.
</P>
<P>
   While All-Everything linebacker Marcus Bell triggers the Arizona
defense, the Wildcats also possess an imposing, deep defensive
line. Don't be surprised if the defensive front emerges as
Arizona's strength this year.
</P>
<P>
   In an extension of the shared duties at quarterback by Keith
Smith and Ortege Jenkins, defensive coordinator Rich Ellerson plans
to employ a rotation. Ellerson has the players to do it.
</P>
<P>
   At Cochise, nine effective defensive linemen were evident. Want
to stop the run? Send in sophomore Keoni Fraser. Need to put some
pressure on the quarterback? Call on sophomore Alex Luna.
</P>
<P>
   Some other names are senior J.J. Joppru, junior Idris Haroon,
junior college transfer Austin Uku, senior James Lewis and freshman
Young Thompson. Remember Thompson's name. He's a cousin of Jack
``The Throwin' Samoan'' Thompson, the former Washington State and
Cincinnati Bengals quarterback. This Thompson is 6-2 and nearly 300
pounds. His legs are island-sized, and he moves along the line of
scrimmage like a riptide.
</P>
<P>
   The key to the rotation is at the bookends with junior starters
Mike Robertson and Joe Tafoya.
</P>
<P>
   ``The defensive line is one position that takes the most
beating,'' said Tafoya, who has become the group's designated
spokesman and leader. ``We're usually the ones who go down first.
If you get a good rotation going, your legs feel fresher.''
</P>
<P>
   The idea is to alternate with wave after wave of fresh troops.
</P>
<P>
   A hint at the level of confidence in the defensive line was
evident in the spring when versatile Eli Wnek, a freshman starter
last season from Glendale Ironwood High School, was moved to the
offensive backfield as a lead blocker and occasional receiver.
</P>
<P>
   Above all, the defensive front is the opening line in an Arizona
defense that figures to be characteristically creative. Over the
years, Ellerson's schemes have included a variety of labels. From
1992 through 1995, it was called ``the double-eagle flex.''
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1990s, the rest of the nation had another name for
it. It was unyielding, as the Wildcats were the nation's top team
in run defense in '93, No. 2 in '94.
</P>
<P>
   In '94, a Tedy Bruschi-led front was credited with 41 of the
team's 47 sacks, a Pac-10 high. During the past couple of years,
Arizona has introduced the ``whip or flex'' linebacker in senior
DaShon Polk.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we ended up with a reasonably good defense last year,
but not a great defense,'' Tomey said. ``We retain nine of those
guys that started plus a couple of other guys who played a lot. I
think we have a chance to be better.''
</P>
<P>
   If an enduring tradition means anything at all, Arizona's
defense always has that chance. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
