<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-ASU-SCRIMMAGE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUN DEVILS' PROGRESS EVIDENT  
 SNYDER THRILLED BY `GREAT CAMP' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PAOLA BOIVIN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMP TONTOZONA, Ariz. _ Breathe easy, Arizona State fans.
Saturday's camp-ending scrimmage did not reflect what the Sun
Devils achieved during their 10 days in the wilderness.
</P>
<P>
   J.R. Redmond sat out. Ryan Kealy played sparingly. Many of the
defensive alignments _ particularly nickel and dime packages _ were
put to rest for the day. What the competition did provide was a
chance for the coaches to evaluate positions up for grabs, as well
as key reserves.
</P>
<P>
   First, what was accomplished:
</P>
<P>
   Despite their inexperience, the Sun Devils will be deeper and
better in the secondary. ASU will have a rotation of four players
they are comfortable with at safety.
</P>
<P>
   These Sun Devils seem to be closer and have better leadership.
Players are holding themselves accountable. Redmond and Kealy are
more vocal and have the attention of their teammates. Defensive end
Erik Flowers is among those demanding more from the defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was a great camp,'' Coach Bruce Snyder said.
``The players were terrific to coach, they were agreeable and they
played tough.''
</P>
<P>
   Kealy gave every indication that he will have a big year. He
looked confident, poised and extremely comfortable with the
offense.
</P>
<P>
   What's still up for grabs:
</P>
<P>
   Snyder wouldn't say it's a done deal, but it appears Scott
Peters will play center and Levi Jones, a 6-foot-6 former walk-on
from Eloy, will take over at left guard.
</P>
<P>
   The Sun Devils gave junior college transfer Kenneth Williamson
an opportunity to start at center _ which would have put Peters at
guard _ but they don't appear sold on that option.
</P>
<P>
   The backup quarterback job is getting interesting. One of the
top contenders is 6-1 Griffin Goodman, a walk-on who helped Eastern
Arizona to an ACCAC championship in 1997. He is battling with
junior college transfer John Leonard for the spot.
</P>
<P>
   Snyder did not discount redshirt freshman Matt Cooper, who could
be the Sun Devils quarterback of the future, but the contest seems
to be between Goodman and Leonard.
</P>
<P>
   Wide receiver is a big-time concern. Junior Tariq McDonald is
the only sure thing. Junior college transfers Richard Williams, who
was limited by a sore hamstring in camp, Ryan Dennard and Royce
Coachman showed promise, but it's still unknown how they will
perform in games.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Forth (hamstring) won't return until late September, and
Kyran Jones and Shaun McDonald are promising but need experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that's our biggest concern,'' Snyder said. ``I'm sure
they might be offended by that statement, but let them use that as
motivation.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sun Devils are grateful for a generous allotment of talented
tight ends and running backs who can catch.
</P>
<P>
   Both candidates for place-kicker _ Stephen Baker and Mike Barth
_ struggled during the early part of the scrimmage, then came on
strong when the competition heated up. Baker finished 3 for 5 with
a long field goal of 47 yards. Barth was 2 for 5 with a long of 43.
</P>
<P>
   Nick Murphy, a transfer from Scottsdale Community College, is
giving Baker a run at punter. Snyder has said he would like Baker
to concentrate on just one position, but would they replace him at
the spot where he was a freshman All-American last season? &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
