<HEADER>
A5540 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s BC-FBC-ASU-BICKLEY-AZR &LR;      08-22 0761
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-ASU-BICKLEY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISASTROUS SEASON MAY BE WHAT ASU NEEDED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN BICKLEY  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMP TONTOZONA - The pedestal is gone. The program has been
humbled. And so has the head coach.
</P>
<P>
   If you think Arizona State football took a major hit in both
quality and perception during last year's season of contempt,
you're right. And all that's left is an enormous burden of proof.
</P>
<P>
   ``History tells you that you learn more from your failures than
you do from success,'' quarterback Ryan Kealy said. ``And that's
what we're trying to do _ bounce back.''
</P>
<P>
   With all the inherent advantages, there is no logical reason why
ASU football should be where it is: a team on the periphery of the
Top 25, on the mend, hoping to surprise a few people. But the Sun
Devils are here for a reason, and in some regards, a thoroughly
deflating 5-6 season may serve as a turning point in the direction
of the program.
</P>
<P>
   The changes start at the top. The head coach, Bruce Snyder, is
59 years old. With a contract that runs through 2004, his job is
safe. But it's easy to see how his perspective has changed.
</P>
<P>
   Entering last season, it appeared the Sun Devils finally had
joined the elite fraternity in college football. They had won 20 of
their previous 24 games. They had cracked the top five in some
national polls, had been given an outside chance at a national
championship. Then it all fell apart.
</P>
<P>
   ``Definitely a divided team at times,'' Kealy said. ``There was
a lot of finger-pointing when the ship started to sink.''
</P>
<P>
   It may have been easy for Snyder to believe his program was on
cruise control, but there is no question he slipped in 1998. He
overestimated his talent, lost the pulse of his team. But if true
character only emerges from the abyss, then give Snyder credit for
re-energizing himself and his program.
</P>
<P>
   He spent the off-season visiting with other respected coaches.
He talked with LSU boss Gerry DiNardo about practice habits. He
chatted with Army Coach Bob Sutton about leadership. He discussed
strategy with Clemson's Tommy Bowden. He lit a fire under his own
feet.
</P>
<P>
   Snyder also is focusing hard on the concept of chemistry. He was
quick to release or suspend five players from the program. He is on
top of everything, and the lessons of last season run deep. For the
coach and his players.
</P>
<P>
   During the boot camp of Tontozona, Snyder allows his players to
sleep in on Sunday morning. In the past, that has led to some
raucous Saturday nights. But this year, Snyder advised his team to
use the break for slumber purposes only. And they've listened.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just think they're more willing to say (the coach) might
know what the hell he's talking about,'' Snyder said. ``As opposed
to, `He's old and he doesn't know.' ''
</P>
<P>
   And that is much different rhetoric from the coach who once
claimed he did a terrific job in 1998. The coach who told me in our
first meeting that very few people in the state of Arizona know
more about football than he does.
</P>
<P>
   While the Sun Devils won't be playing for a national
championship in January, humility is a fine place to start.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our conditioning this summer has been great, our strength is
greater, and our practice habits are much better,'' Snyder said.
``And it all stems from guys saying that last year was
unacceptable. They've been practicing like crazy because of it.''
</P>
<P>
   No doubt, this season will be a test of Snyder's instincts. He
has imported a number of junior college players, normally a red
flag signaling a program compensating for poor recruiting. But
Snyder really likes this team, and there are signs of optimism.
</P>
<P>
   If he stays healthy, tailback J.R. Redmond can be a phenomenal
talent. If he stays on an even Kealy, the quarterback has the
talent to produce. The defense is more experienced. And while
suspect in quality, the secondary is much deeper than last year, a
necessity in the pass-happy Pac-10.
</P>
<P>
   ``The chemistry right now is terrific,'' Snyder said. ``And
(defensive end) Erik Flowers has something going with J.R. Redmond.
They will not let this team lose. They talk about it all the time.
And we never had much of that last year. Nobody would step forward
to do that. They were all more interested in what bowl game they
were going to.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the Sun Devils have been knocked down. But they're fighting
like mad to get on their feet. And that says something.
</P>
<P>
   Something good. &QL; 
Dan Bickley can be reached at (602) 444-8253 or at
dan.bickley(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-22-99 0038EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990822.0023 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-22 00:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5541 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s BC-FBN-CARDS-QUARTERBACK     08-22 0728
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDS-QUARTERBACKS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BACKUP QBS HAVE HANDLE ON SITUATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By LEE SHAPPELL  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. - No coach wants a backup quarterback to stick out
like a sore thumb _ which is exactly what Cardinals starting
quarterback Jake Plummer has on his throwing hand.
</P>
<P>
   So the Cardinals staff was gratified when backup Dave Brown and
third-stringer Chris Greisen, thrown into action Friday after
Plummer's injury on the first possession, rallied the team to a
27-17 preseason win over Tennessee. Their performances reaffirmed
that if something happened to Plummer in a game that mattered, the
franchise would not unravel.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, an eight-year veteran and former starter for the New York
Giants, is not the most mobile man on the field. He has taken three
sacks in two games, including one that took the Cardinals out of
field goal range on a third down Friday. But he also threw a
touchdown pass to tight end Johnny McWilliams. In two games, Brown
has a completion percentage of .667 (18 for 27).
</P>
<P>
   Greisen, a rookie who guided the team to its only touchdown in
the preseason opener at Denver, was slowed early last week by an
abscess. He took the Cardinals to a go-ahead touchdown in the
closing two minutes, including a drive-saving 10-yard scramble on
third and 9 to the Tennessee 4.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Vince Tobin wanted to get a good look at Brown on Friday,
but not the way he got it. Brown was scheduled to play the entire
second half after Plummer played the first.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dave got us the touchdown to get us back in the ballgame
(after a 10-0 deficit),'' Tobin said. ``Dave made the good throw to
Johnny for the touchdown. He did what you'd hope a seasoned,
experienced veteran would do. We're confident that if something
were to happen to Jake that Dave could step in, move the offense,
and give us chance to win the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Greisen has shown maturity beyond his years.
</P>
<P>
   ``In both games he's showed an awful lot of poise for a young
guy,'' Tobin said. ``He's playing with the second- and third-level
wide receivers, and they don't always run the right routes. Chris
has made check-offs that a lot of more experienced quarterbacks
wouldn't have made.
</P>
<P>
   ``He made that big first down on the scramble, which was a key
play in that ballgame.''
</P>
<P>
   X-rays of Plummer's hand during the game were negative. He had a
precautionary magnetic resonance imaging test Saturday morning.
Results are expected today. The thumb was swollen, bruised and very
sore. He is not expected to practice most of this week and is
questionable for Saturday's preseason visit to Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jake would have to be pretty healthy to play,'' Tobin said.
``We don't want to set him back. He needs the experience of these
preseason games in order to get ready for the regular season, but
we are not going to do anything to jeopardize his health.''
</P>
<P>
   If Plummer can't play, Tobin said he might give the first unit
less work this week and then more in the final preseason game.
</P>
<P>
   Often-injured cornerback Tom Knight made it through training
camp healthy and has elevated his play.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's playing with more confidence than he has had,'' Tobin
said.
</P>
<P>
   Wide receiver Andy McCullough, the leading receiver in NFL
Europe, is beginning to learn the system and step forward as the
projected fourth receiver. Free agent Tony Hamler had been making a
move for the No. 5 spot, but he dropped three passes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Andy was in a completely different system two months ago,''
Tobin said. ``Everything is new to him since he missed minicamp _
responsibilities, alignments, routes. He's fighting to learn.
Hamler dropped a couple. That disappointed me, but he still is a
rookie. I hope he develops consistency because he does have
ability.''
</P>
<P>
   Chad Carpenter also remains in the battle.
</P>
<P>
   On the injury front, tight end Terry Hardy (hamstring) is to
return to practice Monday and center Allen DeGraffenreid (shoulder)
isn't far behind. But defensive linemen Mike Moten (knee) and
Thomas Burke (hamstring) are expected to miss four to six days.
Offensive lineman Jerome Daniels (dislocated elbow) could be out
several weeks, Tobin said, leaving the Cardinals with an acute
shortage of offensive linemen. With the cut to 65 coming next week,
the team does not expect to sign another offensive lineman. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
