<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFL-NOTEBOOK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW LOW CAN THIS AGENT GO? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Trailing badly in the public opinion battle, the agent for
unsigned Cardinals first-round pick  &UR; L.J. Shelton sunk to new
depths last week. He managed to turn  &UR; Bill Bidwill Jr., Cardinals
vice president, into a sympathetic figure.
</P>
<P>
   First, during a dog and pony show that was disguised as a news
conference in his Denver office,  &UR; Lamont Smith threatened to expose
Bidwill Jr. The agent disclosed he had a tape that would prove
Bidwill Jr. had said the Cardinals could ``live with'' a contract
for Shelton that included all of the ``bells and whistles'' the
team vowed it never would give.
</P>
<P>
   Smith claimed he wasn't trying to blackmail the team. In fact,
he said he hadn't deliberately taped their draft day conversation.
It was inadvertent or accidental, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sure. And if you believe that, you must think  &UR; Richard Nixon
inadvertently taped the conversations in the Oval Office during the
Watergate scandal, an accident that brought down the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, three days after Smith threatened to release the
tapes, he didn't show up for a meeting in Tempe with Cardinals
officials. The two sides had met the previous day, and the
Cardinals had scheduled another session to resume negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Cardinals officials maintain they were stood up without even a
phone call. Smith said he hadn't shown up because team officials
had allowed only a short block of time for the meeting. He also was
annoyed that Bidwill Jr. wasn't going to attend.
</P>
<P>
   Smith wasn't interested in serious negotiations. He just wanted
Bidwill Jr. there so they could hash over their draft day
conversation and Smith could let him know what he planned to do
with the alleged tape of their phone call.
</P>
<P>
   There was a reason Cardinals officials had a limited amount of
time for the meeting. They were trying to get to Flagstaff to meet
with the families of offensive linemen  &UR; Ernest Dye and  &UR; Lester
Holmes, &UR; both of whom had been hospitalized in a rollover car
accident on Interstate 17 on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Before leaving town, Smith went on the radio and threatened to
have Shelton, the offensive tackle from Eastern Michigan, sit out
the entire season. He even maintained that Shelton could make more
money next year than the five-year, $5.1 million deal the Cardinals
could pay him as the 21st selection overall.
</P>
<P>
   Smith didn't suddenly become media-friendly. He hasn't returned
one phone call since February from ``The Arizona Republic,'' the
state's largest newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, ever canny, went on the offensive because he thought he
could prey on the unpopularity of Bidwill Jr., whom fans blame for
almost everything that goes wrong with the Cardinals, even when he
isn't involved.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, the agent for first-round pick  &UR; Andre
Wadsworth, &UR; Eugene
 &UR; Parker, &UR; blamed Bidwill Jr. for nixing a deal. Callers on talk radio
went nuts. Volunteer workers for the Rio Salado Crossing stadium
project threatened to quit because of all the flak the team was
getting for the Wadsworth holdout.
</P>
<P>
   Less than a week later, Wadsworth signed, on the eve of the
regular season opener.
</P>
<P>
   But if Smith is expecting public opinion to force the Cardinals
to sign his client, he is kidding himself. There is no pending
stadium vote. Wadsworth, the third pick overall, was penciled in as
a starter on draft day. Thus, he had all the leverage.
</P>
<P>
   Shelton, who was expected to battle for a starting job, has
little leverage. He has missed three weeks of camp and would be a
backup even if he signed today.
</P>
<P>
   All along, Smith has misplayed his hand, showing a terrible
sense of timing.
</P>
<P>
   Here, the franchise is reeling from a tragedy that could cost
Dye his right arm, and Smith, piqued that he doesn't get a chance
to confront Bidwill Jr. about the silly tape, storms out of town. &QL; 
Amazing grace &QL; 
When Cardinals players finally got to visit Dye at Flagstaff
Medical Center last week, they weren't sure what to expect.
</P>
<P>
   Few had ever seen Dye, whose right arm was nearly amputated in
the car accident, without a smile on his face.
</P>
<P>
   Dye made sure the players felt at ease. He told one teammate,
``Tell the guy in the next room, he owes me a Mercedes.''
</P>
<P>
   The guy in the next hospital room was offensive guard  &UR; Lester
 &UR; Holmes, &UR; who had been driving Dye's Mercedes 500S when it
hydroplaned on I-17, spun around three times and rolled over twice.
</P>
<P>
   Dye had been in surgery for more than eight hours, and yet he
could still joke around with his teammates. &QL; 
Looking good &QL; 
Ravens Coach  &UR; Brian Billick made a popular move with some in the
team's front office when he signed former Cardinals quarterback
 &UR; Stoney &UR; Case.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at the guy,'' Billick said. ``He belongs on the cover of
``GQ.'' I'm a hero with the secretaries.''
</P>
<P>
   But can Case play? He made only four appearances in four seasons
with the Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   The Colts signed him to a two-year, $2 million deal in the
off-season but cut him after one preseason game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was out of the blue, totally unexpected,'' Case said.
``Next to  &UR; Peyton Manning, &UR; I thought I was the last person that
anybody thought (was in trouble). I was out there working hard,
doing good things. I had a good game against Chicago. Three days
later, they call me and say they're going to go with  &UR; Steve Walsh
as No. 2.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `Are you serious?' It was a two-minute conversation.
They didn't give me a reason.''
</P>
<P>
   Case is reunited with former Cardinals quarterback coach  &UR; Matt
 &UR; Cavanaugh, &UR; offensive coordinator for the Ravens.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got a lot of ability,'' Cavanaugh said. ``He's just very
raw right now.'' &QL; 
Class act &QL; 
There wasn't one Giants player who questioned Coach  &UR; Jim Fassel for
leaving the team in training camp to be with his ill mother in
Scottsdale.
</P>
<P>
   Fassel missed the Giants' preseason opener to be with his
mother,  &UR; Dorothy, &UR; 76, as she began kidney dialysis treatments last
week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him going to Arizona to see his mother was was the best
coaching decision he ever made,'' Giants defensive end  &UR; Michael
Strahan said. ``I told him he would have regretted it if he hadn't
gone. And I told him he made us realize how much family matters.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first thing I did after he left was call my mom.''
</P>
<P>
   Fassel appeared weary when he returned to Albany, N.Y., from
Scottsdale.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's stable,'' Fassel said of his mother. ``She's fighting.
She's a tough lady.'' &QL; 
Short shots &QL; 
The Chiefs continue to bash holdout first-round draft pick  &UR; John
Tait, &UR; the offensive tackle from Brigham Young who attended Tempe
McClintock High School.
</P>
<P>
   ``I barely remember his name,'' Kansas City Coach  &UR; Gunther
 &UR; Cunningham said.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine Hall of Famers  &UR; Chuck Noll or  &UR; Tom Landry doing this?
Billick, the former Vikings offensive coordinator who is in his
first year with the Ravens, gave himself the game ball after they
beat the Eagles in the preseason opener. What will he do when the
Ravens win a game that counts? &QL; 
Includes information from other media sources. Steve Schoenfeld can
be reached at (602) 444-8334 or at steve.schoenfeld(at)pni.com via
e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
