<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-22 01:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5555 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-POLLY-100-AZR &LR;      08-22 2023
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLLY-100-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLLY ROSENBAUM: `THE FIRST 100 IS THE HARDEST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 (Resending to correct first graf) 
 
 By MAUREEN WEST  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Schoolteacher Edwynne Prendergast, 30, was brimming with her
usual optimism when she arrived in Arizona in search of adventure
and a good paycheck.
</P>
<P>
   She was hardly the typical young woman to step off a train in
Tucson that September day in 1929.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, she was college-educated _ political science and
history at the University of Colorado. For another, she was
divorced.
</P>
<P>
   Like so many before her and after, Edwynne Prendergast, who was
born in Ollie, Iowa, came to this remote, sparsely settled state to
start over.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike most, Prendergast _ soon nicknamed Polly for that
incurable optimist, Pollyanna _ stayed to help write Arizona
history.
</P>
<P>
   Prendergast, known to Arizona as Polly Rosenbaum, will celebrate
her 100th birthday on Sept. 4. The former legislator never had
children. But for 70 years, she has worried over the state as
though it were her family.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the Legislature and out, Rosenbaum has influenced
Arizona's laws and educational system and fought to preserve its
history.
</P>
<P>
   And long before Arizona won national attention for its ``fab
five'' women in top political positions, Rosenbaum blazed the
lonely trail that they and others have followed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was tough for women back then if you let it get to you, but
I didn't,'' Rosenbaum says today in her crisp, staccato tones.
</P>
<P>
   ``They tolerated you. It was especially tough for a woman all
alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one could have dreamed of the progress that was made this
century _ in every area.''
</P>
<P>
   Evelyn Cooper, director of the Arizona Historical Foundation,
says Rosenbaum epitomizes the brand of tough, tireless optimism
that Americans associate with its Western pioneers _ and thus with
Old Arizona. Plus, Cooper said, she's a walking history of Arizona
that is yet to be written down.
</P>
<P>
   When she arrived in Tucson, the young teacher lodged at the
Congress Hotel. She had to wait overnight for the Model T Ford that
would take her to the mining town of Hayden, where she had been
recruited to teach typing, shorthand, history and civics.
</P>
<P>
   As was her custom, she immediately began soaking up local
politics. As a child, Rosenbaum said, she would pull the political
section from the morning newspapers, leaving the social pages to
her sisters.
</P>
<P>
   It was a good time to be an optimist: The news in Arizona
newspapers was mostly positive. Though the Great Depression loomed
just weeks ahead, Arizona industry, especially mining, was enjoying
its best year in history.
</P>
<P>
   Americans could buy Whippets, Buicks, Fords and Cadillacs, each
with great loads of copper tubes and tanks and wires. Members of
the burgeoning middle class could buy a first-class luxury car for
about $1,000, new. A 3-year-old Buick Roadster could be found in
The Arizona Republican for $485.
</P>
<P>
   High-boy Atwater Kent radios were selling for $188 _ a fortune
for the times. Cars, radios and airplane ads filled newspaper
pages. The state's agriculture, cattle and tourism industries were
also booming as never before.
</P>
<P>
   Rosenbaum took the open-air ride to hot and dusty Hayden; it was
over 110 degrees when she finally stepped out of the coach, her
wool suit soaked in muddy perspiration.
</P>
<P>
   But the town charmed her. Hay den, a copper-boom company town of
2,200 near the confluence of the Gila and San Pedro rivers, then
featured a pretty downtown and had access to a riverfront golf
course. It was more livable than today, Rosen baum said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We went to dances every Satur day and played golf every
Sunday,'' Rosenbaum recalled.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had bridge clubs and meet ings of Eastern Star and the
Rebekahs, and, my, you could take a walk at 2 a.m. if you wanted to
and feel perfectly safe.
</P>
<P>
   ``You knew everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Even when the Depression hit, the little town kept dancing for
two more years. Rosenbaum taught school and lived in a women's
dormitory-style hotel owned by the mines.
</P>
<P>
   But the nation's hard times finally caught up with Hayden.
Scrambling to find a steady paycheck, Rosen baum became a secretary
at Inspi ration Copper Co.
</P>
<P>
   From 1929 to 1939, as the Depression deepened and as the towns
of the copper crescent fell on harder and harder times, Rosen baum
was a blur of happy activity in the towns of Hayden and Globe. She
would always be the one to look on the bright side.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your attitude means every thing,'' she still says today. ``If
you think you can do something, you can.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1939, her company lent her as a temporary secretary in
Phoenix for the short session of the Arizona Legislature. She was
paid $5 a day. Legislators were paid $8.
</P>
<P>
   There, she met and married William G. ``Rosie'' Rosenbaum,
majority leader of the Arizona House. When he died in the 10th year
of their marriage, his wife was invited to serve out his term _ so
the state didn't have to pay for an election.
</P>
<P>
   It was not exactly an early victory for feminism.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't have to come down to the Legislature,'' one lawmaker
as sured her. Another told her he didn't want ``any woman'' on his
commit tee.
</P>
<P>
   She would serve in the Legisla ture for almost 46 years, until
she was defeated in 1994 at age 95.
</P>
<P>
   And she became an almost leg endary figure, even to her critics.
The late Republic columnist John Kolbe wrote this about Rosenbaum
after her 1994 defeat: ``Although time had long passed her by, and
she ceased to be much of a power from her back-bench seat in the
minority, on the narrow issues where her interest lay _ such as the
state library _ her wish is still law, so universal is the esteem
and affection in which she is held.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be sure, she she hasn't always been a profile in courage.
Her lightning-quick scurry out the back door when a controversial
bill comes up for a vote is legendary.''
</P>
<P>
   Rosenbaum readily admits that, in part because she was a Demo
crat, she was no flamboyant leader, rarely giving floor speeches or
sponsoring major legislation. In stead, she was a tireless be
hind-the-scenes worker.
</P>
<P>
   During her long career, Rosen baum became friends with a wide
range of Arizonans, from alleged trunk murderess Winnie Ruth Judd
to former Gov. Rose Mofford.
</P>
<P>
   ``Between Rosie (her husband) and I, we knew all the governors
since Arizona became a state in 1912,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1980s, local historian Marshall Trimble recalls sitting
on a selection committee for the Ari zona Women's Hall of Fame,
which Rosenbaum helped establish. While he and others spoke of what
they read about the illustrious characters from Arizona's past,
Rosenbaum spoke of them as people she knew.
</P>
<P>
   ``I swore that if we had brought up the name Martha Washington,
Polly would have reeled off an anecdote about something they did
during the Revolution,'' Trimble said.
</P>
<P>
   As a legislator, she was an especially strong advocate for edu
cation and libraries. Because Hay den didn't have a library when
she arrived, she worked to ensure that Arizona's little towns had
their share of libraries. She also spear headed the development of
Arizona's community college system.
</P>
<P>
   All along, she punched holes in the glass ceiling: In 1968, she
and others went through the Arizona Constitution word by word,
elimi nating ``male'' as a requisite for becoming an elected state
official.
</P>
<P>
   ``She wears me out,'' says Mof ford, who calls her a personal
role model and the most remarkable woman she has ever known. Rosen
baum's famous for outwalking most people in both speed and
distance.
</P>
<P>
   ``So many places to go,'' Rosen baum says.
</P>
<P>
   Even now, as she gets ready for her second century, Rosenbaum
says she doesn't feel much different than when she was a teenager
during World War I.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first 100 is the hardest,'' she says. ``The second hundred
should be easier because I have crossed all the bridges.''
</P>
<P>
   Though she still considers Gila County her home base, for the
past five years her full-time residence has been a two-bedroom
condomin ium in central Phoenix. She con fesses that she doesn't
invite visitors because her home is a bit of a mess. She has been
sorting through 30 large boxes of papers from her legislative days.
She still has 10 left.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, she drives to the state Capitol to give a tour of the
historic House and Senate chambers. She's also a regular at the
state's gem and mineral museum at 15th Avenue and Washington
Street, which she helped establish and which bears her name. Her
love of minerals goes back to her copper town days.
</P>
<P>
   Driving around town is becoming more difficult, she says,
because many of the older buildings that are her landmarks are
disappearing.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the problems with Phoe nix is its lack of memory,'' she
says. ``Newcomers come, and what do they care about what happened
50 years ago?''
</P>
<P>
   She cares. In her later years as a legislator, Rosenbaum fought
to preserve a number of historic sites, including the Evans House
on West Washington, across from the old Carnegie Library, which she
also helped preserve. The Evans House was a shambles, though it was
one of only three great Victorian speci mens left in the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``She, better than anyone, under stands that historic buildings
tie our society to a sense of well-being and give us community
spirit,'' says Phoenix City Councilman Phil Gor don, who worked
with her on the Evans House.
</P>
<P>
   Nor are Rosenbaum's political days quite over. Along with former
state Attorney General Grant Woods, she has been asked to be
co-chairwoman of an effort to end gerrymandering of political
districts by creating an independent redis tricting commission. The
proposal is headed for the ballot in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told them, `You bet your life. I'll be glad to give you some
pointers,' '' she says. ``I'll never quit politics.''
</P>
<P>
   Rosenbaum is getting used to people asking her about her almost
being 100 _ when they get over their disbelief that she's that old.
</P>
<P>
   ``Aren't there a lot more impor tant things to talk about?'' she
asks. ``Making 100 is just something that happened.''
</P>
<P>
   But she feels fortunate to have never had a serious illness or
operation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never had time to be sick,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   The secret to a long life? ``Being interested in other people
and things.''
</P>
<P>
   Her birthday wish for Arizona is that state officials get back
into the habit of thinking carefully about the important issues.
She also worries that children aren't taught to think; all their
time is filled with activity and entertainment, she fears.
</P>
<P>
   And she wishes a wish for mutual respect in politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``My husband taught me that you must respect the other person's
viewpoint, even if it is different than yours,'' Rosenbaum says.
``That's gone now.''
</P>
<P>
   She's not much for partisanship. She became a Democrat because
there wasn't a Republican in sight when she first came to the
state. She stayed a Democrat but never con sidered herself a slave
to any party.
</P>
<P>
   Today, she says, she would con sider being an Independent, which
is really what she considers herself to have been all these years.
</P>
<P>
   Even after 100 years, Rosenbaum isn't interested in leaving this
life any sooner than she has to: She doesn't have time to die.
</P>
<P>
   Still, one of her fondest memories is a beautiful funeral in the
1940s in rural Gila County.
</P>
<P>
   An old World War I veteran had died, and his family wanted a
military funeral for him. They found a good flag to put on his
coffin. They found a 12-year-old boy who could play a trumpet. The
next day, everybody climbed a hill out in the middle of nowhere and
put the old man in the ground, adding rocks atop his grave to keep
the wild animals away. The boy's taps, beau tifully played, echoed
through the hushed landscape.
</P>
<P>
   She remembers like it was yester day.
</P>
<P>
   ``People should remember some of these things,'' Rosenbaum says.
``They will never come again. It was a whole different life.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, she shakes off the melan choly and smiles a bright,
century-old smile.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's talk about something else,'' she says. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
