<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-RED-SOX-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS TOP RED SOX BEHIND ZIMMERMAN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Right-hander Jeff Zimmerman stepped on the
mound ready to rumble.
</P>
<P>
   The bell rang, and Zimmerman scored a first-pitch knockout
during last night's most significant at-bat of the Rangers' 9-2
victory against the Boston Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   All-Star shortstop Nomar Garciaparra, who produced three hits
during his previous three plate appearances, stepped into the
batter's box for his seventh-inning at-bat with runners at the
corners and the Red Sox prepared to whittle into the Rangers' 4-2
advantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I had Zimmerman on the mound,'' Rangers manager Johnny
Oates said of the matchup that pitted All-Star vs. All-Star.
</P>
<P>
   Zimmerman expected that Garciaparra _ who entered the contest
hitting an American League-best .359 _ would be anticipating a
first-pitch slider. So, Zimmerman jammed him with a first-pitch
fastball, and that produced a mere-mortal popup that second baseman
Mark McLemore corralled for the inning's second out.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers escaped the inning with their 4-1 lead intact after
Zimmerman induced an inning-ending fly ball from left fielder Troy
O'Leary, and the booming bats of designated hitter Rafael Palmeiro
and left fielder Rusty Greer turned the affair into a blowout with
their seventh- and eighth-inning home runs.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers moved 24 games above .500 for the first time since
1997 when Rangers finished 26 games above .500 with a 94-68 record.
</P>
<P>
   Right-hander Rick Helling (10-7) pitched six effective innings
for the Rangers, but Oates went to the league's most reliable
bullpen at the first sign of trouble. Red Sox right fielder Trot
Nixon drew a leadoff walk to open the seventh inning, and Oates
wasted no time summoning for right-hander Tim Crabtree to preserve
the Rangers' 4-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Red Sox second baseman Jose Offerman and center fielder Darren
Lewis greeted Crabtree with consecutive singles, and Oates again
went to the well that seemingly never runs dry.
</P>
<P>
   Left-hander Mike Venafro entered with the left-handed-hitting
Brian Daubach scheduled to bat, but Red Sox manager Jimy Williams
countered with right-handed-hitting Mike Stanley. Nixon scored on
Stanley's medium-deep fly ball to left field, and Offerman advanced
to third base.
</P>
<P>
   ``Venafro got a big out on Stanley,'' Oates said.
</P>
<P>
   Oates then called upon Zimmerman to complete the job, and the
Rangers bombarded the Red Sox with their late-inning home runs.
Palmeiro, who drove in the Rangers' third run with a third-inning,
solo home run, gave the Rangers' a 7-2 lead with his three-run home
run during the bottom half of the seventh inning off left-hander
Rheal Cormier.
</P>
<P>
   Palmeiro became the major leagues' 54th player to hit 350 or
more home runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had no idea,'' said Palmeiro, who has 11 home runs during
August and six during the past six games. ``I knew I was getting
close, but with the excitement of the game, I kind of lost track.
It's always nice to do something like that at home, though. I
thought it came in a pretty key situation, and that made it
better.''
</P>
<P>
   Greer, who also produced a two-home run game, applied the
finishing touches with his two-run, eighth-inning home run off
right-hander Bryce Florie.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got a well-pitched game to begin with, and I think Raffy
had the big hit in the game with his three-run homer,'' Greer said.
``He's been doing it for us all year long. You can't say enough
about what Rafael has done for club.''
</P>
<P>
   Again, it was the bullpen that allowed the Rangers' bats to make
a difference. The Rangers improved to 53-5 this season when leading
after six innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time they go out there, the results are great,'' Helling
said. ``It's kind of a double-edged sword for me because I want to
go out there and stay in the entire game. Yet, Johnny wants them
out there with the way they're going.''
</P>
<P>
   Who can blame him?
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
