<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ERSTAD READY TO COME OFF DL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ANDREW BAGGARLY  
 San Bernardino County Sun  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ The Anaheim Angels expect Darin Erstad to be
ready when the first baseman/outfielder is eligible to be activated
from the disabled list Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Erstad was placed on the 15-day DL after twisting his right knee
while swinging during the Angels' game against Cleveland on Aug.11.
He was diagnosed with a strained medial collateral ligament.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's feeling fine,'' Erstad said. ``I don't know all the
technical terms for all the treatments I've done, but I know it
feels good.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the two-week layoff will help to recharge Erstad's
psyche as well. He still has no explanation for his dismal season,
in which he has batted .246 with 10 homers and 37 RBI.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been abused (by opposing pitchers) and I haven't made the
right adjustments,'' Erstad said. ``It's not for a lack of effort
or work. It's just been a season-long learning experience about the
mental side of baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   Erstad was the one player the Angels didn't expect to have an
off-year. He was the first overall selection in 1995, he hadn't
batted lower than .284 in his previous three seasons, and his power
and RBI numbers had increased each year. Greatness was forecast for
him.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike last year, when hamstring pulls dogged him, Erstad had
been injury-free until twisting his knee against the Indians.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just never got going,'' Erstad said. ``I never got a good
rhythm and never got comfortable at the plate. I've never been
through something like this before. It's a humbling experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I can do now is finish the season strong and try to leave
a good taste in my mouth for next year.''
</P>
<P>
   Numbers don't lie: How sorry has the Angels' offense been this
season?
</P>
<P>
   It ranked last in the majors with 505 runs entering Saturday's
game. Even Montreal and Florida, bad teams that don't have the
benefit of the designated hitter, had scored more runs than the
Angels.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels are on pace to finish the season with 676 runs, which
would be the fewest by the franchise since the 1992 team scored
579.
</P>
<P>
   That '92 team, by the way, featured Hubie Brooks and Von Hayes
as its 3-4 hitters, and posted a 72-90 record.
</P>
<P>
   Aesthetic change: Very soon, Edison Field will be a completely
natural-grass stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels ripped out the lime-green AstroTurf adjacent to the
rock fountain in center field and painted the area to match the
stadium's dark-green seats and walls. A smaller AstroTurf area on
the other side of the fountain will be similarly renovated in the
offseason.
</P>
<P>
   The turf was getting damaged by sun, water from the fountain and
falling residue from fireworks, said Kevin Uhlich, vice president
of ballpark operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to wait until the season was over, but it really had
to be done,'' Ulich said.
</P>
<P>
   The change also improves the batter's eye _ and makes the
outfield area look less like an oversize putt-putt course.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
