</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-PATRIOTS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS FAIL TO STOP BIG PLAYS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RAY BUCK 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBORO, Mass. _ Big plays given up by the Cowboys' defense in a
34-14 loss to the New England Patriots last night at Foxboro
Stadium even overshadowed the fact that Dallas has not won a
preseason game with Chan Gailey as the team's head coach.
</P>
<P>
   At a time when there is less emphasis on winning than on
evaluation, Gailey's 0-8 preseason record as Cowboys coach becomes
a minor irritant.
</P>
<P>
   The same isn't true about a Cowboys defense that gave up several
big plays, including 24- and 36-yard touchdown passes and a 21-yard
pass that set up New England's first TD. Dallas is now 0-3; New
England, 1-1.
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys quarterback Troy Aikman played one quarter, completing a
preseason-low four of 12 passes for 33 yards. He had his first
touchdown pass, but he also threw behind rookie wide receiver Wane
McGarity on an interception.
</P>
<P>
   In three games, Aikman has completed 62.2 percent of his passes
(23 of 37) for 222 yards, one TD and two interceptions. He has yet
to be sacked this preseason, although rookie linebacker Andy
Katzenmoyer leveled him once just as he released the ball.
</P>
<P>
   With Arizona quarterback Jake Plummer being forced to leave the
Cardinals' 27-17 victory against Tennessee Friday night with a
hyperextended thumb on his throwing hand, there is something to be
said for just getting through one of these preseason games ``sans''
injury to your starting quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   Two areas on offense for the Cowboys that screamed for
improvement coming into this game were red-zone scoring and
third-down efficiency (8-for-26).
</P>
<P>
   ``We executed better in the red zone,'' said Gailey, ``but we
had some difficulties in some third-down situations.''
</P>
<P>
   After going through the first two preseason games against
Cleveland and Oakland without getting as much as even a glimpse of
the end zone, the Cowboys' first-team offense moved downfield
rather methodically to score a touchdown on its second possession.
</P>
<P>
   After a short-field TD drive by New England, the Cowboys went 57
yards in nine plays with Aikman hitting a wide-open David LaFleur
for a 6-yard touchdown. LaFleur, coming off the injury list (ankle)
and playing in his first game since January's playoff loss to
Arizona, beat strong safety Lawyer Milloy.
</P>
<P>
   On the drive, Emmitt Smith popped loose for a 21-yard gain
behind Erik Williams, plus a downfield screen thrown by Michael
Irvin. It was the Cowboys' longest run from scrimmage of the
preseason.
</P>
<P>
   Before that carry, the NFL's leading active rusher had carried
the ball six times for 10 yards this preseason. Last night, he had
eight rushes for 43 yards, including a nifty 10-yard pickup on a
direct snap, as Gailey opened the Cowboys playbook a little wider.
</P>
<P>
   ``Offensively, we put some new things in for this game,'' Gailey
said. ``Some of those things worked well, others did not.''
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback Drew Bledsoe and the Patriots' first-team offense
were able to give their water-soaked local fans something to cheer
about early, compliments of two first-quarter touchdowns after Toby
Gowin punts that were knocked down by the wind and rain.
</P>
<P>
   First, Gowin's 27-yard punt was returned 27 yards by Troy Brown,
then Gowin's 37-yard punt was returned 22 yards by Brown, who was
flipped in the air on a open-field tackle by the Cowboys punter.
This wasn't a good night for the Cowboys' punt-coverage team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our punt-coverage put us in a few tough spots ... and we gave
up a few big plays on defense,'' said Gailey. ``Those are things
that can be corrected.''
</P>
<P>
   Gowin's punt for a net zero yards led to a five-play, 45-yard TD
drive by the Patriots; the 15-yard net punt led to a two-play,
37-yard TD drive. Both touchdowns came against the Cowboys'
first-team defense.
</P>
<P>
   The most-abused Cowboys player along the way: left cornerback
Kevin Mathis, twice beaten deep by Patriots wide receiver Terry
Glenn.
</P>
<P>
   ``With their starting corners out,'' said Bledsoe, referring to
the injured Deion Sanders \Rtoe\S and Kevin Smith \Rbulging disk\S,
``we felt that we could exploit that, and throw a few deep balls.''
</P>
<P>
   Except that Mathis is an incumbent starter after beating out
Smith for a starting job last season.
</P>
<P>
   First, Glenn fought off Mathis' bump-and-run at the line of
scrimmage and gathered in a 21-yard toss from Bledsoe, leading to a
2-yard TD run by Kevin Faulk, a 5-foot-8, 197-pound rookie who
scored by slipping away from Dexter Coakley and carrying Randall
Godfrey into the end zone.
</P>
<P>
   Less than nine minutes later, Glenn beat Mathis deep on a
straight-go in the first quarter. This time there was no
bump-and-run by Mathis. This time it went for a 24-yard TD pass.
With 2:49 still left in the first quarter, the Pats led, 14-7.
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe and New England extended their led to 21-7 when tight
end Ben Coates beat Cowboys safety Omar Stoutmire badly with 3:59
left in the first half for a 6-yard touchdown reception.
</P>
<P>
   After playing poorly the week before at Oakland, Cowboys
quarterback Mike Quinn, in his quest to win the No. 3 job,
immediately hooked up with a wide-open Jason Tucker of TCU for a
55-yard touchdown pass play. It came on Quinn's first attempt of
the game.
</P>
<P>
   Quinn read the corner blitz, which left Tucker uncovered, as
safety help was nowhere to be found.
</P>
<P>
   In the second half, New England put together 12- and nine-play
field goal drives in the second half before rookie quarterback
Michael Bishop _ a seventh-round pick despite being the 1998
Heisman Trophy runner-up _ launched a desperation TD pass to rookie
Sean Morey that covered 36 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Singor Mobley was beaten on the play.
</P>
<P>
   Last week against Washington, Bishop threw two TD passes and
nearly had a third one as time expired.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is fun to watch,'' Patriots coach Pete Carroll said.
``Granted, he's doing this in the fourth quarter against backup
players ... but they're not getting even close to him.''
</P>
<P>
   Evaluation vs. winning. For whatever it's worth, the Cowboys'
last preseason victory came against Tennessee in August 1997.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
