<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-LAFLEUR-TEX </SLUG>
 
LaFLEUR COULD HOLD THE KEY 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBORO, Mass. _ Much has been made of the Cowboys' off-season
addition of wide receiver Raghib Ismail.
</P>
<P>
   And there is no discounting what his speed will bring to the
Cowboys' offense.
</P>
<P>
   But talk to any member of the Cowboys' coaching staff or front
office and they'll say that the return tight end David LaFleur is
just as important if not more so to any Cowboys offensive success
this season.
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys scouting director Larry Lacewell says the 6-foot-7,
280-pounder is crucial to the Cowboys' running game and inside
passing game and cites the loss of an injured LaFleur for the final
three games of 1998 as a big reason for the late-season decline of
the Cowboys' offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's doubly important to what we do,'' Lacewell said. ``He's a
standout blocker and he gives Aikman such a big target, especially
on inside of the field and in the red zone. You double the guys on
the outside, but its tough to single cover him on the inside
because of his size.''
</P>
<P>
   But what had been clear up until last night's 34-14 loss to the
Patriots is that, like Ismail, LaFleur had yet to contribute
anything in preseason.
</P>
<P>
   Both sat out the Cowboys' first two exhibition games _ Ismail
with a sprained shoulder and LaFleur because of off-season ankle
and back surgery.
</P>
<P>
   While Ismail remained on the sideline, LaFleur trotted out on
the field with the first-team offense against the Patriots, making
his presence felt immediately.
</P>
<P>
   The former LSU star caught two passes for 10 yards, including a
6-yard touchdown pass. It was also no coincidence that running back
Emmitt Smith had his best outing of the preseason, rushing eight
times for 43 yards, including a 21-yard burst.
</P>
<P>
   LaFleur's day was not without mistakes, as rustiness from the
layoff showed on a dropped pass and a false start.
</P>
<P>
   The third-year veteran, who returned to the practice field for
the first time in training camp last week, said he was just happy
to be out there. LaFleur played between 12-15 snaps in the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It felt good to be out there,'' LaFleur said. ``I wanted to
get in and get a few snaps and get back into the flow of the game.
I was a little rusty, but I liked being in the huddle.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys didn't waste any time helping him do that, as
quarterback Troy Aikman called his number on the second play of the
game, resulting in a 4-yard reception.
</P>
<P>
   The next series started off badly, as LaFleur dropped a pass
while being covered tightly by Patriots linebacker Andy
Katzenmoyer.
</P>
<P>
   However, it ended when Aikman found him in the end zone after
beating Patriots safety Lawyer Milloy on a out route.
</P>
<P>
   While LaFleur said he didn't make all the plays, he said he was
pleased that the Cowboys seemed to be trying to get him involved _
a trend he hopes continues throughout the season after catching
just 20 passes in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``Troy definitely seemed to be looking my way,'' LaFleur said.
``It felt good on my first game back to be worked in the offense
and be called on in that situation. I might get a few more looks
this season.''
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys coach Chan Gailey, who said he was excited to see
LaFleur back in uniform, can't wait to get him more time on the
practice field.
</P>
<P>
   ``A couple of times, it looked liked the ball got on top of him
in a hurry,'' Gailey said. ``So there's some rustiness still coming
through. He wasn't expecting the ball. That's why it was important
to get him back into the fray. Hopefully he'll progress even more
the next two weeks.'']
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
