<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-LEBRETON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOY, WE GOT WRONG NUMBERS ON PALMEIRO
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LEBRETON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ We were so wrong about Rafael Palmeiro, it's
embarrassing.
</P>
<P>
   We were wrong about his hitting. We were wrong about what he
means to a team's lineup. We were wrong about what he means to a
clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   We were dead wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Some of us _ including yours truly, I must wincingly confess _
were even convinced that that chilly November afternoon in 1993,
when Will Clark became a Ranger and replaced Palmeiro at first
base, was a red-letter day for the franchise.
</P>
<P>
   Wince.
</P>
<P>
   But I don't come here today, friends and Romans, to bury Will
Clark. In a way, he did that himself yesterday, shutting down his
1999 season to have surgery on his left elbow.
</P>
<P>
   Clark finishes this season for the Baltimore Orioles with a .303
batting average in 251 at-bats. He had 10 home runs and 29 runs
batted in.
</P>
<P>
   Wince.
</P>
<P>
   Palmeiro, on the other hand, in the month of August alone, has
11 home runs and 27 runs batted in. His second home run last night
was the 350th of his career and pushed him to 36 for the season
with 115 RBI.
</P>
<P>
   They are linked steadfastly, rightly or wrongly, Clark and
Palmeiro. Their baseball careers yoked in the '80s, when they were
fair-cheeked teammates at Mississippi State. On the 1993 day that
Clark signed here as a free agent _ while Palmeiro's agent was
still playing money games, the club said _ Raffy felt betrayed and
angered.
</P>
<P>
   Just wait, he said that day, to every TV minicam that came to
his Colleyville home's door. You'll see.
</P>
<P>
   Simply comparing numbers, the rout was on. Though he is only six
months older than Palmeiro, Clark's body began a fickle decline. In
the five years that he was away, Palmeiro played in 127 more games
than Clark _ nearly a full season. He batted 623 more times.
</P>
<P>
   In numbers that rang the loudest, and never failed to produce a
snarl from Clark when they were mentioned, Palmeiro outhomered him
182 to 77 and had 156 more RBI.
</P>
<P>
   The statistics speak for themselves. Yet, in fairness, Clark
came to the Rangers because he was deemed a winner who would bring
a fiery temperament to what had become a languid clubhouse. And in
that regard, Clark delivered.
</P>
<P>
   With him at first base, the Rangers won their first division
title and finished atop the division three of the five years. He
brought a _ how shall I put this? _ shrill intensity to the
franchise. The injury that apparently still shackles him, bone
chips from a broken elbow, came about on a play when Clark was
playing like, well, Will Clark _ charging after a foul ball.
</P>
<P>
   A free-agent signing that failed? No. Not at all.
</P>
<P>
   But that doesn't mean we weren't wrong.
</P>
<P>
   We were wrong about the other half of the 1993 shuffle.
Palmeiro's textbook swing didn't unravel as he grew older and
slower, as some predicted. It prospered, as Palmeiro adapted in
Camden Yards to become a feared home run hitter.
</P>
<P>
   He now stands, at age 34, on the threshhold of a notable rush at
some hitting milestones. If Palmeiro has four more seasons anything
like his past seven seasons, he will eclipse 500 home runs, have
nearly 1,700 RBI and be within 200 hits of 3,000.
</P>
<P>
   Those are Hall of Fame numbers.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's right there,'' said Rangers coach Bucky Dent. ``He
performs, day in and day out. He has the hits. The power. Doubles.
Home runs. The RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he stays healthy and plays for the right number of years,
it's very possible.''
</P>
<P>
   The one thing, of course, that could stamp Palmeiro's ticket for
Cooperstown would be a World Series. And who's to say now, with
Palmeiro anchoring the Rangers lineup, that that isn't possible?
</P>
<P>
   Some guys are vocal team leaders. Palmeiro leads by quiet
example. He has commanded respect, especially among the team's
young players.
</P>
<P>
   His ``voice'' comes on the scoreboard. Before last night, with
runners on base this season, Palmeiro was hitting .383. With two
outs and men in scoring position, his average is .327. He has a
team-high 17 game-winning RBI, tying the club record.
</P>
<P>
   Dent points to his old Yankees teams, who had players such as
Chris Chambliss and Willie Randolph, as examples of winning teams
that also didn't need a booming clubhouse voice.
</P>
<P>
   ``A rah-rah guy?'' Dent said. ``No. You don't always need that.
With Rafael, there's a quiet intensity.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the way I like to do,'' Palmeiro said last night.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly six years ago, when he left for Baltimore, we called him
a whiner. We said he was just after the money. On his first trip
back into town, some Rangers fans even booed Rafael Palmeiro.
</P>
<P>
   They were wrong, of course. We all were wrong.
</P>
<P>
   How symbolic, we thought yesterday, that on the same day when
the previous first baseman announced his injury-riddled season was
over, Rafael Palmeiro showed why he is this season's most valuable
Ranger of all.
</P>
<P>
   How grand of him to return home. On his way to Cooperstown.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
