<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANCER-ATHLETES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRIVE TO SURVIVE: ATHLETES STRICKEN WITH CANCER OFFER LESSONS IN
COURAGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STACY FEDUCIA 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ In December 1993, professional golfer Paul
Azinger learned he had lymphoma _ cancer _ in his right shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   Azinger returned to the PGA Tour the next season. An estimated
11,500 men died from the disease in the United States that year.
</P>
<P>
   Professional cyclist Lance Armstrong found out he had testicular
cancer in October 1996. Armstrong crowned his comeback to cycling
with a victory in the 1999 Tour de France _ the second by an
American and first by a cancer survivor. But about 370 men in the
United States with testicular cancer died in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   In February, doctors told guard Kim Perrot of the WNBA's Houston
Comets that she had lung cancer. She was one of an estimated
171,600 Americans who will receive a diagnosis of lung cancer this
year.
</P>
<P>
   She died Thursday. She was 32.
</P>
<P>
   In the arenas of sport, they are lauded for being athletes, but
in the cancer wards of hospitals, they are treated for being human.
</P>
<P>
   They are, in fact, statistics _ just a fraction of the estimated
12 million cases of cancer discovered in the United States] since
1990. No research indicates that they are any more or less likely
to be stricken with cancer than the rest of us, but by virtue of
their public lives, their private struggles become national news.
</P>
<P>
   New York Giants running back LeShon Johnson. Florida Marlins
third baseman Mike Lowell. Canadian rower Emma Robinson. Former
Pittsburgh Penguins center Mario Lemieux. St. Louis Cardinals
outfielder Eric Davis. Cowboys quarterback Troy Aikman, whose
cancerous mole on his left shoulder was removed in the earliest
stage of malignancy in May 1998. Azinger. Armstrong. Perrot.
</P>
<P>
   Cancer does not discriminate.
</P>
<P>
   Being an athlete doesn't change that, but in some ways, it does
change how athletes react to their conditions and how they handle
cancer's aftermath. Many attack the disease as though they would an
athletic competition and, as victor or vanquished, offer lessons in
courage. Some, as Armstrong, become public spokesmen, pouring
thousands of dollars into research and awareness efforts, while
others, like Azinger, offer encouragement from a private phone call
or card. Still others, like Robinson, shun the role-model label
altogether.
</P>
<P>
   ``These stories are important because the public can't believe
that someone so fit and so dedicated to a sport can be stricken
just like anyone else in the population,'' explained Dr. Jeff
Murray, a pediatric oncologist at Cook Children's Medical Center
who has raced with Armstrong. Athletes ``are not gods. They're not
infallible. Bad things can happen to them just like they can happen
to me. I think that somehow personalizes it more for the population
and reminds them how fragile life is for everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Their stories are as different as the renegade cells that attack
from within, but the greatest unifying impact of their stories is
hope. TOP PROSPECT New York Yankees outfielder Darryl Strawberry.
St. Louis Cardinals outfielder Eric Davis. Los Angeles Dodgers
outfielder Brett Butler. Atlanta Braves first baseman Andres
Galarraga. Philadelphia Phillies first baseman John Kruk.
</P>
<P>
   Lowell, a 25-year-old rookie third baseman, entered spring
training this season with the Florida Marlins in hopes of joining
those major-league luminaries but found himself inextricably linked
with them after a preseason physical uncovered testicular cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Except perhaps for behavioral risks, such as chewing tobacco or
extended exposure to the sun, no studies indicate that baseball
players are at a greater risk for cancer than the general
population. But Strawberry, Davis, Butler, Galarraga, Kruk and,
most recently, Lowell have brought colon cancer, cancer of the
mouth, lymphoma and testicular cancer onto the field of play.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be honest, I think it's found more often in athletes
because we're tested more often. We have to take physicals every
year,'' said Lowell. ``I think it just proves we're as human as
everyone else.''
</P>
<P>
   What Lowell has that everyone else might not have is the
discipline, determination and drive that come from years of
athletic training _ something he believes helped him through
recovery and brought him back to the ballpark before the All-Star
Game last month.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have this inner motivation and self-discipline,'' Lowell
explained. ``I thought my major-league career was on hold, if not
stopped, but then I just viewed it as another thing I had to
overcome. A lot of people never said I'd make it to the big
leagues. This is another thing that I have to prove them wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Lowell, after Friday's game, was batting .252 with 29 runs
batted in and seven home runs with the Marlins _ not quite where he
would like to be, but good considering the circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   Lowell went directly from surgery and radiation treatments into
the baseball season. Lowell looks forward to the off-season, when
he will have time to return to peak physical condition
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the pro athlete has a little advantage over others
because of the lifestyle habits they have in place before they get
cancer,'' Murray explained. ``Dedication, perseverance, the will to
win whatever the race is _ the physical, psychological and
emotional habits are as good as they can be going into cancer, and
I think those habits do make a difference to some degree.''
RELUCTANT ROLE MODEL After doctors diagnosed his testicular cancer
in 1996, Armstrong formed a foundation to promote education and
research, and embraced the role as a cancer spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't so effective when I was in the hospital because I was
in bad shape,'' Armstrong recalled. ``But when I would return for
my checkups, I always asked the doctors, `Do you have any testes
patients here? Anybody I need to go see?' That was new for them.
They'd never had anybody say that. You never know what you're
walking into. It's an illness that's uncomfortable at times, but as
a patient and a survivor, it's easier for me to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Though athletes like Armstrong take a public role in educating
people about their disease, others prefer to maintain their privacy
as though they were private citizens.
</P>
<P>
   Canadian rower Emma Robinson chose to announce publicly in
February that she had thyroid cancer and would have surgery to
remove it. She hoped that being open about cancer would put her
teammates and competitors at ease and would help her control how
that information was received. What she could not control was the
media blitz that followed when Robinson and her partner Theresa
Luke won the gold medal in the coxless pairs last month at the Pan
American Games.
</P>
<P>
   Canadian newspapers trumpeted her ``amazing comeback'' which was
``paved with gold.''
</P>
<P>
   The second-year medical student had approached her disease with
the same focus that she had developed from lonely days rowing on
open water.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm used to thinking about how to control my emotions and feel
calm and not be distracted by outside things,'' Robinson said. ``I
think that helped me with the diagnosis because I was able to stay
focused on training despite all the distractions and the attention
from the media.''
</P>
<P>
   Removed from the ``amazing comeback'' headlines, Robinson is
preparing to defend her world championship this month in Ontario.
She would prefer to mount her defense as the 1998 world champion,
not as a gold medal-winning cancer patient.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be positive if someone gets checked out because of
this, but I don't see myself as a role model or champion,''
Robinson said. ``Right now, people know me because of cancer. The
next time my name comes up, I want it to be because of my rowing
achievements.'' CANCER CHAMPIONS Given a diagnosis of cancer in
1993, just months after winning his first major championship, Paul
Azinger recently passed the five-year mark of being cancer free
since the completion of chemotherapy in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   The 1993 PGA Championship was his third victory of that season
and his most recent Tour victory. Unlike Robinson or Davis, Azinger
wants people to know about his success against the disease, but his
platform has shrunk.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to be a source of hope and inspiration for people that
are fighting the disease,'' Azinger said. ``I would like to play
better to be more in the spotlight. It's been so long since I've
done well that I'm sure there are people battling cancer who watch
golf that don't know what I've been through.''
</P>
<P>
   Azinger became a cycling fan this summer, when Armstrong
accomplished his historic feat, and Azinger knows intimately what
Armstrong's achievement meant to lesser-known persons who are
battling cancer today.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was an inspiration to me and everyone else out there who
can't see the light at the end of the tunnel,'' Azinger said.
``When you're in the middle of six months of chemotherapy, or a
year of chemotherapy, it seems like a lifetime. To be two
treatments or three treatments into it, it's so bad, you don't see
any end in sight. Then, to see a guy like that doing what he's
doing and beating all odds, that's a total inspiration.''
</P>
<P>
   His story has made history: Lance Armstrong, the American cancer
patient who was dumped by an elite French cycling team in the wake
of his diagnosis, joined the American U.S. Postal Service Cycling
Team and rode to victory in the most prestigious event in his
sport.
</P>
<P>
   But Armstrong is not naive about the crush of popularity he has
enjoyed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a story,'' Armstrong said. ``Here's the kid that was good
before, and he got sick, and everybody dropped him and said he
couldn't come back. Sports fans love comebacks. I think this
brought in a lot of people that watched football or basketball or
baseball because of the story.''
</P>
<P>
   The victory parade that greeted Armstrong in Austin two weeks
ago, the appearances on ``The Late Show with David Letterman'' and
``Good Morning America'', the Nike commercial, the official White
House visit _ it is a great story, but one that is rarely told.
</P>
<P>
   More than 12 million Americans have died from cancer since 1990.
For every Lance Armstrong, there is a Kim Perrot.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong was given a 50 percent chance of survival when his
cancer was discovered to have spread to his lungs and brain. His
doctors predict only a 2 percent chance of recurrence for
Armstrong, and even by their accounts his recovery has been
miraculous.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a terrible illness,'' said Armstrong, who befriended a
young Austin cancer patient who died from the disease last year.
``My story is one of success, and hopefully continued success, but
they're not all like that, and we have to be realistic.''
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 7,400 new cases of testicular cancer will be
diagnosed this year, and an estimated 300 men will die from the
disease in the United States this year. Though he has given hope to
people like Kelli Davidson, a young cancer patient at Cook
Children's Medical Center, has Armstrong set the bar too high?
</P>
<P>
   For that matter, have Lowell's strong return and Robinson's
gold-medal comeback reinforced the idea that athletes with cancer
are somehow more-than-human?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's one of the potential downsides to all the
goodness that's come out of Lance's comeback,'' said Murray, who
treated Davidson to daily videotapes of Armstrong's journey through
France. ``It can give the general public a false sense and give the
cancer community too much optimism. What everyone has to remember
is that cancer is very different from person to person.
</P>
<P>
   ``To think what Lance has done is going to make people cured is
false thinking. Will it make the lives of people with cancer
better? Absolutely, because it gives them hope, maybe not of living
longer, but for having a special victory in their life and giving
them the perseverance to go on.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
