<HEADLINE>
ARMSTRONG IS WORLD-CLASS IN CYCLING AND THE CANCER COMMUNITY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By Jeffrey C. Murray 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jeffrey C. Murray, M.D., is the associate medical director of
Hematology &AMP; Oncology Center at Cook Children's Medical Center in
Fort Worth and a competitive cyclist. He gives his views on what
Lance Armstrong has accomplished.
</P>
<P>
   The athletic and medical triumph of professional cyclist and
testicular-cancer survivor Lance Armstrong in winning the grueling,
23-day Tour de France is an achievement unparalleled in
professional sport and medical oncology.
</P>
<P>
   In October 1996, at 25, the near-peak performance age of a
professional cyclist, Lance was diagnosed with testicular cancer,
which spread to his brain, lungs and abdomen.
</P>
<P>
   The 1993 world professional road race champion was suddenly
confronted with a race whose prize was life, rather than a colorful
cycling jersey. After several surgeries, intense chemotherapy and
intense perseverance, he was rendered free of cancer in 1997. His
turbulent, but ultimately successful, return to professional racing
represents an intensely emotional triumph of modern oncology,
competitive endurance athletics and the human spirit.
</P>
<P>
   As a pediatric oncologist at Cook Children's Medical Center and
a competitive Texas cyclist for 10 years, I have a unique insight
into some of the factors that may have led to this incredible
comeback.
</P>
<P>
   Just to be competitive, cyclists must adopt a complete lifestyle
of sacrifice and intelligent and intense training.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong has mastered these traits. He didn't win the Tour de
France because of luck, happenstance or some ill-defined genetic
talent, but because of his ability to intensify his athletic
lifestyle traits. In fact, Armstrong's victory over cancer and his
rise to the pinnacle of cycling are inseparably, and marvelously,
intertwined.
</P>
<P>
   Cycling helped him win his battle with cancer, and cancer helped
him win the Tour de France.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong had more than modern medical care on his side in his
fight with cancer; he had the personal traits he has used for all
of his athletic life. The human spirit and the will to live are
poorly understood but thought to play at least some positive role
in the care of the cancer victim.
</P>
<P>
   As an oncologist who cares for young people, I see many of the
same traits in adolescents and young adults fighting cancer that
professional cyclists and other star athletes have: persistence,
willingness to sacrifice certain life pleasures and the ability to
endure discomfort.
</P>
<P>
   And his comeback from testicular cancer to win the Tour de
France will leave more of an enduring legacy for the cacer
community than it will for cycling and sport in general. Perhaps
this will be Lance's biggest victory.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong created a foundation in 1997 to help others who must
walk (or cycle) down the same cancer path as he has. The Lance
Armstrong Foundation has become a premier organization in the quest
to promote public and medical profession cancer awareness and
education, testicular-cancer research and the mission of ``cancer
survivorship.''
</P>
<P>
   A special focus for Armstrong and the foundation is improving
life after cancer treatment. Persons fortunate enough to survive
the cancer experience are often faced with very important medical
and psychological issues. My colleagues and I at the Hematology &AMP;
Oncology Center at Cook Children's Medical Center are working in
partnership with the foundation to create a unique cancer
survivorship clinic focused on after-therapy care.
</P>
<P>
   That clinic will be one more victory for Armstrong, a
world-class champion of cycling and the cancer world. / nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
