<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-TIGERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEAVER LIFTS TIGERS OVER ANGELS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ANDREW BAGGARLY  
 San Bernardino County Sun  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ The Detroit Tigers are 27 games out of first
place. They have the worst record in the American League. But Jeff
Weaver was feeling pennant-race sized prickles on his arms Saturday
night.
</P>
<P>
   With more than 100 friends and family members in attendance, the
Simi Valley High graduate tossed seven shutout innings and won for
the first time since May 27 as the Tigers beat the Anaheim Angels
5-0 at Edison Field.
</P>
<P>
   Combined, the Tigers and Angels are 49 games out of first place.
At this point they aren't even playing for pride so as much as
trying to salvage what little they have remaining.
</P>
<P>
   Weaver didn't have to search far for his incentive. With his
parents in attendance for the first time since his major-league
debut April 14, the 1998 No. 1 draft choice allowed three hits and
struck out a career-high seven to snap a 13-start winless streak.
</P>
<P>
   Weaver (7-9) began the season by winning six of his first nine
starts, but then he hit the skids. He lost six consecutive
decisions during his drought and watched his ERA over that span
bloom to 7.39.
</P>
<P>
   But against the worst offense in the majors, Weaver looked
unhittable. He allowed just three singles, walked two and hit a
batter. Only one Angel, Orlando Palmeiro, got as far as second
base.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels were shut out for the 10th time this season. Only the
Tigers (11) have been blanked more times.
</P>
<P>
   Angels starter Jarrod Washburn failed to match Weaver,
surrendering a run in the third inning and losing his composure in
the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   Gabe Kapler (Taft High/Moorpark College) led off with a single,
was sacrificed to second, moved to third on a deep fly ball and
scored when a high Washburn pitcher went off the tip of catcher
Matt Walbeck's glove for a wild pitch.
</P>
<P>
   Washburn's second start of the season turned into a meltdown in
the fourth. He gave up two singles and a double, then issued
four-pitch walks to Damion Easley and Bill Haselman _ all before
recording an out.
</P>
<P>
   The second of those walks forced home the Tigers' third run and
drove Washburn (0-2) from the game.
</P>
<P>
   Reliever Al Levine turned in a heroic effort to get out of the
jam, inducing a pop-up from Kapler, striking out Kimera Bartee and
getting Gregg Jefferies to fly out to end the inning and strand all
three inherited runners.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels like the fact that Washburn is young, left-handed and
can throw three pitches _ fastball, curve, changeup. But he hasn't
escaped the fourth inning in either of his two starts this year,
and his ERA has risen to 8.56.
</P>
<P>
   The game was a nightmare for normally sure-handed Angels
shortstop Gary DiSarcina, who committed a career-high three errors.
He bounced a throw in the first inning and committed a pair of
gaffes in the eighth: throwing wide to the bag on a Juan
Encarnacion grounder and taking a potential double-play ball off
his chest, loading the bases with nobody out.
</P>
<P>
   DiSarcina had committed nine errors in his first 51 games this
season and made 14 errors all of last year. The three errors were
the most by an Angel since shortstop Spike Owen committed three
against Texas on Aug. 5, 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Huson pinch-hit for DiSarcina leading off the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Edmonds provided a few highlight splices in the field.
Proving again that his defensive instincts are as sharp as ever, he
sprinted to make an over-the-shoulder catch of a deep Jefferies fly
ball in the third.
</P>
<P>
   Edmonds struck again in the fifth when Dean Palmer hit what
looked to be a sure double off the center-field wall. Edmonds
played the carom perfectly, caught it bare-handed and made a strong
throw to DiSarcina covering second base. Palmer, expecting to coast
into second base, was startled when DiSarcina received the throw
and tagged him out.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
