<SLUG> BC-SOC-GALAXY-METROSTARS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO LETDOWN FOR GALAXY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM BARRERO  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ Letdowns are a part of any sport and it would
have been easy for the Los Angeles Galaxy to suffer one Saturday
night.
</P>
<P>
   With the hapless New York/New Jersey Metrostars in town and the
end of a grueling stretch of games in sight, the tendency to relax
seemed to be one of prime concern.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the Galaxy of old _ the one from the first games of the
season _ might have let it happen, but this group wouldn't have any
part of such notions, dominating the MetroStars 4-1 in front of
12,045 at the Rose Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know they've been having a down streak, so sometimes it's
hard to get motivated for a team like that,'' said Zak Ibsen, who
scored his second and third goals of the season. ``But we came out
with the intensity in the first 10 minutes trying to get a couple
of goals.''
</P>
<P>
   The victory was the 10th in 12 MLS games for the Galaxy, which
has moved within a regulation win (three points) of catching
Western Conference-leading Colorado. The conference leaders play
one another twice over the final nine regular-season games, the
first coming Sept. 18 in Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   The MetroStars, meanwhile, tied a league record for futility
with their ninth consecutive loss. They join New England, which has
set the mark twice.
</P>
<P>
   Any thoughts of L.A. overlooking N.Y./N.J. ended when the Galaxy
struck in the eighth minute. Greg Vanney curled a left-footed
corner kick into the middle of the box that forward Carlos
Hermosillo headed down and into the left corner for a 1-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Hermosillo, who missed the Galaxy's previous four MLS games
because of a lower-back strain, scored his second of the game in
the 59th minute. He now has six goals in seven matches.
</P>
<P>
   Nine minutes later, L.A. pushed the lead to 2-0 when Cobi Jones
chipped across the defense to an onrushing Ibsen on the right side.
Ibsen snuck behind defender Billy Walsh and met Jones' loft at the
perfect moment, sending a right-footed volley into the middle of
the net that gave Metrostars' goalkeeper Mike Ammann had no chance.
</P>
<P>
   Ibsen's second goal came in the 88th minute, and it was
extremely similar to his first. He took a cross from Vanney _ the
defender's third assist of the night _ and after a bounce fired
another blast past Ammann.
</P>
<P>
   Jones assisted on the second Hermosillo goal with some quality
work on the right flank before chipping to the middle, setting the
table for the Mexican striker.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly scoring two goals early made the game easier, but we
also talked about this game putting us within three points of first
place,'' Galaxy coach Sigi Schmid said. ``Plus, I told the guys
they get two days off if they won. I think maybe they wanted the
two days off more than the three points.''
</P>
<P>
   It could have been a lot worse for the MetroStars had the Galaxy
converted several other quality chances, including a header by Paul
Caligiuri that was tipped off the crossbar by Ammann and two shots
by Jones from in deep.
</P>
<P>
   The MetroStars did have good chances on semi-breakaways by Henry
Zambrano _ two in the first half and one in the second, which
displeased Schmid _ but the Colombian pushed two of them wide with
goalkeeper Kevin Hartman making a point-blank save on the other.
</P>
<P>
   N.Y./N.J. scored in the 72nd minute on a penalty kick by Mark
Chung after he was fouled in the box by Steve Jolley.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
