<SLUG> BC-FBC-USC-McCOWAN-LADN </SLUG>
 
AFTER PRISON, A NEW VIEW FOR McCOWAN 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ As Howard McCowan sits in his Public Policy and
Management 225 class, he listens to other USC students talk about
changing the world. From his experience, he knows life isn't how it
is portrayed in textbooks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to tell them, `It's not like that. This is bull,' ''
the 27-year-old McCowan said.
</P>
<P>
   He's past the point of dreams. He's not like his younger, more
idealistic classmates. Almost seven years of prison changes a
person.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do feel that I'm separate. That has something to do with my
experiences,'' McCowan said. ``I don't know if it will ever leave
me. That's just the way I feel.''
</P>
<P>
   After an eight-year absence, McCowan is a USC student again. He
savors every minute in a classroom. It's almost as precious as his
freedom.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you think of all the kids who come out of incarceration
and never approach the idea of going to college, let alone USC,
it's incredible,'' USC athletic director Mike Garrett said. ``He's
one in a million.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1990 McCowan was a part-time starter at free safety for the
Trojans and made 30 tackles as a redshirt freshman. He figured the
NFL would be a natural progression in his athletic career.
</P>
<P>
   But he never played pro football, or even finished playing at
USC.
</P>
<P>
   On April 23, 1991, McCowan went out with teammate Marcel Brown
and Brown's friend, Garlyn Coleman, to pick up a videotape at the
home of USC wide receiver Johnnie Morton in Torrance.
</P>
<P>
   They never made it to Morton's, instead driving to Westwood
where they went on a one-night robbery spree that led to McCowan
spending 6{ years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   McCowan, who said he never personally robbed any of the victims,
said it wasn't about the money. It just happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're a kid, you have a lot of energy. The night it took
place, it wasn't planned. It wasn't choreographed,'' McCowan said.
``My motivation wasn't to rob anybody or hurt anybody. It was
something physical and something extremely exciting. It was
criminal but it was physically exhilarating.''
</P>
<P>
   According to police reports, several victims were beaten up; one
had his nose broken when he was pushed facedown into the sidewalk,
and was briefly unconscious. Victims were robbed of their automatic
teller cards.
</P>
<P>
   One of the lead investigators was former LAPD Det. Mark Fuhrman,
who later became famous in the O.J. Simpson case.
</P>
<P>
   ``My anger came from a lot of different areas,'' McCowan said.
``There were things in my personal life I wasn't too happy about. I
would get into fights. I was destructive.''
</P>
<P>
   So why did he do it?
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything looked hunky-dory to someone on the outside. I was
19. I was at a major university,'' McCowan said. ``Frustration and
anger were my motivation.''
</P>
<P>
   With his football career over and a lengthy prison sentence
ahead, it would have been easy for McCowan to become just another
failure in the world of college sports, a lawbreaker who would
never amount to much.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't happen.
</P>
<P>
   McCowan is back at USC, earning a 3.5 grade-point average last
fall and a 3.25 in the spring semester. By next May, he hopes to
receive his diploma. His transcript will show he attended USC from
1989-2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't feel like I'm accomplishing any great feat,'' McCowan
said. ``I'm doing what I'm supposed to be doing. I think I'm
blessed. I had a few people who cared about my well-being.''
</P>
<P>
   McCowan credits his mother, Thelma, and former USC athletic
director Mike McGee as being instrumental in his rehabilitation.
</P>
<P>
   While he was serving his sentence at Wasco State Prison, about
130 miles north of Los Angeles, McCowan received a visit from McGee
_ the only visitor from USC that McCowan ever had.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was harsh,'' McGee said of his visit to Wasco. ``You go in
there and go through all of the steps to go inside the fence. Here
was Howard.''
</P>
<P>
   McGee made a promise to McCowan: If he could demonstrate he was
interested in academics and stay out of trouble, USC would honor
his athletic scholarship when he was released.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like we had failed Howard and that we needed to provide
him an opportunity,'' McGee said. ``Howard came to USC as a good
student and we did not keep an eye on things as close as we
should've.''
</P>
<P>
   It was not easy for McCowan. While still in prison he began
taking correspondence courses from UC Berkeley, although he had
never read a book in its entirety before being incarcerated. During
his first stint at USC, his grades were C's and D's.
</P>
<P>
   But his mother wanted him to stay clean and go back to school.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just loved (USC) for allowing my boy a second chance,''
Thelma McCowan said. ``I was willing to spend whatever I had on
him. I felt he made a mistake but he had never been in trouble
before.''
</P>
<P>
   McCowan also began writing some short plays in prison, which he
likes to call ``mini-novels.''
</P>
<P>
   And he stayed out of trouble. Most of the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got into a lot of fights,'' McCowan said. ``I don't know if
it got me into trouble or got me out of trouble. I went to prison
when I was 19. I was still angry. I needed something to identify
with. Guys I knew from the neighborhood or guys who knew guys I
knew. We started to jell.''
</P>
<P>
   McCowan hung out with gang members, many of whom he grew up with
in Carson. But he also completed his courses and remembered McGee's
promise.
</P>
<P>
   On Dec. 17, 1997, McCowan was released from prison. Gaining his
freedom was not the end of his troubles, however, as McCowan
discovered a whole new set of problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first 30 days, I had a big fear they would come get me and
take me back,'' McCowan said. ``I know for a fact I couldn't do it
again. Seven years is seven years no matter how you look at it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took me six months to get my personality back, to laugh and
joke. I used to be an upbeat personality. For some reason, that's
been dulled.''
</P>
<P>
   McGee had since moved on to become the athletic director at
South Carolina, although Garrett, now the AD, upheld McGee's offer.
</P>
<P>
   McCowan attended El Camino College in the spring and summer of
1998 before re-enrolling at USC. His progress was monitored by Fred
Stroock, who is Garrett's special assistant for academic affairs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once he got out, he had to prove himself at a JC, which he
did,'' Stroock said. ``I had to believe this is a student worth
taking a chance on.''
</P>
<P>
   With the fall semester beginning next month, McCowan is unsure
of what he will do after graduation. He's interested in criminal
justice and he's considering a master's degree.
</P>
<P>
   McGee will be there when McCowan gets his diploma and beyond _
McGee said he will help McCowan in obtaining his master's, possibly
at South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish I could say I put it all in the past and everything is
fine,'' McCowan said. ``I've got a lot of mental struggles, and for
the most part, I've overcome them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I figure when it's all said and done, I will have experienced
life at its highest and its lowest.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-22-99 0221EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990822.0039 </DOCNO>
