<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAKING SECOND LOOK AT FIRST-ROUNDERS 
</HEADLINE>
 NOTEBOOK-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ It used to be the precious stone of trade talks, the
diamond that elevated any discussion to serious status. You
mentioned a first-rounder in a deal and it was big news. Not now.
What we are seeing instead is the plummeting of a formerly sacred
bargaining chip.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's interesting,'' said Garry St. Jean, general manager of
the Golden State Warriors. ``This year, I've seen as many
first-rounders moved as I can remember. What I'm wondering is if
there is another part to some of these deals that don't make the
newspaper or the talk show. You know, some of these first-rounders
are probably protected.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``protected'' first-rounder is also a 1990s fad. Too many
teams have watched their traded first-rounders turn into All-Stars,
so they specify that the pick has top three, top five, or lottery
protection.
</P>
<P>
   This month alone, Atlanta traded two first-rounders to the
Clippers for Lorenzen Wright and not many people flinched. The Suns
traded two first-rounders, Danny Manning, and Pat Garrity to the
Magic for Penny Hardaway; many people in the NBA still don't
believe the Magic got enough. The Hawks had four first-rounders
going into the draft and didn't want them. The Celtics gave up
their 1999 first-rounder for Vitaly Potapenko, who never has
started for a full season.
</P>
<P>
   Does this confirm that players aren't as good as they once were?
</P>
<P>
   ``Not necessarily,'' said Ernie Grunfeld, the former Knicks GM
now with Milwaukee. ``You have a lot of teams with different draft
philosophies now. Some teams feel they can trade a pick because
their rosters are locked. But some teams still like young
players.''
</P>
<P>
   They may like them, but not many teams cling to draft picks with
the idea that they may have the rights to the next Larry Bird or
Michael Jordan. The Magic have an arsenal of first-rounders in
central Florida _ 10 over the next five years. That means
something, but not nearly as much as it used to.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you can point out the great players in the draft we just
had,'' Celtics coach Rick Pitino said, ``then you're a better man
than me.''
</P>
<P>
   Pitino said that after he traded one of his 1997 first-rounders
(Ron Mercer) to Denver for a package that included cash, players,
and, naturally, a first-rounder.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He should be covered in the business pages rather than the
sports pages. He is talked about as if he were a trendy stock
option on the Internet. Going up or down? Staying or going? Those
are always the central issues when the subject is Antoine Walker.
</P>
<P>
   The Walker Stock Market was cool last spring, but it became more
active at the beginning of this summer. That's when there was a
lively discussion between Walker and a Celtics assistant coach in
Chicago. Walker apparently was more upset with the assistant's
boss, Pitino, than with the assistant himself. The dispute centered
around Walker's and Pitino's dramatically different interpretations
of what ``offseason'' means.
</P>
<P>
   Now there's talk that Walker will be traded after the season.
What are we to make of this stock?
</P>
<P>
   ``All of this talk about Antoine being traded is pure
speculation,'' said Mike Higgins, Walker's agent. ``I'll be shocked
if he is traded. People have all kinds of things to say, but no one
has talked to Antoine. He hasn't said anything. He's just getting
ready for the season.''
</P>
<P>
   Walker has been playing in an informal Chicago summer league,
which features several Bulls and pros from the area (Tim Hardaway,
Juwan Howard, Michael Finley). During one game a few weeks ago,
Walker went for 47 points. He won't be asked to score that much for
the Celtics, but with Mercer's offense gone Walker will need to be
a consistent scorer. If he stays.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's the kind of job that has you celebrating 20 percent success
rates.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's about how often you can make a trade work,'' St. Jean
said. ``I don't know if fans realize it, but out of every 10 trades
we talk about, eight of them don't work. You go home with a sense
of despair or you go home feeling euphoric.''
</P>
<P>
   St. Jean experienced that last week when he thought he had a
chance of acquiring Mitch Richmond. Instead, the former Warrior
re-signed with the Wizards. ``I'm not going to hide that we were
trying to do some things,'' said St. Jean, who used to coach
Richmond in Sacramento. ``We were going to need creativity to pull
it off, but I thought we had a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   It's also the kind of job that plays mental tricks on you. You
feel like you should be wearing a uniform, but you look in the
mirror and you're wearing a button-down with a tie.
</P>
<P>
   ``You feel a different kind of competition,'' Grunfeld said.
``It's the kind of competition that goes on behind a desk.''
</P>
<P>
   Many fans believe that they could be NBA GMs. Especially after
examining some of the trades/signings of the past couple weeks. A
few examples of questionable GM behavior:
</P>
<P>
   --Clippers sign Tyrone Nesby and Eric Piatkowski to contracts.
</P>
<P>
   What's So Bad About It: Most people would take Nesby and
Piatkowski on their teams, but the Clippers overpaid for them. They
could have had both of them for a total of $4 million; they wound
up paying nearly twice as much as they had to.
</P>
<P>
   But Here's What Scares Other GMs: A frontcourt of Lamar Odom,
Michael Olowokandi, and Maurice Taylor. That's one of the most
promising threesomes in the league. But the Clippers' problem never
has been accumulating talent. They've had trouble keeping it.
</P>
<P>
   --Hawks sign Chris Crawford to a seven-year contract.
</P>
<P>
   What's So Bad About It: Seven years.
</P>
<P>
   But Here's What Scares Other GMs: The Hawks got younger,
quicker, and bigger without giving up Dikembe Mutombo. They added
point guard Jason Terry, guards Isaiah Rider and Jim Jackson, and
power forward/center Lorenzen Wright.
</P>
<P>
   --Raptors sign Michael Stewart to $24 million contract.
</P>
<P>
   What's So Bad About It: It had absolutely nothing to do with
basketball. In exchange for Stewart signing a one-year contract
last season, the Raptors agreed to give him a six-year deal later.
So a man who last year scored less than a hoop a game and grabbed
just over two rebounds now makes $4 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   But Here's What Scares Other GMs: Vince Carter and Tracy McGrady
being surrounded by yet another veteran, Antonio Davis.
</P>
<P>
   --Nuggets acquire Mercer (who may not sign with them), Popeye
Jones, and Dwayne Schintzius and give up a first-rounder and cash
in the process.
</P>
<P>
   What's So Bad About It: They look silly if they don't trade
Mercer and he leaves at the end of the season.
</P>
<P>
   But Here's What Scares Other GMs: Mercer, Antonio McDyess, and
Raef LaFrentz on the same team. LaFrentz, who played in only 12
games last season, is playing again. Before suffering a torn
anterior cruciate ligament, he averaged 14 points and 7.6 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Magic made yet another trade last week, this time sending
Manning and Dale Ellis to the Bucks for Armen Gilliam and Chris
Gatling. Gatling has two years left on his contract and Gilliam,
the man who recently traded the ``o'' in his first name for the
``e'' now there, has one year remaining. Because it will have so
much cap space in 2000, Orlando is being viewed as a major player
in the Tim Duncan Chase. The Bulls are in that category, too. But
it is doubtful that Duncan will leave San Antonio, especially since
there will be a new arena to replace the Alamodome. Still, it
wouldn't be a bad idea for the Spurs to sign Duncan to the
six-year, $73 million contract extension he is eligible for now
rather than allowing him to become a free agent . . . Now that
Hardaway is out of Magic Land, a few behind-the-scenes nuggets are
beginning to emerge from his final days with the Magic. One is that
there definitely was an apology to Hardaway from Magic chairman
Rich DeVos. After the Magic lost to the 76ers in the playoffs,
Hardaway complained about the team and DeVos responded with some
complaints of his own about Hardaway. The private apology came when
new coach Doc Rivers made it clear that he wanted the team to keep
Hardaway. But all the words were too late. The team desperately
tried to keep Hardaway before reluctantly agreeing to trade him to
the Suns . . . It is also known that Shaquille O'Neal asked
Hardaway to join the Lakers. The two have had their differences,
but they appear to be settled now . . . The easiest summary of
Scottie Pippen's desire to be a Laker: Phil Jackson would love to
have him; the West Coast Jerrys _ West and Buss _ aren't so sure .
. . Grunfeld was asked what he thought of the East. Which team does
he think is the early favorite? ``I think you have to go with the
defending Eastern Conference champs,'' he said. He was referring to
the Knicks, the team he built. Last week, Grunfeld managed to
praise the city and its ``extremely knowledgeable fans'' without
once mentioning Jeff Van Gundy and Dave Checketts . . . Grunfeld
traded for Latrell Sprewell and is now a GM in Sprewell's hometown.
The 6-foot-5-inch guard is a free agent after next season, but
don't expect the Bucks to get involved with him. They already have
Ray Allen at shooting guard and Glenn Robinson at small forward.
Ironically, St. Jean probably wouldn't mind having him back at
Golden State (the problem there was with P.J. Carlesimo; St. Jean
and Sprewell got along fine). But that won't happen, either . . .
We are still more than a month away from training camp, but three
rookies _ Atlanta's Terry, Charlotte's Baron Davis, and Phoenix's
Shawn Marion _ already are being discussed with excitement. The
Hornets say they like former Celtic David Wesley at point guard,
but he could be moved before the start of the season . . . Rest in
peace, Kim Perrot.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
