<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-22 02:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5575 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-FBC-CROUSE-COLUMN-LAD     08-22 0943
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BENNETT LEARNING LEADERSHIP ROLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ If he had been more vocal, Drew Bennett might have
been able to defuse the bomb that was dropped on the UCLA program
this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Long before 16 of his teammates were busted for unlawful
possession of handicapped parking placards, Bennett knew what was
going on. He was outraged, but seethed in silence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want something to come between me and my teammates,''
Bennett said. ``It was not worth making enemies of people you have
to spend so much time with.''
</P>
<P>
   Bennett has a chance to affect the season from here on. He is
front and (behind) center after spending two seasons as the
understudy for UCLA football's glamour role. He may not look or act
the part as it is usually cast, but we think he's perfect as the
Bruins' next starting quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   He's tough and not just because he ran the L.A. Marathon one
year on a whim. Running 26.2 miles in basketball shoes was easy
compared to playing Bubby Brister to Cade McNown's John Elway.
</P>
<P>
   Bennett never complained. He just showed up every day and amazed
his teammates with his athleticism.
</P>
<P>
   When the Bruins were hit last year by a spate of injuries at
receiver, Bennett filled in nicely at that spot. He'll be playing
downs on both sides of the ball for at least the first two games
next month, until his suspended teammates return.
</P>
<P>
   The junior would sooner be struck by lightning than brag on
himself. So not many people beyond the cozy confines of Spaulding
Field know he is arguably the best athlete to grace UCLA since
Jackie Joyner-Kersee.
</P>
<P>
   Bennett, who turns 21 on Thursday, can jump so high and run so
fast it doesn't seem possible he and Dan Marino were born to play
the same position.
</P>
<P>
   His teammates, his friends and his coaches all say he's a rare
athletic specimen. Ask Bennett for confirmation and you get a
cackle.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind being the best athlete on the field. Bennett says
he's not even the best athlete in his family. He boasts about his
younger brother Richie and soon he's watering a patch of natural
grass with his tears.
</P>
<P>
   Richie, a sophomore at Cal, has cerebral palsy. He is confined
to a wheelchair but hardly confined by it. He is the Michael
Johnson of the wheelchair set, counting many 400-meter national
titles among his litany of achievements.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has all these plaques on his wall,'' Bennett said. ``He's
really amazing.''
</P>
<P>
   Bennett learned from his father Rick, who was Cal's leading
rusher as a sophomore in 1966, and he spent two years at McNown's
side. Yet all he knows about football he learned from Richie.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've learned more from him than anybody,'' Bennett said.
</P>
<P>
   The tears well up before he can continue. He squats down, takes
a couple of deep breaths, then completes his thought in a near
whisper, ``Just his joy in doing things.''
</P>
<P>
   At that moment it's so obvious how blessed Bennett is. Never
mind his physical gifts, he sees what so many others altogether
miss. Namely, that happiness is a state of mind and not something
gained from starring or even starting.
</P>
<P>
   Hours later, Bennett is back on the field for a scrimmage that
will help determine whether he or redshirt freshman Cory Paus will
succeed McNown when the Bruins open their season Sept.4 against
Boise State.
</P>
<P>
   No one is questioning Bennett's grasp of the offense. His
mechanics are the issue. If he were consistently throwing the same
tight spirals he did as a freshman, the same tight spirals he
unleashes in this scrimmage, UCLA head coach Bob Toledo would have
one less headache in this migraine of a summer.
</P>
<P>
   Bennett completes 4 of 5 passes for 50 yards and sounds
inordinately relieved for someone set to inherit the starting job.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just glad I played well,'' he said. ``It's been a long
week.''
</P>
<P>
   There's a lot of pressure, to be sure. To the victor go the
spoils: campus-wide acclaim, national attention, all the prettiest
girls.
</P>
<P>
   None of which matters to Bennett, who already has a lovely
girlfriend, Margie, dear friends and no discernible ego in need of
stroking.
</P>
<P>
   What lights his fire is this: For two years he has put in his
time, paid his dues. He'd like to think he has earned this
promotion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like I'm maturing every day,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bennett, who started only one season at Miramonte High and then
walked on at UCLA, is pleading the case of dreamers and late
bloomers everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd be real upset if I'm not (named the starter) because I've
put a lot of time into this,'' he said, then added quickly: ``But
if anybody has to play above me, I'd pick Cory.''
</P>
<P>
   So much for wondering if Bennett will leave if he doesn't get
the starting job. Incoming freshman J.P. Losman surveyed the
competition at quarterback this past spring and took off for Tulane
without bothering to give UCLA campus life a try.
</P>
<P>
   It obviously takes more heat than that to drive Bennett from the
pocket. It's not as though he arrived in Westwood from his hometown
of Orinda and instantly felt welcome.
</P>
<P>
   He remembers feeling plenty uncomfortable at first. He was a
non-scholarship player surrounded by highly recruited classmates,
all of whom seemed to know one another from high school all-star
games and recruiting visits.
</P>
<P>
   There were four quarterbacks ahead of Bennett in the beginning.
The three directly behind McNown may have had more promise but none
had Bennett's patience.
</P>
<P>
   He persevered and before he knew it he was being groomed to take
McNown's place some day.
</P>
<P>
   He hopes his time is now.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
