<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHL </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A NEW TRADE FOR CARPENTER 
</HEADLINE>
 NOTEBOOK-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Bob Carpenter, who grew up here as ``The Can't Miss
Kid,'' stared retirement in the face for a second, saw all those
leisurely, laidback hours flash before his eyes, and, in so many
words, said, ``Can't do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Until further notice, then, he is Coach Carpenter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, I'm not going into this with the aspirations that I
want to be a head coach,'' said the former St. John's Prep star,
reached last week, shortly after his decision to become an
assistant coach in Albany, the New Jersey Devils' AHL affiliate.
``I just knew I couldn't sit and do nothing _ I think that can be
dangerous for anyone _ and this is something to try, see how I feel
about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Carpenter, 36, broke into the league as an 18-year-old offensive
phenom after the Capitals made him the No. 3 choice in the '81
draft _ the highest an American had ever been drafted.
</P>
<P>
   In his first four seasons, he averaged 36 goals, collecting a
career-high 95 points in his fourth season in Landover. In the
early '90s, after stops in New York (Rangers), Los Angeles, and
Boston and a brief return to Washington, he reinvented himself as a
dogged checker in New Jersey and was a key to the Devils' winning
the Stanley Cup in '95.
</P>
<P>
   It was then-Devils coach Jacques Lemaire who taught Carpenter
the importance of being earnest without the puck.
</P>
<P>
   ``He made me realize what a great challenge the checking job can
be,'' said Carpenter. ``He basically said, `Look, you don't have to
score, you don't have to be out there on the power play _ just do
this job and you'll be fine.' I took it as a challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could still be an important part of the team. OK, maybe I
wouldn't be the guy who got the goal, but I could be the guy who
kept Mario Lemieux to no points, and that gave us the same chance
to win, maybe.
</P>
<P>
   ``It taught me a lot about the game. And it taught me a lot of
respect for the guys who did that job.''
</P>
<P>
   Carpenter's first real taste of checking came in '90, when he
was in Boston and the Bruins made it to the finals against the
Oilers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mike Milbury threw me out there against Mark Messier and said,
`OK, check him,' '' said Carpenter. ``That was something different.
I loved my time in Boston. Those years, along with winning the Cup
in New Jersey . . . nothing beat that.''
</P>
<P>
   Eighteen NHL seasons behind him now, Carpenter moves on to his
new career. He'll work under a former Bruins assistant coach, John
Cunniff, and find out whether full-time work without a stick can be
as rewarding as lugging one.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think if I'd never gone to New Jersey and retired after,
say, 12 years, I would have been a little bitter about the whole
experience,'' reflected Carpenter. ``I wouldn't have been on a Cup
winner. And people forget, the money didn't really improve until
the start of the '90s. Before then, people thought if you signed,
say, a four-year deal worth $1 million, you were set for life.
That's nuts. Not if you want to put your kids through school, buy a
car when you need one. It doesn't go that far.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was lucky. The tail end of my career just made it to when
the money was good'' _ he made just under $1 million in each of his
last two seasons _ ``and that helped a lot. It made it so I could
try something new like this without worrying too much.''
</P>
<P>
   In that sense, he's still living the ``Can't Miss'' life.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cam Neely will be shuttling between Boston and Atlanta this
hockey season. The ex-Bruins power forward recently signed on with
the Atlanta-based PMT Corp., a credit card and check-verification
company, and he will assist the company's marketing and promotional
efforts _ with obligatory luxury box appearances at the new Philips
Arena, home of the Thrashers . . . Is Atlanta a hockey town?
Consider: The Thrashers will open in October with a season-ticket
base of 13,000. The NBA Hawks are believed to be down to about
5,000. There is an undeniable novelty factor built into the
Thrasher figure _ how many will hold on after a year or two? _ but,
remember, the Flames were doing very well at the gate before they
bolted for a sweetheart deal in Calgary . . . It doesn't look like
ex-BC Eagle Bill Guerin will be with the Oilers at the start of
training camp. Guerin made $1.5 million last season and is now a
Group 2 free agent, believed to be looking for $3.5 million or
better . . . Tony Twist will be rehabbing for the rest of this
calendar year after fracturing his pelvis and ankle when he smashed
up his motorcycle earlier this month. Twist's agent, Don Meehan:
``He's lucky to be alive.'' . . . Alexander Mogilny has to rate as
one of the league's most disappointing talents his last three years
with the Canucks. Long gone are his prolific days in Buffalo, where
in '92-93 he potted 76 goals with Pat LaFontaine dishing him the
biscuit. ``He's really a good kid,'' explained Canucks GM Brian
Burke. ``He doesn't like it when he's not playing well.'' In hopes
of igniting Mogilny's scoring touch, the Canucks this summer
obtained free agent Andrew Cassels, once one of Burke's Forever
.500s in Hartford. If it's the right pairing, perhaps the Canucks
finally will get some value from the trade that saw them send
Michael Peca, among others, to the Sabres in July '95 . . . Mario
Lemieux still hasn't closed his deal to buy the Penguins, and the
cash-strapped flightless birds needed creditors to infuse even more
money last week to say afloat. Lemieux's coterie of
lawyers/financial advisers continues to contend he'll get it done
(will they place a widow's walk atop the Igloo?). Eventually,
federal bankruptcy court will have to push the issue to resolution.
It's yet another example of how the legal and financial systems of
America operate with a different set of rules (read: bend
shamelessly) when dealing with pro sports franchises . . . How
about Derek Plante, once deemed so valuable in Buffalo that the
Sabres could loan him to Team USA for the '94 Olympics, taking a
pay cut ($1 million down to $750,000) with Dallas? He barely
figured in the Stars' plans en route to winning the Cup. But he's
still gainfully employed, at a price that not long ago was
considered exceptional money.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Among the reasons Dominik Hasek decided to announce his
retirement (effective next spring) in the middle of this summer: He
had a book, written in Czech, about to be released, and the last
chapter revealed his plan to call it quits after '99-00. His agent,
Rich Winter, talked him out of quitting prior to this season.
Hasek, still summering in Pardubice, underwent a 40-minute hernia
repair in Germany last week, too . . . The Lightning must have
pushed the patience of the Players' Association when management
paid for ice time all last week and invited anyone on the roster to
enter the voluntary workouts, with GM Rick Dudley and head coach
Steve Ludzik watching rinkside. Anyone truly fighting for a job _
which is about 98.7 percent of the Bolts' roster _ had to feel the
pressure to lace up the blades . . . Surprising end for Anders
Hedberg in Toronto. When Mike Smith's deal wasn't extended with the
Leafs, it appeared that Hedberg would be the GM, but team president
Ken Dryden handed GM duties to head coach Pat Quinn. Following all
this? Then Dryden hired Nick Beverley, an old Quinn pal from the LA
days, to oversee scouting and run the draft. Hedberg essentially
got the heave-ho and resigned, but he was handed his final year's
pay (about $275,000) as a parting gift. Hedberg exited saying he'll
hold on to the dream of one day running an NHL club. The league
would do well to add him to the Gary Bettman regime. He would be a
perfect ambassador between Manhattan and Europe, dealing with
international/Olympic issues . . . LA's top two lines, headed into
training camp, will be stocked with no fewer than three ex-Bruins.
Jozef Stumpel will be the pivot for Luc Robitaille and Ziggy
Palffy, while Bryan Smolinski and Glen Murray will work with Donald
Audette. The Bruins now have only Byron Dafoe on their roster to
show for the deals in which they lost Stumpel, Smolinski, and
Murray. Stumpel exited in the Dafoe-Dmitri Khristich swap.
Smolinski and Murray left in the Kevin Stevens-Shawn McEachern
exchange . . . The Islanders will enter battle this year with a
payroll of some $15 million _ about 25 cents on the dollar compared
with the Rangers. The disparity, on paper, is an embarrassment, and
there will be greater cause to blush brighter than the red line
when the acres of empty seats in Uniondale get flashed incessantly
on ``SportsCenter.'' Meanwhile, a potential buyer has surfaced.
Reportedly, Charles Koppelman, former owner of EMI Group North
America, has offered $185 million _ only $10 million less than what
the Islanders sold for last year. Bang the gavel and scream,
``Sold!''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Once-promising Bruins forward Jarmo Kekalainen was named the
Senators' director of player personnel, filling the spot vacated by
Marshall Johnston, now the GM. Kekalainen spent recent years as
Ottawa's European scout and also was GM of IFK Helsinki the last
four seasons . . . Where will the Bruins find those 29 goals that
left town when they issued Khristich ``walkaway'' free agency? Dave
Andreychuk is part of the answer. Two more candidates to keep in
mind: Joe Hulbig, the former Oiler signed as a free agent this
summer, and Jeff Zehr, a former Islander prospect who also signed
as a free agent in the offseason. Hulbig was the 13th pick in the
'92 draft, and the Islanders took Zehr 31st overall in '97. None of
those three alone could be expected to equal Khristich's
production, but two of the three should make up for much of the
loss . . . Top Calgary prospect Robyn Regehr just began working out
last week after having both his legs broken in an automobile crash
earlier this summer. The 6-foot-2-inch defenseman lost 25 pounds
soon after the accident but already has gained half of that back.
Regehr was the 19th pick in the '98 draft, the spot Boston handed
to Colorado for the Landon Wilson-Anders Myrvold acquisitions. The
Avalanche then handed Regehr to the Flames for their short-term
rental of Theo Fleury (now another multimillionaire Manhattanite) .
. . Dave King won't be behind the Canadiens bench, aiding head
coach Alain Vigneault this season. King, who failed to land a head
coaching job elsewhere, now will head up the Habs' scouting efforts
in Europe, setting up shop in Germany or the Czech Republic. His
mission: find older, non-draft-eligible players who could help
immediately . . . Think Peter Blute could land a job with the NHL,
maybe as the guy designated to fill the Cup with champagne each
spring? Sounds like a Moet moment to me. In the offseason, he could
book player cruises.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-22-99 0231EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
