u s BC-BOX-BOXINGNOTEBOOK-BO     08-22 2367
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-BOXING </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REID'S EYE AGAIN THE FOCAL POINT 
</HEADLINE>
 NOTEBOOK-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The prevailing strategy when fighting World Boxing
Association super welterweight champion David Reid is to attack his
left eye because of an odd ailment that causes the lid to drop down
like a window shade as a fight progresses.
</P>
<P>
   According to his promoters, this condition is a reaction to the
bright television lights at ringside, although many of Reid's
opponents claim it's a result of being hit too often under those
lights.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the cause, Reid eventually begins to look like Moshe
Dayan in boxing trunks, which cannot make his job any easier
despite his protests to the contrary.
</P>
<P>
   Reid has had this malady since the 1996 Olympics, when his
bashful eye seemed to be permanently winking at opponents. A
knockout victory in the gold medal match, a world title after only
11 professional fights, and several operations have done nothing to
change this vexing problem for the undefeated Reid (13-0), and it
is a constant topic of conversation whenever a fight approaches.
</P>
<P>
   Next Saturday, he will be in with former World Boxing Council
154-pound champion Keith Mullings, a tough man not averse to
punching an opponent in his weak spot, wherever it may be. Yet
Mullings insists he will take a different approach to Reid when
they meet at the Hard Rock Casino in Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   ``You try to exploit any weaknesses,'' Mullings said from his
training camp. ``If his eye is a problem, I'm going to hit him in
it. But what I'd really like to do is shut the other eye first.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would be the best thing, I would think. If one eye isn't
working, you shut the good eye and let the bad one take care of
itself.''
</P>
<P>
   Mullings raises a good point, but Reid offers a reasonable
counter.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been this way since I turned pro,'' said Reid. ``It
doesn't bother my vision, and I'm glad it don't. If it did, I
wouldn't have won the title.''
</P>
<P>
   That's not necessarily so, but it makes for a good argument.
Reid has not knocked anyone down in over a year, for example, yet
he has visited the canvas several times himself. Some will say the
latter is a result of not being able to see right hands coming at
him.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the reason, Reid's performances have suffered of late,
and boxing people who had been hyping a big-money match with former
Olympic teammate Fernando Vargas, holder of the International
Boxing Federation version of the title, now wonder whether Reid
will survive long enough to get to him. Not surprisingly, Mullings
(16-5-1, 11 KOs) is first among them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Reid has all the potential to be one of the best boxers in the
world, but today's not the day,'' Mullings said. ``With the number
of fights he's had, he hasn't grown with the skills he has yet, so
a lot of guys pose a problem to him. Hopefully, I'll be able to
exploit and take advantage of that.''
</P>
<P>
   Many believe Mullings will try to take advantage of that lazy
eyelid, but the former champion believes the new champion's true
weakness actually lies elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I'm going to be testing is his chin,'' Mullings promised.
``His chin is more suspect than his eye. Sure, I'll hit him in his
eye. But I'll hit him in his nose and his ear and his throat,
too.''
</P>
<P>
   To this, Reid replied, ``I could tell from his demeanor he's
very high on himself.''
</P>
<P>
   That was the type of measured response people have grown
accustomed to hearing from Reid, who has become famous for his
controlled approach to life. Yet he knows what hangs in the balance
next weekend and cannot ignore it.
</P>
<P>
   First there's the big-money payday with Vargas that HBO is
already plotting, and then, possibly, a bigger one with Oscar De La
Hoya if the present welterweight champion gets by Felix Trinidad
and successfully pursues the WBC version of the junior middleweight
title in December, as planned.
</P>
<P>
   Considering all that's at stake, Reid would have good reason to
be worrying about his eyelid's cooperation, Mullings's opposition,
and the widely held proposition that he needs a spectacular victory
to get back on the same pedestal on which Vargas is now perched
after a one-sided manhandling of another ex-champion, Raul Marquez,
last month.
</P>
<P>
   To this, Reid responds the way his eye does to TV lights. He
nods off.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course I'd love a knockout, but the name of the game is
winning, not how you win,'' Reid said. ``You gotta get the win the
best way you can.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if it's with an eye wide shut.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here's how hot De La Hoya-Trinidad has become in Puerto Rico:
They're trying to show it in prison. Hector Figueroa, a longtime
closed-circuit operator in Puerto Rico, got the government to pay
$30,000 to have the fight shown live in four prisons in exchange
for Trinidad saying a few words before the broadcast to encourage
the prisoners. It was all set up until Trinidad's father got wind
of it and balked, although the deal still could go through . . .
With 55 percent of the people in Puerto Rico living below the
poverty line, local politicians are cutting deals with Figueroa to
buy the broadcast and have it piped into homes, a case of boxing
striking a blow for politics. Figueroa is hoping combined
pay-per-view and closed-circuit sales will reach $2 million, which
would shatter the previous Puerto Rican sales record of $200,000 .
. . Orlin Norris has agreed to fight Mike Tyson for $800,000 and
has been told it's 95 percent set he'll be Tyson's opponent on Oct.
23. That's also the first night of the World Series, but Showtime
is ready to go through with it. The problem remains Tyson, who has
not signed the contract . . . Strawweight champion Ricardo Lopez
packs on 3 more pounds to venture up to junior flyweight and
challenge IBF champion Will Grigsby Oct. 2 at the MGM Grand. Lopez,
one of the littlest men in boxing, fills in for one of the biggest,
Tyson, who had been penciled in for a fight but now will not appear
before Oct. 16. On the same card, Julio Cesar Chavez launches
another American comeback vs. veteran Willie Wise. It would be
wiser for him to forget the whole idea. But he won't . . . After a
recent rash of out-of-the-ring problems for high-profile fighters,
HBO is considering adding a morals clause to its long-term
contracts with champions. The recent arrests of Vargas and
heavyweight contender Ike Ibeabuchi convinced some HBO executives
that the cable giant needs more protection from the properties it
does business with . . . By the way, have you seen any of the
apologists and ``friends'' of Ibeabuchi lately, now that he needs
$2 million in bail money to get himself out of jail in Las Vegas?
The guys who were pushing him into boxing rings when he needed to
be pushed into a psychiatrist's office don't seem so helpful or
concerned about him now, which is why he's likely to stay in a
Clark County jail cell until a hearing Wednesday on sexual assault
charges. Ibeabuchi's bail was reduced from $5 million, but there
were no takers because everyone in boxing believes they've seen the
last of him for a while. Hence the end of a beautiful friendship .
. . Boxing lost a good friend, and Main Events lost a straight guy
when chief operating officer Mike Boorman opted recently to leave
the company rather than continue to endure the backbiting and
infighting of the Duva clan over control of the organization. Word
is that Dino Duva, who left for personal reasons months ago, wants
back in and along with his sister, Donna, and father, Lou, is
trying to buy out the company's owner, Kathy Duva, wife of Dino's
late brother, Dan. Turns out that when Dan formed Main Events and
Monitor Promotions, he cut his brother and sister in for 30 percent
each of the profits, leaving him with 40 percent. What they didn't
know was that that is all they were cut in on. Word is, after Dan's
death they learned that the company was left to a trust controlled
by Duva's wife and his longtime attorney, Pat English. Dino and
Donna believed all along they controlled 60 percent of the stock
along with the profits, but it turns out they were left with no
voting power, and the mess degenerated into a family feud that has
made it difficult to do business. Boorman, who is married to Lou
Duva's youngest daughter, chose to leave boxing for a teaching
career, something he had been considering for several years. That's
education's gain and boxing's loss. Unfortunately for the Duvas,
his departure leaves Main Events without the most capable member of
the family to run the business. Where they go from here is anyone's
guess, but either Dino, Donna, and Lou buy out Kathy or a
remarkable 15-year rags-to-riches success story comes to a sad end
sooner rather than later . . . Two-time world champion Kennedy
McKinney goes back into action Saturday at the Grand Casino in
Mississippi vs. Mario Diaz in a 10-round junior featherweight fight
McKinney hopes will get him back into the Naseem Hamed sweepstakes
. . . Ivan Robinson learned what happens when you lose a fight.
He's off HBO and back to ESPN2 Sept. 3 vs. Golden Johnson for the
vacant North American Boxing Federation lightweight title. Robinson
twice defeated Arturo Gatti but didn't fare as well against Angel
Manfredy, so it's back to the provinces. Johnson is 17-3-2 but
dangerous. Two of his losses came against Shane Mosley and Pito
Cardona, two of the best lightweights in the world. Mosley has
since moved to welterweight, and Cardona will fight for the vacant
IBF title later this year . . . WBC bantamweight champion Veerapol
Sahaprom (22-1) of Thailand defends his title next Sunday in Japan
vs. Joichiro Tatsuyoshi (17-5-1).
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dariusz Michalczewski, the World Boxing Organization light
heavyweight champion, is making big money in Germany, but he's
growing weary of not getting the shot he wants _ a fight with Roy
Jones Jr. Michalczewski has made 15 consecutive defenses of his
title and is now 40-0 with 33 KOs. Although he'll make his 16th
defense against Montell Griffin Saturday in Bremen, Germany, it is
not Griffin who is on his mind. ``The time has come now, and Jones
must finally take me on,'' Michalczewski said recently from
Germany. ``The whole boxing world wants to see a fight between
Jones and me. We should fight as long as we are both on a winning
streak. There are only a few of those possible big fights in
boxing. It's Holyfield-Lewis, Oscar De La Hoya-Trindad and
Michalczewski-Jones.'' . . . Jones, by the way, discounted talk
that he might want to fight Shannon Briggs when he learned that
Briggs was 6 feet 4 inches and 230 pounds. . . In case you missed
it, Italian Stefano Zoff upset WBA lightweight champion Julien
Lorcy, winning a split decision in France. Do you have any idea
what it takes to win a split decision from a Frenchman in France?
Apparently Lorcy made no friends after upsetting fellow Frenchman
Jean-Baptise Mendy to win the title in April . . . Fading former
featherweight champion Kevin Kelley was upset last weekend in a
$5,000 tuneup fight in Louisiana by Benito Rodriguez, a lightweight
with a 27-25 record who probably outweighed Kelley by 20 pounds.
The loss cost Kelley an already planned farewell to boxing against
another faded former champion, Junior Jones, underneath the
Hamed-Cesar Soto featherweight unification fight in Detroit Oct.
22. Ireland's Wayne McCullough is on the same card, in a title shot
against WBC super bantamweight champion Erik Morales . . . Bob Arum
has nearly locked up a January unification fight between Morales
and WBO titleholder Marco Antonio Barrera, a fellow Mexican, for
big money as well . . . Talented WBO super middleweight champion
Joe Calzaghe (27-0, 23 KOs) finally has an opponent for his Sept.
18 title defense on the De La Hoya-Trinidad undercard. He'll take
on little-known Canadian Alain Bonnamie (18-8, 11 KOs) . . . NABF
welterweight champion Vernon Forrest takes on Roberto Duran's
nephew, Santiago Samaniego (27-4-1, 23 KOs), in Augusta, Ga.,
Friday . . . Bantamweight champion Paulie Ayala makes his first
title defense Sept. 25 vs. No. 1 challenger Saohin Sritbai Condo
(17-6, 12 KOs) of Thailand.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-three-year-old Mickey Ward (33-9) gets one more chance to
put himself into a world title fight when he takes on
seventh-ranked Reggie Green Oct. 1 in Salem, N.H. The winner could
earn a shot against WBA super lightweight champion Sharmba Mitchell
with a strong (but not too strong) performance. Green (30-3) lost a
12-round decision to Mitchell in April . . . Word is Vinny Pazienza
will earn $350,000 and Dana Rosenblatt $185,000 for a fall rematch
at Foxwoods . . . It was learned last week that Reyes Munoz, who
was knocked out in one round by Arturo Gatti last weekend at
Foxwoods and carried from the ring on a stretcher to the hospital,
suffered from cranial nerve palsy, a form of epilepsy, and will
never fight again. The quick action of ringside neurologist Anthony
Alessi prevented any permanent damage. Munoz was first taken to a
local hospital in Norwich and then transferred to Yale Hospital's
trauma center. Alessi said it would have been nearly impossible for
the problem to have been found in prefight physicals. To his
credit, Gatti went to the hospital after the fight to check on
Munoz . . . WBC lightweight champion Stevie Johnston came away from
his win over Manfredy at Foxwoods last weekend a little light
despite his strong performance. Both Johnston and Manfredy were
docked $2,000 by the WBC for failing to participate in weigh-ins 30
days and seven days before the fight. The WBC has a safety rule
that demands fighters in world title matches be no more than 10
percent above their division's weight limit 30 days before the
fight and no more than 5 percent above it a week before the fight .
. . Johnston forgot his boxing shoes and had to borrow those of
Saugus's Bobby Tomasello, who asked only that Johnston sign the
shoes when he was finished, which the champion gladly did . . .
Hartford heavyweight hopeful Lawrence Clay-Bey comes back from a
16-month layoff (he had a broken hand) to face undefeated Dale
Crowe (15-0, 9 KOs) underneath Reid-Mullings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
