<HEADLINE>
EVERYTHING OLD IS NEW AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
 NOTEBOOK-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE CONCANNON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CONCORD, Mass. _ The first time the PGA Senior Tour set up shop
in Massachusetts was 18 years ago, in the dog days of June at
Marlborough CC. The flashback is to Billy Casper, outside the
clubhouse, weighing his newly discovered life in golf.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two days ago,'' said Casper, ``I was a veteran. Yesterday I
became a rookie. I think it's neat. It's exciting.''
</P>
<P>
   This was a born-again existence for the old guys who once faced
into the woodwork, teaching at club jobs and living with the ghosts
of tournaments past. They'd play into their 40s, with little
competitive light at the end of the tunnel. There was the venerable
PGA Seniors' Championship and the US Senior Open. There was the
infant Legends of Golf. Then came a meeting of legends named Sam
Snead, Bob Goalby, Don January, and the late Julius Boros, Gardner
Dickinson, and Dan Sikes on Jan. 16, 1980.
</P>
<P>
   Out of it was born the PGA Senior Tour, which is celebrating its
20th year. The old Marlborough tournament moved to Nashawtuc CC in
1985, and the event now known as the BankBoston Classic has aged
gracefully. It has drawn sizable crowds and is now the oldest
54-hole event on the PGA Senior Tour. Is there an end in sight?
</P>
<P>
   Some say the PGA Senior Tour has become old hat, that the
novelty has worn off, paralysis has set in. It's Hale Irwin versus
Gil Morgan. There is a sameness. But it's funny how quickly things
can change. The tour suddenly has a fresh new lease on life, with
rookies shining in what has shaped up as a transitional year. Bruce
Fleisher is No. 1 on the money list, Allen Doyle of Norwood is No.
3.
</P>
<P>
   Before the end of the year, Doug Tewell, Tom Watson, Lanny
Wadkins, and Tom Kite will turn 50, so the new millennium should
bring a further revitalization of the Senior Tour.
</P>
<P>
   ``Watson will bring great credibility and has great
credentials,'' said Irwin. ``Whether or not his game will be up to
the past as we all think it should be is another matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there are people we're overlooking. Doug Tewell's
coming out very soon. Then we have Tom Kite and Lanny Wadkins
shortly thereafter. A lot of talk has been featured on Tom Watson,
and I don't hesitate to say he will give the Senior Tour a new
face. He'll be great for us. He'll be followed by other players who
very nearly have the same type of profile. It'll be tremendous. I
think the year 2000 is going to be a very exciting year. I think
we're going to see a real show next year.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not easy to earn your way onto the PGA Senior Tour, and
it's harder to stay there. The top 31 from the previous year's
money list make it, as well as the top 31 from the all-time money
list not otherwise exempt. Also in are the top eight players out of
the Senior Qualifying School. Winners of Senior events are exempt
for one year, and past champions from PGA Tour events make it on a
space-available basis.
</P>
<P>
   Dana Quigley of Barrington, R.I., was in limbo when he turned 50
on April 14, 1996. He tried to qualify or get sponsor's exemptions.
He finally broke through and won the Northville Long Island Classic
two years ago, and he has since won five more times. Quigley is one
of the most active players on the tour, and as a veteran, he can
recognize the changing face of Senior golf.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes some people about three months,'' said Quigley, ``but
it took me about two years. I never felt I belonged out here, but
when I got my first win, I felt I was headed in the right
direction. We're now getting the best players from every country in
the world: Jose Maria Canizares, Hugh Biochi, John Bland, Christy
O'Connor.
</P>
<P>
   ``The list is just going on and on, and when they see the
success these guys are having, there's just going to be more coming
over every year if they find some way they can get out here. Q
School is a tough avenue to go through. I was really lucky. If Jay
Sigel didn't three-putt those greens (at Northville), I might have
not have gotten through the Q School, and all of this might not
have happened.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Ryder Cup apparently has a decidedly different connotation
to the Seniors than it does to malcontents such as Tiger Woods,
David Duval, Mark O'Meara, and Phil Mickelson, who have raised the
dander of traditionalists by questioning why money from the event
isn't distributed to players, who can give it to their area
charities or do with it what they will. You wonder why Woods was
heckled on the last day of the PGA Championship, when the crowd
suddenly adopted Sergio Garcia as its hero?
</P>
<P>
   The Ryder Cup has provided Irwin with some of his most
pressurized and cherished moments in golf.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're trying to pull together as a common cause, rather than
playing as an individual with a single cause,'' said Irwin.
``You're actually going out hoping to contribute to the success of
this team through your own performance. It's not a team sport in
the same sense as baseball or football, but it's as close to that
as we can get in golf.''
</P>
<P>
   Irwin was at Kiawah Island in 1991, when it came down to a
missed putt by his opponent, Germany's Bernhard Langer, on the
final hole to give the US the victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``It became a very explosive environment at Kiawah,'' said
Irwin. ``You don't want to be the person who lets the team down.
This is a different environment, and that's why I think it's so
unique. You have other people who are really and truly pulling for
you. They're not just giving you lip service.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could see that as our match progressed. More and more
people were falling back to the last match. I told my wife the
night before when the pairings came out, `I have a feeling it's
going to come down to Bernhard and me.'
</P>
<P>
   ``You have a lot of intense time together that week, talking
about how you collectively might play. There's a lot of give and
take of information, and that, by itself, is different. It's nice.
It's a refreshing change of pace.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always thought the Ryder Cup was something special. Money
was never an issue with me, nor with the players. It was just never
an issue. I think most of the older players had a different
attitude, but it's the same in all sports.
</P>
<P>
   ``We played for the fact we were representing the US. Now we're
into this other thing, which in my opinion has put a pall over the
whole idea of the Ryder Cup. There are still enough very good
players on that team. They just have to put that aside.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're playing a great golf course. I really like The Country
Club. I don't think you can count the Europeans out. They've got
the Cup. They're playing in a hostile environment, and sometimes
that rallies the troops to get together and stay together.''
</P>
<P>
   Englishman Brian Barnes, who once beat Jack Nicklaus in singles
twice in the same day, pulled no punches regarding the money
matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a bloody disgrace,'' said Barnes. ``If you're not
proud to play for your country, then you shouldn't even be out
there. To even consider being paid for it brings it down to the
same level as any other sport.
</P>
<P>
   ``Golf is way above any sport that is played, due to the fact
that every time we go out there, we have to be honest and put our
own resolve on the line. There is also the matter that the only two
organizations that seem to derive any benefit from it are the PGA
of America and the PGA of Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to see a lot of the money put into the charities in
the players' names. Let's be honest. Most of these guys are already
millionaires, and they have contracts that reward them.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Hayes played in the 1979 Ryder Cup at the Greenbrier, when
the competition was conducted in virtual solitude. You could walk
right in and watch; nobody was there.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't that hectic then,'' said Hayes. ``It started to
snowball after that year. I still think golf stands alone in terms
of the integrity of sport. I think this is one way to show we will
stay above the greedy aspects of the sport.''
</P>
<P>
   Dave Stockton, who was the US captain at Kiawah, said, ``It's a
little different between your role as a player and as a captain. I
remember being on the first tee at Kiawah, and I couldn't even see
the fairway. You patted them on the back, wished them good luck,
and said, `Thank God I'm not the one who has to hit your shot.' I
would expect (Ben) Crenshaw to win at Brookline, but there's a lot
of pressure.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of all the flak over where the Ryder Cup money goes,
it is worth pondering the identity of the next US captain. The
storm that Crenshaw has been in may heat up even more before the
next matches in 2001. Stockton feels the next captain should be
selected now and be present at The Country Club as an observer. ``I
knew Watson was going to succeed me as captain,'' said Stockton.
``That was an exception. I would have very much liked to have
Watson at Kiawah. I think the next captain should be on site. It
puts us in a little bit of a bind, because by the time you learn
how to do it, as I did at Kiawah, I was ready to go the next year.
I understood part of things that go wrong and right, but all of a
sudden it was Tom Watson's turn. I don't know who's following
Crenshaw, but to my way of thinking, whoever's going to do it
should be invited here.'' . . . Jim Ireland, who retired two years
ago after 18 years in sales and an executive capacity with
MacGregor and 26 years as an executive with Titleist/FootJoy, is
the ninth recipient of the Ernie Sabrayac Award, which recognizes
contributions to the business side of golf. This is the PGA of
America's highest honor. Ireland, who resides on Boston's South
Shore, will be honored Sept. 29 at the PGA merchandise show in Las
Vegas . . . The Europeans will firm up their 12-man Ryder Cup
roster at the conclusion of Sundya's BMW International Open in
Munich. The players from the Ryder Cup teams, in addition to those
from last year's Presidents Cup teams, will converge in Akron,
Ohio, this week to play the second event on the International
Federation of PGA Tours/World Golf Championship at Firestone CC.
The purse is $5 million. Isn't this a spinoff from the Ryder Cup's
success? . . . Ten of the 12 US team members will be at The Country
Club a week from Monday to walk the course with Crenshaw and after
lunch play 18 holes. Woods and O'Meara have prior commitments.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-22-99 0234EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
