<DOCNO> NYT19990822.0044 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-22 02:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5583 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBN-NFLNOTEBOOK-BOS &LR;      08-22 3308
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFL </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A $50 MILLION QUESTION FOR KRAFT 
</HEADLINE>
 NOTEBOOK-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Is he worth the money?
</P>
<P>
   That's what New England fans will be asking themselves for quite
some time, and it's what Patriots owner Robert Kraft has to be
worrying about today, with the ink barely dry on the seven-year,
$50 million contract extension he handed Pro Bowl cornerback Ty Law
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   That deal made Law the second-highest paid corner in football
and the highest-paid Patriot in history, pushing him past $42
million quarterback Drew Bledsoe, and assured that Law's best years
in football will be played in New England.
</P>
<P>
   But is he worth the money?
</P>
<P>
   That will be a persistent question the next few years because
the Patriots have not had much luck betting on the future lately.
They invested $16 million in bonuses and $50 million total in Ted
Johnson and Willie McGinest and haven't gotten a full season _ or a
Pro Bowl performance _ out of either of them since. They invested
$2.5 million a year in Max Lane and Todd Rucci, but by the end of
last year Lane was on the bench and the Patriots were trying to
find a way to get Rucci in the same place, although before it's
over both will start again this season.
</P>
<P>
   Only time, luck, and Law will provide an answer to that question
but Law's emergence as one of the game's best cornerbacks was
obvious a year ago after he intercepted nine passes and reached the
Pro Bowl for the first time. When you add the fact that he's only
25 and is so consumed with becoming the best corner in the game
that he spent most of the offseason working with Olympic track
coach Bob Kersee, you can breathe a little easier than it ever
seemed wise to do with those other signings. They were bets made
far more on future potential than past production, whereas Law
already has had the kind of season you pay big for, so at least you
know he can do it.
</P>
<P>
   One sign of his obsession was spending several weeks in
Foxborough with Lawyer Milloy working on conditioning after the
Patriots were eliminated from the playoffs last year. He wanted to
be ready for February's Pro Bowl, and he was rewarded for his
efforts, making an interception that he returned 67 yards for a
touchdown and being named the game's co-MVP.
</P>
<P>
   He then worked much of the offseason with Kersee, first at UCLA
before moving on to St. Louis in the late spring, when Kersee moved
his speed camp there. That work ethic is the best insurance Kraft
can have, although it didn't help him in the case of McGinest or
Johnson, who are weight room warriors themselves. Also, cornerbacks
with speed and cover skills traditionally play at a high level
relatively injury-free for many years.
</P>
<P>
   But the question persists. Is he worth the money?
</P>
<P>
   The great George Young, who ran the Giants' personnel operation
during their Super Bowl years and beyond before moving over to the
NFL office, used to say, ``That's the most redundant question ever
asked.'' His point was that no one is actually worth the money, and
on some level that's true.
</P>
<P>
   But that's what you get paid if you're at the top end of the
cornerback market these days. Perhaps a healthy Deion Sanders
exceeds him because of his speed, but we may never see a healthy
Sanders again. That being the case, who is a better cover corner
than Law at the moment?
</P>
<P>
   Weeeeeeeeeeeeeeeellllllll??????
</P>
<P>
   That's what I thought you'd say.
</P>
<P>
   So if Law avoids injury, the only thing that can turn this into
a bad investment is a loss of nerve or a reduction in will now that
at least $14.2 million of the money is in the bank. The former is
unlikely if you know Law, a player for whom the term ``hard-nosed''
could have been coined, and the latter doesn't seem likely for a
guy who has been demanding to cover the opposition's top receivers
since his rookie year under Bill Parcells.
</P>
<P>
   Injury is another matter, which is why New England now has $50
million reasons not _ I repeat, not _ to grant Law his request to
return punts. That is not, as in not under any circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   For a reason, one need only cite the season-ending knee injury
to the Giants' Jason Sehorn a year ago on his first and only punt
return. But that is not the only reason.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders remains the best cover corner in the league in most
people's minds, but he clearly asked too much of his body for too
long and now both he and the Cowboys are paying the price. His
injured toe continues to keep him in street clothes and his body
seems to be turning on him. Baseball had something to do with that,
but so too did being asked to return punts and play wide receiver
and make half the field disappear whenever the Cowboys were on
defense. A body _ no matter how finely tuned _ can take only so
much, and this the Patriots need to remember even as Law continues
to agitate for a wider role on offense, which is sure to continue
if the team struggles.
</P>
<P>
   Why? Because Law easily could play cornerback for years without
facing a career-threatening injury. That's true if one simply goes
by the NFL's actuarial tables, which have become favorite reading
in some corners of the Patriots' front office.
</P>
<P>
   But put Law back to catch a punt, and the odds against staying
in one piece take a quantum leap. With a $50 million gamble made on
Law _ and a $25 million one on Johnson's body possibly already lost
_ it's time for common sense to enter the equation.
</P>
<P>
   There are those who would argue that paying someone who has had
just one Pro Bowl season in four years and has averaged only 4 1/2
interceptions a season already flies in the face of common sense,
and they might be right because no one can know what that
team-record signing bonus might do to a player's will. But the
Patriots are betting that Law was a man of his word when he said
Friday afternoon, ``When I retire, five years later I want to be
inducted into the Hall of Fame.''
</P>
<P>
   That is a lofty goal and will require many more years like last
season. Clearly, Law has the gifts _ the speed, the agility, and
the temperament to cover fast men _ and has reached an elite level
through a combination of offseason work and tireless film study.
</P>
<P>
   If the money doesn't change that and injury doesn't derail him,
Law may have his wish answered when his career ends. If so, Kraft
will have had his prayers answered.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   While Akili Smith and the Bengals continue to war over the size
of the rookie quarterback's contract, incumbent Jeff Blake declared
this week that the battle, if there was ever going to be one, is
over. While Smith and agent Leigh Steinberg continue to reject the
Bengals' contention that much of the money should be tied to
playing time and performance incentives, Blake said the rookie's
three-weeks-and-counting holdout has cost him any chance of
becoming a productive player this season. ``It's impossible,'' said
Blake. ``He could get by on athletic ability but that will only
take you so far. That's why they have training camp.'' Owner Mike
Brown agrees, claiming that a rookie quarterback who misses camp is
assured of being on the bench all season . . . Speaking of Blake,
he may not have touchdown twin Carl Pickens to throw to anymore but
he doesn't mind aiming at Darnay Scott, either. With Pickens
threatening a year-long holdout, it has been predicted that Scott
could blossom. He and Blake connected for a 66-yard touchdown
against Indianapolis in the exhibition opener. While Blake has
thrown 43 touchdown passes to Pickens in the last five years, he's
also chucked 15 to Scott, with eight of them being 38 yards or
longer . . . On Aug. 14, Byron and David Boston made NFL history
when they became the first father-and-son team to be an official
and a player in the same NFL game. When the Cardinals' rookie
receiver caught his first career pass right in front of his father,
though, he forgot what he was supposed to do. Not so with the next
catch, an 8-yard reception. He flipped the ball to his Dad, who
signaled a first down as the rest of their family cheered behind
the Cardinals' bench. The scene will not be repeated, however. The
league does not allow a father to officiate his son's games in the
regular season . . . Apparently, talkative Denver tight end Shannon
Sharpe now says he won't speak to the media this season. Sure he
won't . . . There is a quarterback controversy brewing but it's not
in Denver, where locals tried to speculate that Bubby Brister was
in some kind of trouble because of a poor performance in the first
exhibition game in Australia. Brister has taken this in stride, and
coach Mike Shanahan called ``ridiculous'' the idea Brister might be
beaten out by Brian Griese or Chris Miller. But believe it or not,
up in Buffalo there are forces already greasing the skids for Doug
Flutie. Flutie remains the starter, but factions within the
organization still like Rob Johnson better. Johnson is bigger,
younger, faster, and has a stronger arm. What he lacks is magic,
something Flutie had in abundance a year ago. But don't be shocked
to see things happen if the Bills' offense struggles or, worse,
Flutie gets hurt.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Curtis Martin never has been one to pop off, so perhaps what he
says should be taken seriously. If so, the Jets will be a problem
because Martin has been talking lately about rushing for 2,000
yards this season. ``It's not a selfish `me, me, me' thing,''
Martin says. ``This is a goal I've set with the team in focus and
not myself. If I can rush for 2,000 yards it would put us in the
best possible position to do what we all want to do this year.''
This comes at the same time that coach Bill Parcells and offensive
coordinator Charlie Weis are insisting they want to take some of
the load off him by giving Leon Johnson more carries . . . Not long
after Jacksonville wide receiver Keenan McCardell went down at
practice with what at first appeared to be a fractured leg, coach
Tom Coughlin was informed it was only a bruise. His reaction? He
made the sign of the cross . . . Size is everything in the NFL.
Even if you're not in the NFL. Just ask Willie Clyde Thomas, who
was arrested in Las Vegas after a five-month investigation by NFL
Security. It seems Thomas was getting free hotel rooms and other
comps in Las Vegas, including limo rides, by posing as various NFL
linemen. The 6-foot-7-inch, 305-pound Thomas was arrested at the
Fremont Hotel in a free room he got by claiming he was the Bengals'
Jamain Stephens. He also had gotten rooms in the past claiming to
be 49ers tight end Chad Fann. Don't you think somebody would have
asked the guy why he wasn't in training camp before they forked
over the key? . . . Although he's been nothing but a tease up until
now, the Chiefs' explosive Tamarick Vanover is getting another
chance to turn into a deep threat as well as a return man under new
coach Gunther Cunningham. Only half-jokingly, Cunningham said,
``We're going to get him the ball or I'll get some new coaches that
will. You think I'm joking? He's got to get the ball.'' Vanover
might have been happy to hear that but you'll never know. He's not
talking this summer. Former coach Marty Schottenheimer made Vanover
a starter in 1996 and he had a big day in the season opener with
seven receptions but he was injured the next week and was never the
same receiver. A year ago, they moved him to running back to
utilize his speed but that was a failed experiment so he's back at
wideout with the new head coach on his side, which can't hurt . . .
Speaking of the Chiefs, negotiations with No. 1 pick John Tait have
slogged to a halt and GM Carl Peterson now says it would be false
to even call it negotiating. The sides are fighting over making the
fifth year of his contract voidable, something Peterson is refusing
to do in part because he now says this will be a lost season for
the former BYU All-American tackle. Perhaps the Chiefs should have
seen this problem coming. When they were ready to draft Tait with
the 14th pick, they called and asked him to sign a six-year deal
before they made the pick. His agent refused. They then offered a
five-year deal. He again refused. They drafted him anyway. Tait was
not happy when the Chiefs tried to rush him into a deal while they
were on the drafting clock and those feelings were compounded when
the team refused to pay for an insurance policy to protect him
during minicamp.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If you're a quarterback in the NFL, you can expect to be
criticized. But by your wife? According to the Bears' nominal
starter, Shane Matthews, after he played poorly in Chicago's first
two exhibition games, his wife Stephanie told him he wasn't the
quarterback she was used to seeing. He didn't disagree, but who
wants to hear it at home after losing a starting job to a rookie
(Cade McNown) a month into training camp and now facing the threat
of losing the backup job to Jim Miller, who hasn't played in an NFL
game since 1996? . . . Although McNown appears to have taken over
as the starter, word is more than a few Bears veterans are upset
with what they feel is his constant finger pointing when errors are
made. After a loss to the Steelers last weekend, Chicago offensive
coordinator Gary Crowton spoke to his players as a group, urging
them not to point fingers, and many veterans believed the comment
was directed at McNown. This is a situation that may bear watching
in Bears land . . . Ryan Leaf can't seem to stay out of trouble in
San Diego. He not only got into a beef with a heckler in the stands
after a practice but told the local media, ``I just don't feel like
anybody wants me here.'' A year ago they gave Leaf a five-year,
$31.25 million contract. How much convincing does a guy need?
Believe it or not, despite throwing 15 interceptions and just two
touchdown passes last season, Leaf met the criteria to have his
contract voided after next season despite the fact that he's out
this year with a shoulder injury. That's because he was in for 35
percent of the Chargers' offensive plays last season and San Diego
won one more game than it had in 1997 (five instead of four).
Obviously there was no requirement that the offense actually move
forward while he was in . . . With all that's on his mind, you'd
think Steelers coach Bill Cowher would have more important things
to worry about than how many tailgaters have been displaced because
of a change in parking lot policy around Three Rivers Stadium.
Construction of the new stadium nearby has taken up enough space
that tailgaters are no longer allowed to buy several parking spaces
in prime lots near the stadium entrance and Cowher believes that
will hurt the team's legendary home-field advantage. Cowher claims
team buses having to drive through masses of Steeler fans jammed in
the lots was unsettling. And all along we thought it was Mean Joe
Greene and Jack Lambert.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Stat of the Week: Of the 108 playoff teams in the 1990s, only 15
have been led by a new quarterback, and none with a new face under
center have reached the Super Bowl. Only two QBs _ Joe Montana in
1993 and Vinny Testaverde in 1998 _ even took their teams to the
conference championship. Eight lost in the wild-card game on the
first weekend of the playoffs. If that holds true this season, at
least 10 teams already are eliminated from playoff contention . . .
Stat of the Week II: According to the Packers, they have just about
50,000 names on the waiting list for season tickets and only seven
moved off those rolls to become ticket-holders this season. At that
rate, it will take more than 7,000 years for the last person on the
list to get a ticket. That person is obviously an optimist . . .
Defensive end Chris Doleman, who declined an offer to come out of
retirement and return to the 49ers this summer, called his old team
and his old line coach this week about work. Doleman dialed up
Minnesota director of personnel Paul Wiggin to discuss the
possibility of returning to the Vikings but it's a long shot unless
he plays for near the minimum. Doleman is also talking with the
Redskins but has demanded a salary in excess of $3 million.
Although he had 15 sacks a year ago, Doleman is 37 and can play
only on passing downs . . . A veteran special teams player usually
knows the score in the NFL better than most people. That's why it
didn't come as a shock to Jim Schwantz when the Bears released him
even though he anchored the fourth-rated special teams unit in the
NFL a year ago. ``Teams won't keep a guy to cover kicks for what
the veteran minimum is nowadays,'' the former Pro Bowl special
teams player said. Schwantz led the Bears in special teams tackles
last year, a season in which that unit went from 27th in the NFL to
fourth. But despite that, the Bears could not justify paying
Schwantz $400,000 to run under kicks when they could have a younger
body do it for less than half the price . . . Not long after Colts
No. 1 pick Edgerrin James signed his seven-year, $49 million
contract in Indianapolis, he was asked if he was better than Ricky
Williams, the Heisman Trophy winner whom James was picked ahead of.
``Ask Mr. (Bill) Polian,'' James said. Polian is the Colts'
president and the man who decided to take James ahead of the NCAA's
all-time leading rusher . . . Speaking of the Colts, center Jay
Leeuwenburg was shocked to learn he had lost his starting position
to Larry Moore. ``I don't think they have the best five players on
the field now,'' said Leeuwenburg, who had started 37 straight
games. Indianapolis coach Jim Mora has built a new offensive line,
with Tarik Glenn at left tackle, Steve McKinney at left guard,
Moore at center, Waverly Jackson at right guard, and Adam Meadows
at right tackle. Moore and Jackson are new starters . . . Figure
this out. Fourteen members of the Buccaneers are sleeping on
special Select Comfort air beds at training camp while the rest of
the team is jammed into usual dorm room-size bedding. That includes
some guys sharing the same room. That must make for pleasant
conversation . . . Old friend Irving Fryar's three-year, $6 million
contract with the Redskins isn't quite what it appears to be. Fryar
received a $400,000 signing bonus and a $600,000 salary for this
season, but the likelihood of his being paid the remaining $5
million at age 37 is slim. Fryar had been working for a TV station
in Philadelphia at the Eagles' training camp when word came that he
had agreed to a deal with the Redskins. This led cornerback Troy
Vincent to say, ``Irv, we want the bike back.'' That was a
reference to the motorcycle given to Fryar by the Eagles at a
retirement ceremony . . . Speaking of the Redskins, coach Norv
Turner finally had no choice but to acknowledge the obvious: If his
team doesn't reach the playoffs, he won't be back. That's because
on Tuesday the George Steinbrenner of the NFL _ new owner Dennis
the Menace (I mean Daniel Snyder) _ said publicly he would fire
Turner if the team didn't make it to the postseason. This came
during a conversation during which Knute Snyder also criticized the
play of tackle Joe Patton. And people think Kraft is a meddling
owner? . . . Oft-mentioned but seldom seen running back Terry Allen
still isn't in New England, but he was in Detroit last week
visiting the Lions. Despite his injury history in recent years,
Allen would at least give Detroit a veteran presence at running
back. With Barry Sanders gone, the only back in camp who has an NFL
carry is Ron Rivers . . . Lawrence Phillips's debut as a 49er
Thursday night resulted in a dropped pass on the first ball thrown
to him and 6 yards rushing on three carries. Has it occurred to
anyone in the NFL that the guy just isn't that good? What he is, is
what so many other runners at Nebraska have proven to be: a product
of 300-pound linemen in front of them. Wait and see.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
