<HEADLINE>
ANOTHER LOSS LEAVES DIVISION HANDICAPPED 
</HEADLINE>
 NOTEBOOK-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON INDRISANO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The season-ending injury to Real Quiet, on the heels of
the retirement of Victory Gallop, leaves the handicap ranks in
shambles.
</P>
<P>
   The two 4-year-olds, who finished 1-2 in last year's Triple
Crown campaign (Real Quiet won the Kentucky Derby and Preakness,
Victory Gallop the Belmont), were the heart and soul of the
division for older horses. Now the 5-year-old Behrens is the only
handicap horse with any credibility left in training.
</P>
<P>
   Last Sunday, Real Quiet was training for the $1 million Pacific
Classic (at Del Mar Aug. 29) when he suffered a fractured splint
bone in his right front leg while breezing 7 furlongs at Santa
Anita. The minimum recovery time for such an injury is three
months.
</P>
<P>
   ``It probably happened in the work; he was fine until then,''
said trainer Bob Baffert. ``There was a little filling, and X-rays
showed a little crack at the top of the splint bone. We'll wait 90
days and see how it looks. He's finished for this year.''
</P>
<P>
   The fracture will not require surgery, but it would be
career-ending if it does not heal perfectly.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big thing would be to bring him back at the top of his
game,'' said owner Mike Pegram. ``If that can be done, he will
definitely be back. If not, he's going to go to that good life. We
are all hopeful he will come back. It's Bobby's decision, but we
hope he will be able to run in the year 2000.''
</P>
<P>
   The Aug. 13 announcement of Victory Gallop's retirement blew the
first big hole in the handicap division. He apparently tore a
suspensory ligament in his left front leg while defeating Behrens
by a nose, following a desperate stretch battle, in the Whitney at
Saratoga Aug. 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had a little filling behind the pastern,'' said trainer
Elliot Walden, who discoverd the injury Aug. 12. ``He had an
ultrasound, and it revealed a tear. He's too valuable a horse to
try to rehabilitate, and it would have been a six-month process. We
decided to retire him quickly. After doing the homework, it was the
right thing to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``The injury didn't really show up until he had a couple of days
of galloping. That's what happens with a soft tissue injury. It
might separate and tear during the race, but when they do something
on the track after the race, that's when the hemorrhage comes.''
</P>
<P>
   Victory Gallop, a son of Cryptoclearance, retires to stud at
Prestonwood Farm in Versailles, Ky., with a career record of
17-9-5-1 and more than $3.5 million in earnings. This year, he won
three of four starts, with a third in the $5 million Dubai World
Cup, and was a definite Horse of the Year candidate.
</P>
<P>
   If Real Quiet's career is over, he will go to stud at Vinary in
Midway, Ky. The son of Quiet American has a career record of
20-6-5-6 and more than $3.2 million in earnings. His last start, a
convincing victory in the $1 million Hollywood Gold Cup June 27,
seemed to indicate that Real Quiet was on the top of his game.
</P>
<P>
   The Pacific Classic, the closing event of the 11-race NTRA
Champions series, has been blown apart. Prior to the injuries,
Victory Gallop was headed to Del Mar to face Real Quiet for the
first time since the 1998 Belmont. That would have been drama. Now,
little-known local standout Mazel Trick, who won the San Diego
Handicap at Del Mar Aug. 7, will face talented 3-year-old General
Challenge, also trained by Baffert, and Malek, who always tries
hard but seldom wins.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Jim Bond, who trains Behrens, said his charge, who
numbers the MassCap at Suffolk Downs May 29 among his victories,
may not race again until the $1 million Jockey Club Gold Cup at
Belmont Oct. 9.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, the handicap ranks lost Silver Charm, the
1997 Derby and Preakness winner, and Free House, the 1998 Pacific
Classic winner and this year's Santa Anita Handicap victor.
</P>
<P>
   A division that once went five-deep has been reduced to a single
star.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Running Stag, the top dirt horse based in England, is returning
to the United States for the $300,000 Saratoga Breeders' Cup next
Sunday. Running Stag ran second in the MassCap, with Real Quiet
third, then put on a dazzling display to take the Brooklyn at
Belmont June 12. He returned to England and most recently worked a
half-mile in :48 at Lingfield. The 5-year-old son of Cozzene will
arrive in New York Monday to prepare for his Saratoga engagement.
Running Stag opened the year by finishing seventh in the Dubai
World Cup, then ran second in a turf race at Goodwood in Great
Britain before coming over for the MassCap. If he scores at the Spa
and stays in North America to race, could he become a leader in the
handicap division? The way things are going, maybe so . . . Harry
Vega, who won 10 races, was named Jockey of the Week at Rockingham
Park. Vega won three races on Sunday and four on Monday. As it does
each week, Coors Light donated $200 in the winning jockey's name to
the national Jockeys' Guild Disabled Riders Fund. Vega also won the
honor the opening week of the meeting in June . . . Plainridge
Racecourse plans to hold two major events in October. The harness
track will reintroduce the Beckwith Memorial Pace, which had been a
fixture at defunct Foxboro Park, and add the Pasquantonio Memorial
Trot. Details, such as purse and date, are to come.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
