</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-COWBOYS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATRIOTS BOUNCE BACK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ If it's progress you wanted from the second
exhibition game of the season, you got it.
</P>
<P>
   The New England Patriots, 20-14 losers to Washington in their
first exhibition game a week ago, rebounded with a solid 34-14 win
over the Dallas Cowboys on a drizzly, foggy Saturday night at
Foxboro Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   So bad was the weather, and perhaps the spirits of Patriots'
fans, that 9,476 didn't show up.
</P>
<P>
   But the 50,816 that were in attendance saw Drew Bledsoe, playing
all but the last two minutes of the first half, completing 13 of 19
for 147 yards and one touchdown, showing no signs of a mildly
sprained ankle incurred in the Washington game. Of course, as if
scripted, rookie quarterback Michael Bishop threw a late 36-yard
touchdown pass to Marshfield's Sean Morey, while also gaining 26
yards on four scrambles.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots' first team played much better on both sides of the
ball. Bledsoe connected with Terry Glenn five times for 85 yards
and one touchdown before giving way to backup John Friesz.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was as simple as wanting to score more points,'' said
Bledsoe of the Patriots' game plan. ``We knew they were missing
their corners and we thought we could get the ball downfield. We
accomplished that with Terry.''
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots' defense was also on target as defensive end Willie
McGinest, who was on the field for 17 plays, was able to make it
through the first half without injury and managed a key
second-quarter sack of Dallas quarterback Jason Garrett on a
third-down pass rush where he anticipated the snap count, got a
strong rush on tackle Oliver Ross, and swiped Garrett with his left
arm and brought him down.
</P>
<P>
   Rookie linebacker Andy Katzenmoyer, who played most of the game,
also looked much more comfortable in the middle, once blitzing and
altering a Troy Aikman pass. He also covered the backs well and
moved well from sideline to sideline.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like night and day with Katz,'' said Patriots defensive
coordinator Steve Sidwell.
</P>
<P>
   Safety Chris Carter, who replaced Willie Clay, picked off an
Aikman pass over the middle in the first quarter and returned it 16
yards to the Dallas 35.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots, playing without defensive tackles Chad Eaton and
Henry Thomas, got good efforts from backups Chris Sullivan, Garrett
Johnson, and Leonta Rheams. Rheams, the Patriots' fourth-round pick
last year from Houston, also forced and recovered a fumble.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, the Patriots did well in virtually every area except
running the ball. While they gained 127 yards as a team, rookie
running back Kevin Faulk managed only 17 yards on 11 carries. The
kicking game was both hot and cold as well, with Adam Vinatieri
booting three field goals (two from 42 yards, one from 40), but
missing another and coming up short on several kickoffs.
</P>
<P>
   A combination of Bledsoe's throwing, Troy Brown's punt returns,
and a turnover-conscious defense all played parts in a 14-7
first-quarter lead.
</P>
<P>
   After nickel back Kato Serwanga broke up a third-down pass by
Aikman on the first series, Brown took a 27-yard punt by Toby Gowin
and raced 27 yards to the Dallas 35. Bledsoe hit Glenn with a
21-yard fade down the right sideline to the 14. A 6-yard run by
Lamont Warren helped set up Faulk's second-effort, 2-yard run for
the first Patriots' score with 11:24 remaining in the first
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys came right back on the next series, marching 57
yards on nine plays. Emmitt Smith broke off a 21-yard run, and
Lawyer Milloy was beaten on passes to the fullback and tight end,
the latter to David LaFleur on a 6-yard scoring pass from Aikman.
</P>
<P>
   Brown put the Patriots back in good field position with a
22-yard punt return to the Dallas 37. Bledsoe went right to work,
finding Harold Shaw in the right flat for a 13-yard gain. That set
the stage for the most artistic play of the exhibition season, a
24-yard post to Glenn, who made one swift inside move on cornerback
Kevin Mathis and exploded to the end zone where he caught the ball
over his shoulder for the score.
</P>
<P>
   With 3:59 remaining in the second quarter and the first team
still in, the Patriots made it a 21-7 game.
</P>
<P>
   Starting at the Dallas 46, Bledsoe again picked apart the
Cowboys. He hit Shaw for a 5-yard gain and then went right back to
Glenn down the right sideline. The receiver made an outstanding
grab and managed to keep both feet in bounds for a 25-yard gain.
Glenn was slow getting up and was forced out of the game, but the
injury did not appear serious. Bledsoe threw successfully to Warren
for 11 yards and Brown for 8 before the quarterback found his
favorite target _ tight end Ben Coates _ for the first time in the
game on a 6-yard touchdown pass.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots added a 42-yard field goal by Vinatieri in the
third quarter after the offense went 47 yards on 12 plays, while
Dallas kicker Richie Cunningham missed from 35 with 3:11 remaining
in the third quarter. But the Cowboys scored with one throw, a
55-yard scoring bomb from third-string quarterback Mike Quinn to
Jason Tucker with two minutes remaining in the third quarter,
reducing the Patriots' lead to 24-14.
</P>
<P>
   Toward the end of the third, the crowd perked up when Bishop
entered the game. The rookie quarterback dazzled again, escaping
pressure and what appeared to be a sure sack by scrambling for a
16-yard gain on third down as the quarter ended. It led to a
40-yard field goal by Vinatieri early in the fourth. The kicker
missed a chance to add to the score later in the quarter, hitting
the left upright.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-22-99 0245EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
