u s BC-BBA-REDSOX-RANGERS-BO     08-22 1027
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RED </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED SOX' ROSE PLUCKED BY RANGERS 
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-RANGERS-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Two batters into the bottom of the first
inning, catcher Jason Varitek was at the mound, talking to Sox
rookie Brian Rose.
</P>
<P>
   Four batters into the game, pitching coach Joe Kerrigan was out
for a word.
</P>
<P>
   One batter into the fifth inning, manager Jimy Williams was out
for the ball.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, the slump Rose had vowed to break hadn't lost its grip
in Saturday &UR;  &LR; night's 9-2 loss to the Texas Rangers, who received
two more home runs and four more RBIs from Rafael Palmeiro
Saturday &UR;  &LR; night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where do we go? We have to figure that out,'' Williams said
when asked about Rose, who is 2-4 with a 7.90 ERA in his last 11
starts. ``I'm not going to change anything as we speak. He's still
in the rotation.''
</P>
<P>
   Rose trailed, 2-1, one out into the game, and 3-1 in the third
after Palmeiro took him deep on a 2-and-2 changeup that broke over
the plate instead of away. It became 4-1 after Rusty Greer led off
the fifth with another home run, hitting a 3-and-1 pitch that Rose
threw outside as he intended, but high enough for Greer, who likes
to go the other way, to get the barrel of his bat on the ball.
</P>
<P>
   The home run was the 14th allowed by Rose in the last 49
innings, a pace that not even John Wasdin, the man who relieved him
Saturday &UR;  &LR; night, has matched.
</P>
<P>
   ``He looks like he's lost some confidence,'' said Ken Macha, who
managed Rose in the minors and now coaches with Oakland, after
Rose's early departure in his last start.
</P>
<P>
   Rose didn't dispute the point. ``It's not hard to lose
confidence when you only pitch three innings in your last five or
six outings,'' said Rose, who has pitched five innings or fewer in
nine of his last 11 starts.
</P>
<P>
   ``When things are going good, you don't have to think about
much. When they're not going well, you have to try and fix it. It's
just a pain in the butt. I wish things would turn my way.''
</P>
<P>
   Palmeiro, who also homered Friday night and drove in three runs,
has six home runs in his last six games. His three-run homer off
reliever Rheal Cormier in the seventh was his 36th _ and 350th of
his career _ not bad for a guy who had two knee surgeries in spring
training.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never had any doubts about what I would be able to do,''
said Palmeiro.
</P>
<P>
   And yes, in case you were wondering, the Sox entertained the
idea of signing Palmeiro as a free agent last winter to replace Mo
Vaughn, but general manager Dan Duquette decided that there was no
point in getting into a bidding war with Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``It got a little serious, it did,'' Palmeiro said of his winter
talks with the Sox. ``But my main focus was to work something out
here or in Baltimore. This has always been home, even when I was
playing for Baltimore (for five years), I still lived here. So it's
nice to be home.''
</P>
<P>
   Greer hit his second home run of the game and the Rangers'
fourth of the night in the eighth inning off Bryce Florie, as the
AL West leaders collected a dozen hits in beating the Sox for the
second time in two nights.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, there's a crisis blooming in the Sox rotation, with
no easy solution in sight. No Bret Saberhagen. Ramon Martinez, the
one-man cavalry on the horizon, was lit up for six runs, including
three home runs, in five innings  &UR; last night &LR;  in Pawtucket. There
is always Pedro Martinez's stand-in, Florie, of course, but is this
any way to run a wild-card race?
</P>
<P>
   And Sunday night's starter, Tim Wakefield, will take the mound
against ex-Sox pitcher Aaron Sele with far more questions than
answers as he returns to the rotation after 14 weeks as the team's
closer.
</P>
<P>
   Not that Sox hitters did anything to take the pressure off their
beleaguered pitching staff in losing their third straight game and
fourth game in their last five.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox had a run two batters into the game when Jose Offerman
hit his league-leading 10th triple into the right-center-field gap
and scored on Darren Lewis's ground out. They then spent the rest
of the night squandering one scoring chance after another.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had the right people up,'' Williams said. ``It just didn't
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   They wasted Trot Nixon's leadoff double in the third. They
wasted Nomar Garciaparra's leadoff double in the fourth. They
wasted singles by Garciaparra and Varitek in the sixth, when pinch
hitter Reggie Jefferson lined deep to right.
</P>
<P>
   In the seventh, Rangers starter Rick Helling departed after a
leadoff walk to Nixon, and Offerman and Lewis singled off his
successor, Eric Crabtree. Mike Stanley, batting for Brian Daubach,
brought home a run with a sacrifice fly off reliever Mike Venafro,
but the fourth Rangers pitcher of the inning, rookie Jeff
Zimmerman, coaxed Garciaparra to pop out on the first pitch, and
came back from a 3-and-0 deficit to Troy O'Leary to retire the
slumping left fielder (1 for 27) on a fly ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to get him to chase,'' Zimmerman said of his faceoff
with Garciaparra, whose three hits raised his league-leading
average to .363. ``I know I'm not going to walk him. He's up there
swinging the bat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to go after him with 0-and-2 quality pitches, get him
to chase one out of the zone. I think he was looking away for a
slider. I threw him a fastball inside, which I think surprised him,
and I popped him up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've faced him three times, and he's made great adjustments
each time. The first two times, I threw him first-pitch sliders and
he made the adjustments, tried to hit 'em to right. That's why he's
the best hitter in the league. Against him, it's like playing mind
games.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, in the bottom of the inning, Stanley dropped Cormier's
throw after the pitcher had slipped fielding Rusty Greer's roller
down the first-base line. Stanley's error was followed by a single
by Juan Gonzalez, who had tripled home a run in the first, and
Palmeiro drained the night of any remaining drama by lining a home
run into the right-field seats.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still like us, though,'' Williams said. ``I still like the
way we're playing. We just need a good start.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
