<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-HOLLEY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLEDSOE'S GROWING MATURITY NO LAUGHING MATTER 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ Sometimes I wonder if he gets into his car,
blasts Everclear, and laughs hysterically about the silly things
said and written about him. Drew Bledsoe must have done that at
least once in the past six years. I am convinced of it.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots quarterback has been here since 1993. During that
time you may have heard that Bledsoe is not mobile enough. Not
tough enough. Taps the ball too much before throwing. Throws the
ball off his back foot too much. Won't be the same without Bill
Parcells coaching him. Won't be the same with Pete Carroll coaching
him. Doesn't scream enough.
</P>
<P>
   What you don't hear is that the 27-year-old Bledsoe now throws
the ball better than most of the men who play his position.
Quarterbacks are similar to pitchers _ they seem to get smarter as
they get older. Actually, they don't really get smarter; they just
have a better idea of what they're trying to do.
</P>
<P>
   All of this was obvious Saturday night at Foxboro Stadium, when
thousands of people watched Bledsoe and the Patriots practice
against the Cowboys. The NFL calls these matchups exhibition games,
but they are glorified warmups that happen to cost a lot of money
if you want to attend one. Many of the exhibition Patriots realize
they are simply borrowing the uniforms they wear, the same way you
borrow a tuxedo. The real football begins in September.
</P>
<P>
   But even in the Patriots' 34-14 practice win, Bledsoe looked
good. He threw 19 passes and completed 13 of them. He threw for 147
yards and two touchdowns in the first half. During the second half,
he stood on the sideline like a coach, wearing a headset. No one
ever questioned his arm strength. Now, if practice is an indication
of anything, there won't be many questions about the decisions he
makes, either. He is entering his seventh season. He has an idea of
what he wants to do.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday &UR;  &LR; night, he had a simple plan before he took the field.
He was going to attack the Cowboys' cornerbacks. Deion Sanders and
Kevin Smith were hurting. And although third-year man Kevin Mathis
is a starter, he doesn't cause quarterbacks or receivers to worry.
Late in the first quarter, Bledsoe and Terry Glenn made Mathis look
bad.
</P>
<P>
   ``Terry beat him so bad at the line of scrimmage that (Mathis)
had no chance,'' Bledsoe said.
</P>
<P>
   After beating Mathis on an outside route earlier in the first
quarter, Glenn took him inside and scored easily on a 24-yard play.
The next quarter, going against Cowboys second-teamers, Bledsoe
decided that he was going to pass to tight end Ben Coates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rod Rutledge tried to come in the game on that play, but Ben
sent him out,'' Bledsoe said with a smile. ``That should have been
the first clue.''
</P>
<P>
   Some things have changed since Bledsoe's rookie season. But he
has consistently gone to Coates when he needs to make a play. He
saw him in the back of the end zone from 6 yards away and found him
again Saturday &UR;  &LR; night. It would be the Patriots' final score of the
half and give them 21 points in the first 30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the essential Bledsoe story is that an offense which he
directs will not have to suffer for long. I think of the 1994
season when I say that. That's when a young Bledsoe threw for 4,555
yards _ the eighth highest single-season total in NFL history _ and
25 touchdowns. He threw to men named Leroy Thompson, Kevin Turner,
Vincent Brisby, Coates, and Michael Timpson. For much of that
season, the starting running back was Marion Butts. Now, he is
surrounded by upgrades. He still has Coates and Brisby, but has
added Glenn, Shawn Jefferson, and a much more confident Troy Brown.
He has Tony Simmons and Kevin Faulk, too. He also has his
experience.
</P>
<P>
   Have you looked and listened to Bledsoe lately? He's not so much
of a kid anymore. When he first arrived in town, he was a single
man with a girlfriend who lived out of town. Now the girlfriend is
his wife, and they have a couple of children together.
</P>
<P>
   It should also be clear that he has helped his coaches just as
much as they have helped him. Parcells, a lover of the ground game,
is the coach who watched Bledsoe throw a league-record 691 times in
'94. Carroll, seemingly questioned about his job since he got to
town, simply handed the offense to Bledsoe (and coordinator Ernie
Zampese) and told him to create. That's smart. Bledsoe knows how to
throw. He knows how to throw well. That is indisputable. It can be
argued that he knows how to throw well, even when he is laughing at
his critics.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
