<HEADLINE>
JONES BELIEVES RIGHT CARD PLAYED WITH LAW 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL MCDONOUGH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ He is the father of Salary Cap Poker in the
National Football League and keeps a wary eye on all of the other
card players.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Jones knows better than anyone when to hold them, when to
fold them, and when to grab someone else's discards.
</P>
<P>
   So he watched the most recent ``big play'' in the NFL, the
Patriots' generous seven-year, $50 million contract, with a $14
million signing bonus, to cornerback Ty Law.
</P>
<P>
   ``I give them a thumbs up on that one,'' said Jones, the Dallas
Cowboys owner who isn't always so generous with his praise when it
comes to the way other teams spend money.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got three or four teams in this league that continue to
baffle me,'' said Jones Saturday &UR;  &LR; night, prior to his team's
exhibition game with the Patriots at Foxboro Stadium. ``These teams
continually give out big contracts to players who play positions
that do not warrant being paid what I call home run money.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, there are four positions on your club where the big
money should go, and one of those is cornerback, which is why I
applaud the Patriots for what they have done with Law. He is one of
the best in the game. They have locked him up for the rest of his
career.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, the four key positions are quarterback, left tackle,
cornerback, and wide receiver. But still, you don't give those guys
the big contracts unless you consider them Hall of Fame kind of
players.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at our club. We've got Troy Aikman at quarterback. He's
got three Super Bowl victories to his credit already. And we feel
he can still play six or seven years and be productive. So he
deserves the big money we have paid him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Deion Sanders, when he is healthy, is the best cornerback in
football. When we signed him away from San Francisco in free
agency, he won us a Super Bowl. And any time you win a Super Bowl,
making that kind of acquisition, regardless of the price, it is
worth it.
</P>
<P>
   ``You not only win the championship, but you make your team
special off the field as well as in the eyes of the fans. The
perception of how people think of you as a team is very important
as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``At running back and wide receiver we tied up Emmitt Smith and
Michael Irvin with big contracts when their time cam up. I think
Emmitt still has from three to five years of good play left; and
Irvin has several. I can't put a number on him as easily. Larry
Allen, who we signed as a left tackle, is considered by many people
the best offensive lineman in the game. Every one of these players
I mentioned has a chance at the Hall of Fame in my opinion, so this
is where we put our money.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones and son Steve, the Cowboys' director of player personnel,
have enjoyed a close relationship with Patriots owner Bob Kraft and
his sons, Jonathan and Dan. When Kraft bought the Patriots six
years ago, he was smart enough to have his sons visit Dallas and
spend time keeping up with the Joneses on how to operate a team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Back home in Dallas we have a setup in our building where we
chart every team in the league and what they are doing. When anyone
makes a personnel move, whether it is a signing or letting someone
go, we study it and have our own opinion on whether they have made
a good move or not.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Patriots have been doing the right thing. They've been
giving the money to the people they should be giving it to and
letting guys go who in our opinion should be let go because it
would not have been smart to give them the kind of money they were
looking for.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones said the Cowboys have spent $180 million in signing
bonuses over the past nine years and feels they have played the
salary cap game well.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have three Super Bowls and if it wasn't for free agency
coming in when it did, we would have had a few more in our
opinion,'' he said. ``Because we had so many outstanding football
players, young players as well, on those championship teams, we had
to make a lot of critical decisions on who to keep and who to let
go.
</P>
<P>
   ``To do it right, you have to put your own value on every
player. Sometimes the player can get a lot more money from some
other team than you think he is worth. This is when you have to
bite the bullet and let him go. We've had more than our share of
those.
</P>
<P>
   ``But in our opinion we have kept the core of our impact players
_ Aikman, Sanders, Allen, Smith, Irvin. We have 10 players still
left from our first Super Bowl team and 15 more from our last. Yet
we still have one of the youngest teams in the league because most
of the rest of the players on our squad have three years or less
experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people think we are on the way down as a team. I don't
think that way at all. Now we have made our share of mistakes. We
didn't get the production out of Charles Haley that we thought we
would get from the money we gave him on his last contract with us.
I still can't believe he is back and playing football in San
Francisco. Jay Novacek cost us because he got hurt and couldn't
play again. Same with Tony Tolbert. There is no way you can predict
injury, but you have to be accountable for them and move on. In
this business you can't guess on something like that.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is all important that when it is time to make a decision on
a player, like New England had to do this time with Law, you have
the courage to pull the trigger. You can't second-guess yourself.
And you can't fold and be fearful of what might happen. You have to
give the player a contract and move on. When the time comes to
dance, you have to pay the fiddler. We just had to roll the dice
with Deion. He has had a serious foot injury and we had to decide
whether to extend his contract or cut our losses if he can't play
again the way he used to play. We decided to extend. If he doesn't
make it, we move on. Fortunately, we had been able to make some
accommodations in some contracts, that if it doesn't work out the
way we hoped, we get hurt but we don't get buried. If Deion can't
make it, it will hurt but we will survive.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones says he has no regrets over the way he has played his
cards.
</P>
<P>
   ``When free agency came in, we (owners) thought we had a hard
cap,'' said Jones, ``and I wished we really didn't. But then San
Francisco started playing with a soft cap and if we wanted to stay
competitive we had to start making some moves of our own. And we
did. But let me say this, after enough years of doing this, we are
back to a hard cap. Most of us have paid out so much money in
up-front bonuses, we can't stretch too much anymore. There are only
so many times you can keep on restructuring contracts before you
run out of room. Each year it seems like you have fewer dollars to
work with so it becomes more important each season that you make
the right calls on how to spend the money.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
