<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-KATZENMOYER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROOKIE'S OUTING IS PASSABLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ This time he looked comfortable. This time
he seemed to belong on the field. This time Patriots rookie Andy
Katzenmoyer displayed a hint of the linebacker he may become.
</P>
<P>
   Most of all, Katzenmoyer showed marked improvement from last
week. Improvement in a rookie from week to week is the true
barometer by which to judge his performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt comfortable out there,'' said Katzenmoyer, who played
nearly three quarters in the Patriots' 34-14 exhibition victory
over the Cowboys Saturday &UR;  &LR; night at Foxboro Stadium. ``Except for
my run reads, I felt I had a good handle on what was going on.''
</P>
<P>
   The rookie was thrust into the starting role when Patriots
mainstay Ted Johnson suffered a torn biceps tendon earlier this
month. In the Patriots first exhibition game nine days ago,
Katzenmoyer at times looked lost on the field _ as did the entire
defense against Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were all embarrassed by the loss to the Redskins,'' said
Katzenmoyer. ``This time we wanted to come out flying.''
</P>
<P>
   Tedy Bruschi symbolized the physical attitude of the defensive
unit by knocking Emmitt Smith 2 yards back in the first quarter,
and while Katzenmoyer was not as physical as his teammates, he
seemed to know his place.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just wanted to go out there and take my time and do my
job,'' said Katzenmoyer. ``It's been a long week of staying and
working hard on the field for me and all of us.''
</P>
<P>
   The improvement of Katzenmoyer's play was most evident in pass
coverage. In the first quarter, for instance, the rookie was a
virtual shadow on Dallas tight end David LaFleur. And when Troy
Aikman threw a bullet over the middle toward LaFleur, Katzenmoyer
leaped and knocked away the pass, forcing the Cowboys to punt.
</P>
<P>
   ``LaFleur's really tall and I had to jump for the ball,'' said
the Patriots' rookie. ``And I was happy to be where I should be.''
</P>
<P>
   Katzenmoyer also made a key play in the first half when his
number was called on a blitz. He forced Aikman into a hurried throw
on third down. ``I was kind of surprised because nobody picked me
up and I sort of hesitated when I got near Aikman,'' said
Katzenmoyer. ``But I guess he had to rush his throw.''
</P>
<P>
   Patriots coach Pete Carroll said he won't be able to give a full
evaluation until the usual coachly review of the tape, but Carroll
saw enough to say the rookie had improved markedly from his first
game.
</P>
<P>
   Katzenmoyer ``came through and he did some nice things out
there,'' said Carroll. ``His getting better is important to us.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to being very effective at pass coverage,
Katzenmoyer also made several plays on run defense. The rookie made
a crisp tackle on Tarik Smith in the first half. And was seldom
seen out of position. ``I'm trying,'' said the rookie. ``But we
still have a long way to go. At times I felt comfortable out there
and at times I didn't. But I felt more comfortable than I did last
week.''
</P>
<P>
   The rookie said he was proud of his pass coverage and that he
has to do better against the run. ``I like to be versatile,
covering passes and stuffing the run. And I feel the more versatile
I am the better I'll be. Right now, I just want to go out there and
do my job.''
</P>
<P>
   Carroll said the rookie made some plays that stood out.
</P>
<P>
   ``And,'' said Katzenmoyer, ``I have to keep on making those
plays.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
