<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-REWRITE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEAVER LIFTS TIGERS OVER ANGELS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(OPTIONAL: Adds quotes, details) 
By ANDREW BAGGARLY  
 San Bernardino County Sun  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ The Tigers are 27 games out of first place.
They have the worst record in the American League.
</P>
<P>
   But Jeff Weaver was feeling pennant-size goosebumps on his arms
Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   With more than 100 friends and family members in attendance, the
Simi Valley High graduate tossed seven shutout innings and won for
the first time since May 27 as the Tigers beat the Anaheim Angels
5-0 at Edison Field.
</P>
<P>
   ``It feels like a breath of fresh air to start over again,''
said Weaver, winless in 13 consecutive starts. ``It feels like I
have my feet back on the ground.''
</P>
<P>
   Combined, the Tigers and Angels are 49 games out. At this point,
they are playing to salvage what little pride they have remaining.
</P>
<P>
   But Weaver didn't have to search hard for his incentive. With
his parents in attendance for the first time since his major-league
debut April 14, the 1998 No. 1 draft choice allowed three hits and
struck out a career-high seven batters in breaking his six-game
losing streak.
</P>
<P>
   Weaver allowed just three singles, walked two and hit a batter.
Only one Angel, Orlando Palmeiro, got as far as second base against
Weaver.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was locking up right-handed hitters like he did at the
beginning of the season,'' Tigers manager Larry Parrish said.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels were shut out for the 10th time this season. Only the
Tigers (11) have been blanked more often.
</P>
<P>
   Angels starter Jarrod Washburn failed to match Weaver,
surrendering a run in the third inning and losing his composure in
the fourth when he gave up two singles and a double, then issued
four-pitch walks to Damion Easley and Bill Haselman _ all without
recording an out.
</P>
<P>
   The second of those walks forced home the Tigers' third run and
drove Washburn (0-2) from the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I exploded, didn't I?'' Washburn said. ``I can't explain it. I
thought I had pretty good stuff, but in the fourth, I just blew
up.''
</P>
<P>
   Washburn allowed three runs on six hits and two walks in
three-plus innings. His line would have been worse had not reliever
Al Levine come in with no outs and stranded all three baserunners.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels like the fact that Washburn is young, left-handed and
can throw three pitches _ fastball, curve and changeup. But he
hasn't escaped the fourth inning in either of his two starts this
year, and his ERA has risen to 8.56.
</P>
<P>
   ``I honestly don't feel any different than last year,'' Washburn
said. ``I'm not intimidated to be in the big leagues. I've been
here before and I've been successful. But my command has been
terrible.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is that I'm not pitching very good.''
</P>
<P>
   The game was a nightmare for normally sure-handed Angels
shortstop Gary DiSarcina, who committed a career-high three errors
and admitted after the game that he was suffering from a dead
shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   DiSarcina bounced a throw in the first inning and committed two
gaffes in the eighth. He threw wide to the bag on a Juan
Encarnacion grounder, then bounced a potential double-play ball off
his chest, loading the bases with nobody out.
</P>
<P>
   DiSarcina was hit by a pitch on the shoulder last week in
Chicago, and he tweaked the arm again while making a diving play
Friday night. He probably won't be in the lineup today.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a pretty helpless feeling when you have a ball in your
hand and don't know how to get it over there,'' DiSarcina said.
``It's a pretty sure sign something's sore.''
</P>
<P>
   DiSarcina wasn't about to ask out of the game, but after the
third miscue, he glanced toward the dugout.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know when hockey teams pull their goalies?'' he said.
``That did cross my mind.''
</P>
<P>
   DiSarcina committed nine errors in his first 51 games this
season, and made 14 errors all of last season. The three errors
were the most by an Angel since shortstop Spike Owen made three
against Texas on Aug. 5, 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Huson pinch-hit for DiSarcina leading off the eighth.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-22-99 0251EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
