<HEADER>
A5591 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-ANALYSIS     08-22 0878
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-ANALYSIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER FALL, GLENN SHAKEN, BUT STIRS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ There was silence when there should have
been cheers Saturday &UR;  &LR; night, because you can't cheer while you're
holding your breath.
</P>
<P>
   It was late in the second quarter of a meaningless exhibition
game with Dallas that the Patriots were dominating when the air
went out of New England's football fans. Terry Glenn had just made
a leaping catch on the sidelines for a 26-yard gain _ his fifth
catch of the night _ and he tumbled to the ground in apparently
unspectacular fashion.
</P>
<P>
   He fell down, people thought at first. Happens all the time in
this game. So what's the big deal?
</P>
<P>
   Then Glenn didn't get up, and it got awfully quiet in
Foxborough. The fans have seen what happens to the Patriots'
offense when Glenn doesn't get up. When he doesn't get up for a
long time, the offense doesn't, either.
</P>
<P>
   As Glenn lay motionless on the 16-yard line, flat on his back
just 19 yards from where Pete Carroll stood stunned, stiff, and
staring downfield at a crumpled heap of hope, two doctors sprinted
into action. They squatted down and spoke with Glenn, but the
fragile touchdown maker didn't move. The silence grew more
frightful.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn had just spent nearly half a game making obvious to even
the most untutored observer why he remains the most important
Patriot on offense this side of Drew Bledsoe. Glenn had already
turned poor Kevin Mathis inside out like a reversible raincoat
twice, beating the Cowboys' cornerback upfield on a 21-yard fade
route two minutes into the game and then toasting him with one
quick outside step and then an inside fly by that the Blue Angels
couldn't have executed any faster a few minutes later.
</P>
<P>
   On the latter play, Mathis never caught up to Glenn as he pulled
in a 24-yard touchdown pass from Bledsoe that gave the Patriots
their second score, 38 seconds after they'd gotten the ball back
from the Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   In all, Glenn had accounted for 85 receiving yards, a 17
yards-per-catch average on a slippery track. He had left his fans
bellowing his name after he had slowly walked over to the ones who
filled the end zone stands to exchange hugs and smiles after his
touchdown catch.
</P>
<P>
   But now Glenn was on his back _ a position he's been in more
often than he's been in the end zone the last two seasons _ and no
one was smiling anymore. Hyperventilating, perhaps, but not
smiling, because the season was on the ground on a wet August night
and no eyes could look away, although none could bear to watch,
either.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is such a weapon when he's on the field,'' Bledsoe said
later. ``If this had been a regular-season game, they never would
have blitzed the way they did and left Terry one-on-one with those
corners like that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless it was Deion (Sanders at corner), they wouldn't have
taken those chances. Now other teams will see what happened, and
they won't take those chances, either.''
</P>
<P>
   That's the power of Glenn when he's healthy, which is why
Carroll surely was thinking of the broken ankle last year that
sidelined Glenn and the repeated pulled hamstrings that hamstrung
New England's offense for too much of the past two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   As Carroll waited and watched, he thought what everyone in the
stands and Bob Kraft up in the owner's box were surely thinking,
whether he was ready to admit it later or not. He was thinking the
only thing you could think.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, no,'' would be the polite way to categorize what was
surely running through his mind, although that's probably not a
literal translation.
</P>
<P>
   Then, slowly, Glenn got up. It is the only thing he does slowly,
but he finally did it, and a sigh echoed throughout the stadium,
briefly blowing away the gathering gloom.
</P>
<P>
   Under his own power, Glenn walked to the sidelines, sat down on
the bench, and was surrounded by medical attendants and concerned
teammates. Among them stood the grizzled veteran Ben Coates, who
has played with more pain in his career than Evel Knievel ever did.
</P>
<P>
   He stood over Glenn for a while, saying little but offering the
kind of support your big brother gives you the first time you learn
for real what a punch in the nose feels like.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him, `You better get up,' '' Coates joked later. ``He
don't always get up, you know, but we need him to. He jumps so damn
high all the time that when he comes down, sometimes he can land
kind of funny. I need him to get up to get that double coverage off
of me. He can do that.''
</P>
<P>
   With similar thoughts on the minds of most of his teammates,
Glenn finally leaned back and smiled as the stadium lights
reflected off his diamond earring. When he did, Coates was
satisfied and walked away. Minutes later, The Season was wearing a
Patriots' cap and sitting alone on the bench, safe and sound.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was all right,'' Glenn assured the world soon after, a smile
on his face. ``I just came down awkward and hit my head. Nothing's
wrong with me.''
</P>
<P>
   Nothing's wrong, Glenn said, and all New England started
breathing again. The storm had passed. Although he would not play
again Saturday night, Glenn was what the Patriots most needed.
</P>
<P>
   He was in one piece.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
