<HEADLINE>
MCGINEST RACKS UP A SACK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE BURRIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ Dallas Cowboys backup quarterback Jason
Garrett dropped back to pass from shotgun formation on third down
Saturday night. Willie McGinest closed in. The Patriots' hulking
defensive lineman got the signal-caller in his grasp, held on while
fighting off a block, then pulled Garrett to the ground.
</P>
<P>
   Any questions concerning McGinest's rehabilitation from
offseason groin surgery were answered there.
</P>
<P>
   It was his only contribution to the Patriots' defensive
statistics. But it spoke volumes about the status of the team's
defensive mainstay in his first action of the preseason.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was great to see Willie make a great play,'' said Patriots
coach Pete Carroll following his team's 34-14 triumph over Dallas.
``We played him like he would have played the first game.''
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots coach praised his team for rebounding from a dismal
showing last week against Washington, and undoubtedly McGinest's
sack, which stalled a Cowboys second-quarter drive from the Dallas
16-yard line, keyed the defense's charge.
</P>
<P>
   ``He played for 17 plays,'' said Carroll of McGinest. ``For him,
we had 15-20 plays in mind. I'm really glad to see him make a great
play. I don't know about the rest of his play, but he did well on
third down.''
</P>
<P>
   McGinest seemed pleased with his output.
</P>
<P>
   ``It always feels good to get a sack. I knew I had him. I was
just trying not to let go,'' said the former first-round pick from
Southern California. ``It's kind of hard when you've got a
300-pounder on your shoulder. But it's just preseason.''
</P>
<P>
   McGinest, who is 11th all time in Patriots sacks with 30 1/2,
started the first six games of last season before a nagging groin
injury kept him out of seven of the next nine games.
</P>
<P>
   He finished the season with 24 tackles (including seven in the
team's last two games of the season) and ranked fourth on the team
with 3 1/2 sacks.
</P>
<P>
   Last March, McGinest, who has battled an assortment of injuries
the last two seasons (including hamstring and knee woes in 1997),
had surgery to loosen a groin muscle. He has participated in
practice, but did not play in last week's first exhibition game
against Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're bringing me along the right way,'' said McGinest, who
is looking to start in every game for first time since the 1996
season. He made his only Pro Bowl appearance that year.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he is waiting to see how the groin will respond to
contact, he fired back, ``I'm not worrying about the groin. I'm not
babying it. I'm out there going hard and I feel healthy.''
</P>
<P>
   McGinest keyed a Patriots unit that collected 50 total tackles
and two sacks for 14 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a start for us. We've got a lot more plays,''
McGinest said. ``We're coming together as a defense. We've got a
lot more work.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
