<HEADLINE>
ARMSTRONG FEELS IMPACT OF HIS VICTORY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN BICKELHAUPT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST DOVER, Vt. _ Lance Armstrong talks a lot about his cycling
_ how could he not, after becoming only the second American to win
the Tour de France? And he talks a lot about his experience
surviving testicular cancer.
</P>
<P>
   But though he's quick to say how much his Tour victory this
summer has meant to the Lance Armstrong Foundation, which he helped
found a year and a half ago, he's less eager to brag about his
personal impact on cancer patients _ how he contacts them, or what
he says.
</P>
<P>
   It comes out, though. One example of his work behind the scenes
showed up last month when he appeared on ``Good Morning America''
to talk about his Tour win. There via satellite was a little girl
in a hospital in Texas, a cancer patient whom Armstrong presented
with a mountain bike.
</P>
<P>
   Their relationship started about a year ago, when Armstrong went
to yet another autograph session in his hometown of Austin, Texas.
He greeted thousands of bike fans and some cancer patients, all of
whom had followed his incredible return to racing.
</P>
<P>
   As he spent a few hours saying hello and signing pictures, one
image kept nagging Armstrong. It was of the little girl who had
been first in line, who told the cyclist that she herself had
cancer.
</P>
<P>
   After he left the store, Armstrong said he had to get in touch
with her, but had no idea how. So he called every hospital in the
city searching for a Kelly Davidson and finally discovered the
12-year-old had been a patient at Children's Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the two have become pen pals. Armstrong sent her a
road bicycle last Christmas, and he presented her with another bike
on ``Good Morning America.''
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong tries to answer all the e-mails he gets from people
who contact him though his Web site (www.laf.org). But he does that
surreptitiously, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``I usually don't hear from the patients themselves, but from a
friend or relative,'' he said. ``So when I e-mail them, they're
amazed at how I got their address.''
</P>
<P>
   And though Armstrong wants to limit his letters to patients who
are suffering from the same kind of cancer he had, he's hearing
from people who have faced all kinds of obstacles. Like the man who
was trying in vain to lose weight and couldn't get himself to start
running until he was inspired when he saw Armstrong win the Tour.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong has been home only briefly, as his visit to the States
has included trips to New York, Los Angeles, and Washington, but
he's aware of how many people have been in touch with the
foundation wanting to make donations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Tour has been fantastic for the foundation,'' he said.
``The phones just kept ringing, they didn't stop.''
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong made a video appearance earlier this month when he
delivered a greeting to riders in Sturbridge, Mass., about to set
out on the Pan-Massachusetts Challenge to raise money for the Dana
Farber Cancer Institute.
</P>
<P>
   And if he's modest about his work, he's not modest about why his
feat has turned him into a role model. He knows his cycling
comeback serves as an example to people to show they can overcome
hardships.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's proven that we can survive, and it's proven that there
are success stories in a sad situation sometimes,'' he said. ``And
that we have to deal with those things now, of surviving, and
returning to life, returning to our family, and returning to
work.''
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong said that, aside from the illness itself, one of the
most debilitating consequences of cancer is the feeling of despair
that attacks the patient, even after he or she has recovered. For
him, it meant abandoning a bike race in Europe and returning home
to Texas, where he kept his bike packed up in the garage for a
month.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not easy being a sick person and being treated,'' he
said. ``Because when you come out and realize maybe you're going to
live, then what are you going to do?
</P>
<P>
   ``You feel like you deserve a vacation, or you deserve to win
the lottery, or something like that, but it doesn't always
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   In his case, something big did happen with the Tour win, but
Armstrong insists he hasn't changed from the person he was a year
ago. Even though his whirlwind tour home has included a visit with
President Clinton at the White House and an appearance on the David
Letterman show.
</P>
<P>
   ``So it's been more hectic, but to be honest, I look at myself
the same way,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Mostly, he said, he hopes the Tour victory won't make him _ or
the fans _ overly confident about a repeat victory next summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope that next year, when I'm training in the spring and
getting ready for the Tour, that I can approach it like I did last
year,'' he said. ``That person was an outsider, who nobody expected
to win the Tour. I hope I can still approach it with the same
hunger.''
</P>
<P>
   That hunger is what has brought Armstrong to Mount Snow, where
he's trying another kind of bike racing. For the rest of the
season, in fact, Armstrong has put aside his road bike and is
focusing on mountain bike racing. After Vermont, he'll ride the
Tour of the Rockies stage race at the end of the month in Steamboat
Springs, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   And even though he might resume off-road races next year,
Armstrong quashed any speculation that he might try to go to the
Olympics in Sydney for both road racing and mountain bike racing.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, I don't deserve to go,'' said Armstrong, who hopes to
represent the United States in the road race time trial. But not on
the mountain, though Armstrong has more than proven his ability
this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``These guys _ the best Americans _ are better than me,'' he
said. ``So I'm really not considering that.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Armstrong can revel in being the best American _ make
that the best rider _ in the most prestigious bike race in the
world.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
