<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RED </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MINOR SETBACK FOR RAMON MARTINEZ 
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-MARTINEZ-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY WHITESIDE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PAWTUCKET, R.I. _ In his days with the Dodgers, righthander
Ramon Martinez was a legend. Saturday night, he was all too human.
</P>
<P>
   On his latest stop on the comeback trail, Martinez, 31, took
such a pounding from the Triple A Buffalo Bisons that it appears
just wishful thinking that he will resume his major league career
in time to help the Red Sox in their wild-card chase. To most of
the 7,156 who braved the cold and steady drizzle at McCoy Stadium,
the one positive thing he did in the Pawtucket Red Sox' 6-1 loss
was show up on time. No controversy about that.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez, however, merely shrugged off his poor performance in
which he gave up six hits, including three home runs, and lasted
just five innings. He clung to the fact that the Bison only got to
him in the second and third innings, saying the rest of the time he
had good command. He threw 77 pitches, walked two, and struck out
three.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel a lot of progress was made,'' said Martinez, who made
the ninth start of his rehabilitation program. ``I gave up a couple
of homers. But the way I feel about the way I threw overall is very
good. I'll be ready for one more start down here in five days.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the last three starts I pitched good. But tonight I was
facing a different level. Some major league batters. Even though I
gave up the home runs and walked a couple of guys I didn't worry
about the score. I was worried about how I feel and how I
responded. I said to myself I didn't want to give up the four runs.
It kind of challenged me. That's a good thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez gave up home runs to three former Red Sox farmhands _
Bill Selby, Jeff Manto, and Mark Whiten. The first two wouldn't
have left Fenway Park; the one by Whiten was last seen heading
toward Cape Cod.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whiten is a guy with a lot of power,'' said Martinez. ``I've
faced him before and the pitch I threw didn't go where I wanted it.
That's usually what happens when you make a mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez said that unlike his outings against the other minor
league clubs (Single A and Double A) this one tested him, and he is
anxious to see the tape.
</P>
<P>
   ``My delivery hasn't changed,'' he said. ``But sometimes I get
lazy a little bit and lose my location. I wasn't real consistent.
But I feel much better about the last couple of innings. At the
moment, no one expects me to throw at 95 miles an hour. This is
going to take a little time. I won't get my 95 back again, but I
might be able to throw 92. I've been throwing in the high 80s and
that should be good enough to get some people out. I will get
better.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez thinks he's right on schedule for a return to the big
leagues. One more start should get him to Boston. That decision
will be up to Red Sox general manager Dan Duquette and vice
president of scouting Wayne Britton, who were both in the stands
Saturday &UR;  &LR; night. Neither was available for comment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had some movement on the ball,'' said Martinez. ``That's not
a problem. I have to make some mental adjustments because I don't
have my full fastball. Once you hit the location, it doesn't matter
how hard you throw. Today I threw the changeup and slider for
strikes. I'm not like my brother (Pedro) who can throw three or
four pitches for strikes. I'll let it go but I can throw harder
than I did today.
</P>
<P>
   ``You worry a little. You don't want to start at 90-92 miles an
hour and get hurt. But I can handle it. With the kind of stuff I
have right now, I can pitch. A lot of guys throw 80-82 miles an
hour with good location, good breaking pitches. That's all you
need. I've been around long enough to know how to handle myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez had been building up to this start since June 21, when
he began his rehabilitation program. Before that he was limited to
throwing on the sideline. His first assignment was a two-inning
stint for Lowell against the New Jersey Cardinals. And even though
he struck out three batters, the Sox were in no hurry to rush him.
</P>
<P>
   The next stop was the Gulf Coast Rookie League, where during a
17-day stint Martinez made four starts, pitching 13 innings with a
1.38 earned run average. In August, he moved to Single A Sarasota
of the Florida State League. There he had a 1-0 record in 12
innings of work. In his last start for Sarasota, Martinez worked
five innings in an 8-3 victory over the Port St. Lucie Mets. In
eight starts in his rehabilitation program, he was 2-0 with a 2.00
ERA. He had 27 strikeouts and 10 walks.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday &UR;  &LR; night, Martinez seemed to be on his game in the first
inning, facing only four batters _ he issued a walk to Selby. But
the next two innings were a nightmare. The first batter he faced,
Chris Turner, he hit with a pitch. Then he walked third baseman
Russell Branyan. A single to right by Whiten loaded the bases.
Turner and Branyan scored on ground outs.
</P>
<P>
   Buffalo made it 6-0 in the third. Martinez's stuff didn't fool
anyone, allowing the home runs to Selby, Manto, and Whiten.
</P>
<P>
   ``He finished strong,'' said Pawtucket manager Gary Jones, ``He
seemed to turn it up a little bit the last two innings and threw
the ball pretty good. He located his pitches and kept it down in
the zone. I know it's not the majors but guys at the Triple A level
have a lot of experience. They can do a lot of damage.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
