<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-IRWINDALE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IRWINDALE PIT FIRE LEAVES TWO CREW MEMBERS HURT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEITH LAIR  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRWINDALE, Calif. _ Austin Cameron became the ninth winner in 10
NASCAR Winston West events Saturday night in a race marred when two
Norris Racing crew members were burned in a spectacular pit
explosion.
</P>
<P>
   Donnie Butts of Buena Park and Dave Valdez, residence unknown,
were transported to two area hospitals. There conditions were not
available.
</P>
<P>
   First-time NWWS driver Manabu Orido of Yokohama, Japan, spun on
the entrance to the pits, tapping the outside wall. He turned
around, reached his pits just past the starting line and was taking
on fuel when the rear of the car exploded.
</P>
<P>
   Valdez, a crew member for Eric Norris' car, ran over from the
next-door pits to help clear other crew members and a rolling tire
that was briefly on fire. He was taken to USC County Hospital via
helicopter. Butts, who was the Orido fuel man, was transported to
Arcadia Methodist Hospital via ambulance.
</P>
<P>
   Valdez rolled across the asphalt on pit road, trying to put out
the fire, as a fellow teammate tried patting him down. He suffered
burns to his face, legs and arms. Butts, 37, was propped behind the
pit wall, suffering from burns to his chest and stomach. Neither
crew member was wearing fire-resistant material and both were in
short-sleeve shirts.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the CART and Formula One series, NASCAR does not make
fire-resistant suits mandatory in the pits.
</P>
<P>
   The $105,644 Snap-On 250 for the benefit of the City of Hope
race was stopped at Lap 146 for five minutes as a L.A. County
Sheriff helicopter was brought in to transport Valdez to the
downtown L.A. hospital, 18 miles away.
</P>
<P>
   It was the second most serious accident at the track this
season, the first under race conditions. During practice for
opening night, Mark Desmert of Roseburg, Ore. died when he went
airborne and hit the wall in Turn 4 in a midget car during a
yellow-flag situation.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's race, before a crowd of 5,857 people, was one of
attrition. There were eight yellow flags, for 88 laps. Seven cars
suffered tire blowouts in the early going, including pole-sitter
Sammy Patashnick. After 80 laps in the 250-lap race, seven of the
27 cars had been eliminated. Only 12 cars finished.
</P>
<P>
   The final caution came with 62 laps remaining, just three laps
after the final stop, when Austin, from El Cajon, took the lead
with the best pit stop. Jeff Murray of Alta Loma, who held off a
spin just out of Turn 1, had a tire go flat in Turn 4, causing a
six-car accident, although it only knocked out Brandon Ash, who
contended for the lead the majority of the race.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Richards led the race going into the final pit stops, but
Cameron got out first with Richards not among the Top 3. But
Richards, from Spokane, Wash., moved right back among the leaders
and challenged Cameron for the lead at the finish. But Cameron used
traffic to hold off Richards for his second win at Irwindale, by
0.516 seconds -- first in Winston West. Cameron had won a Super
Late Model race at Irwindale earlier this season.
</P>
<P>
   Richards said the Hoosier tires were OK, but third-place
finisher Butch Gilliland said they went flat because they were
running too hard at the beginning.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's real important to lay back and let the tires work,
Gilliland said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
