<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-22 14:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5632 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-EDIT-CYBERPRIVACY23-C     08-22 0399
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-CYBERPRIVACY23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Give Justice covert computer tool
 &HT;    By Joe Geshwiler
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   It sounds like a technique the ``Mission Impossible''
superspooks might have employed in their TV heyday: sneaking into a
villain's lair to install some miraculous gadget that would give
them access to his memos, diaries, financial records, etc. _ never
mind the codes he might use to conceal his secrets.
</P>
<P>
   In real life, the Justice Department is now preparing to do
precisely that. In legislation it has drafted for submission to
Congress soon, Justice will ask for authority to undertake covert
operations to plant devices that will override encryption programs
on targeted suspects' computers.
</P>
<P>
   Though many members of Congress are rightfully touchy on privacy
issues, this is one intrusive measure that merits their support.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department makes a plausible argument it needs this
additional power. Encryption software is used increasingly to hide
all manner of criminal activities: terrorist conspiracies, money
laundering, narco-trafficking, computer fraud, transmission of
child pornography. Little by little, this form of coding is
hampering its investigations, Justice maintains.
</P>
<P>
   This is a restrained course of action compared with an earlier
unsuccessful effort by FBI Director Louis Freeh to win legislation
requiring software makers to install so-called ``back doors'' that
would, in effect, allow authorized investigators to go around
encryption barriers. That was overreaching and would have equipped
Justice to cast far and wide on fishing expeditions.
</P>
<P>
   Authority for this new, covert initiative is strictly limited.
Approval must be given by a federal judge in the same manner he
would issue a wiretap order. By the way, recourse to eavesdropping
orders is infrequent; only 34 warrants were issued last year
allowing officers to enter a home or business to install a wiretap.
</P>
<P>
   This time it appears Justice is right in insisting its proposal
is ``consistent with constitutional principles.'' Just the same, if
and when it gets Congress' OK, the department should make it a
point to use this new investigative tool sparingly _ only when
absolutely essential.
</P>
<P>
   (Joe Geshwiler is a member of the editorial board of The Atlanta
Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
