</P>
<P>
   TURKEY-QUAKE (Istanbul, Turkey) _ With hope of finding survivors
of Turkey's devastating earthquake now all but gone, the Turkish
authorities are turning their attention to caring for survivors. By
Stephen Kinzer.
</P>
<P>
   TURKEY-SCENE (Yalova, Turkey) _ As the sun beat down on this
seaside resort, several dozen people spent the day Sunday watching
and waiting as noisy power shovels tore through a 50-foot-high pile
of debris that was a handsome apartment house less than a week ago.
By Stephen Kinzer.
</P>
<P>
   TURKEY-LESSONS (Istanbul, Turkey) _ Is Turkey going to draw any
lessons from this experience? By Celestine Bohlen.
</P>
<P>
   HONGKONG-PLANE-CRASH (Hong Kong) _ A Taiwanese jetliner
crash-landed and burst into flames during a tropical storm here
Sunday evening, killing two people and injuring 206, government
officials said. By Mark Landler.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-BANK-LAUNDER _ A look at the backgrounds of the two women
who work for the Bank of New York and who were involved with the
accounts that are the targets of a money laundering investigating.
By Timothy L. O'Brien.
</P>
<P>
   ERITREA-ETHIOPIA (On the Badme Plain, Eritrea) _ Rifle fire
still rings out and mortar rounds still drop down, but after 15
months of a particularly senseless conflict, the killing may in
fact stop soon along the disputed border of Eritrea and its larger
neighbor, Ethiopia. Eritrea has accepted all points of a peace
plan. Ethiopia is asking questions about only a few details. By Ian
Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   FRANKENSTEIN-FOOD (Piccotts End, England) _ While genetic
modification of food has been a relatively unquestioned phenomenon
in the United States and Canada, its arrival here has set off
alarms and united demonstrators from lapsed causes into a powerful
protest movement against what they call ``Frankenstein food'' and
the large multinational companies promoting it. By Warren Hoge.
</P>
