</P>
<P>
   GULF-HURRICANE (Corpus Christi, Texas) _ Coastal residents along
the Gulf of Mexico braced for Hurricane Bret, the first major
hurricane of the 1999 season, which whipped the sea with winds up
to 140 mph and was expected to hit somewhere along the Texas coast
Sunday evening. By Jim Yardley.
</P>
<P>
   NY-ARREST-RATE (New York) _ New York City police made more
arrests than ever last year, with crime decreasing for a 10th
straight year; but more and more of those people arrested have been
released before formal charges are brought. Last year, prosecutors
tossed out 18,000 arrests even before a judge reviewed the charges,
more than double the number of four years before. By Ford Fessenden
and David Rohde.
</P>
<P>
   FARM-FIELD-BURNING (Ritzville, Wash.) _ The decades-old practice
of field burning, used by farmers here and in many other parts of
the country as the cheapest, most efficient way to clear their
fields of stubble, weeds and disease-bearing pests, is under
increasing attack in many places, especially near cities in which
most residents lead lives that are not tied to agriculture. By Sam
Howe Verhovek.
</P>
<P>
   TAILHOOK-CONVENTION (Sparks, Nev.) _ Welcome to the post-scandal
Tailhook Convention, a sleepy mix of reunions, symposiums, golf,
cocktail hours and banquets, attended by an overwhelmingly older
male crowd that was all that remained after the Navy divorced the
infamous annual event and made it harder for active-duty officers
to attend. By Christian Berthelsen.
</P>
