<DOCNO> NYT19990822.0063 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-22 15:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5649 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-LINCOLN-CENTER-2TAKES     08-22 0960
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LINCOLN-CENTER-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SHOWCASE FOR DRAMA HAS A MIDDLE-AGE BOUT WITH AN IDENTITY
CRISIS 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By ROBIN POGREBIN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It was designed with grand goals: to be America's
national theater, on the level of the Old Vic in England or the
Comedie Francaise; to be a repertory theater with an impressive
troupe of actors in productions from the classic to the avante
garde.
</P>
<P>
   Now, as Lincoln Center Theater approaches the 35th anniversary
of its main stage, no one would say it has fulfilled that vision.
Instead, it has accumulated an oddly checkered record, creating
unassailable hits and unequivocal flops; attracting respected
leaders and testing their reputations, and going dark for six years
while its management fought over its future.
</P>
<P>
   Given this rocky past, the theater _ which includes the
1,000-seat Vivian Beaumont and the 300-seat Mitzi E. Newhouse _ has
come a long way; last season its productions were nominated for 16
Tony Awards and won 2. Nevertheless the contradictions in its
identity and mission persist.
</P>
<P>
   As he enters his eighth season as artistic director, Andre
Bishop _ who was the crown prince of nonprofit theater after
producing hits like ``Sunday in the Park With George,'' ``The Heidi
Chronicles'' and ``Falsettos'' in his 17 years at Playwrights
Horizons _ is feeling the pressure.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a hard road for me,'' he said, talking at his
Greenwich Village home. ``I was used to being everybody's
darling.''
</P>
<P>
   He continued: ``The problem for anyone who has the job that I
have is everyone wants Lincoln Center Theater to do what they want
you to do. At the same time, one cannot be all things to all
people.''
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, Lincoln Center Theater's coming season seems to
typify the poles it is pulled between. In December, ``Marie
Christine'' a new musical by the young composer Michael John
LaChiusa, is to open. Later in the season the theater plans to
produce ``Time of the Cuckoo,'' Arthur Laurents' 1952 drama.
</P>
<P>
   Bernard Gersten, who has served as executive producer since
1985, with Gregory Mosher before Bishop, said these extremes were
simply emblematic of the theater's range, which Bishop is
continuing.
</P>
<P>
   ``He grew up and spent his entire life at one theater, which had
a very discrete mission: the discovery, nurturing and development
of new American plays,'' Gersten said. ``When he came to Lincoln
Center, the mission altered. He was charged with running a theater
that had one 1,000-seat house and one 300-seat house, and making
them work. And he couldn't operate with the same repertoire and the
same playwrights.''
</P>
<P>
   Linda LeRoy Janklow, chairwoman of the theater's board,
dismissed the idea that it is a national theater, saying it can be
only the expression of an artistic director. ``You go with his
vision,'' she said. ``It has always been thus.''
</P>
<P>
   While Bishop, 50, gives the impression of being under siege,
this in part reflects his self-abnegating personality, and he said
he welcomed the challenge. ``I wanted to throw myself up against
the lions again,'' he said. ``And I was so lucky to go to Lincoln
Center. Even though, boy, you never rest easy up there. Ever.''
</P>
<P>
   Bishop, diminutive and scholarly, said he was proud of his
accomplishments, particularly with the Beaumont, a theater
complicated by acoustic and sightline problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I got the job I thought the big challenge was the
Beaumont,'' Bishop said. ``No other management has made it work.
What has been achieved there is continuity, enthusiasm, productions
of very high quality and the best directors in the country.''
</P>
<P>
   His supporters say the theater is in the difficult position of
trying to be a nonprofit operation that makes bold artistic choices
and a Tony-eligible entity that plays in the big leagues. (Lincoln
Center Theater also produces plays in Broadway houses, like David
Hare's ``Via Dolorosa'' last season.) And that, combined with its
central location, powerful board and Lincoln Center cachet leaves
the theater subject to greater scrutiny and tougher standards.
</P>
<P>
   With two sizable theaters, there are many seats to fill and
48,000 members to satisfy, each of whom pays $35 a year and $30 a
ticket. And like any nonprofit theater, Lincoln Center's must pay
its bills, which are high, with production costs that rival those
on Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're under the gun all the time,'' said the Broadway
producer Emanuel Azenberg. ``They have the same costs and the same
difficulties that the commercial theater has except they can't
afford failure.''
</P>
<P>
   And, theater professionals say, it is considerably harder to
develop work quietly with a budget of $20 million to $26 million at
Lincoln Center Theater than it was at the 140-seat Playwrights
Horizons, with a $4 million budget.
</P>
<P>
   Bishop is also up against the challenge for every nonprofit
theater, particularly those with aging subscribers: balancing
artistic risks with financial responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   He and Gersten seem to have the strong support of the board.
``Like picking money managers, you don't look at what they did in
the last five or six months,'' Ms. Janklow said. ``You look at what
they did over the last 10 years. And there's so much exciting and
interesting work that an occasional disappointment, you just chalk
it up.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the board seems to recognize the need to develop
more new straight plays. ``I think the board is now feeling that
perhaps it's good to open our doors a bit wider,'' said Daryl Roth,
the independent producer and a board member. ``I think we'll see
less of the old chestnuts, hopefully, in favor of new American
writers.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Some perceive Lincoln Center Theater as increasingly timid and
unexciting. Several producers, agents, reviewers, publicists, and
playwrights say the theater has abandoned its mandate by playing it
safe. Bishop is producing the work of tried-and-true playwrights
rather than gambling on new voices, they say, presenting straight
plays acquired from elsewhere, and in some cases making
compromising commercial alliances like its co-production of
``Parade'' with Livent, whose bankruptcy _ coupled with the
production's mixed reviews _ helped force the show to close.
</P>
<P>
   Although Bishop made his reputation by developing playwrights
like Wendy Wasserstein, Christopher Durang, Jon Robin Baitz and
William Finn, many say he has failed to nurture a comparable crop
of new voices at Lincoln Center, and that he has stuck with people
he knows, with classics and with middle-brow revivals like ``Ah,
Wilderness!'' and ``The Little Foxes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When he was at Playwrights, he was able to serve the artist
more,'' said James Freydberg, a Broadway producer. ``He's lost
because it's not what he does. What he was so successful at was his
ability to midwife artists and not have them in a situation of
having to please a large audience.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Even ``Juan Darien,'' the allegorical puppet show, was a
revival, some producers have pointed out. The theater's acclaimed
revival of ``Carousel'' was an import from London, as was Tom
Stoppard's ``Arcadia.'' And ``Parade'' originated with Livent.
</P>
<P>
   Bishop ``doesn't seem to be doing the kind of new plays that he
did at Playwrights,'' said Robert Brustein, the artistic director
of the American Repertory Theater in Cambridge, Mass., and the
theater critic for The New Republic. ``And it puzzles me because he
does have that Mitzi Newhouse. It's a nice theater for new plays,
and he's got impeccable taste.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps most striking, some directors and playwrights have said,
was agreeing last spring to have the musical ``It Ain't Nothin' but
the Blues'' move into the Vivian Beaumont after ``Parade'' closed,
the first time in its history that the theater has simply offered
itself up as real estate.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've gone the whole hog,'' said John Heilpern, who worked
as an assistant director to Sir Peter Hall at the National Theater
in London and is now theater critic for The New York Observer. ``It
is now apparently a theater for hire, and that's not what it's on
earth for.''
</P>
<P>
   Gersten replied that nonprofit theaters rent their spaces all
the time, and that it cost $30,000 a week to leave the house empty.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Some theater executives said that Lincoln Center Theater's
critical ups and downs _ ``The Heiress'' triumphed in 1995, ``God's
Heart'' bombed in 1997 _ have curtailed its artistic courage, that
the hits have trapped the theater into trying to repeat them and
the misses have made the theater nervous about taking a chance.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the argument goes, Lincoln Center Theater tends to
stick with what works, like having Gerald Gutierrez direct ``Ring
Round the Moon'' and ``Ivanov'' because he directed two hits in a
row _ ``The Heiress'' and ``A Delicate Balance'' _ or like
producing the reliable monologuist Spalding Gray, which the theater
plans to do again next season.
</P>
<P>
   There is generally accepted to be a scarcity of good new work
and every theater is hungry for it. But look at off-Broadway,
others counter, and there is strong material on which Lincoln
Center has missed out: ``Wit,'' ``Side Man,'' ``This Is Our
Youth,'' ``Killer Joe.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's clear that they are afraid of breaking in new American
playwrights at their theater,'' said one young playwright who
insisted on anonymity. ``They worry that the scale of their
productions and the scrutiny those productions undergo can place
too much pressure on a new playwright. Why they don't try to do
productions on a smaller scale, I can't imagine.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   This debate, however, may be Lincoln Center Theater's
birthright. In 1958 several theater professionals were asked to
weigh in with their ideas for the new theater in The New York Times
Magazine. Tyrone Guthrie, the director, wrote, ``A repertory
theater should not indulge in the highly speculative business of
producing new work,'' adding that a national theater, like a
national picture gallery, ``must keep a selection of great
masterpieces constantly in view.''
</P>
<P>
   Conversely, the actress Cornelia Otis Skinner suggested, ``A
theater presenting only the classics or near-classics would soon
take on the character of a museum, and while there is nothing wrong
with museums, the aims of a good repertory should be toward growth
and innovation.''
</P>
<P>
   Following his predecessors _ Elia Kazan and Robert Whitehead and
then Herbert Blau and Jules Irving _ Joseph Papp took over in 1973,
vowing to bring new American playwrights, black authors and rock
musicals to the stage. Subscribers canceled, and Papp left in 1977.
</P>
<P>
   Then, under Richmond Crinkley, the theater remained dark for six
of his seven years while the board sparred with Lincoln Center Inc.
over various issues.
</P>
<P>
   Although Mosher gets credit for reviving the theater in 1985, he
was called too Broadway-conscious because of crowd-pleasing
productions like ``Anything Goes'' and ``Speed-the-Plow,'' starring
Madonna.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Bishop said the work of new writers belongs in smaller theaters,
not in big ones like the Vivian Beaumont. ``Developing new writers
is a private process and should be protected and nurtured, not
thrown out into the limelight,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, he said one of his dreams was to have a third,
black-box space ``away from it all'' for developing new writers.
</P>
<P>
   If he is producing plays with mass appeal, Bishop said, it is
because he genuinely likes them. ``I have never considered myself
to be a radical,'' he said. ``I've always been attracted to
individual, idiosyncratic writers, but popular writers.''
</P>
<P>
   His theater gets points for producing new musicals like last
season's ``Parade,'' which won two Tony awards. And it has earned
the respect of some Broadway producers, including Rocco Landesman,
president of Jujamcyn Theaters, who in 1988 publicly accused
Lincoln Center of betraying its raison d'etre by being ruled by the
box office. ``I would like to see fewer British imports and more
American plays,'' he said. ``But Andre has brought a coherent
artistic sensibility to that enterprise.''
</P>
<P>
   Bishop said he was committed to doing new work, even if it is
the work of his old friends. He said he planned to produce new
plays by Tina Howe, Ms. Wasserstein and Baitz.
</P>
<P>
   Members of his old guard say Bishop should be commended for this
loyalty. ``I am moved by the fact that this man continues to
believe in me,'' Baitz said. ``When I finish writing a play, there
are three people that I give it to, and Andre is one of them.''
</P>
<P>
   The playwright Richard Greenberg added: ``Do we want playwrights
to have opportunities when they're young and nowhere to go when
they're old and mature? Not every theater should be about what the
28-year-olds are doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Bishop said he felt the heat and has done his share of
hand-wringing. But he also said he must ultimately trust his
instincts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone once said that being an artistic director is the
intelligent exercise of one's own taste,'' Bishop said. ``And that
is what I believe with all my heart and soul.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``If you start second-guessing yourself in advance, I
think you're done for.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
