<DOCNO> NYT19990822.0068 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-22 16:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5656 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-TEST-DRIVE25-COX     08-22 0640
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEST-DRIVE25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tundra ready for big horizons
 &HT;    All-new pickup from Toyota a quiet giant
 &HT;    By Russ DeVault
 &HT;    c. 1991 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Toyota may be tardy in coming to the big-pickup game, but its
all-new Tundra is definitely a player.
</P>
<P>
   The dictionary will tell you that tundra is a treeless arctic
plain, but your eyes and the seat of your pants will tell you that
a second meaning is a monstrous pickup truck with an engine to
match its size.
</P>
<P>
   Toyota has done about everything possible to Americanize the
Tundra, including building it at a new $1.2 billion facility in
Princeton, Ind. The Tundra has the features and some styling cues
of the big trucks marketed by Chevrolet, Ford and Dodge. Building
it in the United States enables Toyota to avoid the import tariff,
so its pricing can be competitive.
</P>
<P>
   The base V-6 Tundra lists for about $14,995, while the white
test truck with four doors _ Toyota calls it an ``access cab'' _
and shift-on-the-fly four-wheel drive listed for $25,585 and
totaled $29,617 after adding options and destination charge.
</P>
<P>
   The 4.7-liter V-8's advantages are obvious. It generates 245
horsepower at a strangely quiet 4,800 engine revolutions per minute
and 315 pounds-feet of torque at an even-quieter 3,400 rpm.
</P>
<P>
   Toyota has made the Tundra one of the quietest pickups on or off
the road. At highway speed, which the Tundra manages very easily (0
to 60 mph in about eight seconds), only the stiff ride and firm
seats really remind that this is a truck.
</P>
<P>
   With all that power, it can be a workhorse, too. The payload is
2,000 pounds, and the Tundra can pull about 7,000 pounds. The only
puzzler is why opting for the big engine means settling for a
6.5-foot bed, while the V-6 version can be had with an 8-foot bed.
</P>
<P>
   Its four doors mean the Tundra has a lot of flexibility for
moving people and cargo. Comparison shoppers will note that while
other manufacturers put the handles for the extra doors on the
jamb, Toyota puts them on the outside.
</P>
<P>
   The rear seat bottom folds up for access to the jack and other
tools and for storage. The rear doors swing back past a right angle
to provide good access.
</P>
<P>
   The cabin, fairly easy to enter because it has running boards,
is roomy enough, although the seating needs to be refined,
particularly in the rear. Optional cloth captain's chairs give a
good driving position and comfort for one passenger, and there's
plenty of storage with a center console and pockets on all four
doors. A minor annoyance is the optional visor mirrors that lack
covers and can be distracting when the visors are in use.
</P>
<P>
   The instrumentation, in keeping with Toyota's style, is simple,
and the controls are straightforward. Push buttons and rotary
controls are large and easily operated.
</P>
<P>
   Pound for pound _ and the Tundra's curb weight has about 4,400
of them _ it is a big truck with big power and big potential, but
there's nothing crude or rude about it.
</P>
<P>
   Test vehicle: 2000 Toyota Tundra two- or four-wheel drive,
four-door pickup
</P>
<P>
   Price as tested: $29,617 (base: $25,585)
</P>
<P>
   Drivetrain: 4.7-liter V-8 engine with 32 valves (245
horsepower), four-speed automatic overdrive transmission
</P>
<P>
   Safety features: dual air bags, side-impact beams, optional
power anti-lock brakes with daytime running lights, $630
</P>
<P>
   Other options on test vehicle: package with power windows and
locks, sliding rear window, dual extended sun visors, $1,060;
five-spoke alloy wheels with chrome wheel arches, $600; six-speaker
stereo with CD and cassette players, $250; captain's chairs, $75;
fog lamps, $100; bedliner, $298; carpeted mats, $106; towing hitch
and wiring harness, $435
</P>
<P>
   EPA figures: 14 mpg regular unleaded city, 17 mpg highway
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
