<HEADER>
A5668 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-GUNS-MAGS-MEDIA-850&AMP;A     08-22 1188
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUNS-MAGS-MEDIA-850&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIREARMS MAGAZINES FLOURISH DESPITE MOVES TO CURB GUN SALES 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ALEX KUCZYNSKI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Along with the highly publicized acts of gun violence the last
year _ including episodes in Littleton, Colo., Atlanta and Los
Angeles that received front-page newspaper coverage and 24-hour
news-channel surveillance _ comes a peculiar, and to some
disturbing, flowering of the gun media.
</P>
<P>
   From Guns &AMP; Ammo, which is owned by EMAP Petersen and is one of
the American gun industry's largest magazines, to
smaller-circulation titles like Shooting Times, owned by Primedia,
the gun magazines have enjoyed a minor but notable surge in
popularity the last two years. They are retooling their designs,
printing on better-quality paper and publishing articles about the
threat of rioting at the turn of the millennium. The combined
result is that the magazines are, for the most part, attracting
more readers.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the renewed interest in gun magazines follows the
vagaries of the gun manufacturing industry, which operates on the
principle that when gun violence raises the political pressure to
restrict gun sales, people rush out and buy more guns.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a curious thing, but the whole gun industry, for many
years, has thrived in an adverse legislative climate and withered
in a benign one,'' said Jan Libourel, the editor of Gun World: The
Total Journal of Firearms, which is published by Y-Visionary
Publishing Co. of Orange, Calif. ``It's very simple. Consumers get
scared that their guns won't be available. With that, the gun press
gets more attention.''
</P>
<P>
   Libourel said the market for gun magazines was robust, which
might seem odd considering signs that sales have plummeted _ to 1.5
million handguns a year in 1998 from about 4 million in 1994, he
said _ since the passage of federal laws in 1994 that banned an
array of assault weapons. ``I wouldn't say that the market for gun
magazines is booming,'' he said, ``but I would say that it is
definitely surprising.''
</P>
<P>
   The manufacture of guns in the United States, including
revolvers, rifles, shotguns, pistols and machine guns, has declined
precipitously since 1993, according to the Bureau of Alcohol,
Tobacco and Firearms. (It does not keep figures on sales.) In 1993,
5.2 million guns were manufactured; in 1997, the number had
decreased to 3.6 million. The number of guns imported in 1993 was 3
million; in 1997, the number decreased to 930,000.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the downturn, gun magazines remain the firearm
industry's favorite, and most uniformly supportive, marketing tool.
Negative reviews are rare, and advertisers provide a constant
stream of advertising revenue. Advertising pages in Guns &AMP; Ammo
were up by only 1 percent for the first half of 1999, compared with
the first half of 1998, but advertising pages in Handguns _ also
published by EMAP Petersen _ were up 19.4 percent for the same
period.
</P>
<P>
   Among the titles with circulations exceeding 100,000 are Shotgun
Sports, Guns, Handguns, Gun World, Combat Handguns, Petersen's
Rifle Shooter, Rifle &AMP; Shotgun Supershooting and American
Handgunner. EMAP Petersen _ the New York-based publisher of
consumer titles like Teen and Motor Trend _ is the largest
publisher of handgun magazines in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Skip Johnson, the group publisher of the Petersen Outdoor
division, which publishes 10 gun-related magazines, said Petersen
planned to keep the gun-magazine market growing, despite the
shrinking gun market.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've done a little bit better with all of the magazines in
the past year,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson argued that the magazines' popularity was unrelated to
gun violence. ``We believe that we can trace their success to
improvements in the actual magazines,'' he said. ``We have focused
on hiring better-quality writers. We've increased the package size
and added more four-color pages. We've started working closer with
the newsstand distributors so that the magazines are placed where
they are most likely to be sold.''
</P>
<P>
   Guns &AMP; Ammo's circulation has climbed steadily since 1995, when
it was 570,000, according to the Audit Bureau of Circulations.
Johnson said circulation was 610,000 in the first half of 1999.
Mediamark Research Inc. reported that figures from spring 1999
showed that Guns &AMP; Ammo's total audience was 5.8 million readers.
Shooting Times, which is published by Primedia _ also the publisher
of New York magazine _ saw its circulation rise to 205,000 in 1998
from 180,000 in 1995, according to the audit bureau, while Rifle &AMP;
Shotgun, published by Natcom Inc., was up to 120,000 in 1998 from
96,000 in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an area of writing that is superbly uncritical,'' said
Tom Diaz, the author of ``Making a Killing: The Business of Guns in
America.'' ``It's hypermarketing, and Guns &AMP; Ammo is the 500-pound
canary.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the only titles to suffer in terms of circulation is The
American Rifleman, a publication of the National Rifle Association
that is given free to members; its circulation dropped to 1,276,600
in 1998 from 1,716,700 in 1995, but that dip was caused in part by
the fact that the NRA started producing another magazine, American
Guardian, that is also offered to NRA members. They can choose one
of three magazines.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   And there are more gun magazines to come. In 1998, Petersen
began publishing two new gun titles: Petersen's Shotguns and
Petersen's Rifle Shooter. But 2000 will see a veritable bumper crop
of gun-related titles, many of them one-time publications EMAP
Petersen hopes to grow into full-fledged annuals, including Guns &AMP;
Ammo 2000 Annual Handguns, Guns &AMP; Ammo The Complete Book of
Big-Bore Handguns, Guns &AMP; Ammo Firearms for Law Enforcement, Guns &AMP;
Ammo Military Surplus, Guns &AMP; Ammo Modern Knives and two editions
of Guns &AMP; Ammo Fishing Annual. The company is also introducing a
gun title for women.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the magazines address gun violence, and some do not.
Libourel wrote in the August issue of Gun World that the Columbine
High School shooting spree was attributable not to the fact that
the teen-agers were able to obtain guns, but that they were ``a
couple of maladjusted weirdos with Nazi leanings.'' And in American
Rifleman, the name of Charlton Heston, president of the NRA,
appears on a monthly political column.
</P>
<P>
   But at EMAP Petersen, Johnson said Guns &AMP; Ammo was not concerned
with political opinion-writing, and indeed the magazine rarely
issues editorials defending handguns or assault weapons of any
kind.
</P>
<P>
   Samir Husni, a professor of media studies at the University of
Mississippi who closely tracks magazine trends, said gun journalism
appears to be thriving.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are more titles than ever before, and that's because
they are even more specialized,'' he said. ``Now you have specific
magazines for specific machine guns and magazines for assault
rifles and magazines for owners of Colt .45s and magazines for
women and guns.'' He added: ``Is it healthy? I don't know if it's
healthy for readers, but it's healthy for the magazines.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
