<HEADER>
A5669 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-FORD-AD-COLUMN-760&AMP;AD     08-22 1169
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FORD-AD-COLUMN-760&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: FORD FOCUSES ON ITS SPORT UTILITY VEHICLES 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By KEITH BRADSHER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Trying to establish a common brand image for its
ever-growing family of sport utility vehicles, Ford Motor Co. is
preparing to start next month one of the largest advertising
campaigns ever in the auto industry.
</P>
<P>
   After relying for nearly two decades on its ``built Ford tough''
theme for pickups, it has created a separate slogan, ``no
boundaries,'' for its sport utility models and will start
advertising them as a group, as well as individually. Because it
will also be putting three new sport utilities on the market in the
next six months, Ford and its dealers are planning to spend huge
sums on television, print and Internet ads.
</P>
<P>
   ``Collectively with our dealers, it'll probably be the biggest
thing we've ever done,'' said Jan Klug, marketing and advertising
manager for Ford brand cars and light trucks. ``It'll be
unavoidable.''
</P>
<P>
   Ford introduced the campaign at a gathering here that attracted
3,500 of the nation's 4,300 Ford-brand dealers. The dealers,
invited mainly to see the offerings for the 2000 model year, seemed
to like the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a good idea,'' said David Kruse, a Detroit
dealer, ``because you can go whenever you want, wherever you want
with these vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   The visual footage for the TV ads is usual fare for sport
utility vehicle spots _ men and women rafting rapids, hiking alpine
trails, climbing cliffs and mountains and leaping into pristine
lakes. Each ad shows all the models, with an extra emphasis on the
giant new Ford Excursion.
</P>
<P>
   The television ads will run particularly during athletic events
this autumn, and Ford plans to step up its sponsorship of sports
like downhill skiing. Ford and its agency for the campaign, J.
Walter Thompson, a subsidiary of WPP Group, are still working on
the print and Internet campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Klug refused to give the campaign's budget, but sport
utility vehicles are already among the most heavily advertised
products in the country. The most advertised automobile last year
was the Jeep Grand Cherokee, with $136.4 million in ads, according
to Competitive Media Reporting, a New York company that tracks
advertising spending. Ford and its dealers spent $63.7 million on
ads last year for the Expedition, $61.8 million for the Explorer
and $13.7 million for ads featuring the two vehicles together.
</P>
<P>
   Ford plans a new marketing approach inside its dealerships to
complement the campaign. The sport utility vehicle areas at
dealerships will be dubbed ``Ford outfitters,'' a name that will
also appear in the advertising. Ford will sell tents, backpacks and
other camping equipment at deep discounts to its dealers this
autumn, to be arranged around the vehicles in showrooms.
</P>
<P>
   The 1,000 largest dealerships in terms of sales will also be
offered whitewater kayaks and other, more elaborate gear, said
Joseph Collins Jr., Ford's brand manager for sport utility vehicles
and minivans. Ford will not enter the market for outdoor gear,
however, and customers who want to buy the equipment they see in
dealerships will be steered to companies that specialize in the
business, he added.
</P>
<P>
   The advertising and marketing program is ambitious partly
because of the new models Ford is introducing. The Excursion, the
world's largest sport utility vehicle, officially goes on sale next
month, but production began last month and dealerships are already
selling some of the first vehicles. The Ford Explorer Sport, which
will go on sale later this autumn, is a restyled version of the
two-door model.
</P>
<P>
   The Ford Explorer Sport Trac, which will reach dealerships early
next year, is technically a sport utility pickup. It is identical
to an Explorer back to the second rows of seats, but has a short,
open pickup truck bed in the back instead of an enclosed cargo
area. Ford will include the Sport Trac in its sport utility vehicle
advertising, partly to avoid competing directly with the Ford
Ranger Super Cab, a four-door pickup that it closely resembles.
</P>
<P>
   With so many new models joining the Explorer and Expedition,
Ford needed to establish a common brand identity for its sport
utility vehicles to contain advertising costs, Ms. Klug said. ``We
don't want to have to support every name plate with 40 million
bucks apiece,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   James Gregory, chief executive of Corporate Branding LLC, a
brand strategy company in Stamford, Conn., said that creating a
common brand made sense because of the sheer number of sport
utilities. ``It's getting to the point where its oversaturated, so
building an umbrella over the whole group is a brilliant idea,'' he
said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Advertising the giant Excursion with the Expedition and Explorer
may also help the smaller models. The Excursion, which weighs
almost twice as much as a Jeep Grand Cherokee, has attracted
considerable attention. Ford has already received orders from
dealerships for every one it will produce this year, despite
criticisms of the vehicle by safety and environmental activists.
</P>
<P>
   Ford also makes the Lincoln Navigator and Mercury Mountaineer
sport utility vehicles. But these will not be included in the Ford
brand advertising campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike some sport utility ads, Ford does not show any of its
sport utilities actually using their four-wheel-drive capability.
Instead, the vehicles are shown on paved roads or on dry, smooth
dirt roads that could be easily traversed in a car. Ford is working
with the National Park Service on a separate campaign urging people
in wilderness areas to ``tread lightly'' and inflict as little
damage as possible on the environment.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the vehicles' ability to cross rough ground is
suggested in the ads' narration, which is by John Corbett, a star
of the former television series ``Northern Exposure.'' During
mountain climbing scenes at the start of one ad, Corbett says,
``Out here, the stories unfold like a map, stories written across
the sky with the tip of an eagle's wing or read between the lines
of a sheer rock face.''
</P>
<P>
   After further scenes of outdoor adventure, Corbett concludes the
ad by saying, ``You'll need an outfitter for the journey, an
outfitter for your dreams. Introducing Ford outfitters, offering
you the most far-reaching sport utilities on Earth, created to take
you where the stories begin and never end.''
</P>
<P>
   Industry surveys have shown that most sport utilities are
actually used for commuting, running errands and other mundane
tasks. Collins acknowledged this to reporters here, saying, ``SUVs
are about image, they're about taking people where they want to go,
not necessarily where they really go.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, for all the adventurous sports depicted in the ads, Ford
plans to continue advertising during golf tournaments. ``Golf is a
huge interest for people who buy sport utilities,'' Ms. Klug said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
