<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-EMPIRE-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`CRUCIBLE OF EMPIRE': `REMEMBER THE MAINE,' AND SO THEY DID 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: Time, channel are for New York area; check local listings.
Production notes are at end of review.) 
(js) 
 By WALTER GOODMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The most ambitious early adventure of the United States in
creating an American empire, otherwise known as the
Spanish-American War, receives colorful treatment Monday night,
enlivened with period flavor, political contradictions and populist
enthusiasms.
</P>
<P>
   ``Crucible of Empire,'' a two-hour PBS offering narrated by
Edward James Olmos, begins with the closing of America's Western
frontier, leaving a vigorous young nation in search of ways to
express its energies outside its borders. Spain, that brutal but
faltering colonial power, became the chosen target; the restive
peoples of Cuba and the Philippines became allies of the United
States, or its pretexts. Theodore Roosevelt, before he became
president, spoke for the popular spirit when he said, ``I should
welcome almost any war, for I think this country needs one.''
</P>
<P>
   Opposition to such imperialist tendencies did not have a chance
against jingoists like the publisher William Randolph Hearst and
his star reporter, Richard Harding Davis, whose accounts of Spanish
atrocities stirred American outrage. The February 1898 explosion
aboard the battleship Maine, which killed 266 U.S. sailors in
Havana harbor, brought a new national slogan and new demands for
war. More than 1 million men responded to President William
McKinley's call for volunteers; among them was the young Theodore
Roosevelt.
</P>
<P>
   So America embarked on a two-ocean war, presumably in behalf of
Cuban and Filipino rebels, but in reality, as Monday night's
historians agree, in behalf of the nation's own ambitions.
Confusion was rampant, but the romance of warfare, featuring Adm.
George Dewey's defeat of the Spanish fleet in Manila Bay and the
Rough Rider charge up San Juan Hill, captured the nation.
</P>
<P>
   We are reminded that this was ``the first filmed war,'' and a
fake at that. Most of the pictures, one historian reports, were
shot on the roof of New York buildings with toy boats in bathtubs
and men blowing cigar smoke to simulate the smoke of battle.
</P>
<P>
   It was an ambiguous victory in which many more Americans died of
disease than in combat. Spain lost its empire, but the Cuban and
Filipino rebels were disappointed in their dreams of
self-government; the United States soon found itself encountering
rebellions against its rule.
</P>
<P>
   In a prescient prediction shortly before his assassination,
McKinley, no great fan of the war, alerted his countrymen to their
new global responsibilities as they began to compete in a world
market. The United States was ready to do business.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `CRUCIBLE OF EMPIRE: THE SPANISH-AMERICAN WAR'
</P>
<P>
   PBS, Monday night at 9
</P>
<P>
   (Channel 13 in New York)
</P>
<P>
   Daniel A. Miller and Daniel B. Polin, writers and producers;
Miller, director; Ted Winterburn, editor; original music and song
arrangements by T.O. Sterrett; Edward James Olmos, narrator; Sarah
E. Kramer, associate producer. Kenneth Mandel and Polin, executive
producers. Produced by Great Projects Film Company Inc. in
association with the South Carolina Educational Television Network.
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
