<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-22 16:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5673 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-CONDE-NAST-FASHION-AR     08-22 1021
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONDE-NAST-FASHION-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONDE NAST'S LATEST MOVE HAS FASHION INDUSTRY FIDGETING 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By ALEX KUCZYNSKI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In 1995, Anna Wintour, the editor in chief of Vogue
magazine, fixed her sphinx-like gaze upon her boss, S.I. Newhouse
Jr., the chairman of Conde Nast, and exhorted him in front of a
room full of Conde Nast publishing executives to buy Fairchild
Publications. The company had just been bought by Walt Disney Co.
as part of the Capital Cities acquisition, and Disney did not seem
a natural fit.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the fact that Ms. Wintour has long had Newhouse's ear,
he demurred. He was turned off, said a former Conde Nast executive,
by the prospect of owning dozens of decidedly unglamorous trade
magazines like Supermarket News, Brand Marketing and Footwear News.
</P>
<P>
   But on Friday, the fashion, advertising and magazine publishing
industries hummed with the news that Newhouse, whose company
publishes Vogue, Glamour, Mademoiselle, Vanity Fair, The New Yorker
and a dozen other sleek and stylish magazines, had offered $650
million for Fairchild, the publisher of Women's Wear Daily, W and
Jane magazines.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that seemed to grip most onlookers was that now Conde
Nast, a unit of Advance Publications, would control most of the
American fashion press, and with that would have the ability to
exert considerable influence over the $180 billion American apparel
industry.
</P>
<P>
   Newhouse's head had been turned, say Conde Nast executives, by
the rapid growth the last four years of W magazine _ which has
emerged as an ad-rich, provocative fashion title, combining aspects
of society gossip and lifestyle reporting.
</P>
<P>
   When the deal is complete, Conde Nast will own Vogue and W, two
of the country's leading fashion titles, along with the influential
trade publications Women's Wear Daily and Daily News Record, a
chronicle of the men's apparel industry. And only two fashion
titles in the entire country _ Harper's Bazaar, which is owned by
Hearst Magazines, and Elle, published by Hachette-Filipacchi
Magazines, a unit of Lagardere Group _ will be outside the Conde
Nast corral.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most powerful instruments in the fashion business are
Women's Wear Daily and Daily News Record,'' said Steve Klein,
managing partner at Kirshenbaum Bond &AMP; Partners, an advertising
agency that handles placement in magazines for major advertisers.
``So people are concerned about the fact that all of a sudden the
editorial influence that drives what is on the shelf and what sells
in the stores is in the hands of one company, that the business
power in the fashion industry is now in the hands of the Newhouses.
</P>
<P>
   ``The significant issue, the chatter,'' he added, ``is going to
be: Does so-and-so designer get preferential treatment in Vogue
because they are getting great reviews in Women's Wear Daily?''
</P>
<P>
   Women's Wear Daily _ a whisper-slim daily tabloid newspaper that
does not shy from bad reviews _ is heavily read and influential.
Michael Gould, the chairman and chief executive of Bloomingdale's,
said, ``More people in my business read it every day than they read
The New York Times.''
</P>
<P>
   Designers expressed cautious enthusiasm about the consolidation.
Kenneth Cole, whose footwear and clothing company earned $218
million in revenue in 1998, said the situation resembled a kind of
monopoly on style. ``The more participants, the more points of view
there are, the better,'' Cole said. ``I hope that objectivity does
not get lost here, and certainly there's that concern.''
</P>
<P>
   But John Bartlett, a menswear designer, said the dual ownership
would not make him uncomfortable. ``There are already a lot of
magazines under the Conde Nast umbrella, and they all have their
own personalities and editors,'' Bartlett said. ``It's more about
the relationships that you have at each magazine. To me it's about
getting on the phone with one person, not with an entire
conglomerate.''
</P>
<P>
   Other issues were bandied about in the brand-new Conde Nast
headquarters in Times Square in Manhattan. At Mademoiselle, staff
members speculated that they might be merged with Jane, the
Fairchild title for young women edited by Jane Pratt. (The editor
in chief of Mademoiselle, Elizabeth Crow, pointed out that Conde
Nast had plenty of magazines, like her magazine and Glamour, that
compete with one another, and said she did not see why merging
competitive titles was necessary.)
</P>
<P>
   And at Vanity Fair, editors applauded the decision, which will
guarantee that celebrated Fairchild photographers like Mario
Testino and Bruce Weber will now be permanent fixtures at Conde
Nast and not lost to Hearst or Hachette-Filipacchi.
</P>
<P>
   The acquisition comes as fashion magazines, scrambling for
advertising and readers, are rethinking their approach as they
consider the end of the standard high-fashion glossy featuring
remote cover models and inaccessible fashions inside.
</P>
<P>
   Fashion magazines now have retooled themselves, favoring
celebrities over models on their covers and adding more lifestyle
features, in part to mimic In Style, a celebrity fashion magazine
published by Time Warner's Time Inc. that has come to dominate the
marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   Katherine Betts, who takes over as editor of Harper's Bazaar
next month, has said she will focus on more of a lifestyle
approach. And Elaina Richardson, the editor in chief of Elle, has
already begun doing so, introducing a spinoff title this fall
called Elle's Ultimate Road Trip, a style and travel magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Uptown at Elle's publishers, Hachette-Filipacchi, Jack Kliger,
the company's chief executive, said he was glad his offers to
Disney had been rebuffed, because the final price tag for
Fairchild, under the stewardship of Patrick McCarthy, was
unreasonably high. According to industry analysts, the ABC division
earns about $25 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, we dipped our toes in the water,'' Kliger said. ``But we
found the water to be cold. And expensive.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
