A5676 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT &LR;      08-22 0424
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Monday, Aug. 23, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tropical Storm Bret will cross south Texas and move into Mexico
on Monday, bringing a vast swath of rainfall with it. While Bret
wrought havoc on the coast Sunday, inland locations will be hit
hardest Monday. Weak jet-stream winds above the former hurricane
will cause it to move slowly, allowing the system to drop very
large amounts of rain. Serious flooding will occur in places that
get continuous, heavy rainfall.
</P>
<P>
   Farther north, a low-pressure system crossing the northern
Plains will trigger showers and thunderstorms from Minnesota
southward along the Mississippi Valley. Some of the storms will be
strong, as a potent jet-stream disturbance at 18,000 feet will aid
in the development of the thundershowers. Gusty winds and hail will
be the primary severe element of the storms.
</P>
<P>
   Clouds and showers will also develop across the Southeast, where
a declining front will provide the necessary lift for pockets of
rain to grow. Some of the storms will provide briefly heavy rain,
as weak winds aloft slowly move the showers across the region.
Meanwhile, the Northeast will be partly to mostly sunny and will
turn warmer as high pressure slides off the coast of the Middle
Atlantic States.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the West will be quite sunny and warm, as a large area
of high pressure settles into the area. A weak disturbance aloft
will cross Nevada, bringing a few showers to the northern Sierra
and southern Cascades. A few showers are also possible over the
higher terrain of the intermountain West. Along the coast, offshore
flow will allow temperatures to rise to well above seasonal levels
in the Northwest.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Tornados and Hurricanes
</P>
<P>
   Tornado watches were issued near the southern Texas coast on
Sunday as Hurricane Bret approached the area. While hurricanes and
tornadoes are very different storms, hurricanes at landfall promote
the conditions necessary for tornado formation. All hurricanes have
tall thunderstorms that are the precursors of tornadoes. As a
hurricane moves over land, the low-level winds weaken more quickly
than the winds several thousand feet above the ground. The shifting
wind in the vertical, called wind shear, helps provide the twisting
motions that can be concentrated into a tornado.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-22-99 1713EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
