<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990822.0084 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-22 17:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5677 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-FILM-NOIR-FEMMES-ART-     08-22 1208
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-NOIR-FEMMES-ART-900&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THEY'RE GORGEOUS, MYSTERIOUS AND READY TO MAKE A SAP OUT OF YOU 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV:  Photo  is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By BERNARD WEINRAUB   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ Fifty years after playing femmes fatales and
hard-boiled dames in classic examples of film noir, those shadowy
mysteries often made by emigre directors, the actresses who starred
in them still receive fan mail almost daily. ``These films are very
big all over Europe, and lately Eastern Europe, and I still get
mail asking if I'm married,'' said one alumna of the genre, Audrey
Totter. ``They have no idea that I'm a grandmother now.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Totter, who is a spunky 80 and who starred in films like
Robert Montgomery's ``Lady in the Lake'' (1946), Robert Wise's
``Setup'' (1949) and John Berry's ``Tension'' (1950), is one of
four living actresses whose movies are among those being honored by
Turner Classic Movies this summer on cable television. (Probably
the best-known film noir heroines were Barbara Stanwyck, who died
in 1990, and Gloria Grahame, who died in 1981.)
</P>
<P>
   The other day, Ms. Totter was seated in the Formosa Cafe, a
restaurant on Santa Monica Boulevard that dates back to Hollywood's
golden age. She was joined by Marie Windsor, Coleen Gray and Jane
Greer, who played the gorgeous (often mysterious, sometimes deadly)
women who clashed with Humphrey Bogart, Robert Mitchum, Robert Ryan
and Sterling Hayden.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the reasons film noir is so popular today is that it
left so much to the imagination, in contrast to today when
everything is so explicit,'' said Ms. Windsor, 76. She played the
seductress in the John Garfield classic ``Force of Evil'' (1948),
directed by Abraham Polonsky, as well as similar roles in Richard
Fleischer's ``Narrow Margin'' (1952) and ``The Killing'' (1956),
directed by Stanley Kubrick. ``Everything was implied but not
shown,'' Ms. Windsor said. ``Film noir engaged the audience, let
them use the gray matter between their ears.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Gray, who confessed that even now, at 76, she is still upset
about having often been typecast as a ``good girl'' in those
movies, said that film noir was especially timely because the women
in them were not only tough but sometimes even had careers, seemed
totally disinterested in raising children and being homemakers and
were sexually provocative. (Of course major stars like Bette Davis
and Joan Crawford built their careers playing such women, too.)
``You never spoke of divorce or adultery in movies,'' said Ms.
Gray. ``If you were a married couple, if a man and women were in
bed, one of them had to have a foot on the floor.'' Ms. Windsor
added: ``And you could never show cleavage. And kissing was, well,
a little bit and they'd pan away. Silly.''
</P>
<P>
   Over lunch, the four spoke bluntly and fondly about the old
days, reminiscing about their favorite actors (Alan Ladd, John
Garfield, George Raft), one they didn't like (George Sanders) and
the studio moguls who had reputations for chasing starlets.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a meeting with Darryl Zanuck, and I was a little
nervous; he had a reputation for being a womanizer,'' recalled Ms.
Gray, who appeared in Phil Karlson's ``Kansas City Confidential''
(1952) and with Ms. Windsor in ``The Killing.'' ``The first thing I
did was walk in and say: `How do you do, Mr. Zanuck. You know we're
both from Nebraska. I'm from Staplehurst.' He was very nice. I was
almost disappointed.''
</P>
<P>
   Film noir _ French for black film _ emerged in the United States
around World War II with the influx of German and Austrian
expatriates like Billy Wilder (who made the noir classic ``Double
Indemnity'' ) as well as Fritz Lang, Max Ophuls, Otto Preminger and
William Dieterle. Along with other directors, like Joseph Losey and
Edward Dmytryk, they made movies that were often peopled by cynical
or desperate characters living in a venal and paranoid world, a far
cry from traditionally sunny Hollywood films. The films not only
represented the sensibility of their directors but the mood of the
times: the McCarthy era loomed, and there was a sense that turmoil
simmered beneath the nation's postwar exuberance.
</P>
<P>
   The visual style of noir films _ odd camera angles and harsh
shadows _ was influenced by German Expressionism, compounded by the
realities of movie production in the 1940s and '50s.
</P>
<P>
   ``In an industry where postwar economics dictated recycling of
existing sets, exploiting stock film libraries and generally
minimizing shooting times, the flexibility of film noir made it a
fiscally sounder proposition than many other types of motion
picture,'' according to ``Film Noir,'' a book about the genre
published in 1979 by Overlook Press. (For example, the dark
shadows, shot in high-contrast black and white, which marked most
such films, were often a way of hiding bare-bones sets.)
</P>
<P>
   Film historians consider Orson Welles' 1958 ``Touch of Evil''
the last true film noir, although a new generation of directors was
clearly influenced by the genre. These included Roman Polanski
(``Chinatown,'' 1974), Stephen Frears (``The Grifters,'' 1990) and
Curtis Hanson (``L.A. Confidential,'' 1997).
</P>
<P>
   The women who starred in these films, contract players at
studios like MGM, 20th Century Fox and RKO, said they were amazed
that the genre was currently popular in Europe, especially in
Eastern Europe with the fall of Communism. Ms. Greer said she was
recently offered a role by a German director who thought she was a
young woman. ``He'd have a heart attack once I stepped off the
plane,'' she said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Greer recalled that, recently, ``three tall, handsome blond men
_ all of them Germans'' showed up at her door one morning on a
secluded street in Los Angeles and asked to pose for pictures with
her. They said that they found her address on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ```Out of the Past' is very popular in Europe,'' she said,
recalling her classic 1947 film directed by Jacques Tourneur, in
which she played a woman who helps entangle a private eye, Robert
Mitchum, in a web of murder and double dealings. (The film was
remade in 1984 as ``Against All Odds.'') Ms. Greer said Tourneur's
directorial advice was amazingly simple: ``First half good girl,
last half bad girl.''
</P>
<P>
   With a few laughs the actresses recalled that their major
problem seemed to be that they were taller than many leading men
like Robert Cummings, Ladd, Raft and Garfield, whom they called
Jules, which was his real first name. The women said they would
sometimes play scenes with the actors standing on boxes.
</P>
<P>
   Even now, after all these years, they still spoke vividly about
the parts they missed and how they were sometimes frustrated by
being typecast. ``The bad girls were so much fun to play,'' said
Ms. Totter. ``I wouldn't have wanted to play Coleen's good-girl
parts.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course not,'' said Ms. Gray. ``Who would? Like in `The
Killing.' I was the good girl. It was frustrating! And Marie had
the big fat juicy part.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Windsor smiled. ``They were always the best,'' she said.
``You're quite right.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
