<DOCNO> NYT19990822.0090 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-22 17:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5683 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-MIA-BURIAL-TEXAS-HNS &LR;      08-22 1544
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIA-BURIAL-TEXAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
33 YEARS AFTER BEING SHOT DOWN OVER NORTH VIETNAM, NAVT PILOT WILL
BE LAID TO REST 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: Burial is Monday, Aug. 23) 
 
By JAMES PINKERTON 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   McALLEN, Texas _ From the outside, the old Cameron place looks
the same as always.
</P>
<P>
   The towering cypress tree still guards the end of the driveway
next to the U.S. flag, and Mexican pheasants still prowl the thick
brush of the 24-acre homestead on the north end of town.
</P>
<P>
   But inside, there is a new and unexpected mood in the quiet home
of Leona and Charles Cameron. More than 33 years after their oldest
son was lost in North Vietnam, he is finally home.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday morning, the family and friends of U.S. Navy Lt. Cmdr.
Virgil King Cameron will lay the young pilot to rest in Arlington
National Cemetery.
</P>
<P>
   His polished military casket will be carried to the gravesite on
an ammunition caisson; Navy jets will fly overhead, and he will be
honored with a 21-gun salute.
</P>
<P>
   The delayed interment with full military honors of the U.S.
Naval Academy graduate _ who was 27 when his plane was shot down
during combat over North Vietnam in July 1966 _ is a stirring
reminder of the uncertainty and grief still facing thousands of
American families.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, we were shocked, really, because we really didn't think
we'd ever receive that call because the circumstances of his crash
were bad and we knew his plane exploded on impact in a fireball,''
said Leona Cameron, the pilot's 84-year-old mother.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, it's been hard. We have grieved. But we never
agonized like so many people who thought perhaps their loved one
might still be alive and in the hands of their captors and being
tortured.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, there are 2,054 Americans listed as missing in action
from the war in Southeast Asia, including two more from the South
Texas city of McAllen. The remains of about 100 Americans are
currently undergoing forensic review by the U.S. Army's Central
Identification Laboratory in Honolulu, a Pentagon spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   The long wait has been difficult for Cameron's parents and four
younger brothers and sisters, not to mention his bride. The young
pilot had been married for only six months to his high school
sweetheart, McAllen native Ellen Watson, when he was shot down. She
did not remarry for 11 years as she waited for confirmation of his
death.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a godsend. It's sort of like a miracle,'' said Bill
Levingston, a college friend and Continental Airlines pilot from
Spring, Texas. ``I'm really happy for his family that they're
finally able to put this to rest.''
</P>
<P>
   Levingston plans to attend the service for Cameron, whom he
first met when they attended Schreiner Institute (now College) in
Kerrville, Texas, in 1957. Levingston, also a U.S. Navy pilot,
began his combat tour of Vietnam a few months after King was shot
down.
</P>
<P>
   During the years after Cameron's A-4E Skyhawk was lost over
North Vietnam, the family worked to bring attention to the growing
numbers of U.S. servicemen held prisoner or missing.
</P>
<P>
   They joined a national organization of the families of Prisoners
of War and lobbied Washington for the release of prisoners and the
return of the remains of those who had been killed.
</P>
<P>
   King's mother and father, Charles E.R. Cameron, a former McAllen
science teacher and longtime Immigration and Naturalization Service
inspector, helped organize a petition drive seeking a full account
of missing servicemen.
</P>
<P>
   The family photo album includes a picture of Charles and Leona
Cameron and daughter, Diane, delivering the petition signed by
25,000 Valley residents to then-U.S. Sen. Bob Dole in Washington in
1974. It was the same year the U.S. Navy declared that King was
killed in action, and the family held a memorial service in
McAllen.
</P>
<P>
   To call attention to the harsh treatment of American captives,
Charles Cameron even constructed a full-sized model of the crude
bamboo cages the prisoners were held in and pulled it down main
street during a Fourth of July parade.
</P>
<P>
   But it would take decades longer _ in May of this year _ for the
Camerons to receive the telephone call they had been waiting for.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was May 7th, the day before King's birthday, and they said
both blood tests were positive down to the last sequence. There was
no doubt about the match. That was a shock,'' Leona Cameron
recalled.
</P>
<P>
   In October 1998, Defense Department officials had asked Leona
Cameron and her daughter, Diane, to provide blood samples for an
identification process called mitochondrial DNA sequence analysis.
Although this form of DNA testing has been available for 15 years,
it was only approved in 1995 for use by Pentagon labs in
identifying human remains, said Larry Greer, spokesman for the
Defense Department's POW/Missing Personnel Office.
</P>
<P>
   At that time the family was told the Pentagon wanted the blood
tests to see if they would match a set of remains they suspected
were those of Cameron. The Vietnamese government had handed over 20
boxes of human remains on Sept. 13, 1990, Greer said. The Camerons
were told their son's remains were recovered from a roadside grave
where he had apparently been buried by North Vietnamese villagers
after the crash.
</P>
<P>
   On July 7, a trio of government officials traveled to McAllen
and presented their final report to King's parents and four
siblings, including the findings of DNA testing by the Armed Forces
DNA Identification Laboratory in Rockville, Md.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess we were amazed that something like that could be
done,'' said Drake Cameron, 57, a Houston geophysicist who works
for Exxon.
</P>
<P>
   Age 24 when his older brother was shot down, he recalled he was
on a seismic vessel in Tasmania when he called home and got the sad
news. ``We were all pretty devastated,'' he recalled.
</P>
<P>
   The family learned Cameron was on a mission to attack a barge or
other traffic on a river near the North Vietnamese city of Vihn,
and the jet fighter was hit by ground fire as Cameron swooped down
on the target.
</P>
<P>
   A wingman watched as the crippled plane crashed, exploding into
a fireball on impact. The wingman recalled seeing the sun shining
off the canopy of King's plane, an indication that he could not
eject, and a rescue helicopter did not pick up a distress signal.
Cameron's fellow pilots aboard the aircraft carrier USS
Constellation noticed the crippled plane never turned toward the
ocean, as pilots were trained to do, a sign that Cameron may have
been injured. And no parachute was spotted.
</P>
<P>
   Greer, the Pentagon spokesman, said the 8 1/2-year delay in
identifying Cameron's remains was likely caused by a lack of
supporting evidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we're fortunate we get from the Vietnamese (along) with the
remains, something that would indicate who this particular set of
remains may represent,'' Greer said. ``For example, they might tell
us that these remains were recovered at a specific location, and
the villagers might tell us it's from an American airplane that was
shot down on a specific date.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, he said, a military dog tag or identification card is
included with the remains.
</P>
<P>
   Without some clues or circumstantial evidence, the forensic
anthropologists may spend years ``piecing together a very complex
jigsaw puzzle,'' Greer said.
</P>
<P>
   He said that since January 1995, the Pentagon has identified the
remains of 170 servicemen from Southeast Asia who were once listed
as missing in action. Of that total, he said, 35 were from Texas.
Fifteen of those were identified through the same mitochondrial DNA
testing process used to identify Cameron.
</P>
<P>
   In the weeks since the family learned of the positive
identification, they have spent time recalling Cameron's life and
accomplishments.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was always busy on something, in school, then on hobbies
and so forth,'' said his mother. ``And of course, there was always
a lot of work around here. We had goats and cows, and he'd milk
them before school and deliver eggs to some of our customers in
town.''
</P>
<P>
   Charles Cameron, 93, said his oldest son was a serious but
fun-loving boy who raised white mice and kept alligators in an
upstairs bathtub. An early fascination with model airplanes led him
to join the Civil Air Patrol, borrowing a cousin's small plane to
log additional training hours. At age 16, he had earned his private
pilot's license.
</P>
<P>
   After graduating from Schreiner Institute in 1960, Cameron won
an appointment to the U.S. Naval Academy and earned the top
aviation award there.
</P>
<P>
   Drake Cameron, who flew to Hawaii last week to accompany his
brother's remains to Washington, said his family is grateful to the
government.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're pleased that they do these things for those who have
given their lives to their country,'' he said. ``The family just
wants to make this a time when we close this chapter in our family
history, and make it a time when King is honored, and to honor God
and country.''
</P>
<P>
   The pilot's mother said her faith tells her she will see her son
again.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're all students of the Bible,'' she said of her family,
``and that's where our faith comes from. That's why we feel sure
we'll see King again because we know he was a believer.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-22-99 1744EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
