<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-22 17:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5690 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-ALBEE-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT     08-22 1107
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALBEE-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE LOVE-HATE THEME IN ALBEE'S LIFE AND WORK 
</HEADLINE>
 (Eds.: Publication notes are at end of review.) 
 (William Wright is the author of ``Born That Way _ Genes, Behavior,
Personality'' and ``Lillian Hellman: The Image, the Woman.'')  
(ms) 
 By WILLIAM WRIGHT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It should not surprise us to learn that the author of the
searing ``Who's Afraid of Virginia Woolf?'' has had a turbulent
life, the vicissitudes of the personal side eerily paralleling
those of the professional one.
</P>
<P>
   Edward Albee was adopted by Frances and Reed Albee, who
cherished the infant but had no use for the boy, ultimately driving
him from their home when he was 20. Similarly, theater audiences
and critics were at first dazzled by the new playwriting star when
he exploded onto the New York theater scene in the early 1960s with
``The Zoo Story'' and ``Virginia Woolf,'' only to find that they
didn't care for the maturing, developing dramatist. The feeling
seems to have been that with his increasingly opaque plays Albee
was seeking one kind of obscurity but deserved another.
</P>
<P>
   Albee's personal war was with his mother, with whom he
reconciled, to a degree, three years after the success of
``Virginia Woolf.'' His war with the critics ended happily with the
triumph of his 1994 play, paradoxically about his mother, ``Three
Tall Women,'' which reinstated him as one of the country's top
playwrights. Devotion and rejection, kisses and slaps, raves and
slams: his life has pulsated with the love-hate rhythms that roiled
``Virginia Woolf.''
</P>
<P>
   All this Sturm und Drang has been well captured in Mel Gussow's
readable new biography of Albee, which lends the Albee spectacle
more drama and narrative shape than some Albee plays. Gussow, a
cultural writer for The New York Times, also provides an insider's
chilling view of the near-rejection and critical pummelings of
Albee plays that most critics now see as major works. Over the
years Gussow had many interviews with Albee and for this biography
was given access to his letters, files and scrapbooks. Albee
apparently asked nothing in return.
</P>
<P>
   In portraying the man himself, Gussow doesn't shirk from Albee's
alcoholic years of ``Virginia Woolf''-like verbal knifings of
friends and associates. Still, the man the biography portrays is,
in the end, likable _ touching, funny, compassionate, unafraid to
confront his demons, ironic about himself _ and never less than a
fully dedicated artist aiming for the highest theatrical levels.
</P>
<P>
   Gussow makes frequent allusions to the real-life models for
various characters in the plays. While this can be seen as the
biographer's duty, it can have a trivializing effect. When Albee
speaks about the use of his own life in his plays, he quite
admirably says his hope is that the truth he strives for
``transcends the personal and the private, and has something to do
with the anguish of us all.'' Too much tracking of real-life
inspiration by the biographer tends to drag the plays, and their
bids for universality, back down to the personal and the private,
spinning artistic gold into the straw of gossip.
</P>
<P>
   More serious is the absence in the book of a thorough critical
analysis of Albee's work and an effort to establish his place as an
artist. Throughout the narrative, Gussow dutifully quotes the major
critical reactions to the plays, both pro and con. In the process
he presents dismissive comments from important writers on the
theater like Walter Kerr, who wrote that ``Virginia Woolf'' was ``a
play with a sizable hole in its head'' and Robert Brustein, who
called Albee's plays empty. As these denigrations pile up, even
though outweighed by the many kudos (and three Pulitzer Prizes),
clouds of meretriciousness gather over the Albee oeuvre that Gussow
never dispels.
</P>
<P>
   Even the positive quotations refer less to a play's meaning or
significance and more to strengths like the verbal brilliance,
``the lightning flashes,'' ``the thunderclaps'': attributes that
suggest an MTV approach to serious drama. The criticism quoted
rarely addresses a play's underlying intent or Albee's success in
achieving a specific artistic goal.
</P>
<P>
   Such nagging concerns about the artistic coherence of Albee's
plays are not helped by a number of comments from Albee himself to
the effect that when creating a play he thinks about the characters
for long periods of time, then lets them write it. In his eventual
renunciation of one of his most cryptic plays, ``Tiny Alice,''
Albee admits he wrote it ``totally on instinct.'' Such
self-deprecations reinforce a sense that Albee plays simply happen,
sometimes brilliantly to be sure, but are not meticulously
constructed by a clear-eyed intellect as are the plays of Shaw,
Ibsen and Arthur Miller.
</P>
<P>
   As the critical dust rises in the course of this biography, I
assumed that before the end Gussow would step forward to settle
matters, or at least give his own critical appraisal and seek to
place Albee in the artistic firmament. I would expect this of any
biographer, but certainly one with Gussow's standing in his years
as a critic. Except for a few sentences on the last page, however,
such summary assessment never occurs. Instead, the book bogs down
in overlong discussions of casting decisions and directorial
flourishes in various incarnations.
</P>
<P>
   Although I do not feel these are minor lacks, they by no means
negate the value of this biography. We learn much about how
professional theater works in America, how reputations are made and
destroyed, the agonies of mounting a new play, the fatuous hidden
agendas ascribed to a serious author who happens to be gay.
</P>
<P>
   We are served up generous helpings of theater lore seasoned with
much wit from Albee and some from Gussow. We live through the
40-year struggle of a major dramatist to produce work that is fresh
and important. We are shown how an artist's lifelong obsession with
a formidable mother can embellish many of his dramas and culminate
in a first-rate play about her alone, ``Three Tall Women.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of all, Gussow succeeds, as do the best novelists and
playwrights, in portraying a many-faceted and engaging central
character who leads us through a series of gripping adventures. It
is almost a bonus that the story takes place against the
name-steeped glamour of Broadway and that its hero is one of the
important artists of this epoch who Gussow says, and many believe,
helped change the face of the American theater.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   EDWARD ALBEE
</P>
<P>
   A Singular Journey: A Biography
</P>
<P>
   By Mel Gussow
</P>
<P>
   Illustrated. 448 pages. Simon &AMP; Schuster. $30.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
