<P>
   HURRICANE COVERAGE
</P>
<P>
   CANE-BRET - Hurricane Bret is expected to make landfall along
the Texas Coast late this afternoon or tonight, and a storm surge
of up to 15 feet could flood low lying areas. (Dworin lead writer
with feeds from/Gamboa/Rivera/Stanley/Banta, Austin
American-Statesman). 40. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   NOTE: Reporters are in the hurricane warning area and attending
an EOC press conference with Texas Gov. George Bush in Austin.
American-Statesman photographers are in the Kingsville and Corpus
Christi areas.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   CANE-REFUGEES _ SAN ANTONIO _ Color story from San Antonio where
shelters are filling up with people fleeing the strongest hurricane
to aim at Texas in 20 years. (Alford, Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   NATION
</P>
<P>
   QUAKE-VICTIMS _ ATLANTA _ A report on the Mount Vernon Baptist
Church church service in Atlanta where the Kilic family, which lost
five members in the Turkish earthquake, worships. (Badie, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 12.
</P>
<P>
   COLUMBINE-PLEA _ ATLANTA _ ALance Kirklin, a survivor of the
Columbine High School shooting, visited an Atlanta-area church on
Sunday in hopes of raising money to pay his mounting medical bills
that could total more than $1 million. The lanky, blond-haired
young man strode confidently to the pulpit at Gospel Tabernacle
Christian Church, where he addressed several hundered worshipers.
``It's just amazing to me all the good people in this world who
don't even know someone but they want to help them,'' he said. ``I
just want to say thank you.'' (Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL-DEBT _ Remember the national debt? With all the talk of
a budget surplus that has consumed Washington in recent weeks, the
Concord Coalition says many people have forgotten that the nation
is some $6.5 trillion in the red _ and climbing. So the bipartisan
budget watchdog group has taken its National Debt Clock out of
storage and hit the road to remind the public that the government's
finances are not yet in order. The first stop on the two-week tour
was Sunday in downtown Atlanta. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
