<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-22 17:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5694 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-MUSIC-SPRINGSTEEN-BOS     08-22 0905
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-SPRINGSTEEN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPRINGSTEEN IS BACK 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and e coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOSEPH P. KAHN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Each summer, thousands of Americans pack up the family
car and take off for Mount Rushmore, driving through amber waves of
grain and ample miles of strip malls to gaze upon the likenesses of
four presidential legends who helped shape our nation's political
destiny. Washington. Jefferson. Lincoln. Teddy Roosevelt.
</P>
<P>
   Rock 'n' roll nation is no different in that sense. Each summer,
thousands of armchair rockers, casual fans, and committed
followers, graying baby boomers, and nose-pierced Generation X'ers
turn out to catch a handful of touring legends who have
reconfigured the pop music landscape. This year has brought Bob
Dylan and Paul Simon (together) to the Boston area, and before them
the Rolling Stones.
</P>
<P>
   This week, for a sold-out five-show run at the FleetCenter that
kicked off in raucous style Saturday night, it's Bruce
Springsteen's turn.
</P>
<P>
   The Boss is back, reunited with his E Street Band mates. To rock
mavens, it feels a little like a visit from the pope, or a playoff
series against the Yankees. Horowitz, backed by the New York
Philharmonic. Olivier, with the Royal Shakespeare Company, on tour
as Lear.
</P>
<P>
   Springsteen did not disappoint the faithful. He opened the show
with ``The Ties that Bind,'' as good a description as any of his
potent rapport with live audiences. Half an hour later, most of the
arena was still on its feet. He blasted through songs like ``Prove
It All Night'' and ``Darlington County,'' slapping palms with
front-row patrons and hugging bandmates. Sideman Clarence Clemons
blew his own wall of sound on the sax. It was as if they had never
left, although they did nearly a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   Meet the new Boss, same as the old Boss. Tickets are scarce,
anticipation is high, new Web sites are springing up. If history is
not in the making here this week, it is certainly on the mind of
local Boss buffs who have faithfully followed their guy since the
glory days of the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   Kathy Bradley, 40, a corporate secretary, says she fell hard for
Bruce back in 1975.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was in love with my girlfriend's brother, and I wanted to
like the guy he liked,'' recalled Bradley, dressed in a black
leather jacket. Though she never dated the friend's brother,
Bradley added, Springsteen's songs spoke to her own hungry heart.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was telling people that you can go out and do things,
giving you hope,'' she said, moments before a kindly stranger
upgraded her backrow seats to the first row. ``As a teenager, you
can relate to that.''
</P>
<P>
   That was a quarter-century ago for most of his fans, when
Springsteen, a wiry, working-class kid from New Jersey, was
anointed the ``future of rock'' _ and proved them (mostly) all
right for saying so.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Springsteen has married, divorced, remarried, and
started a family. He has become a multimillionaire, an
Oscar-winning songwriter, and a member of the Rock Hall of Fame,
his election to which last year was as much a lock as Joe
DiMaggio's trip to Cooperstown. He's about to turn 50, the
traditional age for midlife crises. And like many Boss fans, he is
celebrating his passage into middle-middle age by both looking back
and plunging ahead.
</P>
<P>
   What elevates Springsteen above the typical Jurassic Rock arena
act is the covenant he holds with his fans. There is simply no pop
idol around quite like him these days. Elvis was more mythic, Dylan
more enigmatic, and Sinatra far more of a multimedia force. The
tabloids have never lusted for Bruce the way they pant for Michael
Jackson or Madonna. It's doubtful that you'll ever see him do a
Super Bowl halftime show.
</P>
<P>
   Yet success has not seemed to spoil the Boss, either, nor driven
him into some neurotic shell of his former self. His working-class
anthems still ring true because their sentiments seem honestly
purchased. He may have a home in Los Angeles, but there's still a
lot of New Jersey in Springsteen. And he still touches the New
Jersey in all of us.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is music for the guy who loves Bud,'' said Scott Greene,
28, a marketing manager. Greene helped organize an Internet chat
group dubbed LuckyTown that met at the Harp Lounge prior to the
concert. The group has been extra busy this week, swapping
Springsteen tickets on line, one more indicator of how Bruce fans
have adapted with the times.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Weiss, 47, a property manager from Fort Lauderdale, Fla.,
flew into Boston on Friday holding tickets to two of this week's
shows. Weiss was also on hand for Springsteen's May 5, 1974,
Harvard Square concert, when Bruce opened for Bonnie Raitt, and
inspired critic Jon Landau (later Springsteen's manager-producer)
to pen his famous prophesy about having glimpsed the future of rock
'n' roll.
</P>
<P>
   Weiss, who wore a replica ``Born in the USA'' album cover belt,
said that to appreciate Springsteen you really have to see him and
his bandmates in concert. Few rock fans would quibble with that
assessment, especially those lucky enough to be holding tickets to
this week's shows.
</P>
<P>
   ``He writes about people's hopes and dreams,'' Weiss observed.
``And he does it with such dynamic passion. He gets it across to
everyone in the room, even if they're in the top balcony.'' Welcome
back, Boss.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe correspondent Ian Shapira contributed to this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-22-99 1758EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990822.0099 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-22 17:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5695 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-CHINA-DETAINEE-BOS &LR;      08-22 0561
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-DETAINEE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLLEAGUE OF MAN HELD IN CHINA RELEASED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By INDIRA A.R. LAKSHMANAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONG KONG _ While translator Daja Meston of Newton remained
hospitalized with injuries suffered under detention by Chinese
authorities, an Australian colleague was freed Saturday and flown
out of the country, officials and Meston's wife said.
</P>
<P>
   Gabriel Lafitte, 50, a researcher at the University of
Melbourne, was escorted by Chinese authorities on a flight from
Xining, the capital of Qinghai province in northwest China, to the
Beijing airport. Within an hour, he was allowed to talk to
Australian consular officials and call home, before being placed on
the next flight to Sydney, his wife, Helen Verran, said from
Melbourne.
</P>
<P>
   Verran said that in the moments she was able to speak to her
husband, his biggest concern was for a Tibetan man who had been
detained with him and Meston. After the men were detained last
Sunday, Verran said, the two foreigners did not see the Tibetan
man, a Chinese citizen, again.
</P>
<P>
   There were also unconfirmed reports Saturday that other
foreigners traveling in Qinghai, the site of a controversial,
proposed World Bank poverty-relief project, were also in custody.
</P>
<P>
   Lafitte ``obviously feels terrible that bad judgments or
mistakes he may have made may have put this Chinese national in
danger,'' his wife said, referring to the Tibetan who was detained
with them. She added that Lafitte had heard his American friend was
hurt, but ``didn't want to fill him in on the details. He's got
enough to worry about.''
</P>
<P>
   Meston, a Tibetan-speaking researcher who was traveling with
Lafitte, remained hospitalized in Xining Saturday, suffering from
severe injuries that Chinese officials say resulted from his
jumping from a third-story window while in custody on Wednesday.
Meston suffered a broken back, internal bleeding, and organ damage,
US officials told his wife.
</P>
<P>
   The US State Department has been lobbying for Meston's immediate
release but it appeared unlikely he could be moved in his current
condition.
</P>
<P>
   An American doctor who accompanied US consular officials to
Xining on Friday was allowed to examine Meston again Saturday, and
was consulting by telephone with a team of US doctors in Beijing. A
decision on whether to move Meston, based on discussions with
specialists, would be made within days, according to a source close
to the case.
</P>
<P>
   The source added, ``It looks like the Chinese have provided good
medical treatment. . . . If some Chinese official had not acted
extremely quickly in getting medical treatment, this person would
be dead.''
</P>
<P>
   The source cautioned that it is still unclear how Meston
sustained his injuries, whether from a failed attempt to leap to
freedom, as Chinese authorities have said, or from abuse at the
hands of police.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts have speculated that if Meston were abused, it was
probably at the hands of local security officers, without the
knowledge of Beijing authorities, who would have been fearful of
generating bad press.
</P>
<P>
   Significantly, Meston and Lafitte were not accused of advocating
Tibetan independence or of spying, but of ``illegal covering and
photographing in a restricted area.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe correspondent Joyce Hor-chung Lau contributed to this
report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-22-99 1759EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990822.0100 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-22 18:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5696 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MUSIC-SPRINGSTEEN-BOS     08-22 0905
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-SPRINGSTEEN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPRINGSTEEN IS BACK 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and e coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOSEPH P. KAHN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Each summer, thousands of Americans pack up the family
car and take off for Mount Rushmore, driving through amber waves of
grain and ample miles of strip malls to gaze upon the likenesses of
four presidential legends who helped shape our nation's political
destiny. Washington. Jefferson. Lincoln. Teddy Roosevelt.
</P>
<P>
   Rock 'n' roll nation is no different in that sense. Each summer,
thousands of armchair rockers, casual fans, and committed
followers, graying baby boomers, and nose-pierced Generation X'ers
turn out to catch a handful of touring legends who have
reconfigured the pop music landscape. This year has brought Bob
