   Meet the new Boss, same as the old Boss. Tickets are scarce,
anticipation is high, new Web sites are springing up. If history is
not in the making here this week, it is certainly on the mind of
local Boss buffs who have faithfully followed their guy since the
glory days of the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   Kathy Bradley, 40, a corporate secretary, says she fell hard for
Bruce back in 1975.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was in love with my girlfriend's brother, and I wanted to
like the guy he liked,'' recalled Bradley, dressed in a black
leather jacket. Though she never dated the friend's brother,
Bradley added, Springsteen's songs spoke to her own hungry heart.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was telling people that you can go out and do things,
giving you hope,'' she said, moments before a kindly stranger
upgraded her backrow seats to the first row. ``As a teenager, you
can relate to that.''
</P>
<P>
   That was a quarter-century ago for most of his fans, when
Springsteen, a wiry, working-class kid from New Jersey, was
anointed the ``future of rock'' _ and proved them (mostly) all
right for saying so.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Springsteen has married, divorced, remarried, and
started a family. He has become a multimillionaire, an
Oscar-winning songwriter, and a member of the Rock Hall of Fame,
his election to which last year was as much a lock as Joe
DiMaggio's trip to Cooperstown. He's about to turn 50, the
traditional age for midlife crises. And like many Boss fans, he is
celebrating his passage into middle-middle age by both looking back
and plunging ahead.
</P>
<P>
   What elevates Springsteen above the typical Jurassic Rock arena
act is the covenant he holds with his fans. There is simply no pop
idol around quite like him these days. Elvis was more mythic, Dylan
more enigmatic, and Sinatra far more of a multimedia force. The
tabloids have never lusted for Bruce the way they pant for Michael
Jackson or Madonna. It's doubtful that you'll ever see him do a
Super Bowl halftime show.
</P>
<P>
   Yet success has not seemed to spoil the Boss, either, nor driven
him into some neurotic shell of his former self. His working-class
anthems still ring true because their sentiments seem honestly
purchased. He may have a home in Los Angeles, but there's still a
lot of New Jersey in Springsteen. And he still touches the New
Jersey in all of us.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is music for the guy who loves Bud,'' said Scott Greene,
28, a marketing manager. Greene helped organize an Internet chat
group dubbed LuckyTown that met at the Harp Lounge prior to the
concert. The group has been extra busy this week, swapping
Springsteen tickets on line, one more indicator of how Bruce fans
have adapted with the times.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Weiss, 47, a property manager from Fort Lauderdale, Fla.,
flew into Boston on Friday holding tickets to two of this week's
shows. Weiss was also on hand for Springsteen's May 5, 1974,
Harvard Square concert, when Bruce opened for Bonnie Raitt, and
inspired critic Jon Landau (later Springsteen's manager-producer)
to pen his famous prophesy about having glimpsed the future of rock
'n' roll.
</P>
<P>
   Weiss, who wore a replica ``Born in the USA'' album cover belt,
said that to appreciate Springsteen you really have to see him and
his bandmates in concert. Few rock fans would quibble with that
assessment, especially those lucky enough to be holding tickets to
this week's shows.
</P>
<P>
   ``He writes about people's hopes and dreams,'' Weiss observed.
``And he does it with such dynamic passion. He gets it across to
everyone in the room, even if they're in the top balcony.'' Welcome
back, Boss.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe correspondent Ian Shapira contributed to this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
