<HEADER>
A5698 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-UKRAINE-ALUMINUM-ART-     08-22 0790
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UKRAINE-ALUMINUM-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE SUPPLY WARS OF UKRAINIAN ALUMINUM 
</HEADLINE>
 (ART ADV: Map is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036. 
(ms) 
 By TOM WARNER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KIEV, Ukraine _ While Alcoa and Western rivals warily circle
each other in their efforts to retain supremacy in the aluminum
business, a relatively obscure but powerful competitor that
operates extensively in the former Soviet Union has been increasing
its control in a region responsible for much of the world's supply.
</P>
<P>
   Trans-World Group, a privately owned company based in London, is
already the largest seller of aluminum ingots, the bulk form of
processed aluminum. Recently, it has been concentrating its effort
in Ukraine, where it has formed an alliance with the government
that could hurt the company's few remaining regional competitors.
</P>
<P>
   Ukraine is an important source of raw material for the huge
smelters that underpinned the Russian aluminum industry. Those
smelters have been responsible for much of the aluminum that has
flooded world markets in recent years and depressed the price.
</P>
<P>
   Whether Trans-World's activities could change the balance of
supply and demand in the global aluminum industry remains unclear.
But they could potentially exert more effect on prices than the
merger intrigue between Alcoa and Reynolds Metals of the United
States, and among Alcan Aluminum of Canada, Pechiney of France and
the Alusuisse Lonza Group of Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
   For several years now, Trans-World has been trying to expand its
control over aluminum production in all parts of the former Soviet
Union but has been blocked in part by the Mykolayiv Alumina plant,
the region's largest source of alumina, a powdery material made
from bauxite that is used by smelters to produce aluminum ingots.
The state-run company is based in the city of Mykolayiv, 250 miles
south of Kiev.
</P>
<P>
   Mykolayiv's general director, Vitaly Meshyn, had joined with two
Trans-World competitors and resisted pressure to lower his prices
for alumina. But late in June, the Ukrainian government dismissed
Meshyn, accusing him of corruption, and replaced him with Mykola
Naboka, who had formerly run an ore-enrichment plant in Kazakhstan
for Trans-World. Naboka then cut supplies to a Siberian smelter run
by Trans-World's main competitor, Siberian Aluminum, and sent them
instead to one controlled by Trans-World.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the Ukrainian government forced Tajikistan's
state-run smelting operation, the other member of the old alliance
with Siberian Aluminum and Mykolayiv Alumina, to accept new terms
for supplies.
</P>
<P>
   Meshyn, a popular manager who had provided numerous benefits to
his workers, including health care and recreation that includes an
Olympic-size swimming pool, has sued to get his old job back. Many
of Mykolayiv's workers say they believe that Trans-World played a
role in the decision to dismiss him.
</P>
<P>
   Trans-World, Ukrainian officials and Naboka deny that. They say
Meshyn was ousted for skimming profits from the plant into offshore
accounts and for allowing customers to amass large debts.
</P>
<P>
   Trans-World is a holding company formed in the late 1980s by two
British brothers, David and Simon Reuben, and two brothers from
Uzbekistan who are now Israeli citizens, Lev and Mikhail Cherny.
</P>
<P>
   It currently sells about 2 million tons a year of aluminum
ingots, about two-thirds of the former Soviet Union's annual
production and 10 percent of global annual production, industry
figures show.
</P>
<P>
   Trans-World itself would give no estimate of its annual aluminum
sales, but said total annual revenue is about $7 billion. By
comparison, Alcoa, the world's largest aluminum company, is
currently producing about 1.5 million tons a year of ingots and 1.8
million tons of aluminum can sheet and other rolled products.
</P>
<P>
   Trans-World presents itself as a successful Western investor in
Russia, where many others have struggled since the Soviet Union's
collapse at the end of 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the company can overcome resentment at the Mykolayiv
plant remains unclear. Meshyn has been revered among Mykolayiv
workers, who consider him a defender of their job security and
welfare. At a recent festival for plant workers that Meshyn
sponsored annually, featuring lip-synching starlets, children's
games, shish kebab and beer, workers lamented that it would
probably be the last such celebration.
</P>
<P>
   Vasily Radchenko, a compressor-station worker, noted that the
factory had paid for his 8-year-old son's lymphatic cancer
operation, which he could never have afforded on his $120 monthly
salary.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without the factory,'' he said, ``I wouldn't have a son.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
