<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-22 18:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5699 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-AGING-PERFORMERS-ART-     08-22 1250
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AGING-PERFORMERS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVISIONS COLUMN: ON HAVING THE GRACE TO GROW OLD, GRACEFULLY OR
NOT 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By MARGO JEFFERSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Aging gracefully.'' That modest little phrase doesn't begin to
capture the shock and struggle involved. And probably it shouldn't,
for what's the point of grace if the end doesn't transcend the
means?
</P>
<P>
   Performers radically dramatize the questions and strategies we
all have to maneuver through. What's the balance between that which
you want to conceal and that which you must reveal? How does sexual
desire play out against marks of decline and decay? What do you do
with the kinds of power that can only be gained once you admit to
certain losses?
</P>
<P>
   All of these questions flared up then resolved themselves
blissfully as I watched Mikhail Baryshnikov perform last week with
his company, the White Oak Dance Project. Baryshnikov is now being
referred to in passing as ``50-something.'' That ``something'' is a
throwaway when you're in your 20s and an alert for your 30s; it is
embarrassingly coy at 40 and close to an indignity by 50.
</P>
<P>
   He is 51 and in what Henry James nicely albeit mournfully called
the middle years. And he is a great performer, as great as he ever
was but on different terms. It isn't only that he has moved from
ballet to modern dance, and that within modern dance he is
scrupulous about what kinds of movement his body can and cannot _
well, what's the right word? Accommodate, endure, master, submit
to, express.
</P>
<P>
   He always had what seemed like boundless virtuosity, charm and
passion. Now he can exist in the center of silence and stillness,
catching you with the smallest move of the hand or head, the way
the great silent screen actors did. There is an unobtrusive
melancholy here too (as if to say, aren't we always alone, even
when partnering and being partnered?).
</P>
<P>
   He was a beauty, in his quicksilver way. And he is still
wonderful to look at, but he is fully mortal now. The body seems
smaller; the hair has thinned, and the ears are a little big. The
intangibles are there in the face: pains, pleasures,
responsibilities, things done and not done. Everything leaves its
trace.
</P>
<P>
   As weight shifts in the body and skin changes its texture, the
accumulation of memory and experience and feeling alters us. Rudolf
Nureyev fought against all this, and what had been grand and bold
in him turned feverish and hysterical. Annabel Gamson, who restaged
and performed Isadora Duncan's work for many years, took the stage
with her long, beautiful white hair and used her artistry to make
age a haven for innocence and an emblem of experience.
</P>
<P>
   White hair is a litmus test, not only for how we choose to
present ourselves, but for what the consequences will be. And here,
the movies are a pretty good mirror of the lives we lead. For an
aging male star, white hair is striking, infinitely preferable to
hair that's disappearing or has been man-made, however efficiently.
(Bald heads work if the head is well-shaped or if, like that of
Telly Savelas, it dares you to pass judgment.)
</P>
<P>
   If you are a female star you had better be committed to
character roles or you'd better be Elizabeth Taylor. Ms. Taylor has
spent her middle years going through stages (marriages, weight
gains, weight losses, stays at the Betty Ford center) as flagrantly
as Drew Barrymore did in her childhood and adolescence. And there
is Ms. Taylor, with her white bob and her still-dark eyebrows, full
of no-nonsense shamelessness. Whether it's about how she ages or
what she wears, she has, bless her heart, made the principles of
good and bad taste equally meaningless.
</P>
<P>
   Lauren Bacall has chosen a safer, cannier route. She's putting
the grande dame and the tough dame together in one package; she
knows that the loftiness of one needs the earthiness of the other.
Spontaneous? Not for a moment, but terrifically efficient. It's the
mode followed by the men of her famous first husband's generation.
You gave the audience the mask of experience if you were Bogart or
Cooper or Grant. You shifted it a little with each role, just
enough so that experience seemed to be your choice, the manly
choice, and the one that pushed deterioration out of the picture.
</P>
<P>
   Each generation plays it a little differently. Al Pacino, Jack
Nicholson and Harvey Keitel go for strategic deterioration. Mel
Gibson is on a nerve-racking cusp. There is a little too much hair,
and the smile, that boyish, naughty smile, is a little too much
insisted on nowadays. (Tom Cruise is going to face the same _ let's
call them issues _ as he grows older.)
</P>
<P>
   John Travolta is trading vanity for character, while Michael
Douglas tries to make vanity pass for character. And Robin Williams
has diversified with serious roles that take our attention away
from the verbal and physical mania of his youthful comic self. But,
as ``Patch Adams'' showed, when he blends low clowning with high
earnestness, he falls into the ``watch me, I'm still an adorable
extraterrestrial kid'' pit.
</P>
<P>
   What's true of actors like these is true for the human throng.
Old tricks and habits (ways of talking, dressing, reacting) can be
like outmoded pieces of equipment. They're usable, but they take
too much effort to be worth using much of the time. Or as a friend
of mine once observed about a piece of clothing we were looking at:
``You can get away with it. But do you want to?''
</P>
<P>
   Strategic decay is not a viable option for most women. Susan
Sarandon is going through a Baryshnikov-like process, making sure
that she gets better and better at what she does and that she looks
her best without trying to look like her younger self. Meryl Streep
has always played women of so many kinds and ages that her own
appearance is a kind of temporary shelter, the dressing room she
inhabits before going onstage. And like Robin Williams, Whoopi
Goldberg is trying to balance her dramatic gifts against her comic
ones. And to choose better projects too, it appears; bad movies do
not become middle-aged comics.
</P>
<P>
   F. Scott Fitzgerald wrote that the test of a first-rate
intelligence was the ability to hold two opposing ideas in your
head at the same time and maintain the ability to keep functioning.
Clearly, being a pop star and growing older are just such ideas,
and it's almost impossible to find a performer who's willing even
to try holding on to them. They'd much rather grab onto the
signifiers of their glory days and hope that their fans will keep
on believing.
</P>
<P>
   For Diana Ross it's the vast head of curly hair, the archly warm
smile. For Keith Richards it's the jet-black hair and the ultra-hip
costumes. For James Brown it's the waved and processed hair and the
dance steps that now require considerable huffing and puffing. And
for Mick Jagger it's the hair, the clothes, the attitude, the
preening, onstage and off, which, in their own more refined English
way, are as desperate as the black leather, white pleats and gold
jewelry of Elvis Presley's later years.
</P>
<P>
   Enough. Back to Baryshnikov, onstage with five lovely dancers,
all young women. He gives off nary a hint of professional arrogance
(I'm the master here) or of sexual grandstanding. He is using time
and himself in ways that seem transcendent and yet, if the rest of
us are willing to take risks on our own scale, possible.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
