<HEADLINE>
FREE JAZZ; LITHUANIAN HAMLET; DANCE AT JACOB'S PILLOW; BORGES
ANNIVERSARY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass., England)  (js) 
 By LAWRENCE VAN GELDER  
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Street Scene
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Three days of free jazz await audiences at City Hall
Park beginning at 5 p.m. on Thursday, when Herbie Hancock, Mark
Whitfield, Peter Delano, JK and Robyn Spring headline the opening
day of the annual J &AMP; R Jazz Festival. On Friday evening the lineup
consists of Wynton Marsalis, Eric Reed and Charlie Hunter with Adam
Cruz. Starting at noon on Saturday the festival, sponsored by Joe
and Rachelle Friedman, the J. and R. of J &AMP; R Music World, will
offer Rodney Jones, Mike Stern, Jeff Golub, Kenny Garrett and
Nelson Rangell. Information: (212) 238-9000.
</P>
<P>
   Tragic Differences
</P>
<P>
   Is there anything more to be done with ``Hamlet''? Of course.
And the Bath Shakespeare Festival, beginning on Thursday in Bath,
England, is the place to find a Lithuanian production, directed by
Elmuntas Nekrosius, with a rock star (Andrius Mamontovas) as the
Danish prince. The action unfolds against a landscape of perpetual
rain, with water tumbling like mist onto the stage. This ``Hamlet''
plays Sept. 4-6. The festival, running through Sept. 11, includes
``Macbeth _ Director's Cut,'' in which Lady Macbeth does not die,
and Macbeth is not killed. Information: 011-44-1225-448-844.
</P>
<P>
   Imports
</P>
<P>
   Visiting the United States for the first time since touring as a
Soviet ensemble more than nine years ago, principals of the Bolshoi
Ballet and Nina Ananiashvili, a principal dancer with American
Ballet Theater, will offer two U.S. premieres and other works,
Wednesday through Sunday, at the Jacob's Pillow Dance Festival in
Becket, Mass. The premieres, ``Charms of Mannerism,'' revolving
around court etiquette of mid-16th-century Italy, and ``Dreams
About Japan,'' based on Kabuki themes, were choreographed by a
young Russian, Aleksei Ratmansky. Information: (413) 243-0745.
</P>
<P>
   Poet's Corner
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Jorge Luis Borges, who died in 1986, was born 100
years ago Tuesday. Widely regarded as among the greatest and most
influential of Spanish-language writers, this Argentine-born poet,
critic and short-story writer will be celebrated by Penguin Putnam
with the publication Tuesday of the Viking edition of ``Selected
Nonfictions.'' This collection is the third and final volume in its
series of 1,500 pages of new Borges translations. Borges will be
the subject of a PEN forum at the New School on Oct. 7, the subject
of a lecture at the Unterberg Poetry Center of the 92nd Street Y on
Oct. 18, and the subject of programs at the Americas Society, the
Spanish Institute and the Brooklyn campus of Long Island University
in December. Viking series information: (212) 366-2870.
</P>
</TEXT>
