<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-GROWN-UPS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`GROWN UPS' ROLE FITS JALEEL WHITE PERFECTLY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jaleel White has grown up. Turns out he's a fine actor who
doesn't have to exaggerate his appearance or change his voice to
get a laugh. With a high forehead that furrows like an Illinois
cornfield and big sleepy eyelids that are like mood-altering window
shades, White is a young Bill Cosby, able to use his face to
maximum comedic effect.
</P>
<P>
   White's ability lifts an otherwise drab comedy a couple of
notches above average, but ``Grown Ups,'' premiering Monday night
on UPN, isn't likely to be the show that makes people accept White
as someone other than Steve Urkel, the geekchild he played on
``Family Matters'' for almost a decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``Grown Ups'' is a logical title and a logical segue for White.
His character, J. Calvin Frazier, is out of college and struggling
with the idea that ``the job I used to have is now my career.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, not exactly. In Monday night's episode, Calvin has been
promoted to vice president of regional distribution for a
corrugated-box company. But change is afoot. The producers say
Calvin will be leaving cardboard for something more high-tech.
</P>
<P>
   His living arrangements will be changing, too. Soleil Moon Frye,
the grown-up Punky Brewster, plays Calvin's new roomie in the
pilot, but she won't be back, even though the original credits
listed her as a regular.
</P>
<P>
   The core of the show remains intact: Calvin is new to this
postgraduate grown-up thing, and he's making his way as best he can
with the help of best friend, Gordon, and Gordon's wife, Shari.
Sometimes he needs advice, such as this from Shari on proper
etiquette with a female roommate: ``Be considerate, leave the seat
down and don't walk around in your underpants.''
</P>
<P>
   To which Calvin replies: ``That's no problem. I don't even wear
underpants.''
</P>
<P>
   White's timing, his expressions and his physical comedy tend to
be funnier than the lines, which break no new comedic ground. His
support from Dave Ruby and Marissa Ribisi is adequate, but ``Grown
Ups'' will have to succeed on White's everyman appeal. This is
easier at UPN, which doesn't need huge ratings to keep a show on
the air. But even if ``Grown Ups'' lasts a while, its legacy may
not be as the new paradigm of TV comedy but as a notable example of
integrated casting.
</P>
<P>
   Though White is African American and Ruby and Ribisi are not,
the difference in their races is not the crux of this buddy comedy.
No doubt it will come up at some point, as it inevitably does when
blacks and whites hang around together, but by accepting an
integrated living situation without poking fun at it, ``Grown Ups''
is as groundbreaking in its way as ``Room 222'' and ``The White
Shadow'' were a generation ago, especially in a TV season as
diversity-challenged as this one.
</P>
<P>
   Grown Ups. Half-hour comedy about three childhood friends
struggling with the new and unfamiliar responsibilities of
adulthood. Starring Jaleel White, Dave Ruby and Marissa Ribisi.
Season premiere Monday night on UPN. Episode repeats Tuesday at 8
p.m.; series moves to Mondays at 9 p.m. Aug. 30. Parental guideline
rating: TV-PG.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-22-99 1816EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990822.0105 </DOCNO>
