<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-ADDRESS-REGS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UPSTART TAKES ADVANTAGE OF UNCERTAINTIES IN INTERNET NAMING
BUSINESS 
</HEADLINE>
 (ART ADV:  Photo  is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036. 
(ms) 
 By JERI CLAUSING   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Thanks to a combination of foresight, luck and good timing,
Richard Forman has won the right to boast. His company,
Register.com, is the first and most aggressive player in the game
of breaking up the monopoly on Internet address registrations that
a Virginia company, Network Solutions Inc., has enjoyed for six
years.
</P>
<P>
   But the starting gate is still closed to the more than 250
companies expected eventually to compete in what is stacking up to
be a risky venture even by Internet standards.
</P>
<P>
   One big unknown is how far registration fees will drop from the
$70 Network Solutions charges for an initial two-year registration
as more competitors enter the arena. An even bigger gamble is that
key rules for the game remain unknown.
</P>
<P>
   Some of those rules will be decided this week when the Internet
Corporation for Assigned Names and Numbers, or Icann, the nonprofit
corporation charged with introducing competition into the business
of registering names ending in the popular domains of .com, .net
and .org, holds its fourth board meeting in Santiago, Chile.
</P>
<P>
   The group is expected to approve a uniform dispute resolution
policy that the companies will have to follow in cases of
cybersquatting _ the practice of registering domain names just to
hold them in hopes of making a profit _ and other tangles over
trademark issues. The policy will be play a large role in
determining what legal liabilities the new competitors will
ultimately face.
</P>
<P>
   Other important issues also remain the subject of protracted
negotiations between Network Solutions, based in Herndon, Va., and
the Department of Commerce, which chose Icann last year to run the
Internet's addressing system and to establish the framework for
introducing competition to Network Solutions' cash-cow monopoly.
</P>
<P>
   Those issues include contract terms for allowing competing
companies to register addresses in the master data base of domains
that Network Solutions will continue to administer _ including how
much they will pay Network Solutions as a service fee for each name
they register.
</P>
<P>
   Although the delays and uncertainties have a number of potential
competitors in a holding pattern, they have provided an unexpected
bonus for Register.com, which was one of five companies chosen in
April to participate in a pilot round of competition with Network
Solutions.
</P>
<P>
   Register.com, the first of the five to go live, won't say how
many names it has already registered. But Forman, insists that the
numbers are encouraging.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are the second largest registrar in the world,'' he says
with confidence.
</P>
<P>
   Register.com has competed aggressively with Network Solutions in
what are expected to be important areas of the business _ like
providing customer service and computer operations for running Web
sites.
</P>
<P>
   Register.com has entered into partnerships with nearly 20
companies, including Staples and Mastercard, giving it a link on
their Web sites and offering services related to building a Web
site. It also has partnerships with 30 Internet service providers.
</P>
<P>
   But like the registration of domain names themselves, those are
all areas where Network Solutions has had a head start.
</P>
<P>
   With the exclusive right since 1993 to register addresses that
end in .com, .net and .org at $70 each, Network Solutions has
reported snowballing profits for the last 11 quarters. Anticipating
competition, it has spent much of the last two years building
international partnerships and new services aimed at small
businesses that want to build a Web presence. Network Solutions now
has more than 500 employees and averages 400,000 new domain name
registrations a month.
</P>
<P>
   Register.com, by contrast, has about 100 employees and a lot
less cash. But Forman is confident that when the dust has settled,
he'll be on top. ``I spent a lot of money building these systems; I
know how much they cost,'' he said. ``You're going to see a lot of
companies that just can't do the business.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul Merenbloom, an Internet analyst with Prudential Securities,
agrees in part with that assessment. ``The potential here is for a
very large industry,'' he said, ``but it is likely to be controlled
by _ or rather comprised of _ a few rather successful companies,
some largely successful, a few moderately successful companies and
a large number of nominally successful companies.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``I think Rich has positioned himself in the first
heat, and, given the inevitable issues and delays, he and others in
the first group have a natural time advantage. That's not to say
that over time the playing field won't level. I think it will.''
</P>
<P>
   But while those delays offer some advantages to the first five
companies, they are also making it difficult for them and for other
potential competitors to develop solid business plans and raise
capital, Merenbloom said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unclear what the requirements are to be successful _
other than quality service at a reasonable price,'' he said. ``The
real issue right now is that nobody wants to do the wrong thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Complicating the picture are Internet giants like America
Online, which is also participating in the pilot round of
competition. Like the other bigger companies in that group _ France
Telecom and Melbourne IT _ it has done little yet to kick off the
business and has said even less about what its plans are or whether
it will try to go head-to-head with Network Solutions.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Stubbs, chairman of the only nonprofit group participating
in the test round of competition, the Internet Council of
Registrars, said a lot of people were ``waiting to see what comes
out of these negotiations.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If you don't know how much money you are going to make next
week, it's hard to sign a lease on a new apartment,'' Stubbs said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
