<SLUG> BC-TV-DESTINATION-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TALENT SHOW LETS EVERYONE BE A CRITIC 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Watching a talent show is a lot like spending time at the
airport. As the contestants pass in review, one's thoughts are
oddly similar to those that arise at a crowded carousel in baggage
claim: ``What the heck is he wearing?'' ``Is that a man or a
woman?'' ``Nice eyes.'' ``Long legs.'' ``Sheesh, what an annoying
voice.''
</P>
<P>
   And then there are thoughts that are more or less unique to
talent shows: ``Who told her she could sing?'' ``Who told him he
was funny?'' ``What the heck was that?''
</P>
<P>
   Sitting in judgment of others may not be polite, but we all do
it.
</P>
<P>
   And talent shows like ``Destination Stardom,'' which is the
first new fall show to debut this season, pretty much demand it.
Premiering Monday night at 8 on the fledgling Pax TV network,
``Destination Stardom'' has 100 members of the audience pick the
winners. Viewers at home also can vote for their favorites and
parlay their judgmental sides into a free Hawaii vacation.
</P>
<P>
   Lisa Canning of ``Entertainment Tonight'' is the host, taking
over capably where Ed McMahon left off when ``Star Search,'' also
created by longtime producer Al Masini, went bye-bye five years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   Masini has tweaked the format to offer more prize money, but the
concept is essentially the same: Competitors in several categories
go head to head, with each winner receiving a cash prize and the
right to compete the next week against a new challenger.
</P>
<P>
   The categories are singers under 16, singers over 16, comedy,
variety, family variety (in which the members of an act must be
related) and female models.
</P>
<P>
   The models parade around in swimwear, perhaps a tad racy for a
family-values network like Pax TV. But what family doesn't like
cheesecake? (On Monday night, the choices are Norwegian cheesecake,
German cheesecake and Hawaiian cheesecake.)
</P>
<P>
   We won't divulge the identity of Monday night' winners, not even
in the variety category, which pits Jaret Hughes and six members of
the Seattle SuperSonics dance team against a juggling unicyclist
from Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   Well, maybe one winner. That would be Hawaii, where
``Destination Stardom'' is produced. With opening and closing
scenes that play like a travelogue, the show is the sort of
shameless promotional spot that every Chamber of Commerce executive
dreams about.
</P>
<P>
   But ``Destination Stardom'' is about dreams, and what better
place than a vacation paradise to help make them come true?
</P>
<P>
   With slick production and hokey intentions, ``Destination
Stardom'' offers the kind of ``interactive'' connection TV has been
making ever since Ted Mack succeeded Major Bowes and asked each of
us to render judgment on complete strangers who dreamed of making
it big and got a chance to realize the dream.
</P>
<P>
   Destination Stardom. One-hour variety show featuring competitors
in six talent categories. Hosted by Lisa Canning. Season premiere
Monday night on the Pax TV network. Parental guideline rating:
TV-G.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
