<SLUG> BC-FOOD-OWEN-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEAFOOD STEW A BEACHCOMBER'S REWARD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN OWEN  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It has been a lean year for Dungeness crab. Razor clams, once
easy pickings along public Northwest beaches, are fewer and often
far between.
</P>
<P>
   Looking for glass balls from Japan? They're not as abundant as
they used to be. Beachcombers are also bemoaning the fact they
seldom find red beavers, blue turtles, green frogs, yellow plastic
ducks or white Nike sneakers among the driftwood on the shores of
Pacific beaches any more.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike crab and razor clams, it takes a whole lot of plastic
ducks to make a meal. Boil a sneaker for a month and you'd still
need a chain saw to carve it into serving pieces.
</P>
<P>
   That may be one reason the Sneaker Society has disbanded. The
other reason is that it has been almost a decade since five,
box-car-size ``shoe boxes'' were lost off a container ship. A
couple of years later some of the 40,000 Nike sneakers began to
wash up on Oregon beaches.
</P>
<P>
   Some residents of that area collected 40 or more wet but
serviceable shoes. Since Cannon Beach was named for an ancient
weapon salvaged off its shores, it was natural that Oregon
community would serve as unofficial headquarters for the Sneaker
Society, formed so that a resident who found 13 left shoes might
match then up with right shoes in appropriate sizes.
</P>
<P>
   At about the time the tide of sneakers began to ebb, toy ducks,
blue turtles, green frogs and red beavers began to wash up on
Alaska beaches. They were manufactured in Hong Kong and headed for
Tacoma, Wash., when containers were lost during the great storm of
'92. It took two years for the toy creatures to reach communities
like Sitka.
</P>
<P>
   Now residents of Cannon Beach are holding their communal breaths
for a flood of Lego pieces. Some five million tiny building blocks
were lost off England in 1997. Oceanographers predict the currents
may carry them to Oregon beaches in about 2010.
</P>
<P>
   Shipping officials say some 1,000 containers are lost overboard
each year and the cargo is often swept along thousands of miles by
ocean currents.
</P>
<P>
   Unless Dungeness crabs and razor clams begin reappearing in much
larger numbers, oceanfront residents are hoping the next Northwest
tide might bring in some spilled cans of clams and tomato sauce
plus a few errant bottles of wine to form a foundation for this
seafood feast.
</P>
<P>
   Flotsam Stew
</P>
<P>
   32 ounces chopped tomatoes
</P>
<P>
   18-ounce can tomato sauce
</P>
<P>
   1 cup dry red wine
</P>
<P>
   2 medium potatoes, peeled and cut into 1-inch cubes
</P>
<P>
   2 onions, chopped
</P>
<P>
   2 green peppers, chopped
</P>
<P>
   2 cloves garlic, minced
</P>
<P>
   1 bay leaf
</P>
<P>
   Handful of chopped parsley
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon Italian herbs
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   One-quarter teaspoon black pepper
</P>
<P>
   One-half teaspoon (or more) red pepper flakes
</P>
<P>
   One-half pound small shrimp
</P>
<P>
   2 pounds halibut, snapper or cod
</P>
<P>
   16-and-a-half ounce can undrained chopped clams
</P>
<P>
   In a pot combine the first 13 ingredients. Bring to a boil,
reduce heat and simmer covered for 30 minutes, or until potatoes
are fork tender.
</P>
<P>
   Cut the fish fillets into bite-sized pieces and add to the pot
along with the shrimp and clams. Remove from heat when the fish can
be flaked with a fork. This makes six main-dish servings.
</P>
<P>
   The last time I cooked this stew I used large squid steaks,
cubed, instead of the clams. You could also use small squid,
cleaned and cut into rings.
</P>
<P>
   I wouldn't recommend sauteed sneaker laces. But they might help
fill out the meal.
</P>
<P>
   Or, if a few acorn squash from Samoa wash up on the local
beaches, this makes a delicious side dish.
</P>
<P>
   Samoa Squash
</P>
<P>
   2 acorn squash
</P>
<P>
   8 tablespoons butter
</P>
<P>
   4 teaspoons brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   One-half cup water
</P>
<P>
   1-and one-third cups frozen peas, cooked
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons sour cream
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons dill weed
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   Cut the squash in half and remove seeds and fibers. Melt the
butter and add the brown sugar. Divide among the four squash
halves. Place squash in a pan cut side up. Pour one-half cup of
water into the pan. Bake 75 minutes at 350 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Combine the peas with the sour cream, dill and lemon juice.
Divide among the squash, then return them to the oven for 10
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Serves four beachcombers.
</P>
<P>
   You might consider an assortment of plastic toys for table
decorations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
