<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-22 18:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5713 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-HONGKONG-PLANE-CRASH-     08-22 0667
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HONGKONG-PLANE-CRASH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
2 DIE, 206 HURT AS JET WITH 315 ABOARD CRASHES IN STORM AT HONG
KONG AIRPORT 
</HEADLINE>
 (ms) 
 By MARK LANDLER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONG KONG _ A Taiwan jetliner crash-landed and burst into flames
during a tropical storm here Sunday night, killing two people and
injuring 206, government officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The China Airlines plane from Bangkok with 300 passengers and 15
crew members was landing in fierce wind and rain when its right
wing touched the runway. The plane flipped over and skidded to a
stop, as flames swiftly engulfed the aircraft, several witnesses
told local television and The Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for China Airlines in Taipei said the plane, a
McDonnell Douglas MD-11, had been buffeted by strong winds as it
landed on the south runway of the new Hong Kong International
Airport at 6:45 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Several witnesses reported, though, that the plane had been on
fire before it touched down.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw the plane, like a fireball coming down,'' Toshi Hoshino,
a passenger who was changing planes in Hong Kong, told the AP.
``The right wing hit the ground first. The left side of the body
then followed.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for the government could not confirm whether the
plane caught fire before or after it landed.
</P>
<P>
   In interviews with local television, several passengers
described a chaotic scene inside the plane, with people hanging
upside down in their seats as flames moved steady from the front to
the back of the fuselage.
</P>
<P>
   Firefighters quickly gained access to the plane through a rear
galley and led passengers to safety. Most of the passengers were
Thai, but about 80 were Portuguese tourists, the AP reported.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's crash-landing is the first serious accident at Hong
Kong International Airport, a vast $9-billion complex that opened
last July on an island west of Hong Kong. It replaced Kai Tak, a
cramped airfield on Victoria Harbor that was legendary for its
rooftop-skimming landings.
</P>
<P>
   But the accident is the latest in a series involving China
Airlines. In 1993, a China Airlines 747 skidded off the runway at
Kai Tak, landing in the harbor and injuring 23 people. In 1994, a
China Airlines Airbus A300-600 crashed in Nagoya, Japan, killing
264. And in 1998, 196 people were killed when a China Airlines jet
plunged into a row of houses near Chiang Kai-shek Airport in
Taipei.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference in Taipei, Taiwan civil aviation officials
said the plane tilted 15 degrees as it touched down. A spokesman
for the airline, Shih Ping-huang, said ``side wind was very strong
when the plane landed.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for the Hong Kong government said the two
confirmed fatalities were a man and a woman. Their identities were
not disclosed. China Airlines said at least four other people were
seriously injured.
</P>
<P>
   Local television showed pictures of the plane on its back with
its landing gear protruding upward. Although emergency vehicles
converged on the plane within moments of the crash, witnesses said
firefighters struggled to put out the blaze in the gale-force winds
and sheets of rain.
</P>
<P>
   Hong Kong had been lashed by wind and rain throughout the day as
Typhoon Sam moved ashore from the South China Sea just east of the
territory. The storm caused several flight delays, as well as
cancellations of ferry service from the central Hong Kong to
outlying islands.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Sunday, the Hong Kong Observatory hoisted the No. 8
cyclone warning signal, which indicates average winds of 39 to 73
miles per hour. The storm, which generated gusts of 81 miles per
hour during the afternoon, uprooted trees, tore down signs and
flooded roads throughout the territory.
</P>
<P>
   Officials here noted that Hong Kong's airport remains open
during typhoons, even with the No. 8 warning signal is hoisted.
They said it was up to individual airlines and pilots to decide
whether to land. Hong Kong closed the airport immediately after the
crash so that the passengers could be evacuated.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
