   FOLD
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-PROSPERITY-GAP (Moscow) _ The August 1998 devaluation of
the ruble dealt a heavy blow to the nation. Russia's economic
reformers were discredited. The capital's fledgling financial
sector was hit by massive layoffs. The purchasing power of Russian
consumers dwindled. By using the particularly Russian talent for
adapting to seemingly any hardship, however, many Russians have
managed to cling to vestiges of their pre-crisis life. By Michael
R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   (We plan to move the story by 9 p.m. ET in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   ONLINE-HUCKSTERS _ Like snake-oil salesmen who rode into
frontier towns peddling cure-alls more than a century ago, modern
hucksters have taken to the Internet with gusto. Amid the
worthwhile companies promoting themselves on the Internet are
shadowy scam artists who pose a real threat to unwary or
unsophisticated investors. By Timothy L. O'Brien.
</P>
<P>
   (Story has moved in ``f'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   FRANKENSTEIN-FOOD (Piccotts End, England) _ While genetic
modification of food has been a relatively unquestioned phenomenon
in the United States and Canada, its arrival here has set off
alarms and united demonstrators from lapsed causes into a powerful
protest movement against what they call ``Frankenstein food'' and
the large multinational companies promoting it. By Warren Hoge.
</P>
