<HEADLINE>
TURKS WAIT FOR RELATIVES' BODIES TO BE RECOVERED 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also TURKEY-QUAKE, TURKEY-LESSONS) 
(rk) 
 By STEPHEN KINZER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   YALOVA, Turkey _ As the sun beat down on this seaside resort,
several dozen people spent the day Sunday watching and waiting as
noisy power shovels tore through a 50-foot-high pile of debris that
was a handsome apartment house less than a week ago.
</P>
<P>
   Some had already seen the bodies of relatives pulled from the
ruins. The stench was a grim signal that many more are entombed
here.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after noon, one group of aid workers cried out. A power
shovel had broken into a bedroom, and they could see a corpse
inside. The big machine backed away, and workers began pulling away
slabs of concrete by hand.
</P>
<P>
   An hour later, the bloated body of a woman who might have been
about 20 was freed. Workers wrapped it in a blanket, zipped it
inside a green plastic body bag and carried it to a waiting
ambulance, which sped away with its siren blaring.
</P>
<P>
   The emotions brought on by the discovery seemed to subside for a
while, but then one man sitting in the crowd turned pale, wept
silently, and suddenly began screaming.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thirteen years old!'' he shouted, his face contorted with pain
and grief. ``Buried under there! Just a baby! Just 13!'' With both
his hands, he began violently ripping up the grass around him.
</P>
<P>
   Relief workers wiped the man's brow with wet cloths and sought
to comfort him. They managed to calm him after a few minutes, but
he refused to be led away, preferring to maintain his awful vigil.
</P>
<P>
   As power shovels worked, the flotsam of dozens of lives tumbled
out of the rubble. There were clothes, mattresses, bookshelves,
carpets, a television, a washing machine, a radiator, a toilet and
a set of the works of Balzac, translated into Turkish.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone knew we weren't ready for something like this,''
lamented Mehmet Kocadag, 65, who had traveled to Yalova from his
home in eastern Turkey. The bodies of three of his relatives had
been found on Saturday, and he was waiting for a fourth that he
said was surely decomposing in the sticky heat.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the third earthquake I've lived through, and I can
tell you that no matter what you're hearing now, in a week or a
month or at most a year, everything will be forgotten,'' Kocadag
said. ``We'll go back to building with sand, and when the next
quake comes, you'll see scenes like this all over again. The army
and the state will be too late, and thousands more will die.''
</P>
<P>
   Lt. Onur Disbudak, a soldier posted in Yalova, said he had spent
several days listening to complaints like these, along with some
that were far sharper.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are angry and emotional,'' he said. ``How could they
not be? They want someone to blame, and if they want to blame us,
that's fine. But since we've gotten here, things have calmed down a
little. Turkish people aren't afraid of police, but they respect
the army. When we ask them to move, they move.''
</P>
<P>
   The army and government were not the only targets of wrath in
Yalova Sunday. Many people said they would happily help lynch the
contractor who built the collapsed apartment house near where they
were sitting. They said his shoddy workmanship and substandard
materials had caused scores of deaths.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that other buildings only a hundred yards away were
damaged only lightly or not at all lent credence to their charges.
But the contractor, like many others whose work is now being
scrutinized, has disappeared.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
