<SLUG> BC-PATENTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARRYING CELLULAR TECHNOLOGY TO POWER LINES  
 FINDING MISSING PAPERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Md., Calif.)  (mk) 
 By SABRA CHARTRAND   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
 &HT;    
 &HT;    The vast majority of American homes and businesses are wired for
telecommunications. But the phone lines, telephone poles,
fiber-optic cables and switching stations that Americans take for
granted can be scarce in other countries. Installing that equipment
in poorer nations is an expensive undertaking, and so for many in
Asia, Africa or the Middle East, phones remain a luxury. Cellular
networks could eliminate the need to wire houses, lay cable or
erect poles, but suggesting that poor villagers in a nation like
Vietnam use cell phones has something of a ``let them eat cake''
attitude about it.
 &HT;    The governments of many such nations have given the higher
priority to providing electrical power to their citizens, even in
the most rural areas. That may prove to be a telecommunications
solution, too.
 &HT;    Paul Kline, an inventor from Germantown, Md., has devised a
wireless telecommunications system that takes advantage of the
electrical power infrastructure. His invention marries conventional
power lines with cellular technology and standard telephone
equipment to bring phones, fax machines and computer modems into
homes and businesses that have no telecommunications wiring.
 &HT;    Kline calls his invention a ``wireless local loop distribution
system.'' He first installs a transceiver that connects electrical
power lines and standard telephone equipment in homes and offices.
Then he attaches what he calls a ``fixed wireless terminal'' to the
power grid in the region. The phone signal is sent via the power
lines to the wireless terminal, which in turn transmits it to other
wireless terminals or to a base station.
 &HT;    More than one home or business can be linked to a single
wireless terminal because most power distribution systems use
step-down transformers for clusters of homes or businesses. The
transformers reduce the high voltage sent over electrical lines to
the 110 or 220 volts used in homes. Each cluster of buildings
connected to a step-down transformer is effectively isolated from
every other cluster.
 &HT;    Kline envisions that this could mean that clusters of homes or
businesses could also be isolated via his wireless
telecommunications terminals. The terminals would be able to
``multiplex'' the signals from different buildings, according to
his patent filing. Thus, the system could carry more than one user
in each transformer cluster. Kline hopes that one wireless terminal
for several customers would make his invention even cheaper to use.
 &HT;    The wireless terminal is also connected to a power meter, so
that energy use can be transmitted to a power company. Kline
received patent 5,937,342.
 &HT;    
 &HT;     c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Help in Finding That Lost Document
</P>
<P>
   The frustrating search for a single document in a ream of papers
or a room full of files may be over. Marvin Isaacman and Denis
McGreivy, two California inventors, have patented a system that
uses radio signals to pinpoint a piece of paper on its precise
shelf or drawer.
</P>
<P>
   Office files are usually labeled and stored alphabetically,
numerically, by color or bar code. But those systems don't help
when a folder is misfiled or lost. In their patent, the inventors
say a recent study found that ``an average U.S. executive spends
around $10,000 a year searching for missing files.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoping to eliminate this waste, the inventors first tag files or
documents with a passive radio frequency code. The tag is made up
of a small coil or antenna that collects energy and an integrated
circuit bearing an identification code. When someone wants to
locate the document, a computer-controlled transceiver transmits
the coded signal via an antenna in first one, and then a second,
radio frequency. The tags pick up energy from the transceiver; when
a match is made, the relevant tag is activated and sends a signal
back to the transceiver.
</P>
<P>
   Since the signal is a radio frequency, it does not require
direct line-of-sight between the transceiver and the tagged files.
So documents can be stored in a box, cabinet or drawer. Antennas
set up on shelves or in drawers can extend the signal. Once the
correct signal is received, the computer then automatically names
the shelf or drawer where the document can be found.
</P>
<P>
   Isaacman, from Los Angeles, and McGreivy, from Laguna Niguel,
Calif., received patent 5,936,527.
</P>
<P>
   Patents may be viewed on the Web at www.uspto.gov or may be
ordered through the mail, by patent number, for $3 from the Patent
and Trademark Office, Washington, D.C. 20231.
</P>
</TEXT>
