<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TURKEY-QUAKE-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS HOPE OF FINDING NEW SURVIVORS ENDS, RELIEF EFFORT ACCELERATES 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also TURKEY-SCENE, TURKEY-LESSONS) 
(js) 
 By STEPHEN KINZER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ISTANBUL, Turkey _ With hope of finding survivors of Turkey's
devastating earthquake now all but gone, the Turkish authorities
are turning their attention to caring for those who have survived.
</P>
<P>
   A full-scale relief effort in the area hit by the earthquake is
finally beginning after days of confusion. Turkish and foreign
volunteers have been joined by soldiers and police, and heavy
equipment has been moved to almost every victimized town.
</P>
<P>
   Divers scoured the waters of the Sea of Marmara Sunday for the
first time since the quake and reported that they had found more
than 150 bodies. Most of those victims had apparently lived in
homes facing the sea, which lies at the center of the earthquake
zone.
</P>
<P>
   Relief officials said more than 12,000 bodies have been
recovered so far, and a U.N. relief official has estimated that the
final death toll may reach 40,000. More than 33,000 people were
injured in the quake, and at least 200,000 are homeless. Only two
survivors were found beneath the rubble Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The government's crisis center issued an appeal for body bags,
tents, blankets and dry food, but said help ``is especially welcome
if it comes in the form of cash donations.''
</P>
<P>
   Soldiers were visible on the streets of many devastated towns on
Sunday, collecting refuse, keeping spectators away from dangerous
sites, spraying disinfectants and spreading lime powder along
gutters. Military trucks and jeeps moved through streets alongside
power shovels, bulldozers and other heavy equipment sent by nearby
cities and private companies.
</P>
<P>
   Gen. Huseyin Kivrikoglu, the country's top military commander,
toured hospitals and pledged that the military, which has been
criticized for what some say was its slow reaction to the aftermath
of the quake, would do all in its power to aid the relief effort.
</P>
<P>
   Minister of Housing Koray Aydin estimated that 60,000 buildings
had been either destroyed or seriously damaged in the quake. He
said that within a few days, he would begin moving many of the
homeless out of the fields and tents where they are now living.
Some are to be given prefabricated huts, and others will have rooms
in unused hotels.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``Temporary housing compounds will be set up, taking into
account the desire of our homeless citizens to remain close to the
areas where they lived,'' Aydin said.
</P>
<P>
   His announcement was a reflection of the accelerated pace with
which the government is now moving to deal with the crisis.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In another step, Prime Minister Bulent Ecevit fired the
appointed governors of Yalova, Kocaeli and Sakarya, three of the
hardest-hit provinces. He said they had proved unable to meet the
challenges posed by last week's disaster, and he replaced them
temporarily with members of his Cabinet.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have the strength to overcome the devastation of this
earthquake very soon,'' Ecevit said in a televised speech. ``We
only need to trust in the strength of our nation and our state.''
</P>
<P>
   More than a few Turks remained angry, not only at Ecevit but at
the entire state apparatus. They accuse the government of failing
to grasp the magnitude of the crisis for days and then responding
too slowly to save many victims who had been buried alive.
</P>
<P>
   The country's largest newspaper, Hurriyet, devoted nearly a full
page to an account of how two Japanese officials committed suicide
after the Japanese city of Kobe was devastated by an earthquake in
1995. They had been blamed for permitting poor construction and not
responding quickly enough to the needs of victims.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Another newspaper, Cumhurriyet, published a front-page editorial
headlined, ``A Complete Change of Mentality is Needed.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The need for fundamental change in Turkey is obvious,'' the
editorial said. ``If this earthquake does not rouse us from our
torpor, it will be impossible to maintain hope for the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Turkey remains in a state of shock, with smiles rare even in
areas far from the earthquake zone. Each day, newspapers carry
reports and photos that seem more awful and more tragic than those
that came before. In cafes, bars and tea houses, people sit glumly,
shaking their heads and murmuring to themselves as they watch
heart-rending scenes unfold on television.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   By one count, 42 countries and 38 international organizations
have sent aid to Turkey since Tuesday. More than 3,000 U.S. sailors
and marines aboard three warships laden with medical supplies were
expected to arrive early Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The World Bank pledged to send $200 million for emergency
housing construction. Deputy Prime Minister Recep Onal said the
government was considering issuing special ``earthquake bonds'' to
raise more money.
</P>
<P>
   Rescuers found just two living victim of the earthquake Sunday.
One was a 57-year-old woman who was pulled from the debris of her
home in Golcuk. Another woman, 52, was pulled out from the rubble
of her home, southwest of Golcuk, by Israeli, Turkish and Bulgarian
rescue teams, the Israeli army said. Some believe that they may be
the last to be found alive.
</P>
<P>
   Acknowledging that few if any victims remain alive beneath the
rubble, teams of rescue workers from Germany, Switzerland, the
Netherlands, Japan and Britain began packing for their return home.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason we came here was to save people,'' said Edward
Pearce, who headed one of the British teams. ``That has ended.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-22-99 1856EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990822.0122 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-22 19:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5723 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-FBN-JETS-MIRER-NYT     08-22 0760
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-JETS-MIRER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JETS CUT ZOLAK AND MAKE MIRER BACKUP TO TESTAVERDE
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By GERALD ESKENAZI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HEMPSTEAD, N.Y. _ The two most surprised backup quarterbacks in
Jets' camp passed each other Sunday _ Scott Zolak going, Rick Mirer
coming.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Bill Parcells whittled the No. 2 spot down to a more
manageable size by cutting Zolak and, while not announcing it
officially, anointing Mirer the backup behind Vinny Testaverde.
</P>
<P>
   Mirer still was reeling over the Friday night trade with the
Packers that made him a Jet after he thought he had finally found a
home in Green Bay.
</P>
<P>
   And Zolak? He had discovered minutes before he was given his
audition as the Jets' backup on Friday night against the
Philadelphia Eagles that Mirer was his new teammate. The news
didn't help his performance: In six drives, he was unable to lead
the second-stringers to a score.
</P>
<P>
   On releasing Zolak, Parcells said, ``It's a better opportunity
for him to go now.''
</P>
<P>
   Mirer's acquisition, for an undetermined draft pick next year,
echoes last year's arrival of Testaverde, a former Heisman Trophy
winner and the top pick over all in the 1987 draft who had played
for years with bad teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the very first things Coach Parcells said to me it this
is not unlike what happened to Vinny,'' said Mirer Sunday as he
prepared to suit up for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him don't worry about the running game,'' Parcells
said. ``I told him we'll surround him with players. He should just
concentrate on his receivers and their routes.''
</P>
<P>
   It appears, too, that Ray Lucas can now concentrate on his
special teams' skills as well as learning how to play quarterback.
He apparently is no longer a viable contender for the backup job.
</P>
<P>
   Mirer recounted his checkered pro past with almost a sigh, as if
he has never got over his failure to achieve the success he had at
Notre Dame. His play in college led to his being chosen No. 2 in
the 1993 draft, behind Drew Bledsoe, who was taken by Parcells for
the Patriots. Mirer went to Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I'd wind up with Parcells in New England, since Drew
was from Washington,'' Mirer said. ``I guess I've come full
circle.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been dealt a pretty bad hand,'' he said of his pro
career. ``If you can survive that, you learn a lot. But last season
at Green Bay I learned to relax and it rejuvenated me.''
</P>
<P>
   He did not have one snap behind center last year with the
Packers.
</P>
<P>
   But with Seattle in 1993, he set National Football League rookie
records for attempts, completions and yardage. Seattle was a loser,
though, and after his second season, Coach Tom Flores, a former
quarterback who worked well with Mirer, was fired, replaced by
Dennis Erickson.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he came it didn't do me any good,'' Mirer said. He was
dealt to the Bears in 1997 when the franchise was floundering. It
was a time of turmoil for players.
</P>
<P>
   ``The town was against the organization from the start of me
being there,'' he said. ``I just got caught up in bad times. The
hard part was being home and feeling like that. It was my
neighborhood.''
</P>
<P>
   Mirer is from Elkhart, Ind., and broke many of Jeff George's
state scholastic passing records.
</P>
<P>
   Mirer is 29, 6 foot 3 inches and 212 pounds. He has a 20-34
record as a pro. He has a completion percentage of 53.3 with 62
interceptions to only 41 touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you study his history of who was coaching him in Seattle,
you see that there may be reasons for his past,'' said Pat Kirwan,
who was formerly the Jets' director of player administration and
has seen hours of Mirer film. Kirwan, now CNN's NFL analyst, added
that what happened to Mirer ``is a classic case of a high draft
pick who doesn't produce immediately _ you get labeled.''
</P>
<P>
   Kirwan said that Mirer would benefit from his last year in Green
Bay under Coach Mike Holmgren.
</P>
<P>
   Mirer arrived Saturday and immediately spent time in the late
evening with the Jets' quarterback coach Dan Henning. It will be
part of a weeklong crash course if Mirer is to see action next
Saturday night against the Giants.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets have an extra practice day this week, and there will be
several two-a-day workouts, which will benefit Mirer. He takes over
a backup role that has been unproductive so far in two preseason
games: Ray Lucas and Zolak combined for 15 drives that led to only
two field goals.
</P>
<P>
   Mirer said he ``can still play in this league,'' that ``some of
the stuff I've been through it would be easy to call it quits, but
I've taken it head-on.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-22-99 1903EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
