<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-DURSO-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON HORSE RACING: MANDATORY INDUSTRY TAX ON AUCTION SALES IS
CRITICIZED 
</HEADLINE>
 (ms) 
 By JOE DURSO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARATOGA SPRINGS, N.Y. _ You might never have suspected it, from
the slick way the state of racing was portrayed at the annual Round
Table conference of the Jockey Club last week. But John Jacobs, the
son of the late great trainer Hirsch Jacobs and a leading agent for
Japanese money in the booming horse market, states it bluntly:
``There's a storm brewing.''
</P>
<P>
   Or, to put it another way: ``I can't remember any time in recent
years when anything has been so divisive in the racing business.''
</P>
<P>
   Jacobs means the recent decision to impose a tax of 1 percent on
the purchase price of horses at auction sales. You bid $3 million
for a yearling, you pay $30,000 to the National Thoroughbred Racing
Association, the new ``league office'' established 16 months ago to
unify the racing business.
</P>
<P>
   Why? As Tim Smith, the commissioner of the association said in a
letter to thoroughbred buyers, ``These funds not only will go to
support existing, successful programs, like co-op advertising and
expanded TV coverage, but also will enable the NTRA to launch
extremely important, additional marketing programs such as
increased Internet and consumer promotions, customer service
training for track employees, new fan development, on-site
enhancements, data base marketing and the like.''
</P>
<P>
   While you try to translate ``new fan development'' and ``on-site
enhancements,'' you might keep in mind some other fuzzy ideas that
Smith and the seven vice presidents in his league office have
produced. One involves a ``pennant race'' for older horses,
awarding points for a series of handicap races reaching a peak in
the Pacific Classic on Aug. 29. But in recent weeks, Silver Charm,
Real Quiet and Victory Gallop have all been sidelined or retired
with injuries, reducing the Pacific Classic to a meaningless race
in a meaningless pennant race.
</P>
<P>
   No mention was made of such negative trends at the Round Table
conference, which included a film on the Triple Crown that also
didn't mention that Charismatic broke his leg in the Belmont
Stakes. Nor was any mention made of the dispute over the new tax on
buying horses.
</P>
<P>
   But the pitch was made in a recent letter to the ``Dear
Thoroughbred Buyer'' from Bill Greely, president of the Keeneland
track in Lexington, Ky., where 4,000 horses will be put up for sale
in September.
</P>
<P>
   ``Beginning with the September yearling sale,'' Greely wrote,
``an NTRA fee _ 1 percent of the purchase price for each horse _
will be added to your buyer's statement from Keeneland. We will
forward that amount to the NTRA. If you intend to purchase at
Keeneland but do not wish to pay the 1 percent fee, please send a
letter by Sept. 3.''
</P>
<P>
   The letter gives no hint of what would happen if the buyer chose
not to pay the tax.
</P>
<P>
   Greely adds that ``the fee is a worthwhile investment in the
future of the thoroughbred industry.'' But some major members of
the industry don't agree.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could never attach that fee to your statement to Japanese
buyers,'' John Jacobs said. ``They would never pay it. We're trying
to bring new buyers into the business, so why stick an important
new buyer with a tax on what he buys? Adding $30,000 is like adding
a year's training charges. Some people are bitter. There's a storm
brewing.''
</P>
<P>
   Jacobs turned his memory back to the time when Hirsch Jacobs
would send him to Finger Lakes or Green Mountain to sell eight
horses to pay the bills.
</P>
<P>
   ``My father,'' he remembered, ``would tell me, `Don't come back
with eight horses.' I saw many meat-and-potatoes horsemen who had
to survive.''
</P>
<P>
   He is also worried that the 1 percent tax this year might be 2
percent next year. And he is a supporter of the NTRA.
</P>
<P>
   Caesar Kimmel, the prominent horseman and the father of John
Kimmel, the smart young trainer, also sees trouble brewing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The NTRA has to make it on its own,'' he said. ``To impose
more expenses on owners is ludicrous; 95 percent of the owners
don't break even, as it is. And why tax the buyer of a horse? Half
of these horses will never get to the race track.''
</P>
<P>
   Tim Smith and his marketers gave their self-congratulatory
reports to a room filled with racing leaders. They included the
most powerful new force in the business, Frank Stronach, the
Canadian industrialist who recently bought Santa Anita and
Gulfstream Park. He watched silently. This was a few days after he
told The Daily Racing Form: ``I don't like mandatory deductions. I
don't like mandatory anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Stronach's contracts with the NTRA end on April 1, and he has
said the tracks would withdraw unless the association strictly
defines its role and makes certain changes. It's even money that
Tim Smith will blink first.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
