<HEADER>
A5745 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-CLINTON-VACATION-NYT &LR;      08-22 0633
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-VACATION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR THE FIRST LADY, A FUND-RAISING VACATION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass.)  (mk) 
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EDGARTOWN, Mass. _ Hillary Rodham Clinton held her second
fund-raising event of her vacation on Sunday, greeting nearly 250
people at a brunch at the Martha's Vineyard home of Frank Biondi, a
former Viacom executive. The price of admission was $1,000 a
ticket, yielding the first lady _ and her expected New York Senate
candidacy _ nearly a quarter of a million dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Her husband, President Clinton, joined her but did not address
the audience and did not participate in the picture-taking as Mrs.
Clinton stood with guests for snapshots. Clinton did, however, play
the saxophone, which he borrowed from the high school jazz band
that was playing at the brunch, and belted out ``My Funny
Valentine'' in honor of a couple celebrating their 35th wedding
anniversary. The event was closed to the press, but Joe Lockhart,
Clinton's spokesman, described the president's rendition as jazzy.
</P>
<P>
   The brunch was just one more event in a swirl of socializing
since the Clintons arrived here Thursday for vacation. This has
left them little time to spend watching television, which is too
bad for the Republican National Committee in Washington. The
committee began saturating the cable airwaves here on Sunday with a
commercial aimed at an audience of one, the president, urging him
to agree to the so-called ``lock box'' to save money for Social
Security.
</P>
<P>
   The weather has been overcast and drizzly, but the Clintons have
been out and about. After Sunday morning's fund-raising brunch,
attended by many of the Clintons' regular Vineyard friends like
Vernon Jordan and Maurice Tempelsman, they headed to a local
restaurant, Balance, for a birthday party for Kelly Craighead, a
longtime aide to both Clintons.
</P>
<P>
   Upon leaving, the president encountered a young man named Mark
O'Connor, a Boston bicycle messenger who complained about an
ordinance that imposes a $100 fine for not wearing a bicycle
helmet. The president told him that not wearing a helmet was risky.
O'Connor said he was a slow and careful rider and that his helmet
sometimes blocked his view. Clinton told him, ``You may be slow,
but the streets are fast.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton is to take a break from her fund raising until next
Saturday when her family decamps from Martha's Vineyard and heads
for the Hamptons, on Long Island, N.Y., where they will stay at the
home of Steven Spielberg, the director. She has scheduled four
fund-raising events next weekend, two in connection with the
Democratic National Committee, and two more when the family visits
the Finger Lakes in upstate New York for a few days after that. The
total take for her two-week vacation should be about $800,000, said
Howard Wolfson, her campaign spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   After the Clintons flew to Nantucket from Martha's Vineyard on
Friday for the first of Mrs. Clinton's vacation fund-raisers, the
Republicans complained that the first lady was raising money on the
taxpayers' tab.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Pfeifle, a spokesman for the Republican National Committee,
said that Mrs. Clinton's political travel cost taxpayers an average
of $20,000 an hour of travel time. Wolfson said that the campaign
would reimburse the Treasury for the cost of a first-class airplane
ticket to Nantucket, adding that such reimbursement was the same
rule that applied to previous occupants of the White House who made
political trips.
</P>
<P>
   Pfeifle said the cost of a first-class ticket came nowhere near
the actual cost of travel for Mrs. Clinton and her entourage.
Wolfson said Republicans had not objected when the families of
Republican presidents made political trips and reimbursed the
Treasury for the cost of the air fare.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-22-99 1925EDT &QL; 
