<SLUG> BC-TEN-BRONXCLASSIC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POPP FINDS THAT KEEPING HIS COMPOSURE IS PART OF WINNING 
</HEADLINE>
 (ms) 
 By RAY KRUEGER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Alexander Popp is starting to realize that is takes
more than strokes and footwork to be a tennis star.
</P>
<P>
   Popp, of Germany, kept his composure Sunday to beat Sebastien de
Chaunac of France, 6-7 (4-7), 7-6 (7-4), 6-0, to capture GHI Bronx
Tennis Classic, a Challenger Tour event in Crotona Park. In the
women's final, Erika de Lone of Lincoln, Mass., was up, 6-1, when
Els Callens of Belgium retired because of strained left quadriceps.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-foot-7-inch Popp, who at age 22 is ranked 169th in the
world, has risen from nowhere on the Futures Tour, the lowest level
of pro tennis.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't win a match for six months,'' he said of the
beginning of 1998. ``Then I got lucky, won a few matches, and that
improved my confidence and then I won more matches.''
</P>
<P>
   Popp didn't get discouraged Sunday after dropping the first-set
tie breaker to de Chaunac, who crumbled after losing the second-set
tie breaker. Popp held serve at love in the first game of the third
set, and at 30-all in the second game, he hit a forehand passing
shot that appeared to clip the line.
</P>
<P>
   It was called good, but de Chaunac did not agree and glared at
the chair umpire. De Chaunac then pushed a slice backhand into the
net to lose the game.
</P>
<P>
   Popp held his serve in the next game to go up, 3-0, and de
Chaunac received a warning for firing a ball over the fence.
</P>
<P>
   De Chaunac won only 4 points in the next three games and Popp
was handed a $7,200 winner's check.
</P>
<P>
   ``He sort of lost of his composure after he lost the second
set,'' Popp said of de Chaunac. ``I didn't think I was playing well
in the beginning, but I just tried to hang in there.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Popp and the 21-year-old de Chaunac, who is ranked 232nd in
the world, will compete in the U.S. Open qualifying rounds this
week.
</P>
<P>
   Both De Lone, 26, who received a $8,800 winner's check and is
ranked 106th, and Callens, 29, who is ranked 91st, are in the
Open's main draw. But Callens is not sure if her injury will
prevent her from playing. ``I will try to rest and see what
happens,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
