u s BC-FBN-MART-TRIAL-NYT     08-22 0574
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-MART-TRIAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHARACTER WITNESSES EXPECTED TO TESTIFY FOR DOLPHINS' MARTIN 
</HEADLINE>
 (ms) 
 By CHARLIE NOBLES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lawyers representing Tony Martin, the Miami Dolphins wide
receiver, in a federal trial on money-laundering charges will
present what they described as several prominent character
witnesses Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Those character witnesses are presumed to come from the
Dolphins.
</P>
<P>
   Martin flew to San Diego to play in a game against the Chargers
on Saturday night, catching three passes in the Dolphins' 13-10
victory.
</P>
<P>
   Martin is charged with attempting to pay $175,000 in lawyer's
fees on behalf of Rickey Brownlee, the twice-convicted Miami drug
dealer, and with leasing three cars for Brownlee.
</P>
<P>
   If convicted, Martin, who has started for two Super Bowl teams
in the last five seasons could face three to five years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Court Judge K. Michael Moore decided that Martin,
33, would be tried with Brownlee, whom he has known for about 15
years. Thus, the bulk of the nearly three-week trial has involved
Brownlee's alleged drug-dealing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not fair at all,'' said Howard Srebnick, one of Martin's
attorneys, about Martin's case being coupled with Brownlee's.
</P>
<P>
   In April, the Dolphins signed Martin to a four-year,
$14.2-million contract, expecting him to fill the club's longtime
need for a deep-threat receiver.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Jimmy Johnson and a number of Martin's new teammates
attended court on the trial's first day in a show of support.
</P>
<P>
   Martin denied in conversations secretly taped by the government
that he had ever leased cars for Brownlee. On the tapes, Max Lloyd,
owner of Don L. Leasing in Pompano Beach, Fla., and cooperating
with the government, asked him that.
</P>
<P>
   After a pause, Martin replied, ``No.''
</P>
<P>
   A little later Martin became upset at Lloyd, saying Brownlee was
not a drug dealer.
</P>
<P>
   Last Friday, Paul Robarge, an Internal Revenue Service agent,
may have given Martin an inadvertent boost when he testified that
money allegedly laundered by the football player might have come
from legitimate sources _ a restaurant and convenience store owned
by Brownlee.
</P>
<P>
   But then earlier this week, Martin's former business manager,
Rick Norton, who is based in San Diego, asserted that Martin was
nearly broke when the receiver told him early last year that he
intended to put $100,000 in his bank account to cover a check for
Brownlee's attorney.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was in shock,'' Norton said during his testimony. ``I was
concerned it was a money-laundering situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Even should Martin be convicted, the Dolphins expect him to play
this season, because it is anticipated that he would appeal the
verdict.
</P>
<P>
   It is plain that the Dolphins' contract gives Martin _ who
declared bankruptcy in March _ a chance to solve his financial
problems. He made $9.1 million from 1993 through 1998 yet spent
almost $11 million.
</P>
<P>
   Martin, who was a quarterback at Mesa College in Colorado, was a
fifth-round draft pick of the Jets in 1989 and was promptly
switched to wide receiver. He was cut at the end of training camp,
then played five seasons with the Dolphins.
</P>
<P>
   He then played for San Diego, where he began to assert himself
as one of the game's top pass receivers. He averaged 72 catches
over four seasons for the Chargers and led the team to the 1995
Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Last season, he helped Atlanta gain its first Super Bowl berth. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-22-99 1949EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
