<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Columbine victim appeals for help in Atlanta
 &HT;    WITH PHOTO
 &HT;    By Paul Donsky
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Lance Kirklin, a survivor of the Columbine High School
shooting, visited an Atlanta church on Sunday as part of a local
fund-raising effort to help Kirklin's family pay his mounting
medical bills, which could total $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   Kirklin was shot five times during last April's massacre in
Littleton, Colo. The lanky 16-year-old's scarred face has become
one of the most enduring symbols of the shooting.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just amazing to me all the good people in this world who
don't even know someone, but they want to help them,'' Kirklin told
several hundred worshippers at Gospel Tabernacle Christian Church
in east Atlanta. ``I just want to say thank you.''
</P>
<P>
   Kirklin has had five operations and may need five more to repair
his face. A thick scar snakes from behind his left ear and over his
jaw toward a diamond-shaped patch of skin that has been grafted
from his leg. With no medical insurance, Kirklin's father has no
way of paying the hospital tab, now at $229,000.
</P>
<P>
   After the service, Atlanta retiree Richard Wilson donated $10 to
the Kirklins.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is needed to help him go on,'' Wilson said.
</P>
<P>
   Kirklin was brought to Atlanta by Harry Ross, an Atlanta-based
political pollster. Ross has mailed letters to local churches
asking for donations and plans to bring Kirklin back to Atlanta on
Friday to speak at a crime prevention seminar he is coordinating.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is a miracle child, shot five times at point-blank range
and survived,'' Ross said. ``This can happen again if we're not
prepared to wage war against teen-age aggression and teen-age
violence.''
</P>
<P>
   Kirklin, who began school last week, flew back to Colorado
Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   The teen says he does not fear death. In fact, making the most
of every day has become his philosophy of life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just try to live life to the fullest,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone interested in making a donation should make checks
payable to the Lance Kirklin Fund. Accounts have been set up at
local branches of Bank of America and Capitol City Bank &AMP; Trust.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
