</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-QUAKE-VICTIMS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Atlanta church mourns quake vicitims
 &HT;    By Rick Badie
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The rosy faces of David, Jennifer and Jeffrey Kilic
beam from a hallway bulletin board at Mount Vernon Baptist Church
in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``Promoted To Heaven _ A Miracle,'' says a caption above the
pictures. Missing is a photograph of Katie Kilic, the youngest
Kilic sibling to perish in Tuesday's brutal earthquake in Turkey.
</P>
<P>
   David, 2, Jennifer, 5, and Jeffrey, 6, died instantly. Katie, 7
months, died hours later. Their mother, Jan Kilic, suffered head
injuries, but survived the Aug. 17 earthquake. Another daughter,
Natalie, 3, only received a black eye.
</P>
<P>
   It's unclear when the two survivors will return to the Atlanta
suburb of Marietta. William Kemp III, Jan's father, said Sunday it
could be as early as Tuesday. The bodies of the four children are
expected later this week. Nothing's certain.
</P>
<P>
   Left to make sense of the tragedy are grieving relatives and a
church congregation that on Sunday leaned on faith for
understanding. The Kilic children and their mother were well-liked
members of Mount Vernon, where sorrow permeated the 11 a.m.
service.
</P>
<P>
   Make no mistake, the Rev. Sam Boyd told about 600 attendees:
``The root of all tragedies, be they natural disasters or
premeditated acts, is sin. And it's omnipresent.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to see more pain, pestilence and destruction in
this world,'' he said. ``God is trying to get our attention through
these things. . .''
</P>
<P>
   Calling the loss of four children ``irreversible,'' Boyd said
Jan, or anyone faced with extreme adversity, should ``focus on
eternity. I'm sure that God has more planned for Jan and the lives
of those four children than we could ever see,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The worst tragedy in your life could become the greatest
triumph in your life.''
</P>
<P>
   Boyd ended the sermon by inviting people to pray at the altar.
Linda Thompson, Jan's best friend and mother of three girls who
played with the Kilic children, stepped forward.
</P>
<P>
   Before the service, she called Jan a woman committed to
relationships _ with God, friends and family. Jan's husband, Babur,
a Marietta anesthesiologist, did not make the trip to Turkey with
the family. His family had been vacationing in the resort town of
Yalova when the earthquake struck.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jan had a healthy, confident, stable, loving family,''
Thompson said. ``That's the No. 1 thing I can say about her. The
most important thing to her right now is she knows this is God's
hand in her life and that He is close by her.''
</P>
<P>
   Thompson and Gwen Jenkins, the pre-school minister at Mount
Vernon, said the structure Jan and Babur provided their children
was evident in their behavior.
</P>
<P>
   David, the 2-year-old, ``was always trying to tell me
something,'' Jenkins said. ``I didn't always understand him, but he
always talked with a smile on his face.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
