<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NATIONAL-DEBT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Don't forget, national debt clock is still ticking
 &HT;    By Paul Donsky
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Remember the national debt?
</P>
<P>
   With all the talk of a budget surplus that has consumed
Washington in recent weeks, the Concord Coalition is worried many
people have forgotten that the nation is some $5.6 trillion in the
red -- and climbing.
</P>
<P>
   So the bipartisan budget watchdog group has taken its National
Debt Clock out of storage and hit the road to remind the public
that the government's finances are not yet in order.
</P>
<P>
   The first stop on the two-week tour was Sunday in downtown
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people forget that we have a national debt which is
growing,'' said Phil Smith of Atlanta, regional director of the
Concord Coalition. ``We're getting closer to a balanced budget, but
we're not quite there yet.''
</P>
<P>
   The large sign, carried on a 25-foot trailer, gives an
up-to-the-minute estimate of the size of the country's debt. At
4:30 p.m. Sunday, the debt stood at 5,640,616,090,000 and counting.
</P>
<P>
   The sign was on display Sunday afternoon in Atlanta at the
Candler Building, 127 Peachtree St. The clock will visit cities in
Alabama, Mississippi, Texas, Tennessee and Louisiana, Smith said.
The trip, the first since 1997, was timed to coincide with
Congress' two-week summer break.
</P>
<P>
   The nation's booming economy has helped slow the rate the debt
is growing. But the Concord Coalition, co-chaired by former Senator
Sam Nunn of Georgia, wants to make sure people realize it's still
going up.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, some Democrats are arguing that some of the
budget surplus should be spent to shore up social security, while
Republicans are pushing for a big tax cut.
</P>
<P>
   ``So we have a problem on both sides of the aisle,'' Smith said.
``We're praying for gridlock. If neither side gets their way, then
the debt starts getting paid down automatically.''
</P>
<P>
   Reaction to the sign was mixed in Atlanta. Some walked by and
shook their heads after seeing the clock, while others simply
ignored it, Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
