<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-TALK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RETELLING OF NABOKOV'S `LOLITA' CREATES ITS OWN CONTROVERSY  
 ARNETT PLANS TO WRITE HISTORY OF CNN 
THE SMELL OF NEWS FROM LOS ANGELES
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Bylines appear at the end of each item.) 
(ms) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The copyright tiff has ended, but the tensions are still
simmering between Vladimir Nabokov's son and an Italian author who
has written a retelling of ``Lolita'' from the young girl's
perspective.
</P>
<P>
   In June, Foxrock Inc., the publisher of ``Lo's Diary,''
announced a ``Solomon-like agreement'' that allowed American
publication of the book with a 5 percent royalty to Nabokov's son,
Dmitri, along with added commentary from him and the author, Pia
Pera. Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux had earlier canceled publication
after the Nabokov estate sued, charging copyright infringement.
</P>
<P>
   Nabokov's preface is not particularly gracious: ``As some
readers may know, one Pia Pera (henceforth `PP,') an Italian
journalist, author of some stories that I have not read and of a
translation of `Eugene Onegin' into Italian which I have, decided
to seek inspiration, fortune and fame from a book called
`Lolita.'''
</P>
<P>
   Nabokov then notes the many similarities in the book to
``Lolita,'' like ``articles of clothing, hair styles, personal
effects, pets, gifts, even the bacon purloined from a breakfast
tray.'' He concludes by describing the compromise and his hope that
his permission to publish set a precedent without spending money on
costly litigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The path has been a rather tortured one,'' he said, ``the
knock on the door belated. But the copyright to `Lolita' has been
honored, and `Lo's Diary' is in your hands. Whether it draws from
`Lolita' well or badly I leave for you to judge.''
</P>
<P>
   In an e-mail note from Italy, Ms. Pera dismissed Nabokov's
preface as ``a disappointingly dull emulation of his father's
mastery of irony and, on occasions, virtuoso contempt.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Though I have much to say on the questions raised by my book,
I have ultimately decided not to publish an afterword to Lo's
diary: let the work speak for itself,'' she wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Pera made several attempts to write an afterword addressing
issues raised by the copyright dispute. Her early essays ranged up
to eight pages and were angry in tone, the author's American
publisher, Barney Rosset, said. The last attempt, he said, amounted
to one paragraph: ``Never mind how `Lo's Diary' got to you, whether
it traveled first or second class, comfortably or not; never mind,
here it is. I hope you will enjoy it.'' But soon after, the author
withdrew even that remark, leaving Rosset fuming.
</P>
<P>
   ``Believe me, the women whom I have known and loved would not
act in this foolish and fatuous manner,'' Rosset said. ``Can you
imagine Susan Sontag, as a result of an unfriendly critique of her
work, running away and pouting in a corner?'' --DOREEN CARVAJAL &QC;
</P>
<P>
   ARNETT PLANS TO WRITE THE HISTORY OF CNN &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What a difference five months can make. In April, Peter Arnett
was leaving CNN. He and the network had brought each other fame
during the 1991 Persian Gulf war and misfortune over the 1998
Tailwind broadcast, a report about accusations that nerve gas was
used by U.S. forces in Vietnam that was later retracted, and were
parting on not-so-friendly terms.
</P>
<P>
   Now, however, Arnett and Ed Turner, the former executive vice
president of CNN, are shopping around a book proposal for an
authorized history of CNN and assessment of the network's effect on
television news. If things move quickly enough, the work's
publication could be pegged to the network's 20th anniversary next
year. And CNN's top executives are happy to cooperate. ``We were
asked to, and Ted and Tom said yes,'' said Sue Binford, a CNN
spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   Ted is Ted Turner, the network's founder and the vice chairman
of its parent company, Time Warner Inc. Tom is Tom Johnson, the
network's chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Ed Turner, the co-author of the prospective work (and no
relation to Ted Turner) said last week, ``I want to make the book a
combination of things _ not just 24-hour news but the things that
came out of it.'' But, he added: ``We don't have a publisher. We
just have an eager agent and two guys ready to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Arnett, who worked for CNN for 18 years before parting company
with the network, now does interviews of world leaders for a Web
site, ForeignTV.com. &QL; 
-- FELICITY BARRINGER &QC;
</P>
<P>
   THE SMELL OF NEWS FROM LOS ANGELES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The team planning next spring's new look at The Los Angeles
Times had orders to think outside the box. But some executives at
the newspaper might have wondered whether there was such a thing as
thinking too far outside the box when they were asked to give their
newspaper a sniff test.
</P>
<P>
   At a meeting about three weeks ago, consultants from Nissan
Design International, one of three outside firms advising the
newspaper on its redesign, gleefully warned executives that they
had taken the outside-the-box business to heart. Then they passed
around little boxes of shredded newspaper, including The Times, a
unit of the Times Mirror Co., and two competitors.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict, one participant said, was that The Times smelled
``a little sour.'' Then the consultants passed around test tubes
containing alternative scents like laundry detergent, hand lotion,
citrus, coffee and doughnuts.
</P>
<P>
   The coffee scent proved to be a crowd-pleaser, as did the
doughnut smell.
</P>
<P>
   A second meeting with another consultant, Landor Associates,
which specializes in brand identity, had a different
shake-things-up suggestion: a page in which the newspaper's name
was printed in a no-frills, all-lowercase typeface and run together
like a Web site address. It was also chartreuse.
</P>
<P>
   In both cases, participants at the meetings said, the
suggestions were offered less as real options than ways to loosen
people up.
</P>
<P>
   The redesign, the newspaper's first in more than 10 years,
``stems from a desire to organize the paper as best we can and give
maximum exposure to the content we produce,'' said John Arthur, the
newspaper's managing editor for regional editions, who is heading
the 80-person internal redesign team. It also stems from The Times'
shift to a slightly smaller size.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, he said, the newspaper should have a cleaner and
more uniform look. ``This is not going to be a radical new
presentation that is going to alienate readers,'' he said. ``The
idea is to bring in new readers while keeping all the readers we
have.''
</P>
<P>
   Another participant in the design meetings, who spoke on the
condition of anonymity, said, ``I don't think anyone's out there
pouring perfume into the ink.'' --FELICITY BARRINGER &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
