<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   REVAMPED GUN MAGAZINES ATTRACTING MORE READERS
</P>
<P>
   Along with the highly publicized acts of gun violence during the
last year _ including episodes in Littleton, Colo., Atlanta and Los
Angeles that received front-page newspaper coverage and 24-hour
news-channel surveillance _ comes a peculiar, and to some
disturbing, flowering of the gun media.
</P>
<P>
   The gun magazines have enjoyed a minor but notable surge in
popularity over the last two years. They are retooling their
designs, printing on better-quality paper and publishing articles
about the threat of rioting at the turn of the millennium. The
combined result is that the magazines are, for the most part,
attracting more readers.
</P>
<P>
   TENSIONS OVER `LOLITA' RETELLING
</P>
<P>
   The copyright tiff has ended, but tensions are still simmering
between Vladimir Nabokov's son and Pia Pera, an Italian author who
has written a retelling of ``Lolita'' from the girl's perspective.
In June, Foxrock, the publisher of ``Lo's Diary,'' announced an
agreement that allowed U.S. publication of the book with a 5
percent royalty to Nabokov's son, Dmitri, along with added
commentary from him and the author. Nabokov's preface is not
particularly gracious.
</P>
<P>
   ANOTHER BIG PLAYER IN ALUMINUM
</P>
<P>
   While Alcoa and Western rivals warily circle each other to
retain supremacy in the aluminum business, Trans-World Group, a
relatively obscure but powerful competitor that operates
extensively in the former Soviet Union, has been increasing its
control in a region responsible for much of the world's supply.
</P>
<P>
   THE TROUBLE WITH ONLINE RETURNS
</P>
<P>
   E-commerce executives have realized that managing online sales
can be as difficult as managing offline merchandising. Merchandise
returns, in particular, have been nettlesome for Internet stores,
especially those without previous experience in traditional
retailing.
</P>
<P>
   THE RISK OF REGISTERING WEB NAMES
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to a combination of foresight, luck and good timing,
Richard Forman's company, Register.com, is the first and most
aggressive player in the game of breaking up the monopoly on
Internet address registrations. But more than 250 companies are
expected eventually to compete in what is stacking up to be a risky
venture. One big unknown is how far registration fees will drop. An
even bigger gamble is that key rules for the game remain unknown.
</P>
<P>
   FORD TO START BIG AD CAMPAIGN
</P>
<P>
   Trying to establish a common brand image for its ever-growing
family of sport utility vehicles, Ford Motor Co. is preparing to
start one of the largest advertising campaigns ever in the auto
industry. After relying for nearly two decades on its ``built Ford
tough'' theme for pickups, it has created a separate slogan, ``no
boundaries,'' for its sport utility models and will start
advertising them as a group, as well as individually.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
