<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-PADRES </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Braves win on Jordan's hit in 9th
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Brian Jordan is sick of talking about his sore right
hand, and sick of swinging with it too. But he allowed himself to
do a little bit of both for the sake of a 3-2 win over the Padres
on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Spreading some of his hurt around, Jordan singled in the winning
run in the bottom of the ninth inning to complete a three-game
sweep of San Diego. The Cincinnati Reds, contenders in the Central
Division and wild-card races, come into town for three games
starting today.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan's face was still long when he came out of the training
room after the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was about to pull myself out of the game after my third
at-bat,'' Jordan said. ``But then I figured I might as well stick
it out.''
</P>
<P>
   In his fourth at-bat, Jordan singled on the infield to start the
eighth inning, just after the left-field scoreboard at Turner Field
showed the Mets had rallied to beat the Cardinals in the first game
of their doubleheader. That meant the Mets, who would go on to lose
the second game, were a half-game up in first place at that point.
</P>
<P>
   Andruw Jones followed with a walk, but when Jose Hernandez
failed to get a good bunt down, the rally was all but over.
</P>
<P>
   In the ninth, however, the Braves came up with a victory in
their final inning for the 23rd time this season. And the Padres,
who did their best to give the Braves their 4-3 win in the opening
game of the series Friday, were back at it. Reliever Dan Miceli
gave them their opening by walking Gerald Williams on four pitches
to lead off the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   Bret Boone moved Williams to second with a sacrifice and Miceli
walked Jones intentionally to set up a force situation for a
possible double-play _ and possibly a preferred shot at the
sore-handed Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to block everything out with the game on the line,''
Jordan said. ``I tried to go up there with a clear mind, see the
ball out of his hand.''
</P>
<P>
   With San Diego closer Trevor Hoffman safely on the bullpen
mound, Jordan took an inside fastball for a strike from Miceli and
filed away that he'd probably see it again. He took two pitches out
of the zone to work the count to 2-1, got that fastball in again
and pulled it to left field to score Williams easily.
</P>
<P>
   That made a winner out of John Rocker in another successful
outing by Terry Mulholland, who dueled Sterling Hitchcock to a 2-2
tie with eight innings of quality work.
</P>
<P>
   TONIGHT
</P>
<P>
   Opponent: Cincinnati Reds.
</P>
<P>
   When; where: 7:40 p.m.; Turner Field.
</P>
<P>
   TV; radio: TBS; WSB (750-AM).
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
