<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990822.0143 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-22 20:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5769 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-YUGOSLAVIA-DRASKOVIC-     08-22 0672
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUGOSLAVIA-DRASKOVIC-630(2TAKES)(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE OTHER COUPLE IN SERBIAN POLITICS: THE DRASKOVICS  
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By STEVEN ERLANGER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE Yugoslavia _ Vuk Draskovic, the leader of the Serbian
Renewal Movement, and his influential wife, Danica, find themselves
at a political crossroads, suddenly less radical than many of their
supporters, their commitment to the ouster of President Slobodan
Milosevic of Yugoslavia called into question.
</P>
<P>
   Having built a reputation as fierce and combative leaders of the
opposition to Milosevic and his powerful wife, Mirjana Markovic,
the Draskovics now have money, power, position and a lot to lose _
making them much like the tightly knit Milosevics themselves, whom
they detest but to whom they are often compared.
</P>
<P>
   The Draskovics control Belgrade, its many business opportunities
and its powerful television station, Studio B _ all at the
sufferance of Milosevic's Socialist Party.
</P>
<P>
   And their efforts to find a peaceful way to oust Milosevic, to
negotiate with him for new elections while trying to subvert him,
have confused some of their followers and helped keep the
opposition divided.
</P>
<P>
   That was glaringly evident at a large anti-Milosevic rally on
Thursday in Belgrade, which drew up to 100,000 people. When
Draskovic realized how many had shown up, he felt compelled to
crash the rally he had refused to attend.
</P>
<P>
   The bearded Draskovic is normally a compelling orator, a kind of
rock star. But his speech, calling for early elections and not
Milosevic's immediate removal, was too moderate for the crowd,
marking a strange new episode in his career.
</P>
<P>
   The Draskovics' desire for political power and dominance among
the varied opposition leaders has led them to make various deals
with the authorities while holding to the idea of fundamental
democratic change. As they alternate between opposition and
cooperation _ what critics call opportunism _ more people ask
whether they have any other real aim beyond power.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday night on Studio B, Draskovic defended his caution, saying
it would be easy to call for civil war. ``I am Milosevic's
opponent, but I am also opposed to a single head rolling,'' he
said. ``I don't want people to get killed because of Milosevic.''
</P>
<P>
   But many disappointed despisers of Milosevic say the Draskovics
have become afraid of revolutionary disorder, corrupted and
co-opted, more interested in replacing the leader at the top than
in destroying his system of crony capitalism and special favors.
</P>
<P>
   Some suggest that they are so driven by an intense personal
hatred for their erstwhile coalition partner of only three years
ago, the Democratic Party leader, Zoran Djindjic _ an animosity
fully reciprocated _ that the fight for supremacy within the
opposition has overshadowed the fight against Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   Such charges infuriate Vuk and Danica Draskovic, now 53 and 54
respectively. In a recent, four-hour interview at their comfortable
home, Mrs. Draskovic said bitterly: ``Who led the demonstrations in
1991? And '93? And '96? Who led the fight in the streets? Who went
to jail?''
</P>
<P>
   But each time it has been Mrs. Draskovic, a former judge forced
to resign in 1973 by the Communists for refusing to jail a jobless
man, who has pushed her husband, the orator and mover of crowds, to
act boldly.
</P>
<P>
   In late 1996, during enormous street protests that ultimately
forced Milosevic to grant the democratic opposition their victories
in local elections, Mrs. Draskovic was captured on television
urging protesters to take clubs and march on Dedinje, the
neighborhood where Milosevic lives, and to seize power from the
thieves who had stolen the elections.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether it was time now _ after the loss of Kosovo _ to
urge people to take clubs to Dedinje again, Mrs. Draskovic answered
immediately, ``Yes, it's always time.''
</P>
<P>
   Her husband said nearly as quickly: ``No. No one wants a civil
war.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   It is a tension that has defined their relationship, which is
strong and mutually dependent, between the smart, aggressive
daughter of a Chetnik _ a monarchist guerrilla during the Nazi
occupation _ and the son of a proud Partisan, a fighter with the
victorious Communist Tito.
</P>
<P>
   They were law students in 1968, the year of student upheavals
throughout Europe, when they first met and dated, and took part in
protests here against social injustice, inequality and ``the red
bourgeoisie,'' the party bureaucracy.
</P>
<P>
   Tito promised reforms, exhilarating Draskovic and the others,
who danced and shouted, ``Tito we love you!''
</P>
<P>
   But Danica Boskovic, Draskovic remembered in a 1990 interview
with On magazine, was utterly contemptuous of the half-Croatian
Tito and of their faith in him, and she exploded when Vuk tried to
pull her into the celebratory kolo, or dance.
</P>
<P>
   ``What kolo?'' she demanded. ``That bandit, that Ustashe'' _ a
Croatian fascist. ``He's cheated us and fooled us just to get us to
calm down. I thought you were smarter than that.''
</P>
<P>
   Vuk said: ``Don't speak that way about Comrade Tito. Get into
the kolo.'' And Danica said: ``Choose: him or me.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course I chose Tito,'' Vuk said, ``and I seem to remember I
pushed her away.''
</P>
<P>
   A week later, Tito reneged and called the students
counterrevolutionaries. ``I repented,'' Vuk said, ``and for four
years I tried to exchange one word with Danica, in vain. She would
not see me for four years.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a true story, Danica said, laughing. Why did she relent?
``Vuk changed,'' she said. ``He left the party.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   But when is confusing. Communist Party membership was a
necessary ticket for employment in journalism, and he worked for
the Tanjug press agency from 1969 until 1978, when he was yanked
from Lusaka, Zambia, for making up a border war.
</P>
<P>
   He said that charge was nonsense, that he had had ideological
troubles, but he then worked for the official trade union newspaper
in Belgrade. He said he had given up on the party, but actually he
was expelled from it in 1982, when he published the fiercely
nationalist novel ``Knife.''
</P>
<P>
   The novel reopened many of the nationalist and religious issues
that Tito had suppressed but which helped break apart the country,
with so much bloodshed, after his death.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL END)
</P>
<P>
   Combined with Draskovic's deep and mythic Serbian nationalism _
``I'm a victim of my metaphors,'' he said as he expressed his love
for the dead multiethnic Yugoslavia _ his wife's anti-Communist
credentials have given their Serbian Renewal Party a considerable
reach into provincial Serbia, where the more citified intellectuals
of the Democratic Party do less well.
</P>
<P>
   Her fury at the expropriations and hypocrisies of Communism have
helped drive her toward action, she says, and without question
helped him toward political prominence.
</P>
<P>
   He was arrested by Milosevic's Serbian government for the first
time in March 1991, after a huge opposition demonstration against
the unrelenting propaganda of the state television, which the
protesters called ``TV Bastille.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Policemen and demonstrators clashed, and as the marchers
faltered, Danica, standing with Vuk on the balcony of the National
Theater, yelled at him: ``What are you waiting for? Shout,
`Forward!' ''
</P>
<P>
   He did. One policeman and one student died, and he was arrested
for a few days, but he had earned his reputation as ``king of the
streets.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   On June 1, 1993, there was a street riot in Belgrade after
Milosevic _ then president of Serbia, one of the republics making
up Yugoslavia _ engineered the sudden impeachment of the federal
president, the nationalist writer Dobrica Cosic.
</P>
<P>
   Draskovic led a march through Belgrade. But it was Mrs.
Draskovic who called on protesters to storm the federal Parliament.
She was filmed on state television saying, ``We should get inside,
beat up the police and bust up the whole building'' and asking
demonstrators, ``Where are your guns and your bombs?''
</P>
<P>
   The couple was arrested about 1:30 a.m., and both were beaten
badly by the police. Mrs. Draskovic was beaten by the chief of the
city's police, Rade Markovic _ now director of state security _ and
she is said to have behaved impressively, cursing the police and
the government with blood pouring from her mouth.
</P>
<P>
   Draskovic, in a separate cell, reacted differently. He wrote a
letter, later published in a newspaper, full of pathos to Mrs.
Markovic, Milosevic's powerful wife, begging her to free Danica.
</P>
<P>
   ``Danica and I have no children,'' he wrote. ``To me, she is my
wife and my child and my whole family. While she is in jail, my
entire family is in jail. Help her, esteemed Mrs. Markovic, and you
will have helped me, too. I would be endlessly grateful to you, as
long as I live.''
</P>
<P>
   The Draskovics were in jail or prison hospitals for some 40 days
before they were freed on July 9, flown to Paris by Danielle
Mitterrand, the wife of the French president at the time.
</P>
<P>
   But there are persistent reports that Draskovic wrote a second
letter from jail, promising Milosevic that if his wife was
released, the street demonstrations would stop and his party would
``disarm.''
</P>
<P>
   The couple denies that there was any unpublished letter, but
there is no question that Draskovic moved into more conventional
politics and showed an increasing willingness to deal with the
authorities to get a share of power and, it is said, money.
</P>
<P>
   There were already signs of that a year before. In the local
elections of 1992, a democratic coalition including his party won
the upscale Belgrade municipality of Savski Venac, a district
covering Dedinje, a wealthy area with many embassies and official
houses. At the inaugural session of the local Parliament, Draskovic
struck a deal with Milosevic's Socialists and dropped a coalition
partner.
</P>
<P>
   Danica's brother, Veselin Boskovic, took over the department
that managed municipal construction grounds _ in other words, he
controlled building permits and vacant city land. Accusations of
graft and corruption, including cash bribes for building permits,
were so plentiful that he was forced to step down, despite denials,
in part because Milosevic's party kept a dossier on him.
</P>
<P>
   But after the opposition won Belgrade in the 1996 elections,
Boskovic was given responsibility for the same department _ only
for all of Belgrade. Again, there have been numerous accusations of
bribery and graft, of payoffs for permits, which he and Mrs.
Draskovic have denied.
</P>
<P>
   Draskovic's chief of security, a former bodyguard who was a
member of a short-lived Serb Volunteer Guard that Draskovic sent to
Croatia to fight in 1991, was also appointed manager of the large
Tasmajdan Sports Center in downtown Belgrade. There, as with
parking lots, tickets are paid for in cash.
</P>
<P>
   Roksanda Nincic, a political reporter for the liberal Vreme
magazine, says that one of Draskovic's problems ``is that he's
organized a corrupt government that hasn't put Danica's family in
influential places so much, as in places where cash flows.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Draskovic has another brother and six sisters, and in the
interview, she listed each of them and their professions to refute
persistent allegations that she has granted them or their husbands
leases for lucrative shops in good locations.
</P>
<P>
   But Milosevic's Socialists _ which keep Draskovic in power in
Belgrade by not voting against him in the city council _ are widely
believed to have the means to harass and prosecute Boskovic and
other party and family favorites, a stick they use, Draskovic
rivals say, to keep Mr. and Mrs. Draskovic in line.
</P>
<P>
   The Draskovics also see control of Studio B, the Belgrade
television station, as vital to any relatively fair election
campaign _ another reason, some suggest, that Draskovic is not
eager to defy Milosevic too fiercely.
</P>
<P>
   It also helps explain why Draskovic agreed to participate in the
1997 Serbian elections, which Djindjic and most of the other
opposition parties boycotted (against U.S. advice) as unfair
because of a lack of truly independent media and outside electoral
observers.
</P>
<P>
   The election was only credible because Draskovic took part.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   But as he moved more fully into conventional politics, Danica
Draskovic was perceived as too visible and influential. Like
Hillary Clinton, she pulled back from the open play of politics _ a
decision her husband announced.
</P>
<P>
   Even today, he is defensive on the topic. ``She has influenced
me more than you think but less than normal,'' he said. ``She
influences me most when her stand is close to mine, but not if we
are opposed.''
</P>
<P>
   She is fiercer than he, it seems, about Djindjic. In the
interview, she remembered being infuriated by reading, her second
day in jail in 1993, a newspaper citing Djindjic.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said we got what we deserved,'' she said bitterly. When
Draskovic agreed later to go into the Zajedno coalition with
Djindjic in 1996, ``we were very close to divorce,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   She said, a touch sarcastically, ``He said, `I must save Serbia,
I must save my people.' And what happened?''
</P>
<P>
   ``You were right,'' Draskovic said. ``Zajedno was a big
mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Early this year, Draskovic shocked more of his supporters when
he went into Milosevic's federal government as a deputy prime
minister, citing the crisis in Kosovo and the need for national
unity while saying he remained, at heart, in opposition, working to
change the system from the inside.
</P>
<P>
   He became the acceptable face for the regime, its spokesman to
the West and Western media, yet he also criticized Milosevic and
his wife for manipulating Serbian patriotism for narrow political
goals. That finally got him dismissed before the war ended,
allowing him to revive his oppositionist credentials.
</P>
<P>
   Now he is accused of doing another deal with a desperate
Milosevic, favoring early elections in November. Draskovic denies
any deal and says elections are the only way forward. But what he
defines as pragmatic politics, aimed at power, is increasingly seen
here as opportunism. Yet his rivals have no clearer notion of how
to oust Milosevic, other than hoping to do it in the streets.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1990 interview with On magazine, Draskovic mentions that
in a preface to his book, ``Where Are You Going, Serbia?'', he is
compared to a rooster in a famous Ivo Andric short story. The
rooster is killed not because it sings badly, but because it crows
too early.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why it ends up in the pot,'' Draskovic said. ``And
that, I guess, is my destiny.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
