<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-LEDE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Labonte wins after 2-car pass
 &HT;    By Michael Carvell
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROOKLYN, Mich. _ The chase for this year's Winston Cup
championship may be boring, but Sunday's Pepsi 400 featured some of
the most exciting racing of the season.
</P>
<P>
   After watching Dale Earnhardt and Jeff Gordon engage in a
classic battle for the lead late in the 200-lap race, Bobby Labonte
sneaked past both of them at Michigan Speedway for his fourth
victory of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was pretty neat to watch those two,'' Labonte said. ``If
you didn't clear both of them, you knew you were going to be in
trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   After Labonte took the lead, he gradually pulled away from
Gordon to win by .865 seconds, averaging 144.332 mph. Rookie Tony
Stewart captured third place for the best finish of his career,
followed by points leader Dale Jarrett and Earnhardt.
</P>
<P>
   For Jarrett, it was the 13th race in a row he has placed sixth
or better. He expanded his lead in the points to a season-high 314
over Mark Martin, who finished seventh on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd like to win, but more than anything, if we can finish in
the top five, we know they'll have a difficult time catching us,''
Jarrett said. ``It's one more race down and they know they've got
one less to be able to catch up.''
</P>
<P>
   The duel between Gordon and Earnhardt began to shape up soon
after a caution with 33 laps remaining. For six laps in a row,
Gordon tried to pass Earnhardt high and low on the track and was
blocked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time you come up on Earnhardt, he's going to be the
toughest guy to pass, especially when he's leading a race,'' Gordon
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, I was the guy who had to try to get by him, and
it killed me.''
</P>
<P>
   Labonte was waiting patiently behind while the two Chevys raced.
With 17 laps to go, he engineered a stunning three-wide pass on
Earnhardt and Gordon. Labonte got drafting help from Stewart, his
teammate at Joe Gibbs Racing, to take the lead and he went
unchallenged the rest of the race.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hated that Bobby got us three-wide,'' Gordon said. ``That's
what I'm bummed out about. I knew if I could get by Earnhardt, it
would've been tough for anybody to get by me.''
</P>
<P>
   Earnhardt began having handling problems with his car, and
narrowly held off a late charge from Chad Little to finish fifth.
It was Earnhardt's best performance since a second-place showing
six races ago at Daytona.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dale is driving as good as ever,'' car-owner Richard Childress
said. ``I was getting cold chills out there.''
</P>
<P>
   PEPSI 400 TOP 5
</P>
<P>
   1. Bobby Labonte, Pontiac
</P>
<P>
   2. Jeff Gordon, Chevy
</P>
<P>
   3. Tony Stewart, Pontiac
</P>
<P>
   4. Dale Jarrett, Ford
</P>
<P>
   5. Dale Earnhardt, Chevy
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
