</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-GIANTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIANTS HOPE THEIR OFFENSE ISN'T PEAKING IN THE PRESEASON 
</HEADLINE>
 (ms) 
 By BILL PENNINGTON    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ No sacks of a Giants quarterback for the second
consecutive week.
</P>
<P>
   Net yardage: 494, more yards than any Giants team had gained in
14 years.
</P>
<P>
   With Kent Graham, the starting quarterback, throwing for 269
yards in the first half, the Giants' passing total was 393 yards,
the most in 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants have scored 63 points in two preseason games. They
did not come close to scoring 63 points last November. In five
games.
</P>
<P>
   It might be useful to keep repeating this: it's only the
preseason. But something is up with the Giants' offense.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants have already had seven pass plays of 30 yards or
longer. In 16 regular-season games last season, the Giants had 10.
</P>
<P>
   Their third-down efficiency in the opening preseason game at
Minnesota and Saturday night's 27-20 victory over Jacksonville is
50 percent. Last year it was 30 percent in the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   The starting offense has had one sequence of three downs and
out, but twice it has needed just three plays to score a touchdown.
When the starting unit is playing, Brad Maynard has punted once. So
far, Maynard might as well bring a book to read on the bench.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, it's only the preseason.
</P>
<P>
   But the Giants' average gain per play so far is 6.7 yards. Last
year in the regular season, it was 4.4 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Their average gain per pass attempted, a statistic widely
considered the most telling in pro football, is 11.1 yards. Last
season it was 5.1 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the Giants have lost eight fumbles and the 1998 team lost
nine all season. But then, it's only the preseason.
</P>
<P>
   So, who are these guys?
</P>
<P>
   ``Look, I'd feel more comfortable if we were putting up these
numbers in the regular season,'' Giants Coach Jim Fassel said
Sunday. The coach was nearly in retreat, trying as hard as he could
to pull the reins in on the galloping story of an offensive
metamorphosis.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've improved, but I'm still very guarded,'' Fassel said.
``Things change in the regular season. There's game planning, and
defenses react differently. I'm happy, but it's only a foundation
we have to build on.''
</P>
<P>
   Fassel, however, sees the obvious.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now,'' he said, ``we're functioning as a different
offense.''
</P>
<P>
   There are many places to start when explaining this
transformation, but the best place would probably be at the center
of it all.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Williams, the 11-year veteran who had to sit out the last
two seasons because of an eye injury, has forged a bond with the
other offensive linemen that has made them confident and
productive, especially when protecting Graham.
</P>
<P>
   This unit believes in Williams and the new offensive line coach,
Jim McNally, and it plays with a new poise and skill. Williams was
on the verge of a Pro Bowl season when he was injured, and his
presence alone, aside from his leadership qualities, improves the
team.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants scored their first touchdown Saturday night by
running behind Williams. A long pass play in the Giants' second
touchdown drive would not have happened if Williams had not
disengaged from his man to pick off a charging defender who was one
step from burying Graham in the pocket.
</P>
<P>
   Next up for praise is the receiving corps. The receivers are
working as a blend, with disparate but compatible abilities, and
they are aggressively going for the football. The former is a
product of three consecutive years together, the latter is a result
of Graham's willingness to attack the defense with the long pass.
</P>
<P>
   Like a fielder in baseball who never gets a ball hit toward him,
a receiver can grow lackadaisical running his deep routes if he
never sees the football. This was beginning to happen to the
Giants, but since Graham took over with six games to go in the 1998
season, he has stretched the field, telling his receivers in
essence: go deep, I'll find you.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know what the potential of this offense is,'' Graham said.
``There were things we had to unleash, so this doesn't surprise
me.''
</P>
<P>
   For those who might think the Giants' offensive success has come
against simplistic defenses still feeling their way in the
preseason, Graham said Saturday that Jacksonville was trying to
confuse the Giants.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were bringing a lot of stuff at us _ changing rushes,
rolling coverages,'' he said. ``They fooled me a few times early
on. We adjusted.''
</P>
<P>
   Those are a few of the ways the Giants' offense is better so far
this season. There are more ways not quite as advanced, others not
yet proved unsuitable.
</P>
<P>
   But it's only the preseason. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
