<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-22 20:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5801 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-TURKEY-LESSONS-605&AMP;AD     08-22 1059
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TURKEY-LESSONS-605&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TURKS FEAR THAT IN NEXT QUAKE THEY'RE ON THEIR OWN 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By CELESTINE BOHLEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ISTANBUL, Turkey _ Nilhan Sesahan lives in an apartment with a
stunning view of the Bosporus strait, one of many reasons she loves
her ancient, vibrant city and will never leave it.
</P>
<P>
   But after the earthquake that devastated regions east of here,
Ms. Sesahan is thinking of moving to higher ground _ away from the
water and onto firmer soil with less crowded surroundings.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be another earthquake,'' she said. `'I know this, I
have read it in the papers, on the Internet. The city won't do
anything to get ready, but I have started thinking about what I can
do.''
</P>
<P>
   Geologists and seismologists here and abroad predict that the
next earthquake to hit Turkey is likely to be even more deadly,
erupting further west along the volatile North Anatolian fault,
probably in the densely populated city of Istanbul or in the Sea of
Marmara, south of the Bosporus.
</P>
<P>
   ``The next shock will come maybe 30, 40, 50 years from now, but
it will hit in the city of Istanbul, or in the Marmara Sea because
this is the last part of the North Anatolian fault,'' said Turgut
Oztas, a geological engineer who heads a branch of the Turkish
Architects and Engineers Association. ``We are trying to warn
official people about this. Everybody must be ready for this
inescapable fact.''
</P>
<P>
   But in the wake of the overwhelming earthquake disaster on
Tuesday, many residents of this giant city with an estimated
population of 12 million are more doubtful than ever that their
government is capable of planning for such a catastrophe.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't trust the government to plan for this,'' said Ms.
Sesahan, a sculptor. ``Take what is happening today as a model. The
people are being very helpful and supportive of one another, but
the government can't get real help to the people.''
</P>
<P>
   As the scale of last week's disaster sinks in, many people
interviewed in downtown Istanbul expressed shame and disgust at
their government's handling of the crisis. They echoed the
widespread criticism in the Turkish press about the lack of
equipment and of trained personnel in a country that has suffered
repeated earthquakes over the last hundred years.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was not the first major earthquake in Turkey,'' said
Hilal Erkmen, who works in an advertising agency. ``We know we are
living on a fault line. We know from past earthquakes what is
needed. But it wasn't there.''
</P>
<P>
   Serder Balkaya, a student visiting Istanbul last week, said:
``The government is very inefficient. The foreigners came, and for
three days they have been bringing people out of the rubble while
the Turkish government did nothing but watch. That's the part that
hurts the most.''
</P>
<P>
   Alsoy Onder, a 29-year-old contractor whose brother was killed
by the quake in the city of Golchuk, said: ``We have no government.
They are a prop. They don't care about anything. They just work for
themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   The most cynical assessment came from a group of five university
students, who refused to give their names. ``Absolutely nothing
will change,'' said one 18-year-old youth. ``We have no faith in
government. We have all been raised seeing the corruption all
around us.''
</P>
<P>
   In many cities hit by the earthquake, people have turned their
wrath on builders who skimped on materials, using thin iron rods
and concrete mixed with too much sand in obvious violation of
building codes. Often, people say, those violations are overlooked
by corrupt local officials from across the spectrum of Turkey's
political parties in return for cash donations by the builders, and
the votes of the new inhabitants, who were grateful to find
housing.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In the resort town of Yalova, a ferry ride from Istanbul, dozens
of buildings that collapsed in the quake had been built by a
well-known developer, Veli Gocer. He left the country after his car
was burned and his house stoned by furious residents. Interviewed
from Germany by a Turkish newspaper, Gocer admitted that he had
mixed concrete with sand from local beaches and said he had not
known any better.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the state had stopped me, it wouldn't have come to this,''
he was quoted as saying. ``I am a victim of my own inexperience.''
</P>
<P>
   Only a few people interviewed were hopeful that this quake, the
worst in Turkey in this century, will compel officials to replan
the city, knock down shoddily constructed buildings and force
builders to abide by strict anti-earthquake requirements already on
the books.
</P>
<P>
   ``The next earthquake will be another disaster, because hundreds
of thousands of buildings in Istanbul are badly constructed,'' said
Ali Riza Yasa, a freelance writer. ``These should be torn down, but
how much of this can be done?''
</P>
<P>
   Taking advantage of the intense public concern in the days after
the quake, experts have been pressing ahead with a proposed plan of
action. It calls for strict enforcement of existing building codes,
scrutiny of the construction process by private insurance
companies, and site inspections by local authorities _ which are
now not mandatory.
</P>
<P>
   But Sezer Yilmaz, a 28-year-old soldier who was given special
leave after the quake struck his family's apartment _ but spared
their lives _ in the Istanbul district of Avcilar, doubts whether
local officials or the people themselves will draw lessons from the
disaster.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will end up in the same situation,'' he said. ``We are a
passive people. Maybe for one or two years, people will pay
attention, but after that, they will forget again.''
</P>
<P>
   Some people see hope in the spontaneous response from ordinary
Turks, who have flocked to the disaster sites, offering their
services and bringing food, medicine and bedding. In a country that
for decades discouraged the rise of voluntary civic associations,
this reaction is seen as a healthy sign of a growing citizen
awareness.
</P>
<P>
   ``You are going to see people have greater expectation from
their government after this,'' said Lincoln McCurdy, president of
the American Turkish Council, who has lived in Turkey for almost 20
years. ``I've already seen the change. Once this mess is over,
people are going to say they have had enough with all the
corruption.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
