<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-22 20:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5802 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-CAR-NASCAR-NOTES     08-22 0766
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-NOTES </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NASCAR NOTEBOOK
 &HT;    Front row finds frustration fast
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROOKLYN, Mich. _ Starting on the front row is usually a big
advantage for drivers. It was disaster for pole-sitter Ward Burton
and Mike Skinner at Sunday's Pepsi 400.
</P>
<P>
   Burton was the first driver out of the race after colliding into
the retaining wall on turn 3 during lap 52. Skinner, starting
second, at No. 2, broke a rear-end gear while leaving the pits
earlier in the race and had to pull off the track for repairs.
</P>
<P>
   The early departure of the No. 22 Pontiac was a devastating blow
for Burton, who had captured his first pole of the season. Burton's
problems started as soon as the race did, with Skinner taking away
the lead on the second lap.
</P>
<P>
   Burton had dropped down to sixth by lap 37 when he reported
problems with both steering and tire pressure. He was knocked out
of the race after apparently losing control of his car.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not really sure what happened,'' Burton said. ``I'm OK,
other than some bruises and a headache. I'm just disappointed we
didn't have a better day.''
</P>
<P>
   Said crew chief Tommy Baldwin, ``I thought we were going to have
a top-five day. Another dead last (43rd place) ... what are you
going to do?''
</P>
<P>
   Skinner returned to the track and finished eight laps behind in
36th place.
</P>
<P>
   Caution flags
</P>
<P>
   Tony Stewart and Jeff Burton were involved in the day's biggest
wreck while battling for fifth place late in the race. As Stewart
tried an inside pass on the main straightaway of lap 162, he
appeared to be blocked toward the infield area by Burton.
</P>
<P>
   When Burton moved higher on the track, Stewart passed and
clipped the front of the No. 99 Ford, sending it into the wall.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jeff does that every time he gets behind me, he doesn't like
me passing him,'' Stewart said moments after the race.
</P>
<P>
   But after both drivers were called into the NASCAR trailer to
discuss the incident and review the tape, Stewart accepted the
blame.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was my fault,'' Stewart said. ``I came up on the track too
quickly. I thought I had (Burton) cleared. It's a shame; (the
wreck) took down a good car that is racing for points.''
</P>
<P>
   Burton, who was unhurt in the wreck, finished 12 laps down at
37th. He dropped two places in the Winston Cup points standings to
sixth.
</P>
<P>
   Off track
</P>
<P>
   Mark Martin and Jeff Burton, who are second and sixth in the
points standings, signed contract extensions to compete with Rousch
Roush Racing through the 2005 season. ``I've spent the last 12
years with (owner Jack Rousch Roush), and he's always made it
possible for me to race with the best people in the best cars. I
can't think of anywhere else I'd rather be'' ... The winner of TV
Guide's ``Star Car Sweepstakes'' will have his or her picture
placed on the hood of Kevin Lepage's car for the NAPA 500 at
Atlanta Motor Speedway. ... Ricky Rudd denied rumors he has
discussed selling all or part of his racing team to A.J. Foyt, but
said he would not mind talking with the four-time winner of the
Indianapolis 500. Rudd also confirmed that the No. 28 car of Robert
Yates Racing would be his No. 1 choice if he gives up ownership to
concentrate on driving. ... Kevin Harwick, who is in the Craftsman
Truck Series, has been chosen the Busch Series driver next season
for Richard Childress Racing. ``When you grow up watching these
guys on television, there's going to be a little awe at first,''
said Harwick, 23. ``But then you have to have a reality check and
get on with it. Then it's time to start doing business.''
</P>
<P>
   Time of race: 2 hours, 46 minutes, 16 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Margin of victory: .865 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Average speed: 144.332 mph.
</P>
<P>
   Lead changes: 23 among 8 drivers.
</P>
<P>
   Caution laps: 6 for 26 laps
</P>
