<SLUG> BC-RAC-SARATOGA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FURLOUGH TRIUMPHS BY A NOSE 
</HEADLINE>
 (ms) 
 By JOSEPH DURSO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARATOGA SPRINGS, N.Y. _ Furlough, a 5-year-old daughter of Easy
Goer, staged a furious rush in the final yards Sunday to win the
Ballerina Handicap by a nose over Bourbon Belle.
</P>
<P>
   The race was so close that the next two horses, the favored
Catinca and Hurricane Bertie, finished in a dead heat for third,
another length and a half back.
</P>
<P>
   The four horses ran such a tight race down the homestretch of
the Saratoga Race Course that nobody was sure who had won,
including Shug McGaughey, who trains Furlough for Ogden Phipps.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was standing in the clubhouse,'' McGaughey said, ``I
thought she got beat a nose. When she got to the eighth pole, I
thought we had a good chance to win. But the other mare was still
running.''
</P>
<P>
   He meant Bourbon Belle, who set a torrid pace throughout, racing
the first quarter-mile in 22 seconds, the half-mile in 44 3/5
seconds and three-quarters of a mile in 1:09 2/5. Meanwhile,
Furlough was running last in the field of 10 until Mike Smith
nudged her into action on the far turn. Then she came roaring out
of the pack in the final furlong and clipped Bourbon Belle at the
wire.
</P>
<P>
   ``She comes from so far back, it was nice to get away good at
the start,'' Smith said. ``She settled down in the back of the
pack. Then she got on that long lope, and that's a good sign. When
she does that, she usually finishes strong. Once we got some
daylight, I asked her to run, and we got up there just in time.''
</P>
<P>
   Furlough had lost four races in a row since March and was the
7-1 fifth choice in the Ballerina. She completed the seven furlongs
in 1:23 and returned $16.40 for a $2 bet to win.
</P>
<P>
   The trainer John Kimmel said of his horse Catinca's race: ``You
can't go 15 wide and get left at the gate. Jerry Bailey said she
was standing fine in the gate but then got a little edgy. And when
she broke, she may have stumbled and gone to her knees.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
