<SLUG> BC-HURRICANE-EVACUATE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TENS OF THOUSANDS FLEE ADVANCING HURRICANE
</HEADLINE>
 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) By BARRY SHLACHTER 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CORPUS CHRISTI, Texas _ Beverly Jacoby didn't hesitate Sunday
when the mayor suggested that residents evacuate to higher ground
as Hurricane Bret menaced the Texas coast.
</P>
<P>
   ``The things we treasure go into the car,'' said Jacoby, who
moved to Corpus Christi in May from Weatherford in North Central
Texas. She and her husband frantically loaded their most precious
belongings, including family photos and a cherished ``misprinted
$20 bill.''
</P>
<P>
   As she spoke, workers were hammering plywood across the windows
of her ocean-front apartment in preparation for the Category 4
storm.
</P>
<P>
   The Jacobys were among tens of thousands of residents who piled
into vans, cars, pickups and chartered buses and rolled onto
Interstate 37 for the bumper-to-bumper evacuation to San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday was the 80th anniversary of Corpus Christi's deadliest
hurricane, which killed an estimated 300 to 1,000 people. Residents
were taking no chances this time.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Loyd Neal said many people had heeded the city's warning
to evacuate, particularly those in low-lying areas such as North
Padre Island.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor estimated that 30,000 people, about 10 percent of the
city's population, had moved inland in advance of the storm, but
Police Chief Pete Alvarez and others said the number may have been
significantly higher judging from the heavy traffic heading out of
town.
</P>
<P>
   ``Believe us,'' the mayor implored residents in a televised
message. ``This is serious.''
</P>
<P>
   Neal said he was satisfied with the response, as well as with
the city's preparedness.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have a lot of these, but we practice often,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   At 3 p.m., less than two hours before the storm made landfall
south of Corpus Christi, the mayor said people who hadn't evacuated
``should stay in the city but leave low areas.''
</P>
<P>
   Red Cross spokesman Peter Teahen said government and Red Cross
officials agreed not to wait until Monday to decide whether to open
shelters in Corpus Christi ``because it's a force 4 hurricane, and
it's too dangerous for people to stay in the area due to possible
flooding and structural damage.''
</P>
<P>
   Two of the four Red Cross shelters opened in San Antonio quickly
filled with coastal evacuees, and more buildings were likely to be
requisitioned, Teahen said.
</P>
<P>
   Teahen flew in from Cedar Rapids, Iowa, before the Corpus
Christi airport was closed to all but emergency flights at 1:20
p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Hospitals discharged patients who were able to leave Sunday and
were admitting only those requiring emergency treatment and women
in labor, said Laura Cole, spokeswoman for the Spohn Hospital
group. Staff and doctors were invited to bring family members with
them when they reported to work, she said.
</P>
<P>
   A major concern in Corpus Christi was that flooding would
contaminate the water supply, prompting the city to cut off service
to low-lying neighborhoods and North Padre Island at 9:30 a.m.,
said Juan Ortiz, the city's assistant director of emergency
management.
</P>
<P>
   Nueces County Sheriff Larry Oliverez said 325 inmates in a jail
annex that was not built to withstand 120 mph winds were evacuated
to safer quarters, as were boot camp and juvenile detention
residents.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
