<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-22 20:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5808 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-GULF-HURRICANE-ART-73     08-22 0814
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GULF-HURRICANE-ART-730(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS BRACES AS HURRICANE HITS LAND 
</HEADLINE>
  (Significant update to come by 11 p.m. ET.) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic and map
are being sent to NYT graphics clients. Non-subscribers may make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By JIM YARDLEY    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CORPUS CHRISTI, Texas _ With winds reaching 125 mph and a tidal
surge expected to reach 12 feet, Hurricane Bret rumbled ashore
early Sunday evening along the south Texas coast, hours after tens
of thousands of anxious residents evacuated inland along clogged
highways.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the day, the storm moved steadily, if somewhat
unpredictably, first steering directly at this heavily populated
coastal refinery city and then turning westward and hitting land in
rural and sparsely populated Kenedy County. The western edge of the
eye of the storm slowly touched land before 7 p.m. local time and
began pounding the county with heavy bands of rain and high winds.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, gale-force winds had begun buffeting the
long string of barrier islands that form the fragile outer wall for
much of the coastline.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems like we're being whipped,'' said Lt. Robert
Rodriguez, as he and several other police officers rode out the
storm in the evacuated resort town of South Padre Island north of
Brownsville, Texas. ``We're getting all the wind swirls, the
bands.''
</P>
<P>
   With the eye of the storm expected to reach land later Sunday
night, federal and state officials compared its potential ferocity
to Hurricane Andrew, which in 1992 caused more than $1 billion in
damage in Florida and Louisiana. Designated a Category 4 storm, or
extremely dangerous, Hurricane Bret was expected to dump 7 to 20
inches of rain and possibly unleash bands of tornadoes. Hours
before the landfall, Gov. George W. Bush asked federal officials to
declare seven coastal counties major disaster areas in order to
qualify for emergency aid.
</P>
<P>
   The storm, did begin to weaken as it reached land. James Lee
Witt, director of the Federal Emergency Management Agency, said in
a briefing at 7 p.m. New York time that the hurricane had steered
away from populous Corpus Christi but still presented a serious
threat to south Texas. He said the tidal surge and heavy rainfull
could cause severe flooding as the storm moved farther inland
beyond Kenedy County.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very concerned about the Rio Grande area and the
potential of flooding in that area,'' Witt said. ``It is a very
dangerous storm.''
</P>
<P>
   Bret is the first hurricane of the 1999 season and the first
major hurricane to threaten south Texas since Hurricane Allen
caused $55 million in damage in 1980. Last year, the area suffered
heavy flooding from two storms that drifted eastward from the
Pacific Ocean.
</P>
<P>
   With many coastal areas susceptible to flooding, federal, state
and local officials began imploring residents to evacuate toward
San Antonio on Saturday afternoon. City officials in Corpus Christi
declared a state of disaster and declared a general but voluntary
evacuation until late in the afternoon, when remaining residents
were advised to find refuge in the city.
</P>
<P>
   State prison officials evacuated 3,200 inmates to jails and
prisons further inland, while thousands of tourists vacationing in
the resort hotels of South Padre Island also fled the storm. The
U.S. Coast Guard closed the Corpus Christi ship channel, one of the
busiest ports in the nation, and answered several search and rescue
calls from boats struggling through the rough, surging waters of
the Gulf of Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Jo Schweikhard Moss, a spokeswoman for the Texas Division of
Emergency Management, expressed concern that residents might fail
to heed evacuation warnings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We literally have a generation of Texans, either native to the
area or who have moved into the area, who have never experienced a
storm threat of this kind,'' Ms. Moss said. She added, ``Texas, to
this point, has been very, very fortunate, and obviously, it looks
like that luck has run out.''
</P>
<P>
   But from the mouth of the Rio Grande as far as 287 miles up the
Texas coastline to Galveston, residents heeded warnings and left in
droves. Motorists lumbered beneath black morning skies along
Interstate 37 out of Corpus Christi, pouring north and west toward
San Antonio and Austin. Electronic road signs along I-37 directed
the traffic to shelters in San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   Others fled along country roads through Nueces County, where
flat yellow and green fields seemed eerily still as clouds
approached from the Gulf.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to get ugly,'' said Valerie Saenz, 25, as she
stopped at a convenience store in Corpus Christi for food en route
to San Antonio. ``I just packed up all my clothes.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Tony Sterling, 34, a Corpus Christi resident, left early Sunday
morning for San Antonio with his family. His wife, Susan, is
expecting their second child in nine days. ``She's nervous,''
Sterling said. He also said some of his neighbors had scoffed at
the evacuation order. ``I think they're crazy, plumb crazy,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 45 miles offshore, waves reached 26 feet high, the
weather service said, and the tidal surge could surpass 15 feet
when Bret fully hits the coast. The threat of severe flooding
prompted Corpus Christi officials to evacuate 15,000 from Padre
Island, near Corpus Christi, and the local police closed the
causeway connecting that barrier island to the mainland. ``We
expect heavy flooding in that area, and we don't want those people
trapped by rising water,'' said Chief Pete Alvarez of the Corpus
Christi police .
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Baughman, director of operations for FEMA, said Sunday
that rescue and response teams were clustered at a staging area at
Fort Sam Houston in San Antonio, awaiting the end of the storm.
Baughman said officials were gathering generators, bottled water,
ice, blankets and cots to distribute to storm victims. Witt said
that the American Red Cross had opened 14 shelters.
</P>
<P>
   The storm had initially tracked toward the northern coast of
Mexico, then shifted northward toward Brownsville before finally
taking aim at Corpus Christi. But late in the day, Bret shifted
course to the west, steering at rural Kenedy and Kleberg Counties,
raising hopes for less property damage and a diminished threat to
lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, we don't want anybody to get hit,'' said Juan
Ortiz, deputy emergency management director in Corpus Christi.
``But for us, it's a positive thing. It has been a very
unpredictable storm.''
</P>
<P>
   Sheriff Rafael Cuellar Jr. of Kenedy County said his county had
not issued an evacuation order and that the county's 1,000
residents were seeking refuge in three emergency shelters. He said
that the large number of oak trees in the county had slowed past
hurricanes. His wife, Anita, had refused to leave. ``She doesn't
want to leave the little dogs,'' Sheriff Cuellar, 60, said of their
two pets.
</P>
<P>
   In Kleberg County, home of the King Ranch, perhaps the most
famous ranch in Texas, Marcos Perez, the chief sheriff's deputy,
said officers were canvassing the county, making checks on people
who had chosen to stay. Officers planned to check back after the
storm to make certain that those who remained were safe. In
Kingsville, the county seat, city officials ordered the 25,000
residents to evacuate or seek emergency shelter. At the King Ranch
itself, the ranch hands huddled in a central location and prepared
for storm.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just boarding everything up,'' said Wade Roberts, of the
King Ranch security staff.
</P>
<P>
   Farther south, in Cameron County and Brownsville, County Judge
Gilberto Hinojosa said ``at least a couple of thousand people'' had
flocked to local shelters in a county of 360,000 people. On
Saturday, when weather officials had predicted that Brownsville
would take a direct hit, Hinojosa said county workers drove buses
to low-lying areas to evacuate residents, most of whom refused to
go.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got the impression there is a lot of complacency,'' he said.
``People didn't think it was going to hit.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Moss, the state emergency management official, noted that
this weekend marked the seventh anniversary of Hurricane Andrew.
The most violent recent storm to his Corpus Christi was Celia,
which lashed the coast on Aug. 3, 1970, killing 11 people, causing
tens of millions of dollars in damages and flooding much of the
city's downtown.
</P>
<P>
   Witt noted that two other storms are also forming that could
potentially threaten the East Coast of the United States. ``This
season has just really truly started.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-22-99 2037EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
