<SLUG> BC-HURRICANE-BUSH-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH DECLARES 7 COUNTIES DISASTER AREAS, SEEKS FEDERAL DECLARATION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JAY ROOT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Hours before Hurricane Bret slapped the South
Texas coast, Gov. George W. Bush declared seven counties disaster
areas and called on President Clinton to issue an ``expedited
presidential disaster declaration.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Disaster comes like a thief in the night sometimes,'' Bush
said. ``Our hopes are that this storm, as ferocious as it may seem,
will not affect human life.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush and the news media were given an update on the state's
preparedness at the emergency command center in Austin.
</P>
<P>
   At least 1,600 troops from the Texas National Guard were on
standby near San Antonio, and all available state troopers were
helping evacuate people and coordinate emergency activities,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, swift water response teams and search-and-rescue
personnel gathered at the Alamodome in San Antonio in anticipation
of the storm's landfall. Also on standby were 10 Blackhawk
helicopters.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities said some 15,000 people were likely to seek public
shelter, and thousands more were expected to evacuate to hotels or
to the homes of friends and family.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always best to be prepared for the worst and hope for the
best,'' Bush said. ``Now it's just a matter of waiting.'' Bush's
disaster declaration covers the seven counties from the southern
tip of Texas to just north of Corpus Christi.
</P>
<P>
   The governor, scheduled to take his presidential campaign back
on the road Wednesday, is tentatively set to tour south Texas on
Tuesday, an aide said. It is too early to tell if Bret will alter
Bush's campaign schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Besides bracing for strong winds, officials prepared for heavy
flooding, particularly along the Rio Grande and Nueces rivers. Ken
Graham, a meteorologist with the National Weather Service, said
Bret could dump in excess of 20 inches near Laredo.
</P>
<P>
   But he said the storm, which is ``very tight and compact,'' will
not likely bring rain much farther north than Austin.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
