A5813 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BBN-MADDUX-COX     08-22 0596
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-MADDUX-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Maddux has chipped bone
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ If Braves' fans thought this pennant race was
nerve-racking enough, they were sadly mistaken because now there's
Greg Maddux to worry about.
</P>
<P>
   The four-time Cy Young Award winner, who's won six starts in a
row to carry the Braves since the All-Star break, has a bone chip
in his right wrist, a splint on his arm and questions about his
future, both immediate and longer term.
</P>
<P>
   Maddux injured the wrist on his pitching hand diving for a foul
pop against the Padres during his start on Saturday. Maddux pitched
the rest of that inning and another in Saturday's 6-2 victory over
the Padres, his 16th of the season, but by the end of the game it
was bothering him significantly.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I wanted to pitch today, no chance,'' Maddux said Sunday.
``But I'm not going to worry about it until three or four days down
the road. We'll decide Wednesday, see what Bobby (Cox) wants to
do.''
</P>
<P>
   With an off day on Thursday, the Braves could come back with
Terry Mulholland on Friday on his normal four days' rest and go
back through the rotation. That would give Maddux nine days before
he would be up for his next start on Aug. 31 in Cincinnati. But he
could need longer.
</P>
<P>
   Given the significant season-ending injuries the Braves have had
to endure already _ what with the loss of Andres Galarraga
(lymphoma) and Kerry Ligtenberg (elbow) in the spring and Javy
Lopez (knee) and Odalis Perez (elbow) last month _ the Braves are
getting used to bracing themselves for the worst.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be a huge factor if he is out for the year,'' Cox
said. ``But we can cover it. If we had to we might be able to go
the rest of the year (with a four_man rotation). If not, we've
still got (Bruce) Chen.''
</P>
<P>
   Maddux has not missed a start since April of 1997 when he missed
one start with a strained hamstring. He's never been on the
disabled list in his 13-year career in the major leagues.
</P>
<P>
   The costly play came on an aggressive attempt by the Gold Glove
pitcher to snare a John Vander Wal popup on the track in front of
the visitors dugout at Turner Field. He got a piece of it, as did
Chipper Jones, before making a final and diving attempt to get it
and failing and he landed front-first on the ground, using his
right hand to brace his fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like sliding into a base and kind of jamming your
wrist,'' Maddux said. ``That's what I thought I did. It's kind of
like when you roll your ankle playing basketball. I knew I did
something. I'm like `I'm going to try to pitch' and you wake up
(the next day) and it's not good.''
</P>
<P>
   This is not the kind of injury that would require a cast or
immediate surgery, though Maddux might have to get the chip cleaned
out of his wrist in the offseason.
</P>
<P>
   Maddux's six wins since the All-Star break are one fewer than
the seven wins by the rest of the Braves starting rotation. After a
miserable May, Maddux has rebounded to have the same number of wins
as he did this point last season. Is he asking `Why now?'
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' Maddux said. ``This game has been real good to me. I'm
not going to question one thing that goes bad.''
</P>
<P>
   Said teammate Gerald Williams: ``I don't think we dwell on the
things we can't control. I know I don't. Certainly this game is not
based on playing 100 percent in terms of health. Sometimes you've
got to play hurt, sometimes you've got to play banged up and I'm
pretty sure Greg is going to pitch.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
