r s BC-BBN-DIDNOTE-LADN     08-22 0589
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DIDNOTE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARK GETS WIN BUT NOT BEFORE ALMOST OVERHEATING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ On a team which so often plays without fire and
urgency, it seems bizarre that a player can have so much trouble
because he's too emotional. That's what manager Davey Johnson said
about Chan Ho Park, and the right-hander concurred.
</P>
<P>
   Park won for the first time in more than a month Sunday, but it
wasn't without a harrowing inning in which Philadelphia nearly
rallied from a four-run deficit.
</P>
<P>
   ``He seems to sometimes try to do too much or overthrow,''
Johnson said. ``Good hitters come up and he tries to throw it 95
mph instead of hitting his spots and just throwing. Then he fights
himself.''
</P>
<P>
   The bout ensued in the fifth of the Dodgers' 9-7 win. Park
prevailed but only after a pair of two-out walks and three
consecutive RBI singles pulled the Phillies within 5-4. Park (7-10)
got out of the jam and finished allowing four runs on six hits with
six walks in six innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes I have to throw hard to make myself pitch
aggressively,'' Park said. ``Maybe I was too scared about the power
hitters to throw it down the middle because the last two days these
guys hit good, so how can I throw it down the middle? I have to
have more faith in my stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Only left, not right: For the remaining 38 games Todd Hundley
will hit exclusively left-handed. But before the Dodgers catcher
stops switch-hitting for good, manager Davey Johnson would like
Hundley to rethink the idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always hate to see a kid quit switch-hitting,'' Johnson
said. ``I would like him to start with that again (hitting
right-handed) and work on it during the winter and see how he feels
going into the spring. You can always reverse it then.''
</P>
<P>
   Hundley stopped switch-hitting a week ago and is 1 for 3 as a
lefty against left-handers. The one hit is a pinch-hit, three-run
double in Saturday's loss against Phillies lefty Scott Aldred. The
three RBI were one more than he had in 40 at-bats from the right
side this season.
</P>
<P>
   The reconstructive elbow surgery that knocked out Hundley for
most of 1998 and rendered him ineffective for the first two months
this season also cost him the opportunity to work on hitting from
his unnatural right side.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Hundley) kind of reminds me of HoJo (former Met Howard
Johnson),'' Davey Johnson said. ``A real pretty swing from the left
side, short and choppy from the right side.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Arnold down, Herges up: After the game, the Dodgers sent
right-hander Jamie Arnold to Triple-A Albuquerque and recalled
right-hander Matt Herges, who was sent down 10 days ago.
</P>
<P>
   Arnold was 2-3 with a 4.91 ERA, but his stay in the minors isn't
expected to last long.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll get Arnold a couple of starts and then bring him back,''
Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   The quick stint should have Arnold back when rosters expand
Sept. 1, and stretching out his arm will allow the Dodgers to start
him, if they choose, next month.
</P>
<P>
   __ In summation: Jose Vizcaino started at third in place of
Adrian Beltre, who sat out with a swollen ankle and is listed as
day-to-day. . . . A sign of what Johnson wants to accomplish with
lefty-hitting Todd Hollandsworth was on display. Despite lefty
Anthony Shumaker starting for the Phillies, Hollandsworth played
center field. He singled in his only at-bat against Shumaker, who
left after taking a Gary Sheffield line drive off his left hand in
the second inning.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-22-99 2042EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
