<HEADLINE>
IMF MAY SEEK WIDER INDONESIA INQUIRY 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SINGAPORE _ The International Monetary Fund is reported to have
asked Indonesia to add its central bank to an investigation of bank
deals linked to President B.J. Habibie's governing party.
</P>
<P>
   The request would presumably widen a bank scandal has threatened
to undermine the fund's $42.3-billion bailout of the Indonesian
economy.
</P>
<P>
   In an unsigned letter dated Aug. 17 that has been widely
circulated to news organizations, the IMF's first deputy managing
director, Stanley Fischer, asked Indonesia's coordinating minister
for the economy, finance and industry to include the central bank
in an audit of payments involving Bank Bali, Indonesia's
government-appointed bank restructuring agency and a company with
links to Habibie's political party, Golkar.
</P>
<P>
   The controversy revolves around a fee of 550 billion rupiah ($78
million) that Bank Bali paid a company controlled by the deputy
treasurer of the ruling party to recover loans from a bank that the
restructuring agency had taken over.
</P>
<P>
   Opposition politicians contend that the money went to Habibie's
campaign for election in November. A special committee of
Parliament is investigating the bank deals.
</P>
<P>
   An IMF spokesman declined to confirm the authenticity of the
letter or the request.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
