</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-TWINS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POSADA IS A SINGLE SHORT OF A CYCLE AS YANKS DOWN TWINS 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS _ Coping with his horrible performance in the first
half of this season, Yankees catcher Jorge Posada trained himself
to focus solely on the challenges directly before him _ the next
inning, the next at-bat. Don't think about the past, don't think
too far ahead.
</P>
<P>
   When Posada slammed a home run in his first at-bat Sunday and a
triple two innings later, however, he dreamed about the cycle _ a
single, double, triple and home run, baseball's version of a
straight flush _ as he stood on third base. Posada ended the day
just a single short of the cycle, but he and his teammates did
muster some badly needed offense while edging the Twins, 5-3.
</P>
<P>
   Orlando Hernandez pitched seven innings against an unusual
Minnesota lineup to become the Yankees' first 14-game winner this
season. The Yankees collected 13 hits, their most since Aug. 13;
they had reached double figures in hits just once since pounding
out 22 against the Twins nine days ago.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees were unusually subdued in their 6-1 loss to the
Twins and pitcher Eric Milton Saturday, some of them appearing
discouraged as they went through their at-bats in the later
innings, Shane Spencer and Scott Brosius in particular.
</P>
<P>
   Chili Davis mentioned to some of the others that maybe they
didn't really have a good game plan against Milton and that maybe
they weren't as prepared as they should have been. ``If we don't
start scoring some runs, Texas is going to whip our butts,'' said
one player, looking ahead to the series against the Rangers that
begins Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Everything seemed to be going badly for the Yankees at the
outset Sunday. Derek Jeter was thrown out at home plate in the
first inning, Minnesota's Joe Mays struck out four of the first
seven batters he faced, and the Yankees were grumbling about the
massive strike zone of Bill Miller, the plate umpire.
</P>
<P>
   Two outs into the second inning, however, Posada drove a slider
into the upper deck in right, 407 feet away, and paused a moment to
watch the flight of the ball before rounding the bases with his
first home run in 46 at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   The score was tied 1-1 and the Yankees had a runner at first
when Posada batted in the fourth. He laced a line drive to center,
where Jacque Jones charged the ball on the artificial surface, only
to have it skip over his head and roll away. Posada pulled into
third with a run-scoring triple and began thinking of the cycle.
``For me to get a triple,'' Posada said later, ``about six guys
have to fall down.''
</P>
<P>
   Cycles are less common than no-hitters, even more so for
catchers; Boston's Rich Gedman was the last catcher to hit for the
cycle, against Toronto on Sept. 18, 1985.
</P>
<P>
   In the sixth inning, Posada hit the ball down the left-field
line for a run-scoring double, and right away, he began to think
about how difficult it would be to maintain his concentration and
get the last hit. The Yankees led 5-1 after six innings.
</P>
<P>
   The Twins' lineup comprised players who batted left-handed
against Hernandez _ the first time Hernandez had ever seen that, he
said later. It was an attempt to exploit Hernandez's relative
weakness against lefties: Going into Sunday's game, right-handed
batters were hitting .196 against El Duque, left-handers .266.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez's best weapon for retiring right-handed batters _ his
sidearm slider _ is largely ineffective against left-handers, and
Sunday, Hernandez had to find some other method.
</P>
<P>
   So Hernandez threw a lot of curveballs with his first pitch, to
about a third of the batters he faced, and then mixed fastballs and
changeups and largely shut down the Twins, who had two hits in the
first six innings.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees still had a four-run lead with two outs in the
seventh when the Twins' Javier Valentin singled. Cristian Guzman
swung and missed for the third strike, but the ball bounced past
Posada and Guzman reached first to keep the inning alive.
</P>
<P>
   Then Jones doubled and two runs scored, marring Hernandez's
pitching line: three runs (two earned) on four hits and three walks
in seven innings.
</P>
<P>
   Before Posada's fourth at-bat, in the eighth, Luis Sojo
suggested that he bunt for the single, and Posada ``really
thought'' about that option. But he took a first-pitch fastball
right down the middle from Hector Carrasco _ ``He should've hacked
at that,'' Davis would say, wistfully _ before swinging weakly at a
pitch high and outside.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was definitely trying to get a single,'' said manager Joe
Torre.
</P>
<P>
   Posada took a called third strike, however, walking slowly away
from home plate while staring downward. Reporters informed him
after the game that the last and only Yankees catcher to hit for a
cycle was Buddy Rosar, in 1940.
</P>
<P>
   ``See, that just stinks,'' said Posada, rolling his head in
frustration.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
