A5826 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BBN-PENNANT-COX     08-22 0429
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-PENNANT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Pennant race elicits yawns
 &HT;    By Karen Rosen
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Since their last game against the Braves on May 2, the
Reds have been out of sight, out of mind, but not out of
contention.
</P>
<P>
   Yet as Cincinnati arrives for a three-game series starting
today, there was no Reds-baiting in the Braves clubhouse. Chipper
Jones would rather focus his pennant-race thoughts on the New York
Mets in the NL East _ who are sticking to the Braves like gum on
the bottoms of their shoes _ instead of this possible rival for the
wild-card slot.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could be big ... later on in the summer,'' the Braves third
baseman said, ``but right now we're just concentrating on winning
two out of three and staying within striking distance of the
Mets.''
</P>
<P>
   The Braves have a half-game lead in the NL East while Houston
leads Cincinnati by a half-game in the NL Central. Arizona is a
lock in the West.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no extra excitement,'' said Brian Jordan, who had the
winning hit in the ninth inning Sunday in a 3-2 win over the
Padres, the 23rd time this season the Braves have won in their
final at-bat. ``Every game is a big game now. We want to win, and
you got Houston and Cincinnati and the Mets and Atlanta right
there. Somebody's going to be a wild card team, somebody's going to
go home.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, there hasn't been excessive excitement at the ticket
windows, either. Through Thursday, the most recent figures
available, the Braves had sold 28,806 for Monday's game, 35,587 for
Tuesday and 28,469 for Wednesday. Compare that to the Houston
series Aug. 9-11, when the attendance figures were 40,072, 38,303
and 39,578, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Have Braves fans taken October play for granted?
</P>
<P>
   ``They're probably spoiled a little bit,'' acknowledged Roy
Young, a fan who makes the trip from Tallahassee, Fla., as often as
possible. ``They just expect them to win, but they're in a
dogfight. ... I think the players are starting to feel the pressure
a little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   However, oung made his comments with the score tied in the
eighth inning, before the Braves won their 23rd game on their final
at-bat.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to continue to win games in dramatic fashion,'' Jones
said. ``Hopefully we'll get some good pitching performances and
throw some offense on them and have a breather. I don't see that
happening, but surely we're going to have to keep our eye on the
scoreboard and stick to what's been successful the last little
while.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
