</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-KNOBLAUCH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KNOBLAUCH ONLY LAUGHS AT THE BOOS FROM HIS FORMER FANS
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS _ Chuck Knoblauch passed Yankees Manager Joe Torre
in the dugout the other day, and Torre loudly imitated the
Metrodome announcer calling the second baseman's name: ``Chuuuuck
Knaaaaablock.''
</P>
<P>
   And, with a bellowing voice, Torre added the fan reaction to
Knoblauch's name here: ``Booooooo.''
</P>
<P>
   Knoblauch laughed a bit, and nodding, he said, ``Yeah, they love
me here.''
</P>
<P>
   He played seven years with the Twins before forcing a trade that
brought him to the Yankees last year, and Knoblauch probably will
be booed here for the rest of his career. In 1998, he seemed
uncomfortable while playing as a target of the fans' wrath.
</P>
<P>
   But his teammates have noticed this year that Knoblauch has
grown comfortable with the situation and is even thriving on it. In
the three-game series this weekend, Knoblauch went 5 for 12 and
scored three runs, hearing boos in response.
</P>
<P>
   The role of the villain apparently appeals to Knoblauch. ``It's
all right with me,'' he said, shrugging. ``I always liked playing
in this park when I was here _ it's a pretty good place to hit.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott Brosius, booed by fans in Oakland since being traded to
the Yankees before last season, could relate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once you get used to it and know it's coming, you just kind of
make light of it,'' Brosius said. ``They're watching somebody in a
position they would want to be in _ playing on a winning team. It
kind of cracks me up when I hear it.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TORRE LOOKS TO OCTOBER
</P>
<P>
   Manager Joe Torre does not enjoy the interleague play with the
Mets during the regular season, but he would be thrilled by a
subway World Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope it happens because that means we're in it,'' Torre
said. ``That's the whole key to this thing. Sure, I'd pull my hair
out, but if that means we're in it, that's fine with me. I'm not
choosy on who we play.''
</P>
<P>
   Torre grew up a New York Giants fan and was accustomed to seeing
them or the Brooklyn Dodgers meeting the Yankees in the World
Series. A Yankees-Mets World Series, Torre thinks, would draw
greater attention than Subway Series of the past ``because
baseball's bigger. It's more than a sport now.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
