<HEADLINE>
IN FOR THE RIDE OF THEIR LIVES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   If Marion Jones is truly a Cadillac tearing up Seville, Spain _
we'll know more after today's long-jump final if she's two-for-two
in her personal gold rush at what's officially called the 7th IAAF
World Championships in Athletics _ husband C.J. Hunter has been one
world-class chauffeur.
</P>
<P>
   The gold-medal shot put champ let out the loudest of yelps after
his wife captured the 100 meters Sunday. That kind of support will
be key for Jones' success not only later this week in the 200
(Friday) and 4x100 relay (Sunday) but when the former Thousand Oaks
High goddess goes after five golds in Sydney next year, and he's on
the infield with her.
</P>
<P>
   And just imagine the heptathlete/decathlete potential in the kid
we'll see once these two decide to start a family. . . .
</P>
<P>
   __ off!While ESPN ``SportsCenter'' anchor Kenny Mayne continues
time off to enjoy the recent birth of a daughter _ pretty much a
miracle considering the history of prenatal family tragedy he and
his wife have endured _ he's been told that when he returns to work
it won't be as Dan Patrick's partner.
</P>
<P>
   Bristolite decision-makers have split up the post-Olbermann
``Big Show'' tag-team, clearing a path for the less-than-marquee
matchup of ``Boo-Ya'' Scott-Rich Eisen for the top-dog 11 p.m.
(EDT) slot.
</P>
<P>
   This, despite Eisen's middle-school-drama-class, ESPY-nominated
performance in a ``Blair Witch Project'' takeoff he starred in the
other day. . . .
</P>
<P>
   __ Just listen to the artist and song selection each Dodger has
requested to be played when he comes up to bat and it's no mystery
why this team has no chemistry. . . .
</P>
<P>
   __ Despite Sir Ruppert's deep pockets, it'll actually be tough
for the Dodgers to eat contracts this offseason. For one, Sheriff
Malone's pie hole will already be stuffed with crow. . . .
</P>
<P>
   __ Lance Armstrong, the new All-American boy, deserves every
buck of seven-figure endorsement money that Madison Avenue throws
his way, 'cause you know it'll all end up going toward cancer
research anyway. For the next three weeks, with the help of the Web
sites ActiveUSA.com and SportingAuction.com, he's auctioning off
the yellow jersey he wore during the Tour de France. Bidding has
already topped $5,000. Again, the proceeds go to his foundation. .
. .
</P>
<P>
   __ Over at the less-than-foo-foo Islands restaurant in
Calabasas, a writer was kickin' it with Keyshawn ``Just Give Me The
Damn Menu'' Johnson, who over a burger and fries was talking up his
new high falootin' eatery in Beverly Hills called Reign.
</P>
<P>
   An Islands waiter interrupted the former USC and current Jets
receiver to ask for an autograph, which KJ gave up but not without
a warning: ``You know you're not supposed to do that, right? You
know you can get fired for this?''
</P>
<P>
   Only if someone finds out by reading the current issue of Sport
magazine. . . .
</P>
<P>
   __ From Comedy Central's ``Daily Show with John Stewart'' comes
this flash: ``Yugoslavia and Croatia met on the soccer field for
the first time in nine years, and in keeping with the region's
proud tradition, no meaningful goals of any kind were scored.'' . .
.
</P>
<P>
   __ Dallas 'Boys owner Jerry Jones tells the Houston Chronicle he
wants to help Al Davis return to L.A., ``not so much for Al but for
the league. We don't need two teams (in the Bay Area) and I think
the answer to Los Angeles is that maybe it suits moving a team
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Better yet, you can just move your training camp back to
Thousand Oaks. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
