<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Better luck vs. Hitchcock
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Braves might take extra satisfaction from their
three-game sweep of the Padres this weekend because Sterling
Hitchcock didn't get the best of them.
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock was pitching at Turner Field Sunday for the first time
since beating the Braves in the clinching game of last year's NL
Championship Series _ his second win of the series.
</P>
<P>
   He also pitched eight shutout innings against them in a Padres
win May 9 in San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   This time, the Braves reached him for two runs in six innings,
although he struck out eight.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an improvement,'' said Braves hitting coach Don Baylor.
``He's dominated us.''Jordan check
</P>
<P>
   Brian Jordan will visit a hand specialist today to see if
anything more can be done for his ailing right hand that was hit by
a Mike Thurman pitch on June 22.
</P>
<P>
   One solution may be another cortisone shot, but Jordan would
prefer not to because it would mean missing at least three to five
days with no guarantees of any loss of pain. He's had two shots in
the hand already and neither was effective.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll Rogers writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
