<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-22 21:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5836 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BBN-REDS-BRAVES-COX     08-22 0552
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-REDS-BRAVES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    REDS-BRAVES SCENE SETTER
 &HT;    Reds return to Atlanta
 &HT;    By Hal McCoy
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The last time the Cincinnati Reds dropped their
equipment bags in Atlanta, the Braves filled them up with losses
and there were heads hanging lower than Tom Dooley's.
</P>
<P>
   3-0, 5-1, 5-3. . .all Atlanta victories, thanks for coming, and
watch traffic on I-85 on your way to the airport.
</P>
<P>
   It was late April. The Reds were 9-11 when they hit Atlanta,
9-14 when they left. Against John Smoltz, Kevin Millwood and Odalis
Perez the Reds hit .109 over three games (10-92) and batted .100
with runners in scoring position, of which there were few.
</P>
<P>
   Reds' left fielder Greg Vaughn sensed it was a defining point
early in the season. With a flameout of that magnitude, it would be
easy to quit and say, ``We aren't even close to being
competitive.''
</P>
<P>
   So Vaughn locked the clubhouse doors after the third defeat and
delivered a message to an all-ears team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Forget it, it's all right, we'll get them tomorrow, keep your
heads up,'' Vaughn told them. It was not a chew-out session, it was
a positive re-enforcement message. ``Our intensity wasn't there and
I thought that needed to be brought up . . . and it was. I didn't
have the feeling they thought they could win every game we play.
And that's the only way to play this game.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe coincidence, maybe not. Since that day, the Reds are 64-35
as they gas up The Big Road Machine for a return three-game
engagement in Atlanta, beginning tonight.
</P>
<P>
   ``We aren't the same club they saw the last time,'' manager Jack
McKeon said. ``They beat Steve Avery, Pete Harnisch and Denny
Neagle. This time they're getting Brett Tomko, a better Pete
Harnisch (8-0 in his last 12 starts) and a much better Denny
Neagle.''
</P>
<P>
   General manager Jim Bowden nearly puts the three games on the
same shelf with Armageddon when he said, ``This is our chance to
show we can play with
</P>
<P>
   those guys. They are the only team we haven't been able to play
with this year. It is the most important series of the season.''
</P>
<P>
   Third baseman Aaron Boone talks often with his brother Bret
Boone, Atlanta's second baseman, and Aaron senses Atlanta
arrogance.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is happy for me and happy for our success, but I can tell
from his voice inflections that he thinks we are lucky or something
and we're not for real,'' Aaron said.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn didn't face Smoltz in Game One the last Braves series,
but was 0 for 6 with two walks and two runs (half the runs the Reds
scored in the three games) in the last two games.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if Atlanta will see a different Cincinnati team this week,
Vaughn said, ``I hope they just see who we are. We don't have to
prove anything to Atlanta. When you put on this uniform, you don't
have to prove anything to the other team.
</P>
<P>
   ``You prove things to yourself _ can I stay in focus and can I
keep from cheating myself. That's all you can control. If you don't
do your best, you're not cheating the Atlanta Braves, you're
cheating yourself and the Cincinnati Reds,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Come Wednesday, after Game Three of the series, Vaughn doesn't
expect to lock any clubhouse doors to deliver any inspirational
messages.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
