<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-22 21:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5837 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-RUN-WORLDCHAMPIONSHIP     08-22 0692
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUN-WORLDCHAMPIONSHIPS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRAN BLINEBURY  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
SEVILLE, Spain _ Space is starting to get tight in the trophy case
at Marion Jones' house.
<TEXT>
<P>
   One night after husband C.J. Hunter took a surprising gold medal
in the shot put, Jones took the first step in what is hoped to be a
glittering haul of her own by winning the women's 100 meters at the
World Track and Field Championships on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Jones was never threatened in the race, and her winning time of
10.70 seconds was the fastest in the world this year as she easily
beat out American teammate Inger Miller and Ekaterini Thanou of
Greece.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coming off an emotional victory with C.J. last night and
coming in to get this win tonight, well, I'm extremely excited,''
Jones said. ``The goal for this whole week is to get five gold
medals for the family, and we started off in a wonderful fashion.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the expected beginning to Jones' busy week as she will
also go for gold in the 200, the long jump and either the 4x100 or
4x400 relay.
</P>
<P>
   The long-jump finals are next up tonight.
</P>
<P>
   ``But first things first,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   And that was taking care of business in an event Jones has
dominated for the past two years.
</P>
<P>
   Miller may have lost whatever upset chance she had by
false-starting in the finals. Jones got away clean and fast and had
a lock on the race by the 30-meter mark.
</P>
<P>
   Still, with all of the advance hype surrounding her bid for four
golds here and five next summer in the 2000 Olympics in Sydney,
there was pressure to start off right.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, when Jones crossed the finish line, she pumped a fist into
the air, lifted both arms over her head and looked up into the
stands to find Hunter, who was cheering from a spot in the press
section.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's right! That's right!'' Hunter shouted as his wife sped
through the last few meters and then took a joyous victory lap
around the stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I crossed the line and saw C.J., that was a very moving
moment for me,'' Jones said. ``This is not exactly the same feeling
as two years ago in Athens. That was my first gold medal at the
World Championships, and that made it special. This is a different
kind of satisfaction, knowing that I expected to win here and then
I did it.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the only real threat to Jones at all through the four
rounds of the 100 was Jones herself. She made a false start in
Saturday's second round and then another in Sunday's semifinals,
forcing her to sit back in the blocks in fear of disqualification.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last night and again tonight in the semifinals, I seemed to
have trouble hearing the gun,'' Jones said. ``I don't know if it
was crowd noise or what, but that's why I was having trouble with
my starts.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I nailed my start in the finals. That, perhaps, is the
reason I was able to pull off the victory. I knew that Inger was
running extremely fast, and I knew that the woman from Greece was
running extremely fast, so I knew I had to be very ready and on my
toes. I think I executed well today. Before I stepped into the
blocks, what was going through my mind was that I had to execute my
race.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones' 10.70 easily beat the World Championships record of 10.76
that she had set in the second round. In fact, until Miller's
personal best of 10.79 in the finals, Jones was the only woman in
the world to run under 10.81 this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The funny thing is that I was not as relaxed as I could have
been tonight,'' she said. ``But I still ran 10.70. So I'll take
it.''
</P>
<P>
   She'll also take her and Hunter's role as the first family of
track and field.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a completely different kind of feeling between my win
and C.J.'s win last night,'' Jones said. ``That meant so much,
because it was me getting to see my husband accomplish something
that means so much.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been the witness firsthand to all of the days when C.J.
would come home from training hard. This is what I've heard about
him doing every single day since he won the bronze medal in '97. To
see him do it was such an incredible thrill.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, this was a start.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
