<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-22 21:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5840 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBN-METS-CARDS-ART-NY     08-22 1024
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-CARDS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCGWIRE HITS 2 AND KNOCKS A LIGHT OUT; METS GAIN SPLIT
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Two photos are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036. 
(ms) 
 By JUDY BATTISTA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Mets' grasp on first place was loosening during
their first game Sunday, with starter Octavio Dotel displaying none
of the poise of someone who nearly had a no-hitter in his last
start, with the Mets' hitters going up and down like express
elevators, and with Mark McGwire hitting his 49th and 50th home
runs and literally knocking the a light out in Shea Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   But the Mets abandoned their quiet Sunday drive and slammed on
the accelerator in the eighth inning, riding a Mike Piazza's
bases-empty home run and a grand slam by John Olerud to rally from
a 6-1 deficit. Stalling, they fell behind in the top of the ninth
and then _ sending the Shea Stadium crowd into late-September-like
hysteria _ scored two in the ninth inning to beat the Cardinals,
8-7. The victory kept the Mets in a first-place tie _ for a few
hours _ with the Atlanta Braves, who beat the San Diego Padres,
3-2.
</P>
<P>
   By the time the long doubleheader was over, though, the Mets
(76-49) had fallen a half-game behind the Braves, entering a
three-game series against the Houston Astros, losing the second
game, 7-5.
</P>
<P>
   In the second game, the Mets scored just two runs off Cardinals
starter Garrett Stephenson over seven innings. Orel Hershiser, who
took the loss, allowed just three runs on six hits in seven
innings, and the Mets managed to stay close. But their bullpen
uncharacteristically blew up in the eighth when Billy Taylor and
Chuck McElroy came on and allowed four runs, including a three-run
double by Adam Kennedy that sailed over Matt Franco's head in left
field to give the Cardinals a 7-2 lead. Franco, who hit into a
bases-loaded double play to end the sixth-inning, took the blame
for the loss.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets almost had another comeback when they scored three runs
in the ninth, led by Piazza's two-out pinch-hit two-run single that
gave him a Mets record, having driven in runs in each of his last
10 games. Still, the Mets were a bit deflated after missing a
chance to sweep the the series following such a spectacular finish
to the first game.
</P>
<P>
   ''You remember back to the good game but having a loss in the
second game, it takes some of the punch out of the win,'' Olerud
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets' reaction to Edgardo Alfonzo's single to left that
drove in Franco for the winning run in the first game illustrated
how breathtaking that game was and how gripping the pennant race
is. Alfonzo had barely touched first base when he was engulfed by a
stream of giddy teammates who sprang from the dugout when his
grounder went through the gap, their bodies bobbing up and down
like buoys, practicing, it seemed, for celebrations they hope to
stage in the final six weeks of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ''If you can come back from five, why can't you come back from
one?'' Manager Bobby Valentine said, explaining his thoughts going
into the bottom of the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   Then Valentine exhaled hard like a man exiting a roller coaster.
``Wow,'' he said. ``That was a good game. No, lousy game. Good
ending.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the game, Valentine expressed admiration for the grit of
the rookie Dotel, but by the third pitch of the game _ which
leadoff hitter Joe McEwing launched into the left-field bullpen _
it was clear Dotel had none of the nasty stuff that no-hit the
Padres for six innings.
</P>
<P>
   After striking out J.D. Drew, Dotel yielded, on a 91 mph
fastball, another epic home run for McGwire. That shot, measured at
502 feet, shattered a light bulb in the 16 for Cardinal outfielder
Ray Lankford's number about 60 feet high on the scoreboard in
right-center field.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals were up 3-0 by the end of the first and even
though Dotel labored with 25 pitches in the first inning, he stayed
in for five innings. He gave up another run in the third and was
got no help from the offense.
</P>
<P>
   Cardinals starter Darren Oliver faced just three batters more
than the minimum through seven innings and gave up just one run, in
the fourth, when Rickey Henderson led off the inning with a single,
stole second and scored on a single by Olerud. When McGwire smacked
a less-than-mammoth shot off Jeff Tam, just clearing the fence in
left center, to extend the Cardinals' lead to 5-1, the Mets seemed
better off waiting for Game 2.
</P>
<P>
   But Rey Ordonez led off the eighth with a double down the
left-field line. Luis Lopez grounded out and Henderson drew a walk.
Cardinals Manager Tony LaRussa yanked Oliver for Rick Croushore. He
walked Alfonzo to bring Olerud to the plate. Olerud was hitting
.305 entering the game, and he has drawn 100 walks hitting in front
of Piazza while hitting just 14 home runs. But on a 1-2 changeup,
Olerud's smooth stroke sent the Mets' fifth grand slam of the
season down the right-field line. The crowd, which had reserved its
greatest cheers until then for McGwire, erupted and the Mets
trailed by 6-5.
</P>
<P>
   With the roar not yet quieted, Piazza smashed a 1-0 pitch to
dead center to tie the score at 6-6.
</P>
<P>
   But the Cardinals recovered as Mets reliever Armando Benitez,
who ultimately got the victory, allowed a run in the top of the
ninth. Fernando Tatis hit a grounder that seemed destined for a
double play, but Alfonzo's throw to Olerud was high, pulling him
off the base and allowing Drew to score to give the Cardinals a 7-6
edge.
</P>
<P>
   Alfonzo saved himself plenty of grief in the bottom of the
inning. With one out, Ordonez and Franco each drew walks from
pitcher Ricky Bottalico. Henderson, who drove in the go-ahead run
Saturday, singled to right field to score Ordonez and tie the at
7-7. The 40-year-old Henderson got on base all five times he came
to the plate Saturday. Sunday, he was merely 3 for 4 with two runs
scored and he allowed Alfonzo redemption with his dramatic
game-winning roller into left field.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think,'' Valentine said, ``it's better than vintage Rickey,
and vintage Rickey was Hall-of-Fame material.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
