<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    New welcome mat appreciated by UGA's first-year students
 &HT;    By Rebecca McCarthy
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Athens _ As the alma mater thundered through Stegeman Coliseum,
University of Georgia freshman Chad Oliver and his friends from the
third floor of Hill Hall seemed to swell with pride as they sang
the unfamiliar tune, which marked the end of Opening Convocation.
</P>
<P>
   ``President Adams and Governor Miller, they made you feel like
you're not a Social Security number, you're one of them,'' said
Oliver, 18, who's from St. Marys. His friends, Chad Merck and
Torian White, nodded. ``This isn't just a bunch of faculty and
students, this is the family. I want to be part of this.''
</P>
<P>
   The three young men, along with their resident assistant, Arun
Krishnamoorthy, were among the 4,000 or so people _ mostly
freshmen, their families and faculty _ who attended the first-ever
ceremony, which was designed to introduce and welcome incoming
students to the university.
</P>
<P>
   The idea for the event came from student Gretchen D'Huyvetter,
who sat on the speaker's podium with President Michael Adams,
Athens Mayor Doc Eldridge, Student Government President Tricia Page
and Staff Council President Sarah Fraker, among others. They
praised the students for their accomplishments; told them to enjoy
their years at UGA; to become involved in campus life; and to
volunteer in the community.
</P>
<P>
   Also on the podium was former Gov. Zell Miller, a UGA alumnus
and the featured speaker. He holds the Philip H. Alston Jr. Chair
in the Institute of Higher Education at UGA.
</P>
<P>
   ``Knowledge is more of a process than a destination,'' said
Miller, who told the students to recognize the difference between
information and knowledge.
</P>
<P>
   He said the treasures they could gain at the university included
intellectual curiosity, tolerance and perseverance.
</P>
<P>
   ``As you set out on this great adventure here at the University
of Georgia, I encourage you to take full advantage of the
opportunities to learn and grow and mature, and gather into your
life the real, lasting treasures that higher education offers,''
said Miller. ``You are on your way into a future I believe is full
of more promise than ever before.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
