A5846 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BBN-REDLEGS-COX     08-22 0703
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-REDLEGS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    After slow start, it all falls in place for Reds
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It couldn't have gotten much worse than the first
weekend in May. The Cincinnati Reds, new and improved and built to
last, were instead a flop, a loose collection of talents that had
been oversold in spring's annual rush to judgment.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves swept the Reds that first May weekend, allowing them
10 hits in 27 innings, outscoring them 13-4, while Cincinnati
settled deeper into last place, 5 1/2 games back just 23 dates into
the schedule. Reds manager Jack McKeon didn't understand.
</P>
<P>
   Not that he understands now, though the questions have changed.
Instead of trying to make sense of the first weeks, he's trying to
understand the last ones. McKeon freely admits he doesn't know how
the game's new postseason set-up works, now that in the year's
biggest turnabout, his club finds itself in the middle of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as we get in, who (cares) where it is,'' McKeon said.
``We'll play 'em any place. We're going to be tough anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Believe him. The Reds open tonight's three-game series at Turner
Field a team transformed, half a game behind Houston in the NL
Central, the best road team in baseball (38-17) and a possible
Braves postseason opponent. Since mid-May, the Reds are 59-31
(.656). Since the All-Star break, they have lost just one of 11
series, and have won the past nine _ the longest streak in the
majors this year.
</P>
<P>
   And they keep improving.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we get the starting pitching,'' general manager Jim Bowden
said, ``this team can go as far as it wants.''
</P>
<P>
   There is no single explanation. Ron Villone, a journeyman
reliever, becomes a soild starter. Ex-Brave Denny Neagle cools a
sore shoulder for two months before returning in August with some
of his career's best work, bolstering the rotation.
</P>
<P>
   A bunch of kids, foremost rookie Scott Williamson, become the
game's best bullpen. Left fielder Greg Vaughn stalks another
40-homer year. Shortstop Barry Larkin finally resembles himself.
Pokey Resse proves he can play second base. First baseman Sean
Casey, the league's No. 4 hitter, becomes a fullblown star.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a combination of things,'' said Braves second baseman
Bret Boone, who spent his previous five seasons in Cincinnati.
``(Right-hander Pete) Harnisch continued to do what he did last
year. The bullpen with the Williamson kid has made a big
differerence, though they already had a lot of talent there.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lark is healthy and playing like he can play. Pokey stepped in
(for Boone) and did a great job, which they didn't know would
happen. I think the presence of Vaughn. even though he's hitting
around .220 or so, he has his 29 home runs. The emergence of Casey.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not just one thing.''
</P>
<P>
   In retrospect, the slow start was only that, magnified by early
pitching problems of Neagle, Jason Bere and Bret Tomko. Neagle has
a 3.64 ERA since rejoining the rotation July 30. Bere has been
since released and Tomko, demoted and recalled once, may lose his
job again when Steve Parris (7-1) comes off the DL this week.
</P>
<P>
   The late trade for Juan Guzman has fortified the rotation, which
is 15-6 in the second half and 10-3 in August. This in turn will
reduce bullpen exposure, which will only help down the stretch.
Between Danny Graves, Scott Sullivan and Williamson, whose 1.69 ERA
is lowest among NL relievers, all three will log 100 innings this
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to have the right kind of arms to do it and our guys
do,'' McKeon said. ``Other than Williamson, who never pitched out
of the bullpen before, they are all accustomed to it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Braves provide an acid test. Cincinnati has not won a series
in Atlanta in over four years. But these Reds are not about four
years ago or even last May. They are about the playoffs and October
and with the league's third best record (73-49), they are as
legitimate an entry to NL knows.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key is to get in,'' McKeon said. ``Because then, anything
can happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Stinson writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
