<SLUG> BC-BBO-SIDEWAKS-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THEY TOOK A PICTURE AND IT DID LAST LONGER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   On page 33, there's Christy Mathewson limbering up in a New York
Giants uniform. You'd swear it was Tom Seaver.
</P>
<P>
   On pages 72 and 73, Brooklyn Dodgers pitcher Jack Coombs sits in
the shadows of the Ebbets Field clubhouse in 1916, wondering if his
career will ever return to the 31-win season he had with the
Philadelphia Athletics five years earlier.
</P>
<P>
   On pages 176-177, it's a carefree Pee Wee Reese on the dugout
steps with teammates Spider Jorgensen, Eddie Stanky and rookie
Jackie Robinson on April 15, 1947, moments before Robinson would
forever change the game.
</P>
<P>
   Thankfully, these images have not only been committed to film
but revived in the oversized book ``Classic Baseball Photographs:
1869-1947'' compiled by baseball historian Donald Honig ($20,
Smithmark Publishers, 182 pages). It was originally published five
years ago under the title ``Shadows of Summer,'' but a gem like
this will never be out of style as long as baseball fans long for
what the game looked like _ and, even in this case, felt like _
more than 100 years ago. Because these are pictures you feel.
</P>
<P>
   Everything old these days is called ``classic,'' but the word
should be saved for treasures such as this. The original
black-and-white photos are all given a sepia tone, which helps give
the effect of what Robert Creamer calls in the forward ``an
archeological dig.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, many photographers in the early part of the
century worked anonymously, selling their work to newspapers or
wire services. One of the most famous, Charles Conlon, whose photos
were often published in The Sporting News, has seen books and even
a set of baseball cards issued of his collection. And his are
included in this. But Honig and his staff's attempt to identify the
other artists whose work graces the pages of this book produced
only seven names to go with some 160-plus pictures.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it's a poetic conclusion to their search. Because for as
many photos as there are of the stars of that time period _ some
classics permanently etched in fans' minds, such as a DiMaggio
swing or a Cobb slide _ there are the anonymous ballplayers like
Dummy Taylor, Rough Carrigan, Red Dooin, Patsy Dougherty and Stuffy
McInnis, who would otherwise be just names in a history book if not
for someone deciding their portrait was worth the trouble to take.
</P>
<P>
   In light of Reese's recent passing and DiMaggio's death earlier
this year, this book becomes more valuable each year. And for 20
bucks, the price is right.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-22-99 2125EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990822.0176 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-22 21:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5848 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBN-CURRY-COLUMN-NYT     08-22 0894
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-CURRY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON BASEBALL: METS CHASE THE PRIZE THAT MCGWIRE CANNOT REACH 
</HEADLINE>
 (ms) 
 By JACK CURRY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Shawon Dunston was oblivious to history. After Mark
McGwire's 50th homer soared over the center-field fence Sunday at
Shea Stadium, it bounced off a fan's glove and back onto the
warning track. The ball was historic because no other player had
ever smashed 50 home runs in four consecutive seasons. Dunston, who
thought McGwire's scoreboard-bulb-breaking homer six innings
earlier had been the 50th, scooped up a sliver of history and
flipped it into the bleachers.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire received a polite standing ovation for hitting Jeff
Tam's fastball 401 feet and achieving something that not even Babe
Ruth had ever accomplished. There was nothing raucous about the
treatment. It was the way astute fans should respond to an opposing
player and the way Mets manager Bobby Valentine would have
choreographed the scene. Nice, but not too noisy.
</P>
<P>
   The real noise came later. The Mets neatly upstaged McGwire's
antics and shoved the home run race aside in favor of the pennant
race by rallying from a five-run deficit to win dramatically the
first game of the doubleheader against St. Louis, 7-6. The drama
returned in the second game before the Cardinals doused a
ninth-inning rally and won, 7-5.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it was an exciting day at Shea, with about half of the
50,139 fans in their seats when the six hours of baseball finally
concluded.
</P>
<P>
   They will remember McGwire's two homers, but they will also
remember how the Mets scored twice in the ninth to win the opener
and then behaved like 17-year-olds who had won a high school
championship. There were bearhugs and high-fives as McGwire
strolled off the field.
</P>
<P>
   At that moment, the Mets made the home run king a footnote.
</P>
<P>
   Really, this is the way it should be. Even McGwire has admitted
this on a daily basis.
</P>
<P>
   The Home Run Race, Part 2, is not nearly as important as Pennant
Race, Part 200. McGwire and Sammy Sosa gave baseball fans
unforgettable thrills last season, and even though they are
frequently going deep again, the only way they will attend the
postseason is if Commissioner Bud Selig invites them.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no competition in this,'' McGwire said. ``There's no
prize at the end of the season. The only prize at the end of the
season, and I've said this time and time again, is that World
Series trophy.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mets are stylishly earning their chance for that trophy.
</P>
<P>
   Watch them rebound from a five-run deficit in the eighth on John
Olerud's grand slam and Mike Piazza's McGwire-like shot.
</P>
<P>
   Watch them obliterate a one-run deficit in the ninth on Rickey
Henderson's run-scoring double and Edgardo Alfonzo's game-winning
single. The splurge enabled the Mets to overcome a sluggish start
by Octavio Dotel and make McGwire envious.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anybody who puts the uniform on wants to win; they want to go
to the playoffs and the World Series,'' McGwire said. ``Who
doesn't?''
</P>
<P>
   Alfonzo considered McGwire's words and McGwire's statistics on a
shabby team and said; ``You can put up many, many numbers and
that's good for yourself. But everybody wants to win. That's what
this game is about.''
</P>
<P>
   An hour before the game, Dotel was slumped on a black couch
watching videotape of McGwire.
</P>
<P>
   After one of McGwire's homers, Dotel hastily rewound the tape,
studied the at-bat and noticed the fastball was on the inside
corner. Inside? Outside? With McGwire and fastballs, it usually
does not matter.
</P>
<P>
   Dotel had already permitted Joe McEwing's leadoff homer when he
fired a 91-mile-an-hour fastball off the outside corner and McGwire
rolled his wrists and sent the ball zooming toward right-center.
</P>
<P>
   The baseball kept climbing until it resembled a golf ball and
crashed more than halfway up the scoreboard, destroying a bulb in
the numeral 6 in the 16 for Ray Lankford's uniform. The estimated
distance of McGwire's impersonation of Roy Hobbs was 502 feet. Six
hundred two would have been closer.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was pretty good,'' said McGwire, who criticized the
seemingly short estimate. ``That did amaze me.''
</P>
<P>
   One year and three days ago, McGwire slugged his 50th,
coincidentally, off a Mets right-hander (Willie Blair) in the
seventh inning of the first game of a doubleheader. After his moon
shot in the first off Dotel, McGwire hit one off the right-handed
Tam in the seventh. Dunston saw the ball pop out of a fan's glove,
so he retrieved it and tossed it to another man holding his son.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought that was 51,'' said Dunston, who was acquired from
St. Louis last month. ``It was history. I felt so bad. I told Mark
I was sorry.'' McGwire said: ``If the father and the young kid have
it, so be it. Let them cherish it.''
</P>
<P>
   As he did last year, McGwire left New York wondering if he could
break a record. But this time, the record of 70 homers is his own,
so he said: ``I'm chasing myself. How can you get excited about
that?''
</P>
<P>
   As they did last year, the Mets, who have nine important games
with Houston and Arizona in 10 days starting Monday night, are
wondering if they can qualify for the post-season. But this season
should be different. This time, the Mets are a better bet and a
better story than McGwire.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're going to be tough to beat,'' McGwire said. ``They've
got it rolling.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
