<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-22 21:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5852 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBN-KELVINMOORE-COX     08-22 0583
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-KELVINMOORE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Kelvin Moore's spirits are up despite broken neck
 &HT;    By Dave Lance
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PONTIAC, Mich. - Kelvin Moore laid in his hospital bed on Sunday
still unable to move most of his body, but at least the Cincinnati
Bengals safety
</P>
<P>
   was trying to be funny.
</P>
<P>
   And because of his effort, family and friends are beginning to
brighten up, just a couple of days after fearing the worst for
Moore, who broke his neck Friday night during the Bengals'
preseason game with the Detroit Lions at the Silverdome.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's back to cracking his silly jokes,'' said Travis Moore,
Kelvin's brother. ``He'll say something like, 'Oh, my head hurts,'
but his spirits are up and that's what counts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes me smile that he still has his sense of humor.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it's because he knows he's lucky he wasn't paralyzed while
trying to tackle Detroit wide receiver Brian Stablein during the
third quarter. Moore broke the first vertebrae of his spine and
laid motionless on the AstroTurf for more than 15 minutes before
being taken to Pontiac Osteopathic Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   He has remained at the hospital, where he was in intensive care
and listed in stable condition Sunday. Travis Moore said his
brother has some movement
</P>
<P>
   in his hands, but is still under medication and has been fitted
for a halo brace on his head.
</P>
<P>
   Sometime this week, he is scheduled to leave the hospital and
fly home to Los Angeles to receive treatment from a neck
specialist. He won't need surgery and a full recovery is expected,
his brother said.
</P>
<P>
   Kelvin Moore, a 6-foot, 203-pounder out of Morgan State, began
last season on the Bengals practice squad and was added to the
regular roster later in the year. He played special teams and
backed up safety Myron Bell.
</P>
<P>
   During the past few days, Moore has been visited by Bengals
owner Mike Brown, coach Bruce Coslet and several teammates,
including Bell. Travis Moore, a receiver for the Calgary Stampede
in the Canadian Football League, flew in from Canada on Saturday
after being granted a leave of action from his coach, arriving the
same day as his mother, step-sister and brother's girlfriend.
</P>
<P>
   Travis Moore, acting as the family spokesman, asked that no
other family members be interviewed. He said his family has
remained composed during this
</P>
<P>
   ordeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a strong, solid mom,'' Moore said. ``She's our rock.
The whole family in general is handling it well. You can't show a
whole lot of emotion at a time like this.''
</P>
<P>
   The same applies to agents, in this case Angelo Wright, who
visited his 24-year-old client Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``You look at the type of injury ... he's young and strong.
Frankly, I think he'll be OK,'' Wright said.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Bengals trainer Paul Sparling said Moore's career was
over, but Wright and family members believe the second-year pro
might play again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Prior to the trauma subsiding, you can't make that statement
(that Moore's career is over),'' Wright said. ``Football-wise, the
first thing to do is to get him healthy. He's in a lot of pain, but
there was no damage to his spinal column. Once he's OK, then we'll
deal with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was really coming on and he was going to be a factor this
year, but this is the ugly side of this business. Of course, he's
disappointed. The tragedy and irony of this is he works hard
everyday and he has a clean body and mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
