<HEADER>
A5853 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-HURRICANE-SIDER-HNS &LR;      08-22 0737
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HURRICANE-SIDER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COASTAL CITY ESCAPES WITH LITTLE DAMAGE AS HURRICANE TURNS AWAY
FROM HEAVILY POPULATED AREAS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)
<TEXT>
<P>
   By EDWARD HEGSTROM &QL;
</P>
<P>
   c. 1999
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Houston Chronicle &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CORPUS CHRISTI, Texas _ Residents of this coastal city were
breathing easier Sunday night as it appeared they would escape the
brunt of Hurricane Bret.
</P>
<P>
   After bearing down on the Corpus Christi area for more than 24
hours, the storm veered west and came ashore over sparsely
populated ranch land about 70 miles south of the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, we're relieved,'' said David Garcia, the Corpus
Christi city manager. ``We have some damage, but it's not nearly as
bad as it would have been from a direct hit.''
</P>
<P>
   Garcia said the city's evacuation advisory would remain in
effect until the full extent of the storm's impact could be
assessed.
</P>
<P>
   Judi Oestreich, director of the American Red Cross office in
Corpus Christi, said Bret came ashore at the place it could do the
least damage.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were hoping it would go that way because it's the
least-populated area in the region.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure the cows are happy, but we are,'' she added.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, panicked residents jammed freeways as they
tried to heed official advisories to evacuate the city.
</P>
<P>
   Others, deciding to ride out the storm, emptied store shelves of
emergency supplies. Some were caught off-guard by the rapidly
developing storm while a few said they needed to stay behind to
protect property.
</P>
<P>
   ``Texas is a not a mandatory evacuation state, which means we
can't force people to leave,'' said Oestreich.
</P>
<P>
   Bret was originally projected to hit farther south, in Mexico.
But Saturday night, about 24 hours before Bret's predicted
landfall, officials upgraded it to a major Category 4 hurricane and
said that the storm could hit near here.
</P>
<P>
   Evacuation orders were not issued for Padre Island until
Saturday night. The evacuation advisory for the Corpus Christi went
out Sunday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Because Corpus Christi is entirely low-lying and vulnerable to
flooding, the nearest shelter was placed in San Antonio, two hours
away. Some residents who decided to stay behind said they simply
didn't have time to plan for such a trek. Many gasoline stations
were shut down Sunday. Those that remained open soon ran out of
gas.
</P>
<P>
   Jose Zavala and his wife had reserved a hotel room in San
Antonio. But when he got to the front of the line at a station on
his way out of town, he found there was no gas left. ``Oh well,''
he said. ``I think we have enough to make it.''
</P>
<P>
   Most grocery stores were closed and those that remained open
were overwhelmed with customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been here since 2 a.m.,'' said Mark Moreno, a worker at
an HEB market who was still furiously stocking crate after crate of
eggs about noon Sunday. ``We still have everything but bread and
water,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The traffic was another problem. Talk radio programs were
overwhelmed with calls from drivers on cellular phones, calling
with updates on the bumper-to-bumper traffic on roads leading out
of town.
</P>
<P>
   All the reports of problems leaving town proved discouraging for
some. ``It's too late to do anything,'' shrugged Kevin Patton.
``Traffic is already backed up on 37,'' the highway to San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   But Patton was not taking the storm lightly. He spent Sunday
afternoon helping a friend with six children move to slightly
higher ground from an apartment complex along the shore, known as
SeasideVillas. He said he hoped they would be safe in his home,
which was already boarded up and is a few miles inland.
</P>
<P>
   When they were not talking about the traffic, radio talk-show
hosts were railing about the antics of surfers enjoying the waves
while so many others were scrambling to survive.
</P>
<P>
   And then there was David Haynie, a 39-year-old real estate
executive, who just wanted the thrill of being near a big storm.
</P>
<P>
   Haynie spent the afternoon windsurfing off the beach near
downtown Corpus Christi.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the best it gets,'' said Haynie as he wrestled his
sail ashore, the wind already reaching a howl and the rain stinging
as it hit his face. ``My house is already boarded up, so I figured
I would have some fun.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he planned to ride out the storm in his home, just a
couple of blocks from shore. ``I'm not worried,'' he said. ``I was
swimming before I was walking.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
