<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-22 21:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5863 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-BANK-LAUNDER-9     08-22 0968
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-BANK-LAUNDER-950(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIAN MONEY-LAUNDERING IS FOCUS OF INQUIRY 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By TIMOTHY L. O'BRIEN with RAYMOND BONNER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Seven years ago, Natasha Gurfinkel, a young executive
at the Bank of New York, joined an elite contingent of American
bankers sent to Russia and made an important advance in her career.
</P>
<P>
   Her mission was to help the new Russia create a Western-style
banking system, and her self-assured, savvy touch impressed top
bankers and regulators on the trip. Only a few months after her
return, she was promoted to head the bank's division for Eastern
Europe.
</P>
<P>
   At 37, she was taking on a big assignment for a woman at a
buttoned-down New York bank.
</P>
<P>
   She seemed perfect for the job. Fluent in her native Russian,
and able to move seamlessly from Wall Street to Moscow, she built a
lucrative business for the bank. New Russian companies needed
access to American money and American banks and Ms. Gurfinkel
became known as banker who could get things done.
</P>
<P>
   In New York she was a prominent member of a generation of young
Russian emigres who, armed with Western education, were rising
through the ranks of companies angling for business in Russia and
Eastern Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Whether it was at a dinner speech with a Russian leader or a
black-tie Russian ball, Ms. Gurfinkel was an important presence,
especially after she married Konstatin Kagalovsky, a one-time
reformer in the Kremlin who had become a wealthy Russian
businessman.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone knew her,'' said the former chairman of a major
Western bank that does extensive business in Russia. ``Number one,
because of her husband.''
</P>
<P>
   But last week, Ms. Kagalovsky was suspended by the Bank of New
York. She is a central figure in what federal investigators suspect
could be the biggest money-laundering scheme in history.
Investigators say billions of dollars may have been channeled
through accounts at the Bank of New York by Russian organized crime
as well as by embezzlement from Russian companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a serious thing,'' said Ms. Kagalovsky during a brief
telephone conversation at the weekend. ``They've told me not to say
anything. I'm just sorry about the whole thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Kagalovsky is not the only bank executive involved in the
investigation. Lyudmila Edwards, known as Lucy, has been suspended
as well. Ms. Edwards, 41, and also Russian born, was a vice
president in the bank's London office working for Ms. Kagalovsky.
</P>
<P>
   The scope of their role in any money laundering is unclear. The
suspension from their jobs does not mean they are guilty. Wall
Street companies have a long history of singling out ``rogue
employees'' who once raked in big profits as the masterminds of
financial scandals. It is a strategy often embraced by companies
anxious to insulate themselves from lawsuits and other trouble that
can follow embarrassing disclosures.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, government investigators raided Bank of New York
offices in New York and London, seizing documents from the offices
of Ms. Kagalovsky and Ms. Edwards.
</P>
<P>
   The British police also searched the apartment of Ms. Edwards
and her husband, Peter Berlin, who had control over one of the
accounts that authorities are examining _ an account through which
$4.2 billion in laundered funds is believed to have passed.
</P>
<P>
   The Bank of New York said last week that it has been cooperating
with the federal investigation of the matter, which involves the
use of the bank to transfer funds from Russia to other countries.
The bank said there are no allegations of wrongdoing against it and
has repeatedly declined to comment further.
</P>
<P>
   Nor have the women been accused of any wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   The class of ``new Russians'' that Ms. Kagalovsky and her
husband belonged to emerged in Moscow in the early 1990s as Russia
threw open its markets to foreign investment.
</P>
<P>
   These younger Russians, many of them with high-paying jobs that
their parents never dreamed of, were in the vanguard of Russia's
embrace of capitalism. They could be picked out by the ubiquitous
cell phones, luxury automobiles, private security guards and pricey
restaurants they favored.
</P>
<P>
   Western bankers said Ms. Kagalovsky was a well-known member of
that world when she visited Moscow, often adorned in expensive fur
coats. Her husband, a former Russian government official, was a
senior executive at Menatep, a now insolvent Russian bank. He is
now the vice chairman of Yukos, a major Russian oil company.
</P>
<P>
   All of this was a long way from Ms. Kagalovsky's modest
beginnings. Born in Leningrad, now St. Petersburg, in 1954, she
attended what was then Leningrad State University and earned the
equivalent of bachelor's and master's degrees in Oriental studies.
</P>
<P>
   In 1979 she emigrated to the United States and eventually
enrolled at Princeton University, earning a master's degree in Near
Eastern studies. In 1986, she joined Irving Bank Corp., which Bank
of New York acquired in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   At the bank she worked for Vladimir ``Mickey'' Galitzine, a
Russian emigre with a royal pedigree who headed its Eastern
European business. Both reported to Alan R. Griffith, head of
international banking, and Ms. Kagalovsky quickly won Griffith's
favor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Natasha was more pushy, whereas Mickey was more of a
gentleman,'' said a former Bank of New York employee familiar with
Ms. Kagalovsky's rise at the bank.
</P>
<P>
   People who know Galitzine said family problems in the early
1990s distracted him from his work and he began ceding more
authority to Ms. Kagalovsky.
</P>
<P>
   By 1992 she successfully leapfrogged Galitzine and won control
of the Eastern European division, although the two executives are
said to have remained friends. Galitzine declined to comment on any
aspect of the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Like Ms. Kagalovsky, Ms. Edwards was born in Leningrad and
worked at Irving Bank, ending up as an assistant to Ms. Kagalovsky
and Galitzine.
</P>
<P>
   She was born Lyudmila Pritzker in 1958, and might have spent her
entire life in Russia had she not met a young American in the
merchant marine in 1977. Although she was only 19, she married him
that year at the U.S. consulate in Leningrad, a relative said.
</P>
<P>
   The couple moved to the United States and lived in Illinois
briefly before moving further west. She became an American citizen
in 1981, but her marriage was troubled. She and her husband were
divorced in 1987, and Ms. Edwards moved to the East Coast,
eventually landing a job in banking.
</P>
<P>
   At the Bank of New York, Ms. Edwards worked hard enough to win
the London assignment, and she impressed competitors.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was very outgoing, a spunky woman, who really wanted to
take care of her clients,'' said a rival banker who competed for
business in Russia. ``She was very professional. People liked
her.''
</P>
<P>
   A few years ago, Ms. Edwards married Berlin, a Russian who
acquired U.S. citizenship through his marriage to her. And Berlin's
own business pursuits appear to be one focus of the federal
money-laundering investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Berlin, 44, operated Benex, a company he appears to have run in
part from his home in Queens with a telephone and a personal
computer, an investigator added. For a period, Berlin also ran a
travel agency in New Jersey, also under the name of Benex, said a
Brooklyn investment manager who occasionally used his services.
</P>
<P>
   It was accounts related to Benex that sparked the massive
money-laundering investigation. The first federal subpoenas
produced 3,500 pages of documents related to Benex, investigators
said.
</P>
<P>
   Among the services Benex provided was getting visas to the
United States for associates of Semyon Yukovich Mogilevich, a
suspected Russian organized-crime leader, said an American
official.
</P>
<P>
   Mogilevich, Ms. Edwards and her husband could not be reached for
comment. In the past, Mogilevich has denied any ties to organized
crime.
</P>
<P>
   Federal investigators also are trying to determine whether some
of the money channeled through the Bank of New York came from
Menatep, where Ms. Kagalovsky's husband once worked. Western
investors and Russian regulatory authorities suspect Menatep and
related companies of having looted money from Russia, allegations
that the companies have denied.
</P>
<P>
   Kagalovsky could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Ms. Kagalovsky said she has retained Stanley
Arkin, a New York criminal defense lawyer noted for his involvement
in high-profile financial fraud cases. Arkin declined to comment on
the case.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Ms. Kagalovsky may wish she had examined some of her
clients more closely, although doing business with Russian
companies is never easy. As Ms. Kagalovsky said in a 1993
interview, Russian companies are not known for disclosing much.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to understand business needs and try to assess
whether they will survive the coming years, often without the
benefit of annual reports or any written material,'' she told the
newspaper The American Banker.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
