<SLUG> BC-BBL-PLAYOFF-PREVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPOTLIGHT IS ON COMETS AS POSTSEASON BEGINS 
</HEADLINE>
 (ms) 
 By LENA WILLIAMS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   This season, things were supposed to be different in the Women's
National Basketball Association.
</P>
<P>
   The arrival of several elite professional players from the
defunct American Basketball League, the peace of mind that comes
with job security and the expanded playoff format were expected to
bring parity to the league and add last-minute drama to the
post-season.
</P>
<P>
   But the more things changed, the more they remained the same.
</P>
<P>
   With the playoffs set to begin Tuesday night, Houston and the
Liberty, teams with the same core group of players with which they
started when the league began play three seasons ago, are atop the
Eastern and Western Conferences.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, the league's twice defending champions, the Comets,
are the team to beat.
</P>
<P>
   Led by Cynthia Cooper, the WNBA's only most valuable player, and
the All-Star Sheryl Swoopes, the Comets (25-6) have the best record
in the league, home-court advantage throughout the playoffs and a
first-round bye.
</P>
<P>
   If the chance to win a third straight title isn't enough
motivation to get Houston's high-scoring triumvirate of Cooper,
Swoopes and Tina Thompson going, the death last week of their
teammate Kim Perrot, the Comets' point guard and inspirational
floor leader, is bound to be added incentive. Perrot, 32, died
after a nine-month battle with lung cancer.
</P>
<P>
   In the East, the Liberty rebounded from missing the playoffs
last season when it failed to win the conference title, which comes
with a first-round bye and home-court advantage in the second
round.
</P>
<P>
   The Charlotte Sting, which finished third in the East, had been
considered the team most likely to win the conference. The Sting's
lineup is younger, taller and, some thought, stronger than the
Liberty's, which is the oldest of the league's 12 teams.
</P>
<P>
   Without Rebecca Lobo, the 6-foot-4-inch center-forward, whose
season ended 42 seconds after it began last June when she tore the
anterior cruciate ligament in her left knee, the Liberty was given
little chance of making a run at the championship.
</P>
<P>
   But the Liberty (18-14), playing behind Kym Hampton, 36, Sue
Wicks, 32, and Teresa Weatherspoon, 34, stood its ground in the low
post, with help from the 6-2 rookie Tamika Whitmore and Crystal
Robinson, a 3-point sharpshooter from the ABL.
</P>
<P>
   ``I deeply believed in this core group, which is evident in the
fact that I haven't made many changes in that core during the first
three years,'' said Carol Blazejowski, the Liberty's general
manager, referring to Hampton, Wicks and Weatherspoon. ``Because we
understood that our roster was more veteran than some other teams'
and a little bit older, we added youth and size.''
</P>
<P>
   The playoff format was expanded this year from four to six
teams, adding a one-game elimination round for the second- and
third-place teams in each conference. The new format insures that
each conference will have a representative in the championship
game.
</P>
<P>
   Having clinched the Western Conference title two weeks ago,
Houston won five of its last six games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they are so focused right now, if I were a betting
woman, and I'm not, I wouldn't bet against Houston, although there
are competitors,'' Detroit Coach Nancy Lieberman-Cline said Sunday
during a coaches' conference call. The Shock will play host to
Charlotte in an elimination game tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   Houston awaits the winner of Tuesday's elimination game between
the Los Angeles Sparks and the Sacramento Monarchs. The Sparks
(20-12) have the league's second-best record, followed by the
Monarchs (19-12). In head-to-head matchups this year, the Sparks
and Monarchs are 2-2, both winning one game on the opponent's
court. It is the first playoff appearance for both teams.
</P>
<P>
   The Monarchs will be without the 6-3 forward-center Yolanda
Griffith, their leading scorer and rebounder, who averaged 18.8
points (second in the league) and 11.3 rebounds (first). Griffith
sustained a partial tear of the medial meniscus in her right knee
two weeks ago against Charlotte.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our depth is really weakened,'' Monarchs coach Sonny Allen
said. ``We didn't have a lot of depth to start with. Our success
against Los Angeles depends on us hitting free throws and not
turning the ball over.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sparks lead the league in scoring, averaging 76.5 points a
game, and in assists, with 18.1 per game. Factor in 6-5 Lisa
Leslie, their explosive center and the most valuable player in this
year's All-Star Game, along with a playoff-starved home crowd, and
the Sparks have the edge on paper.
</P>
<P>
   But coach Orlando Woolridge was not overconfident Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm scared to death,'' he said. ``In a one-game elimination,
you can't afford to have a bad night.''
</P>
<P>
   The Liberty will face either the Sting or the Shock. Charlotte
and Detroit both finished the regular season at 15-17.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
