<HEADLINE>
FED TO DECIDE IF INTEREST-RATE BOOST IS NEEDED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   All eyes will be on the Federal Reserve this week as its
{Federal Open Market Committee} convenes Tuesday to decide whether
another interest-rate boost is needed to preempt inflation. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The smart money in the financial community has been betting on a
quarter of a percentage point rise in the federal funds rate, which
is what banks charge one another for overnight loans. Since a
further tightening of monetary policy has been widely anticipated
on Wall Street, a modest rate boost has already been discounted by
the financial markets. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Therefore, if the Fed does the expected, it probably will be a
positive rather than a negative development for investors. A boost
of more than a quarter of a point, however, might result in a
market setback. &QL; 
Wednesday &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Many analysts expect July's {existing home sales} report to show
that rising mortgage rates have finally taken their toll on the
housing resale market. The consensus of leading economists surveyed
by Thomson Global Markets expects an annual rate of 5.3 million. If
the call is on target, it would be a drop after June recorded a
10.6 percent jump from May's resale pace. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   - {Orders for durable goods} in July are forecast to have
reflected continued strength for manufacturing. Most economists
expect an increase of 1 percent, which would be a strong rebound
from June's relatively weak gain. An increase for the series, which
tracks demand for big-ticket items with a useful life of three
years or longer, would mark the 11th rise in 14 months. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   - The Treasury has scheduled an {auction of two-year notes.} &QL; 
Thursday &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Most analysts don't expect any significant change in the Gross
Domestic Product numbers when the preliminary update for second
quarter is released. Last month's initial estimate for the
April-June period was an annual growth rate of 2.3 percent. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Friday &QL;
</P>
<P>
   July's rise in {personal income} is forecast to have matched
June's increase, but {personal consumption} is expected to have
declined from the previous month. Economic analysts at Merrill
Lynch call for income to have risen a respectable 0.4 percent. On
the spending side, however, most analysts expect a rise of 0.3
percent, which would be half of June's gain. Any sustained decline
in spending would affect Gross Domestic Product figures for the
third quarter, because personal consumption fuels two-thirds of
economic growth. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-22-99 2203EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990822.0193 </DOCNO>
