<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HURRICANE-TEXAS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HURRICANE SMACKS TEXAS COAST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD CHACON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROWNSVILLE, Texas _ The first major Atlantic hurricane of the
season tumbled onto the South Texas coast Sunday afternoon,
bringing howling winds and stinging rains to a 220-mile area
stretching from the Mexican border to the resort peninsula of Padre
Island, and sending thousands of people fleeing inland for safety.
</P>
<P>
   Hurricane Bret made landfall after churning through the Gulf of
Mexico last week. By the time it hit the coast, Bret packed
sustained winds exceeding 125 miles an hour and poured several
inches of rain throughout the Rio Grande Valley.
</P>
<P>
   There were no reported deaths or serious injuries attributed to
the storm as of early last night, but emergency officials in
several Texas and Mexican cities said Bret's winds damaged scores
of buildings and downed trees and power lines.
</P>
<P>
   In low-lying areas along the coast, where many residents were
evacuated on Saturday, 15-foot-high waves slapped against piers and
ripped boats from their moorings. In Brownsville and Harlingen,
homes and businesses were shuttered and windows were taped.
</P>
<P>
   Compared with Hurricane Andrew, a similarly compact storm that
swept across densely populated sections of southern Florida,
meteorologists and workers said Bret's eye moved through rural
areas between Brownsville and Corpus Christi, which helped to
minimize the number of victims and the amount of damage. Officials
also said that early warnings and evacuations helped save lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been preparing for this since Thursday, when we expected
the storm to come this way,'' said Brownsville city manager Carlos
Rubinstein as he stood at a command center in the city's police
headquarters, where officials monitored the storm and its damage.
``We haven't been hit like this in a while, so there was the risk
that people would get complacent about preparations and warnings.
But so far, things seem to be under control.''
</P>
<P>
   Bret marked the first time the Texas coast had been hit by a
hurricane since Hurricane Jerry killed three people in October
1989. The last direct hit in on this area was Hurricane Allen in
1980.
</P>
<P>
   The eye of the storm, which was classified as a powerful
Category 4 hurricane, passed near Port Mansfield betweeen
Brownsville and Corpus Christi about 5:10 p.m. local time and was
expected to continue moving farther north and west into Texas. The
strongest storms are classified as Category 5. By about 7 p.m., the
winds had died down slightly and the storm was downgraded to a
still-powerful Category 3.
</P>
<P>
   The National Weather Service posted a hurricane warning from La
Pesca, Mexico, to Port O'Connor, Texas, south of Houston. The
strong winds and warm temperatures also prompted officials to issue
tornado warnings for inland areas. Mandatory evacuation orders were
issued for Padre and Mustang Islands as well as for Port Mansfield.
</P>
<P>
   Bret forced a mass exodus of residents and tourists throughout
the region. On Saturday, thousands fled South Padre Island, a
popular vacation resort, for the mainland. By late Sunday
afternoon, officials closed access to the area and said the
normally bustling island was a virtual ghost town. Many families
also packed cars and drove about 160 miles north to San Antonio,
where shelters were set up to help victims.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to reporters in Austin, Governor George W. Bush said,
``I hope my fellow Texans say a prayer for those fellow Texans that
are in harm's way.''
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of others chose to take refuge in local schools and
community centers.
</P>
<P>
   At the Homer Hanna High School in Brownsville, where officials
operated the largest shelter, 900 people, most of them poor
families with children and grandparents, huddled on blankets and
around small television sets in the school's hallways.
</P>
<P>
   Sharon Moore, the principal, supervised the shelter. ``Tomorrow
is supposed to be the first day of school,'' said Moore. ``But
these people have homes that are not secure enough to handle the
winds and floods. This is the safest place for them to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Federico Trevino Zapata, 69, sat up against a set of yellow
lockers next to his wife, daughter, and mother-in-law. From his
blanket, he could see his two adult sons and their families about
25 feet away.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not very comfortable here, but it's safer than our house,
which sits on blocks,'' said Trevino.
</P>
<P>
   Across the border, in the northern Mexican town of Matamoros
early Sunday morning, residents continued their last-minute
shopping for essentials. But by afternoon, when the storm's path
became clearer, Mexican officials said the threat to their coast
had lessened.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-22-99 2204EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990822.0194 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-22 22:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5879 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-CHINA-DETENTIONS-BOS &LR;      08-22 1144
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-DETENTIONS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RESEARCHER HELD BY CHINESE TELLS OF ORDEAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By INDIRA A.R. LAKSHMANAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONG KONG _ Harrowing nights of nonstop interrogation,
intimidation, and sleep deprivation by Chinese secret police
probably drove a Massachusetts man to jump from a third-story
window, according to his Australian travel companion, who returned
home Sunday, a week after the two were detained in northwest China.
</P>
<P>
   Gabriel Lafitte, 50, a scholar associated with the University of
Melbourne, said he and Daja Meston, 29, a researcher and former
Buddhist monk, were seized by 20 public security officers who
stormed their rooms early on Aug. 15 in the small town of
Xiangride, the site of an antipoverty project that was recently
approved for funding by the World Bank.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities separated the men, interrogated them, seized their
notes and film, and transferred them in a 28-hour journey across
mountain passes to the provincial capital of Xining, hundreds of
miles away.
</P>
<P>
   Chinese officials say Meston leaped from a window last
Wednesday, trying to escape detention. US officials who have
visited Meston in a Xining hospital say he is gravely injured, but
stable, with a broken back and internal organ damage. An American
doctor examined Meston for the third day Sunday, and said his
condition had not worsened, sources said. A decision has not been
made to evacuate him to another hospital, and officials note that
he is still under Chinese detention.
</P>
<P>
   Meston's wife, Phuntsok, a Tibetan exile, was granted a visa
Saturday and plans to fly to China as soon as possible to be with
her husband. ``My only wish now is to be with my husband, and to
bring him back home safely as soon as possible,'' she said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Lafitte was deported Saturday and put on a plane home, banned
from China for five years.
</P>
<P>
   Lafitte said he was able to see Meston only when their caravan
of vehicles stopped, and ``even then I could see he was petrified,
absolutely terrified, and just couldn't get a handle on the
situation. I found it difficult, but manageable. I think it was a
lot harder for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Meston, who recently completed coursework for a sociology degree
at Brandeis University, is described by friends as soft-spoken,
gentle, and attention-shy. Authorities may have been more
interested in Meston than Lafitte because Meston is a Tibetan
speaker, an American who was raised in a Tibetan monastery in
Nepal.
</P>
<P>
   Lafitte said he is concerned about the fate of Tsering Dorji, an
ethnic Tibetan and Chinese citizen who was translating local
dialect for them. He was separated from Lafitte and Meston, of
Newton, Mass., when they were detained. Dorji had also worked as a
translator for the European Union last October.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking by telephone from his Melbourne home, Lafitte said that
after their arrival in Xining, he was kept under 24-hour watch by
two secret police officers who sat at his bedside. He said he was
awakened nightly about 1 a.m. and interrogated relentlessly for
about four hours on what he was doing in Qinghai, and forced to
sign numerous confessions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Always the interrogation would begin one hour after I fell
asleep. They were very clear with me that `You are under the
coercive powers of the state security bureau. We can do anything,
you can do nothing. You must obey, you have no choice,' '' Lafitte
recounted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure this is exactly what was said to Daja, and that's
what drove him to utter desperation, perhaps over the brink,''
Lafitte said, discounting speculation that Meston's injuries might
have been inflicted by authorities.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we overestimate the physical crudity of the Chinese if
we think they would physically assault him like that,'' Lafitte
said. ``It's not his body they assaulted; it's his mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Lafitte says he doesn't understand how he and Meston could be
accused of crimesbecause the Chinese government had said that
foreigners were welcome to visit the Qinghai project site
unaccompanied.
</P>
<P>
   The project has come under fire because of letters from local
Tibetans expressing fears about conflicts over limited resources if
50,000 Chinese and Muslim farmers are resettled on Mongol and
Tibetan herding lands. Lafitte is writing a book on Tibetan
grasslands, and studies herding communities.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to familiarize ourselves with the logic of the World
Bank project,'' Lafitte said. ``Nothing we did was secret,
everything was open.''
</P>
<P>
   Lafitte said he had shown police a copy of the letter he had
written to the World Bank on his plans to come to Qinghai. In the
letter, he quoted the Chinese official statement of June 24 that
``visitors are welcome to have extensive contacts with local
people, unattended by Chinese officials.''
</P>
<P>
   Rather than a vindication, the letter was seized as evidence of
guilt.
</P>
<P>
   Foreigners need no special permit to visit Dulan County, where
the men were seized. Yet they were accused of trespassing in a
restricted area.
</P>
<P>
   ``How can you make an illegal visit to an open area?'' Lafitte
asked. ``I tried at the cost of enraging my inquisitor to define
what is an illegal interview. At one point, he said, `If you talk
to anyone, that's an illegal interview.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Authorities wanted to know where the men had been, with whom
they had spoken and what they were told. Lafitte said he did not
question anyone specifically about the World Bank project, nor
about anything that could be construed as state secrets, personal
grievances, or complaints against the government. Nor, he insisted,
did he share opinions of his own.
</P>
<P>
   Lafitte told security officers he was a development specialist
who studies nomadic civilizations. ``But they kept yelling at me,
`What is your true purpose? Why are you here? We know what your
true feelings are!' ''
</P>
<P>
   The thing that saved him, Lafitte said, was knowing ``that the
only thing to do was to plead guilty early and often and apologize
for everything I did. That is the Chinese system.''
</P>
<P>
   Lafitte said that Meston, in contrast, from the moment they were
picked up, seemed ``extremely nervous about signing confessions,
signing records, putting his index finger in red wax'' to mark
documents.
</P>
<P>
   Lafitte said he told officers they were ``making a big mistake,
that the world was watching, that this will prove counterproductive
to China's goal of furthering development. But they never really
heard or understood me.''
</P>
<P>
   Already, there are mumblings within the World Bank that the $40
million funding for the Qinghai project that was narrowly approved
might now be in jeopardy. A bank inspection team is scheduled to
visit the site next month.
</P>
<P>
   Lafitte urged the bank to hold China to its promise that it
would allow unfettered visits by interested parties to the disputed
project site.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
