<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-LITTLELEAGUE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOMS RIVER MAKES CHILD'S PLAY OF LITTLE LEAGUE WORLD SERIES OPENER
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By TARIK EL-BASHIR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WILLIAMSPORT, Pa. _ For anyone wondering whether the team from
Toms River, N.J., deserves the nickname ``Beast from the East,''
they needed only to watch this confident bunch devour the team from
Phenix City, Ala., Sunday night in the opening round of the Little
League World Series.
</P>
<P>
   Combining masterly pitching with a couple of powerful swings,
Toms River took the next step toward defending its World Series
title by defeating Phenix City, 6-0, before a crowd of 12,400 at
Howard J. Lamade Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Toms River is only the third American team to return to the
Little League World Series the year after winning the title. Toms
River plays Boise, Idaho, on Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   Osaka, Japan, defeated Victoria, British Columbia, by 7-3 in the
tournament's first game Sunday. The World Series is divided into
four-team American and international divisions. After round-robin
play in the divisions, the division champions will meet for the
title Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Casey Gaynor of Toms River pitched his second consecutive
one-hitter and his fifth consecutive shutout. He was supported by
two home runs _ a two-run shot by Jeff Burgdorff in the first
inning and a solo home run by Steve Bernath in second inning. Toms
River scored five runs in the first three innings.
</P>
<P>
   Gaynor has been dominant this post-season. With Sunday night's
shutout, he has pitched 30 innings without allowing a run. Three
days after tossing a one-hitter in the regional tournament final,
Gaynor again baffled the opposing team with a mix of control and
raw power, and a nasty curve every now and again.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first game is very important,'' said Mike Gaynor, Toms
River's manager and Casey's father, ``since you probably only need
one win to get into the U.S. championship game.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I was throwing my fastball and curveball today,'' said Casey
Gaynor, who started last year's championship game against Japan but
did not earn the victory. ``I just wanted to throw strikes and make
them hit the ball. I guess my curveball is getting better.''
</P>
<P>
   Gaynor was just as important at the plate Sunday night. In three
appearances, he got one hit and scored two runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just couldn't hit anything,'' said Bryan Woodall, the
Phenix City third baseman. ``And everything we hit, they caught.''
</P>
<P>
   Whenever Alabama threatened, Toms River was bailed out by its
splendid defense. It has been so long since Toms River has
committed an error, Mike Gaynor could not remember it.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of Toms River's supporters made the nearly five-hour
drive to watch their team make another run at winning the Little
League World Series. They are mothers, fathers, sisters, brothers
and friends _ and they all wore black T-shirts that read ``Beasts
of the East.'' Their rambunctious cheerleader wore a gorilla suit.
The fans stood and chanted, ``Let's go East!'' and ``The beast is
back!'' The chants were so loud they drowned out everything else.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Fontenelli, the grandfather of Toms River shortstop Chris
Fontenelli, was among the fans who made the trip. ``My heart just
bursts with pride today,'' Fontenelli said. ``Did you see those
three putouts Chris made?''
</P>
<P>
   ``The team plays with such teamwork,'' he added. ``It's still
early in the tournament, but they really put it all together
tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the fans' support, Casey Gaynor said: ``It's really great to
have everyone from town come down and cheer for us. It helps our
confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   Toms River is trying to defend its championship with an almost
entirely new team. Only Gaynor and Eric Campesi played in the World
Series last year.
</P>
<P>
   In the opening game, Kazuki Sumiyama and Kazutoshi Adachi
combined on a two-hitter for Japan against Canada. Japan last won
the World Series in 1976. Canada has never won it.
</P>
<P>
   Sumiyama was moved to first base after five innings despite not
having allowed a hit and walking just one. Manager Tsutomo Kameyama
said he pulled Sumiyama as an icebreaker for Adachi, who will pitch
Monday against a team from Ramstein Air Force Base in Germany.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
