<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-22 22:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5882 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-TEN-FINN-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      08-22 0903
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-FINN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TENNIS NEEDS SAMPRAS AND AGASSI AS MUCH AS THEY NEED EACH OTHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By   ROBIN FINN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   These guys are nothing alike: in rivalries, as in romance,
opposites attract. Even the corporate marketplace has been
reverential: one is Image, the other Milk Mustache. Whatever club
one belongs to is a club the other, in a twist on Groucho Marx's
credo, would be loath to join.
</P>
<P>
   But they do share the same swoosh, the same tony tax bracket,
the same intrusion of premature hair loss, the same semisorrowful
single guy marital status and, crucial to a deluded sport that
seems to breathe much easier when they are jostling for the same
trophy, Pete Sampras and Andre Agassi are again sharing the rivalry
that heated up men's tennis when this decade began.
</P>
<P>
   With the decade and millennium's final U.S. Open set to begin a
week from Monday, their timing couldn't be better. Sunday, while
the top-ranked Sampras was in the Hamptons nursing a sore hip back
to health for the Open, Agassi was busy bulldozing Yevgeny
Kafelnikov, 7-6 (7-3), 6-1, in the Washington final.
</P>
<P>
   The victory not only moved Agassi past Kafelnikov to second in
the rankings, it also gave him the second seeding for the Open. If
form holds, the next time Agassi and Sampras exercise their
decade-old Grand Slam rivalry, they will be back where it all
began, in the final of the U.S. Open, the major tournament that
launched Sampras in 1990 and ascribed Zen master status to Agassi
in 1994 before breaking his heart in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   More than the sum of its parts, their rivalry, heir apparent to
the truncated point-counterpoint of Borg-McEnroe, combines the
punch of Frazier-Ali with the crosstown one-upsmanship of the
Mets-Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   ``These guys can really revive tennis in America,'' Jack Kramer,
the Hall of Famer whose logo launched a zillion wooden rackets,
raved from courtside in Los Angeles earlier this month as Sampras
beat Agassi in a transcendent two tiebreaker final.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel a certain buzz with the rivalry kind of kicking up,''
Sampras admitted after kicking Agassi off the court in two sets in
the ATP Championship semifinal on Aug. 14 in suburban Cincinnati.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good for tennis in America to have us two competing and
going at it like we've been the past couple of months,'' said the
28-year-old Sampras, who has twice used Agassi as his whipping boy
in U.S. Open finals and last month earned a 12th Grand Slam singles
title, tying him with Roy Emerson's men's record, by outgunning
Agassi in their high-octane final at Wimbledon.
</P>
<P>
   ``He forces me to add things to my game,'' said Sampras, whose
game was already chock full of artillery sufficient to secure him
the year-end No. 1 ranking for a record six years in succession.
</P>
<P>
   But he credits his on-again off-again rivalry with Agassi, which
he leads by a comfortable 16-10 margin, with pushing him to the
sustained heights necessary to sculpture a career that will
outstrip past and future champions. Agassi defeated Sampras for the
1995 Australian Open championship, defeated him that year on hard
courts at the Lipton tournament and the Canadian Open to earn
bragging rights to the No. 1 ranking. After Sampras dethroned him
at the U.S. Open that year, a chastened Agassi seemed to lose
interest. Sampras missed him.
</P>
<P>
   This March, with the rivalry still in mothballs, the top-ranked
Sampras offered up a requiem. ``What we had a couple of years ago
with the Nike commercials and the different games, the
personalities, playing the finals of the Open, if we could have
continued that over the next couple of years, it would have done
wonders for this game,'' he said. ``It was the perfect scenario for
us to really carry this game to a new level. I wish we could have
been consistent, maybe one day to be compared to a Borg-McEnroe
rivalry, but it never really happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Without it, men's tennis didn't have much of a pulse.
</P>
<P>
   The jaws of life in this case was the 1999 French Open title in
June. It put Agassi in the record book as the fifth man in history
and the first since Rod Laver to wrestle all four Grand Slam titles
into his possession, and it resurrected the rivalry, and men's
tennis.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly Agassi, divorced and disciplined at 29, jogged back
into the thick of things, validated by a title and record that
Sampras had yet to pocket. In July, with four years elapsed since
they butted heads with a Grand Slam championship at stake, came
their Wimbledon final and then, as if making the most of the second
chance granted their rivalry, came a final in Los Angeles and the
semifinal in Cincinnati.
</P>
<P>
   That those decisions too went Sampras' way seemed to matter less
than the impassioned tennis they inspired. ``You get to a certain
level where it's not about what you do, it's about just how well
you do it; he has a game that lends for periods of time of
genius,'' was Agassi's Zen-like explanation.
</P>
<P>
   Their next clash, if Agassi has a say in it, will be the U.S.
Open final. ``If I could only have one,'' said the bald one,
unbowed despite bowing in eight of their last 10 bouts, ``I would
take it at the Open.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Sampras, he and Agassi aren't selfish enough to
grab every trophy. ``It's not just going to be Andre and I for the
next couple of years dominating the game,'' he warned.
</P>
<P>
   But there wouldn't be many complaints if they did.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
