<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-22 22:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5883 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f BC-FUTURE-COLOR-KAN &LR;      08-22 1055
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FUTURE-COLOR-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLOR CHOICE OF THE FUTURE? AMERICA'S GOING GRAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOYCE SMITH  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ The color of money these days comes in shades
of gray. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   From silver cars to brushed-steel refrigerators to gray clothes,
cool colors are in. According to color analysts, consumers are
looking for high-tech colors that evoke the coming century. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We see the whole gray movement continuing into the
millennium,'' said Pat Tunsky, creative director at Henry Doneger
Associates of New York, color advisers to several industries.
``It's more of a futuristic color; the metals with brushed and
satin finishes, not high-shine.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Correctly predicting consumer color preferences can make the
difference between huge profits and product failures. Studies show
nearly 40 percent of consumers will switch vehicle brands if they
can't get their preferred color. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When predicting color trends, analysts weigh economics,
environment, politics, history, sports, psychology and other
factors. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Gray and silver show the strong economy and conservatism, while
green symbolizes harmony and counteracts emotional stress.
Psychologists say a move to red cars would reflect a
``spend-it-now'' mind-set. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   White and green, which regained popularity in 1993 and faded in
1998, still are the most popular colors for cars in the United
States, but silver has gained popularity in automotive segments
from sport-utility vehicles to luxury cars. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DuPont, which tracks automotive color choices, said silver and
gray cars posted increases of up to 17 percent in various
categories in 1998, the last figures available. In 1997, the
increase was less than 7 percent. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Blues had been fairly depressed for a while but are showing
quite a bit of movement now,'' said Matt Kester, spokesman for the
GM Design Center in Warren, Mich. ``You're also going to see a lot
of grays out there, which includes silver.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Nick Allen, a partner in several area auto dealerships,
including Independence Lincoln-Mercury, said silver and light blues
are hot. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``In the Honda line, we can't keep enough of the `heather mist,'
which is kind of a silver,'' Allen said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Christine Dickey, color and trim manager for Toyota Motor Sales
USA in Torrance, Calif., said silver was all but extinct as a car
color in the late 1980s and early 1990s, so the public hasn't seen
it in a long time. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks fresh, and the new silvers are brighter, shinier,
more reflective,'' Dickey said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Toyota's 4Runner sport-utility vehicle comes in a ``desert
dune'' color that's not a white, beige or silver, but some of all
three. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It took off from the get-go and is now our lead color in
sport-utilities,'' Dickey said. ``And the `millennium silver' is
the hottest color in the Lexus GS.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Color Marketing Group, an international, nonprofit
association of 1,500 color designers based in Alexandria, Va.,
predicted the gray movement two years ago. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Now, small-appliance manufacturers are responding by putting
brushed aluminum on everything from coffeepots to men's shavers. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Some are adding gold tones to make it look even more
sophisticated,'' said Randy Voss, product manager for Panasonic
Home and Commercial Products Co. in Illinois. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sears Roebuck &AMP; Co. wants to see stainless-steel appliances
before it will consider ordering from a manufacturer. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though we don't expect it to be a top seller, we want to
see it,'' said Peggy Palter, a spokeswoman for Sears. ``Stainless
steel is very hot, especially in high-end appliances. It's a style
statement.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The aluminum appliances complement other silver items in the
kitchen such as toasters, utensils and trim on older appliances. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Todd Dean of Loma Vista Hardware in Westport said furniture
sales had been strong for items such as a brushed-steel coffee
table and love seats with brushed-steel trim. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of influence also is from fashion,'' said Pat Verlodt,
president of Color Services &AMP; Associates Inc. in Huntley, Ill.,
color consultants to manufacturers. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Nike, for example, has added a splash of silver on some of its
shoe lines. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Several national retailers reported that one-third of their
recent clothing inventories has been gray or gray-hued. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Carolyn Moss, a fashion director for Macy's, said gray was a new
alternative to black. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Silver and gray will be the highlight colors of the millennium
season as we celebrate the new year,'' Moss said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Color trends help motivate customers to make a purchase based on
style instead of waiting for an item to wear out. After a decade of
black as the fashion color, consumers were ready for a change, but
nothing too radical, according to the experts. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``They need to take one baby step into a new direction, and gray
has all the same properties as black. It's an empowering color,
very stable, very basic,'' said Leatrice Eiseman of the Pantone
Color Institute near Seattle. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Gray ... is high-tech and futuristic into the new
millennium.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Just a few years ago, hunter green was the accent color for
households in everything from towels to trash cans. Now, softer
shades such as pale pink and butter yellow will be trendy in
clothing, kitchen utensils, bathroom accessories, tiles and more. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But some companies are beginning to play with a more provocative
palette. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ford Motor Co. is picking up the vibrant colors popular in urban
neighborhoods and using yellows, purples and oranges on its sporty
and small cars and trucks. The 1999 Mustang GT convertible comes in
such ``impact'' colors as ``grabber lime'' and ``grabber green
metallic.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, a new and expensive treatment called ``mystic paint''
will cause cars to change colors under different lighting, say from
a purplish to a greenish. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In a year or two, experts expect silver to return to its
historic place as an accent color. That's not too bad when you
consider the once-hot color of avocado has all but fallen off the
consumer map. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Silver looks so elegant and adds a very, very high-society,
high-style effect into people's lives that doesn't necessarily cost
a lot,'' Voss said. ``Consumers very much want to get the best
value for the dollars available.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-22-99 2213EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990822.0198 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-22 22:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5884 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-FUTURE-COLOR-KAN &LR;      08-22 1055
</HEADER>
