   ``Some are adding gold tones to make it look even more
sophisticated,'' said Randy Voss, product manager for Panasonic
Home and Commercial Products Co. in Illinois. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sears Roebuck &AMP; Co. wants to see stainless-steel appliances
before it will consider ordering from a manufacturer. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though we don't expect it to be a top seller, we want to
see it,'' said Peggy Palter, a spokeswoman for Sears. ``Stainless
steel is very hot, especially in high-end appliances. It's a style
statement.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The aluminum appliances complement other silver items in the
kitchen such as toasters, utensils and trim on older appliances. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Todd Dean of Loma Vista Hardware in Westport said furniture
sales had been strong for items such as a brushed-steel coffee
table and love seats with brushed-steel trim. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of influence also is from fashion,'' said Pat Verlodt,
president of Color Services &AMP; Associates Inc. in Huntley, Ill.,
color consultants to manufacturers. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Nike, for example, has added a splash of silver on some of its
shoe lines. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Several national retailers reported that one-third of their
recent clothing inventories has been gray or gray-hued. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Carolyn Moss, a fashion director for Macy's, said gray was a new
alternative to black. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Silver and gray will be the highlight colors of the millennium
season as we celebrate the new year,'' Moss said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Color trends help motivate customers to make a purchase based on
style instead of waiting for an item to wear out. After a decade of
black as the fashion color, consumers were ready for a change, but
nothing too radical, according to the experts. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``They need to take one baby step into a new direction, and gray
has all the same properties as black. It's an empowering color,
very stable, very basic,'' said Leatrice Eiseman of the Pantone
Color Institute near Seattle. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Gray ... is high-tech and futuristic into the new
millennium.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Just a few years ago, hunter green was the accent color for
households in everything from towels to trash cans. Now, softer
shades such as pale pink and butter yellow will be trendy in
clothing, kitchen utensils, bathroom accessories, tiles and more. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But some companies are beginning to play with a more provocative
palette. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ford Motor Co. is picking up the vibrant colors popular in urban
neighborhoods and using yellows, purples and oranges on its sporty
and small cars and trucks. The 1999 Mustang GT convertible comes in
such ``impact'' colors as ``grabber lime'' and ``grabber green
metallic.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, a new and expensive treatment called ``mystic paint''
will cause cars to change colors under different lighting, say from
a purplish to a greenish. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In a year or two, experts expect silver to return to its
historic place as an accent color. That's not too bad when you
consider the once-hot color of avocado has all but fallen off the
consumer map. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Silver looks so elegant and adds a very, very high-society,
high-style effect into people's lives that doesn't necessarily cost
a lot,'' Voss said. ``Consumers very much want to get the best
value for the dollars available.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
