<SLUG> BC-RUN-TRAC-DASH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
100-METER DASH TO GLORY FOR BOTH GREENE AND JONES
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By CHRISTOPHER CLAREY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEVILLE, Spain _ The straw hat came spinning out of the stands
and landed on the fast track near Maurice Greene's incomparably
fast feet. It is the way Sevillans show approval at the bullfights,
the traditional form of entertainment in this traditional city, and
like a triumphant matador who had just been awarded both ears and
the tail by an approving jury, Greene leaned over and joyfully
tossed the hat back in the direction of its owner.
</P>
<P>
   He then celebrated American-style by completing a victory lap at
the world track and field championships with his nation's flag in
hand.
</P>
<P>
   Greene had just recovered from a shaky start to catch Bruny
Surin of Canada and win his second consecutive world title in the
100 meters, missing his own world record by just one-hundredth of a
second. What made that American flag all the more appropriate was
that Greene's teammate Marion Jones had already won her second
consecutive world title in the women's 100.
</P>
<P>
   It was a warm and remarkable night in Seville, and though
neither Greene's nor Jones' victory was anything close to a
surprise, the intensity and historic pace of both finals _ each
more hotly contested than predicted _ created a palpable buzz in
the Estadio Olimpico.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody thought this was going to be a cakewalk, but I think
Bruny and I produced a great spectacle tonight, maybe one of the
best,'' said Greene, who finished in 9.80 seconds to Surin's 9.84,
which tied Surin with Donovan Bailey, the reigning Olympic champion
and a fellow Canadian, for the third best time in history.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's definitely tough to run that fast and still finish
second,'' Surin said.
</P>
<P>
   Jones ran fast enough to finish first: getting off to a fine
start, controlling her power beautifully and crossing the finish
line in 10.70 seconds, the fifth fastest time in history. Only the
late Florence Griffith-Joyner in that unexpected and remarkable
summer of 1988 and Jones herself have run faster with a legal wind.
This was perhaps the most impressive time of Jones' short career
because her personal best of 10.65 came at relatively high altitude
last year in South Africa.
</P>
<P>
   But what was surprising about this race was that, despite Jones'
superb time, she beat her countrywoman Inger Miller by only
nine-hundredths of a second. Ekaterini Thanou of Greece, another
fast-rising sprinter, took the bronze medal in 10.84 seconds. In
all, six women broke 11 seconds, which had never happened before in
a women's 100.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's no walk in the park anymore,'' said Jones, who has not
lost a sprint since 1997. ``Everybody is right there running
fast.''
</P>
<P>
   Speed runs in Miller's family. A Californian, she is the
daughter of the former Jamaican Olympian Lennox Miller, who won a
silver medal in the men's 100 in 1968 and a bronze medal in 1972.
Lennox coached Inger until this season, when, with her father's
approval, she joined Greene and the team of runners who are coached
by John Smith, a former American Olympian.
</P>
<P>
   Smith has a reputation for helping his athletes peak for major
championships, and Miller certainly peaked here, running three
personal bests in two days. Perhaps she should have sensed it
coming when she beat Greene out of the starting blocks in training
last week. ``We're going to see some really good rivalries going on
next year; obviously it's not a one-woman show,'' said Miller, who
will try to push Jones again in the 200.
</P>
<P>
   First, though, Jones will try to win her second gold medal of
this championship on Monday night in the long jump. Her family
already has won two golds, and before Jones walked on the track to
race in the semifinals Sunday, her husband, CJ Hunter, who won the
shot-put on Saturday, made his trip to the podium.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a very big motivation for me,'' said Jones, who watched
her husband's dramatic winning throw from the stands. ``I was very
emotional Sunday after CJ won the gold just because in my opinion
he doesn't get the recognition he deserves. It was a wonderful way
to start the week.''
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, Greene and Jones burst to international
prominence on the same night in Athens by winning the 100s at the
world championship. Since then, they have established their
dominance, become major stars in Europe with high hopes at home and
broadened their ambitions. Jones wants to win an unprecedented four
gold medals here; Greene wants to win three and become the first
man to sweep the 100 and 200 in this championship.
</P>
<P>
   His chances improved considerably when his chief rival in the
200, Frankie Fredericks of Namibia, withdrew from the semifinals in
the 100 Sunday night, citing a thigh injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's on a silver platter now,'' said Ato Boldon, Greene's
training partner and the reigning world 200 champion, who is here
as a television commentator instead of a competitor because of an
injury.
</P>
<P>
   It was a brutally hot afternoon and early evening: one
thermometer in the city center at 6:30 p.m. showed a reading of 113
degrees. It made it rough on the competitors in the heptathlon, won
by Eunice Barber of France, who had to compete before the sun had
slipped behind the oval opening in the stadium. Korsten Kobs of
Germany, the gold medalist in the hammer throw, celebrated by
jogging across the infield and diving into the water-filled
steeplechase pit.
</P>
<P>
   But sprinters generally relish the heat, and Greene, who grew up
running in steamy Kansas City summers, relishes it more than most.
By the time Greene walked onto the track for the final, the
temperature had dropped to 86 degrees, and while the other
sprinters stood still near their blocks as their names were
announced, Greene paced and strutted in his lane, eyes wide,
shoulders bobbing and tongue slipping in and out of his mouth as if
he were preparing to devour something.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks like he's getting ready for a bar fight, and, in
essence, he is,'' Boldon said.
</P>
<P>
   The fight would start poorly for Greene, however, as he stumbled
out of the blocks. But as Surin accelerated toward an upset, Greene
kept his composure and, in trademark fashion, his head down. He
caught the Canadian and moved in front slightly with about 20
meters remaining.
</P>
<P>
   ``At about 75 or 80 meters, I believed I was going to win,''
Greene said.
</P>
<P>
   Said Smith: ``I was impressed with the way he came back, Carl
Lewis-style.''
</P>
<P>
   Greene was soon shouting up at Boldon in the stands that the
victory had been for him. The two are uncommonly close friends for
rivals, and shortly after Greene had returned the hat and the
compliment to the stands, Boldon and another friend, the hurdler
Larry Wade, went out on the track. The three were soon locked in a
collective embrace, but Greene stands alone in the record books
with the two fastest times in history, and if not for that stumble
Sunday night, the world record might already be lower than 9.79
seconds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can go faster, believe me, I can go faster,'' Greene said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
