<HEADLINE>
ISLAMIC NATIONS URGED TO KEEP THEIR CITIZENS OUT OF REVOLT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN WHITMORE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Russia sought help Sunday from foreign governments
whose citizens it suspects are participating in the Islamic
uprising in the republic of Dagestan. President Boris N. Yeltsin
has called the conflict, now in its third week, a threat to
Russia's territorial integrity.
</P>
<P>
   Also Sunday, Moscow claimed an important battlefield victory,
saying its forces had captured part of the village of Tando, a key
rebel base.
</P>
<P>
   But a rebel statement, released over the militants' Web site,
rejected the claim, saying that despite a major offensive by
Russian forces, the rebels still held the village. For most of the
past week the fiercest fighting has centered on Tando, a tiny
strategic village overlooking the town of Botlikh and the valley
where Russian forces are concentrated.
</P>
<P>
   The rebels' main bases are in two villages above Tando, Ansalta
and Rakhata.
</P>
<P>
   Vladimir Rushailo, Russia's top law enforcement official, said
Sunday that volunteers from the United Arab Emirates, Saudi Arabia,
and Pakistan may be assisting the Chechen-led Islamic insurgents.
Rushailo said the Russian Foreign Ministry has sent appeals to
these countries, asking for assistance in stoping the alleged flow
of mercenaries into Dagestan. He added that Moscow did not believe
that the volunteers were acting with the blessing of their
governments.
</P>
<P>
   It was not the first time Russia had alleged foreign
involvement. On Aug. 14, Russia sent a letter to the G-7, the
European Union and the Islamic Conference claiming that
``irrefutable facts attest that the terrorists are receiving
financial, material and other assistance from outside.''
</P>
<P>
   The uprising began on Aug. 7, when Islamic militants, led by the
34-year-old Chechen rebel leader Shaimil Basayev, crossed over
Chechnya's rugged border with Dagestan and captured several
villages. The rebel's stated goal is to pry the region free from
Russia and create an Islamic state.
</P>
<P>
   From 1994 until 1996, Moscow fought a bloody 20-month war
against Chechnya, which gained de facto independence from Russia.
After pulling out its troops in late 1996, Moscow continued to
claim the republic as part of Russia, despite being unable to
influence events there. Late last week, Russian warplanes struck
villages inside Chechnya near the Dagestan border. Chechnya's
president, Aslan Maskhadov, has repeatedly said that his government
has no ties to the rebels.
</P>
<P>
   Over the weekend, the Kremlin appeared to be preparing the
public for another long war in the region. In a radio interview
Saturday, Kremlin spokesman Dmitry Yakushkin quoted Yeltsin as
saying it was ``impossible to expect a quick solution'' to the
uprising and that the conflict represents a ``real threat to
Russia's integrity.''
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Vladimir Putin said on Aug. 10 that Russian
forces would crush the rebellion in a matter of weeks, a claim that
now appears to have been optimistic.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander Iskandarian, a Moscow-based analyst said the region is
slowly but surely sliding out of Moscow's orbit. ``The departure of
the Caucusus from Russia is not an act, but a process. This process
is real, it is happening, but it is happening slowly,'' said
Iskandarian. ``The process is cultural rather than political. If
you ask me if the Caucusus are going to cease to be a part of
Russia in the near future, I would say I don't know. But the
cultural process of seperation is definately taking place.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-22-99 2218EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
