<SLUG> BC-FBC-USC-LADN-(SLANG0 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO RUNNING? NO PROBLEM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVINE, Calif. _ When USC defeated Purdue last August in
118-degree heat on the Coliseum field, players presented a game
ball to strength coach Matt Schiotz for their superior
conditioning. So it seems like Schiotz might be putting his
reputation on the line by advising USC coach Paul Hackett to have
the team skip wind sprints during two-a-day practices at UC Irvine.
</P>
<P>
   But the strength coach is confident he is not letting the
players off the hook.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can see we are in shape. I don't feel fatigue will be a
factor for us,'' Schiotz said. ``We're a lot stronger than we were
last year at this time. The guys are out here in better
condition.''
</P>
<P>
   Schiotz said 80 percent of the team attended every summer
workout, as opposed to 63 percent last season. Although Hackett
admitted being ``concerned'' about not running, he decided to take
Schiotz's advice. USC finally resumed wind sprints Saturday and
Sunday because it only practiced once.
</P>
<P>
   __ Scrimmage follow-up: Hackett said after watching tapes of
Saturday's scrimmage he liked the way the Trojans' defense played
as a unit and thought it was ahead of the offense. He mentioned
reserve defensive linemen Bobby DeMars and Darren Collins as
players who stood out. Offensively, he liked quarterback Mike Van
Raaphorst and offensive guard Donta Kendrick.
</P>
<P>
   Hackett was also impressed with linebacker Markus Steele, who
has been in camp two days, and said he could possibly start the
Hawaii game.
</P>
<P>
   __ What about the line? The offensive line has more experience
than last year but wasn't exactly dominating in the first
scrimmage.
</P>
<P>
   ``It didn't look like we improved at all, but they're all
stronger and quicker,'' quarterback Carson Palmer said. ``Some of
the guys were just drained by the end of the scrimmage.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Scholarship for Arbet? Hackett said it's early, but he might
consider giving freshman walk-on cornerback Kevin Arbet a
scholarship. Arbet, from Stockton, is the son of former USC wide
receiver Jeff Simmons, who caught 56 passes in 1982.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's made a real case at this point,'' Hackett said.
``I'm very impressed. I recruited his father.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Bumps and bruises: Linebacker Zeke Moreno missed practice
with a hip flexor that has bothered him for several days, but he
will try to return today. Freshman wide receiver Marcell Allmond
(hamstring) is also expected back.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-22-99 2222EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990822.0204 </DOCNO>
