<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ORGANIC-FARM-2TAKES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ORGANIC FARMERS STRUGGLE TO KEEP CROPS FROM CHEMICAL
CONTAMINATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT CANON  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CALHOUN, Mo. _ Gary Anson worries that today's chicken manure
isn't what it used to be. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He struggles mightily to keep his corn, soybeans and wheat
pristine _ free of chemicals and laboratory-tinkered genetics. When
he succeeds, his crops earn organic status and fetch a premium
price. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But keeping his fields unspoiled by high-tech agriculture is a
chore without end. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Chemicals sprayed on a neighboring field can drift his way.
Pollen, blown from another farmer's genetically modified corn, can
travel miles in a storm. And Anson worries that the chicken dung he
used in the past to replace chemical fertilizer might now carry
remnants of feed made from gene-spliced corn. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It's coming at me from every direction,'' said the 62-year-old
organic farmer. ``I've got nowhere to hide.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Anson belongs to a growing class of farmers trying to sell food
in a lucrative market even as the planting of genetically
engineered crops explodes across the American breadbasket _
threatening to spoil the organic fun. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On one level, organic farmers have much in common with their
neighbors growing genetically engineered crops. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Both are fast-expanding sectors. While organic farmers still
till a relatively tiny part of the country's farmland, their
numbers have more than doubled in the 1990s. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But the federal government approved the use of gene-tailored
seed in late 1995 and it now dominates the corn, soybean and cotton
fields of America. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Organic and high-tech farmers both put greater investments in
their crops. Organic crops require a tractor to pass through a
field perhaps six times as much as with conventional farming.
Genetically engineered seed costs much more than conventional
hybrids and typically doesn't produce extra seed for planting a
crop the following year. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Yet they can make for troublesome neighbors. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Scott Jung, who farms organically near Cosby, Mo., contends
herbicide sprayed on a neighbor's field drifted across 70 acres of
his land in May 1998. He couldn't sell crops contaminated by
chemicals to the organic market, so he sued. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Although a settlement was reached earlier this month, the
contractor who was spraying the neighbor's field disputes that its
herbicide drifted over the Jung property. The herbicide is
commonplace on farms in the area and long has been used on foods
that end up on American dinner tables. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But because Jung needed certification that his crops were
organic _ key to selling for premium prices on crops headed mostly
to Europe _ any contamination would spoil his crops. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``If he was not organic,'' said Richard Yocum, the lawyer who
defended the herbicide sprayer, ``I don't think there would have
been any problem.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Now Jung worries about what he calls ``gene drift,'' genetically
modified plants from nearby fields pollinating his plants. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no rule at all to say they can't come and plant that
stuff right next to me,'' he said. ``I'm defenseless.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Yet he concedes that his organic operation creates dilemmas for
his neighbors. If he were a conventional farmer, some windblown
herbicide or pesticide would go largely unnoticed and unlitigated.
But with Jung nearby, the time a neighbor has to spray is limited
not just by the planting schedule but by which way the wind is
blowing. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just something else,'' he said, ``for them to worry
about.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Still, the organic market has been most vocal about crop
segregation. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Europeans have been far more wary of chemicals in their crops
than Americans. They have been especially nervous, too, about
consuming genetically engineered crops. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   That cost Chuck Walker the sale of 80,000 bags of corn chips at
$2.50 each. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   His Terra Prima firm has been selling Apache brand organic
tortilla chips in Europe since 1990. Last December, a Dutch
distributor's test revealed they contained a fraction of corn from
genetically engineered plants. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It just devastated us,'' Walker said. ``We had to throw all
the chips away.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With his company's organic-only reputation tarnished in Europe,
Walker said sales this year fell by nearly half. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He checked records on the farms, elevators and the mill his corn
passed through. None showed any evidence of the genetically
engineered crop. He concluded that an organic farmer's field in
Texas _ ``it might have just been a few rows'' _ were pollinated by
a neighbor's laboratory-customized corn. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What was special about the corn that contaminated his chips? It
was tinkered with genetically to build in the pesticide Bacillus
thuringiensis, or Bt, that kills the corn borer. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Europeans have no problems with Bt. The pesticide, in fact, is a
natural substance that organic farmers use widely. The European
objection stems from designing corn genes to contain Bt. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Gerber and Heinz have both moved to different producers so they
can assure their European customers that they don't rely on
genetically engineered corn or soybeans. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Laura Ticciati heads Mothers for Natural Law, a group that
sprung from the transcendental meditation movement and lobbies
against genetically engineered food; she believes Americans pay far
too little attention to the issue. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``But I'm always giving interviews to people in Europe,'' she
said. ``This is huge over there.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Studies have yet to unearth any danger in consuming genetically
modified plants. Critics, in fact, worry primarily that the
long-term effects of consuming genetically modified foods are
unknown. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Promoters of the new technology can rattle off a string of
environmental benefits: greater production with less use of
chemical pesticides and herbicides and lower fuel bills. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With Monsanto's Roundup Ready corn and soybeans, for instance,
someone who once needed to spray several times a season to kill
weeds needs to do so only once. And, unlike traces of the
long-popular atrazine that still is found in soil on many farms,
the Roundup herbicide disappears days after application. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bill Beavis, a geneticist who has spent most of his career
working on agricultural problems, argues that boosting the yields
on Midwestern farms reduces pressure to level dwindling forests in
the rest of the world. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Still, he admits to sharing the worries of Europeans about the
health effects of genetically engineered crops and the risks of
introducing man-made species into the environment. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But they are here. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Department of Agriculture, the federal Environmental
Protection Agency and the U.S. Food and Drug Administration have
approved their use. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Now, Beavis said, the challenge of keeping them separate from
organic foods is baffling. A crop that escapes drifting pollen
could still be contaminated in a cooperative's grain elevator or at
a mill. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just virtually impossible to segregate,'' said Beavis,
now a researcher at the National Center for Genome Resources.
``We'd have to change our whole agricultural system to do that
(and) it would interfere with the freedom of farmers to do as they
please.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For the time being, organic farmers rely on buffers they plant
around their fields and informal neighbor-to-neighbor agreements
about when and where to plant what. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It could still make for a pretty uncomfortable situation if my
neighbor is growing Bt-corn,'' said Ed Reznicek, an organic farmer
near Goff, Kan., who trades labor and shares equipment with a
conventional farmer. ``You want to work with people, but it can be
hard for both sides.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes nature can help. Soybeans are self-pollinating, so the
wind poses no genetic contamination. Most corn varieties favored by
organic farmers tassel later in the season than those used by
conventional farmers. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For years, a crop's organic pedigree came from inspectors such
as Margit Kaltenekker, who travels a circuit checking on farms for
the Organic Crop Improvement Association. She looks at fields,
discusses management techniques and peruses a farmer's receipts for
seed and fertilizer to establish the absence of chemical helpers. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In today's agriculture, however, many organic farmers are also
spending hundreds of dollars per field for genetic tests to prove
their crops avoided contamination. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough for them,'' Kaltenekker said. ``They can do
everything right and still have things ruined by the guy a mile
away.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
