<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEW&AMP;NOTABLE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANNE STEPHENSON'S NEW &AMP; NOTABLE BOOK REVIEWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE STEPHENSON  
 c.1999 Special for the Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``SELECTED NON-FICTIONS'' &QL; 
By Jorge Luis Borges (Viking, $40) &QL; 
``The angels are two days and two nights older than we: The Lord
created them on the fourth day, and from their high balcony between
the recently invented sun and the first moon, they scanned the
infant earth, barely more than a few wheat fields and some orchards
beside the waters.'' With his essay ``A History of'' ``Angels,''
written in 1926, Borges rescues us from the tripe written on the
subject in recent years and leaves us to wonder whether Wim Wenders
read this before he made his haunting film about angels, ``Wings f
Desire.'' ``I always imagine them at nightfall,'' Borges writes,
``in the dusk of a slum or a vacant lot, in that long, quiet moment
when things are gradually left alone, with their backs to the
sunset, and when colors are like memories or premonitions of other
colors. We must not be too prodigal with our angels; they are the
last divinities we harbor, and they might fly away.'' This is the
third volume in Viking's centenary edition of Borges' work in
English, coming after ``Collected Fictions'' and ``Selected
Poems.'' Borges wrote thousands of pages of non-fiction _ essays,
book and film reviews, lectures, encyclopedia entries, historical
surveys and notes on politics and culture, and from them, editor
Eliot Weinberger chose 161 pieces. Most appear in English for the
first time. The rest were newly translated for this edition. Among
the films reviewed (albeit briefly _ as Weinberger notes, Borges
never wrote anything long) are ``King Kong'' and ``The Petrified
Forest.'' Among the books: William Faulkner's ``Absalom! Absalom!''
and Ellery Queen's ``The Door Between.'' It's a marvelous
collection, published to celebrate what would have been Borges'
100th birthday in late August. &QL; 
 &QL; 
HEARTWOOD
</P>
<P>
   By James Lee Burke &QL; 
(Doubleday, $24.95) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Maybe this novel is a bit busy _ to say that it's complex is to
give it too much credit _ but Burke is so much better than other
crime writers that he pulls it off anyway. From the first pages,
we're aware of his virtuosity, although that seems like an odd word
to apply to a man whose characters are world-weary moralists and
vicious schemers and whose setting in this new series (in wake of
his books about Louisiana cop Dave Robicheaux) is a Texas hill town
called Deaf Smith. The hero is Billy Bob Holland, the former police
officer/Texas Ranger-turned-defense attorney, last seen in
``Cimarron Rose.'' In the early pages, Billy Bob suffers the return
to town of a rich man named Earl Deitrich, who long ago wooed and
married Peggy Jean Murphy, the local beauty who was Billy Bob's
high-school lover. Billy Bob is still hung up on Peggy Jean, and
she is still hung up on a boy who died in Vietnam _ both obsessions
that are difficult to believe as the book progresses. Their
attraction is further complicated because the cowboy Billy Bob
takes on as a client is accused of stealing $300,000 in bonds from
Peggy Jean's husband. More plot description would merely make you
dizzy _ suffice it to say that Burke makes all of his characters,
even the odd ones, as real as a Texas moon, and his setting becomes
a character in itself. &QL; 
 &QL; 
LIVING ON THE WIND: &QL; 
ACROSS THE HEMISPHERE &QL; 
WITH MIGRATORY BIRDS
</P>
<P>
   By Scott Weidensaul &QL; 
(North Point, $26) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Thre are some shorebirds that fly non-stop from the southern tip
of South America to the coast of New Jersey _ a trip that takes 10
days, an astonishing 240 hours of uninterrupted flight. And there
are Arctic terns that each autumn fly across the Atlantic to
Europe, then south along Africa to recross the Atlantic toward
South America, finally wintering off of Antarctica. In spring,
writes the author, ``they reverse course, moving up southern Africa
and lancing back to Canada _ a figure eight inscribed on half the
globe, a track that returns them, often as not, to precisely the
same sheltered nook where they nested the summer before.'' Is there
anything more miraculous, more ethereal, more mysterious than the
epic migrations of birds? Weidensaul explores the process with
eloquence, meticulous research and considerable reverence _ and it
does not hurt that his subject is rife with fantastic facts. Did
you know that there are hummingbirds that cross the Gulf of Mexico
twice each year and tiny warblers that fly non-stop from New
England to South America? Did you know that albatrosses leaving the
nest might pass the next four years without touching land?
Weidensaul spent more than six years researching his book,
traveling 70,000 miles by plane, car, boat, horse and foot _ and
yet, he says, he covered fewer miles than a sandpiper would in its
short lifetime, propelled only by muscle and the instinct to trace
those invisible pathways in the sky. &QL; 
 &QL; 
DAYS OF INFAMY &QL; 
By Michael Coffey  &QL; 
(Hyperion, $24.95) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A companion volume to the History Channel's documentary
``Military Blunders,'' this is a survey of mistakes that had
terrible consequences. If the Archduke Franz Ferdinand's chauffeur
had asked directions in Sarajevo on June 28, 1914, he would not
have taken the wrong turn that led to the archduke's assassination.
If the captain of the Lusitania had steered in a zig-zag pattern as
advised, he might have avoided the torpedo that sank the ship and
drew America into World War I. If naval commanders had not
underestimated the threat of air power, the British would not have
suffered the loss of the Prince of Wales and Repulse, two of their
finest ships. If German fliers attempting to destroy oil tanks on
the English coast had not lost their way and bombed the outskirts
of London instead, orders (on both sides) to avoid populated areas
might have stood, saving civilian lives during World War II. You
like war stories? Coffey has war stories, and they prove just how
slender the thread of fate can be. &QL; 
You can reach Anne Stephenson at amstephenson(at)worldnet.att.net,
via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-22-99 2231EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990822.0209 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-22 22:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5901 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-ARREST-RATE-NYT &LR;      08-22 0536
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-ARREST-RATE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLAWED ARRESTS RISE IN NEW YORK 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By FORD FESSENDEN and DAVID ROHDE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Dawad Joseph, a 16-year-old high school sophomore,
was walking to his mother's office with four friends one afternoon
in May 1997 when the young men found themselves in the middle of a
police drug sweep.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph said he was arrested on charges of possessing and selling
drugs, even though police records show no drugs were found on him.
Taken to the local police station house with about 10 other people,
he said, he was strip-searched and put in a holding cell for the
night.
</P>
<P>
   But the next morning, when he was taken to the County Courthouse
for arraignment, he was abruptly freed after a prosecutor reviewed
his arrest and decided it would not stand up in court. Last year
the city paid Joseph's family $12,000 to settle a lawsuit for false
arrest, which city lawyers said stemmed from a case of mistaken
identity.
</P>
<P>
   Though crime in the city has ebbed to historic lows, the New
York City police arrested more people than ever last year. The
inevitable result, courthouse lawyers and some former prosecutors
say, is a surge in the number of flawed arrests. More and more of
those arrested, like Joseph, were jailed and released without ever
having been formally charged with a crime.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, prosecutors tossed out 18,000 of the 345,000 arrests
made in the city even before a judge reviewed the charges, more
than double the number of four years before.
</P>
<P>
   Citywide, about 50 people a day are processed through the
booking system and released because prosecutors reject the charges
against them, often after they have spent hours or overnight in
packed holding cells.
</P>
<P>
   The police contend that the quality of their arrests has not
declined and that prosecutors are failing to prosecute after valid
arrests. But prosecutors are in some cases openly critical of the
quality of the Police Department's felony arrests. More than a
third of felony arrests were reduced before arraignment last year,
and a quarter more were later dismissed, both figures up
substantially from 1993.
</P>
<P>
   All told, more than 140,000 of the 350,000 cases disposed of in
court last year ended in a dismissal, a 60 percent increase in
dismissals over 1993.
</P>
<P>
   The greatest increase has come in the use of a legal device
called adjournment in contemplation of dismissal, or ACD. Under an
ACD, charges against defendants are dismissed as long as they stay
out of trouble, typically for six months.
</P>
<P>
   The legal device was created to keep court dockets and jails
from becoming overcrowded, while giving minor offenders a chance at
a clean slate. Police officials say they do not like the
adjournments, but their use has skyrocketed during Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani's administration _ more than 85,000 were handed out last
year, up from 35,000 in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times computer study of refusals to prosecute in
Manhattan during the first six weeks of 1999 suggest that many of
the cases come from minority neighborhoods, which have been the
focus of much of the stepped-up enforcement activity of the city
police and the source of complaints of police harassment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
