<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-22 22:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5903 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f BC-GOVERNMENT-JOBS-KAN &LR;      08-22 0948
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOVERNMENT-JOBS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NUMBER OF GOVERNMENT WORKERS ROSE 2 PERCENT IN YEAR ENDING IN MARCH
'98 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN A. DVORAK  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Along with high tech, there's another growth
industry around: state and local governments. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The number of workers they employ _ everybody from teachers to
police officers to highway laborers _ rose 2 percent in the year
ending in March 1998, according to a recently released report from
the U.S. Census Bureau. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Kansas stands out. Based on the size of its population, it has a
particularly large public payroll. Missouri ranked closer to the
middle. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Payroll records in Johnson County, Kan., part of suburban Kansas
City, illustrate what's been happening. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, the county employed the equivalent of 2,300 workers.
Four years later, the number hit 2,900. Next year the number should
reach 3,400. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Johnson County government has grown too large too fast,'' said
George Gross, chairman of the County Commission. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   State and local governments nationwide employed the equivalent
of 14.5 million workers, up from 14.2 million the previous year,
the census report shows.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The figures represent the number of employees working the
equivalent of a full-time staffer. Governments actually employ more
people, some of whom work part-time. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Calculated on a per-resident basis, Kansas has more public
employees than all but five states. Missouri slightly exceeded the
national average. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Among the biggest areas of public employment: teachers in
elementary and secondary schools, colleges and universities; police
officers; and firefighters. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``In Johnson County, we've added hundreds of employees over the
last four years,'' Gross said. ``I personally feel we can do with
fewer employees.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Told of the national census findings, Gross said, ``I find it
almost alarming.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone agrees. Increases in public employment don't
automatically mean waste is occurring. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For example, it can be argued that the needs of Johnson County
and other areas change as population rises. Jail expansion is one
reason for more employees in Johnson County. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Census Bureau report was based on counts and estimates for
March 1998. In Missouri, public employment was 297,864, up from
290,054 the previous year. In Kansas, public employment was
167,295, up from 162,776. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I do think it demonstrates that there could be administrative
savings,'' University of Kansas political science professor Burdett
Loomis said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But a variety of reasons, including the size of a state and its
social and political history, control how many workers are employed
by government, Loomis said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Kansas, he noted, has many small rural counties and school
districts. While consolidating them might lower public payrolls, he
said, communities wouldn't easily approve of losing their
courthouses, for example. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Years ago, he said, Kansas created six institutions of higher
learning, deciding to give its young people plenty of educational
opportunities. Today, he said, the state probably wouldn't take
such an expensive step. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Besides cities, counties and school districts, Kansas sports a
long list of special types of local governments: everything from
utility supply boards to groundwater management districts. Other
states don't have so many. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Kansans like local government,'' said Don Moler, executive
director of the League of Kansas Municipalities. ``We have the
amount of services the public wants.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Kansas should cut back on public workers, countered Karl
Peterjohn, executive director of the Kansas Taxpayers Network. Laws
to restrict spending and taxes, he said, would hold down the
payroll. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a lot of government here, the survey reflects that
fact,'' Peterjohn said. ``We have no limitations on our ability to
grow government.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Missouri, he noted, has a state spending lid called the Hancock
Amendment, something that has been proposed but not enacted in
Kansas. And Missouri, he noted, has proportionately fewer public
employees. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Census Bureau study raises those kinds of questions. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Consider Iowa, a state with a population similar to Kansas. On a
per-person basis, it doesn't employ nearly as many state and local
workers. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And Tennessee, a state with nearly the same population as
Missouri, employs fewer public workers. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The numbers do not include federal government workers. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The president pro tem of the Missouri Senate, Ed Quick, a
Democrat, has seen the public-employee question from three sides.
He once worked as a firefighter in Kansas City. Then he served on
the Kansas City Council. Now he leads the state Senate. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Nobody will agree on whether there are too many public
employees, he said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got those who think we do and those who think we
don't,'' Quick said. ``Overall, I don't think we're out of line.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In theory at least, having more workers should mean better
services. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For instance, on a per-resident basis, Kansas has more street
and highway workers than Missouri, the Census Bureau report
showed. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Past studies also have found Kansas roads in better condition
than Missouri roads. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Citizens want a voice in local governments, said Sen. Dick Bond,
a Republican who leads the Kansas Senate. They have a lot bigger
voice in smaller towns than in cities the size of Kansas City, Bond
said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Joining together school districts or cities might result in
fewer public employees. But Bond said citizens aren't demanding
government consolidation. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not hear an unhappy public,'' Bond said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
