<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-22 22:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5908 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-CANE-REFUGEE-COX     08-22 0593
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANE-REFUGEE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Travel-weary Texans head to inland shelters
 &HT;    By Andy Alford and Bob Banta
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO, Texas _ Travel worn and anxious, they came to the
shelters here in droves.
</P>
<P>
   And when the crowds filled the schools and churches in San
Antonio, they headed to Austin seeking protection from Hurricane
Bret, which roared ashore late Sunday afternoon 70 miles south of
Corpus Christi.
</P>
<P>
   Men who had been driving for hours, urged on by the specter of
boiling black clouds in their rear view mirrors. Children with
sleep marks on their faces. Mothers toting babies and bottles.
</P>
<P>
   Like many in the path of the storm, Ray Trevino had to make the
anguished decision to flee his Port Aransas home for San Antonio or
stay and face down the strongest hurricane Texas has seen since
Carla menaced the coast in 1961.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can replace the trailer, but we can't replace our lives,''
Trevino said. He, his wife and their three children found shelter
Sunday through the Red Cross at San Antonio's Trinity Baptist
Church. ``We come first.''
</P>
<P>
   Through the night Saturday, Trevino hovered near his radio and
agonized whether to leave home. Then, with storm force winds
already hammering the shore, police warned residents of the coastal
town that if they were going to go they should go now.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't even put plywood up,'' said Trevino, who left with
his family at 3 a.m. Later Sunday, he sat shoulder to shoulder with
his wife, Brenda, staring transfixed at weather broadcasts of the
storm. ``With winds of 145 miles an hour, there's no way our mobile
home is going to stay.''
</P>
<P>
   Trevino rubbed his face with his hand; his wife patted his
thigh.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took us a long time to get something,'' she said. ``It's so
hard to leave it behind.''
</P>
<P>
   Clay Settje, the shelter's assistant manager, said the church
was full of families like the Trevinos. About 380 would eat, sleep,
play and worry at the shelter until coastal officials said it was
safe to go home.
</P>
<P>
   Across San Antonio and in Austin, similar dramas unfolded as
families mentally tallied their losses. Some, even while they
carried plastic bags filled with family photo albums, clothes and
jewelry or valuables, mourned what they had to leave behind.
</P>
<P>
   Don Gaines of Rockport, left his three dogs when he sought
shelter at the Alamo Heights High School shelter in San Antonio.
``They wouldn't fit in the car,'' he said Sunday from the Alamo
Heights High School shelter. What did fit were his wife, three
children, stuffed toys, stereo amplifier and the family Bible.
</P>
<P>
   ``No matter what, you have to have room for that,'' Gaines said.
``Things will come out all right. We'll just keep praying.''
</P>
<P>
   In Austin, about 115 spent the night at Reagan High School and
the Travis County Exposition Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we got to San Antonio they (Red Cross officials) directed
us up to Austin because places there were already filling up,''
said Roger Garcia, 39, a truck driver from Banquete who stayed at
Reagan.
</P>
<P>
   As his wife, Irene, cuddled their 2-week-old baby, Garcia said
he worried most about the power shortages and drinking water
shortages that often come with hurricanes. ``I did not want to
expose my baby to that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Austin facilities can hold about 450 people each, said Steve
Collier, director of emergency operations for the City of Austin.
If the shelters fill up, other public buildings will be opened, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Andy Alford and Bob Banta write for the Austin
American-Statesman, Austin, Texas.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-22-99 2245EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
