<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-22 22:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5909 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-CANE-BRET-COX     08-22 1072
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANE-BRET-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hurricane Bret slips between heavily-populated areas, slams
Texas coast
 &HT;    By Diana Dworin
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   KINGSVILLE, Texas _ Hurricane Bret, which threatened Brownsville
and Corpus Christi before settling on sparsely populated Kenedy
County, bore into Texas Sunday night with floods and power outages
but little of the predicted devastation.
</P>
<P>
   With a 140-mph vengeance, Bret ended the state's longest
hurricane drought since record-keeping began in 1871.
</P>
<P>
   Port Aransas lost power Sunday morning, and half the town
remained without power late Sunday. Sporadic loss of electricity
and phone service was reported in Kingsville and surrounding areas.
</P>
<P>
   But the most powerful storm to threaten the state since Carla in
1961 had resulted in no reported deaths and little widespread
damage Sunday night. Extra officers brought in by Kingsville
officials were sent home before midnight, and in Corpus Christi,
City Council member Arnold Gonzales summed up the effect: ``Barely
a scratch.''
</P>
<P>
   But no one was taking the storm entirely for granted.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush placed more than 1,600 Texas National
Guardsmen on standby. He also declared seven coastal counties as
state disaster areas and called upon President Clinton for
expedited federal relief. The counties are Aransas, Kenedy,
Kleberg, Nueces, San Patricio, Willacy and Cameron.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said, ``I hope my fellow Texans say a prayer for those
fellow Texans that are in harm's way. A disaster comes like a thief
in the night sometimes. I hope this storm, as ferocious as it may
seem, will not affect human life.''
</P>
<P>
   Bret's path bypassed cities and barreled into rural Kenedy
County, home to fewer than 500 people and more than 50,000 head of
cattle at the historic King Ranch.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of people fled the coast throughout the morning Sunday
to seek safety in emergency shelters as far away as Austin, where
Reagan High School and the Travis County Exposition Center were
housing more than 100 evacuees.
</P>
<P>
   The hurricane's impact stretched deep into the coastal region
late Sunday, and meteorologists expected spin-off showers to hit
Central Texas as early as this morning.
</P>
<P>
   Motorists from South Padre Island to north of Corpus Christi
brought Interstate 37 to a virtual crawl in the northbound lanes.
Large sections were gridlocked, and officials in Corpus Christi
told residents by mid-afternoon that they were better off staying
in town than getting stuck on the freeway.
</P>
<P>
   Evacuees had many reasons for leaving, and many reasons for what
they took with them.
</P>
<P>
   Ian Henkel, 17, said he wasn't worried because he had his
essentials.
</P>
<P>
   ``Got all my guitars in the back of my car,'' the Port Aransas
High School senior said. ``Left the school books at home.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the evacuees were students at the State School in Corpus
Christi and patients at a Texas Department of Mental Health and
Mental Retardation facility in Nueces County. Some were evacuated
to San Antonio while others came to Austin State Hospital, which
planned to house about 90 of those evacuees, most whom live in
group homes.
</P>
<P>
   Many opted not to leave the coast, and some even returned as
Bret approached.
</P>
<P>
   Elvert Mack, a life-long Corpus Christi resident, said he was
not afraid of the storm. He was filling up his car with gas at an
Exxon station on Interstate 37 near Choke Canyon State Park on
Sunday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``A hurricane is wind and water and if God plans for us to live
it out we'll still be there tomorrow,'' said Mack, 44. He had
dropped one daughter off for her freshman year at Texas Tech
University in Lubbock, and he was on his way back to Corpus Christi
to join his 16-year-old daughter and other family members.
</P>
<P>
   At the King Ranch, one of the country's largest, employees were
sent home but the 55,000 head of cattle were expected to ride it
out. Wade Roberts, a security officer for the ranch, said the sheer
number of livestock made it impossible for workers to round them
up. ``This thing came up so fast,'' Roberts said. ``There's nothing
we can really do''
</P>
<P>
   Because Bret was one of the rare hurricanes to form in the Bay
of Campeche of the Mexico coast, it reached Texas only three days
after becoming a tropical storm. Most hurricanes originate across
the Atlantic, and take weeks to make landfall.
</P>
<P>
   The shorter warning made for rushed preparations and
evacuations, but most areas reported little severe damage Sunday
night. However, with rainfalls of up to 20 inches possible, as well
as a wide area primed for tornados, optimism was guarded.
</P>
<P>
   Meteorologists first thought Bret would hit in northern Mexico
or the Lower Rio Grande Valley. But it stubbornly stayed in the
Gulf before finally turning inland. Ken Graham, a National Weather
Service representative, said Bret moved slowly and strengthened
quickly because of two weather features: a high pressure system
centered over New Mexico, with clockwise winds trying to push Bret
to the west, and a low pressure system over Mexico bumping Bret
from the south with counter clockwise winds that tried to push it
to the north.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a battle of the meteorological features,'' Graham
said.
</P>
<P>
   As a category 4 storm, Bret was similar in size and magnitude to
Hurricane Andrew when it made landfall in Florida in 1992. Andrew
killed 14 people and caused more than $15 billion in damages.
Bret's path resembled 1980's Hurricane Allen, which packed winds of
185 mph and did $55 million in property damage but killed only two
people when it came ashore.
</P>
<P>
   A statewide emergency team kicked into action Sunday as
officials from a variety of agencies coordinated emergency duties
ranging from aircraft pooling to public safety to communication.
</P>
<P>
   The Civil Air Patrol has flown satellite telephones to the coast
as backups if power lines go down, and amateur radio operators in
the storm area established a communications network with the state
police Sunday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Also, 60 national guard helicopters are positioned in the region
to aid in search and rescue operations, and state water rescue
teams in the Hill County have been alerted for possible flooding.
</P>
<P>
   Diana Dworin writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas. Suzanne Gamboa, Dylan Rivera, Holly Sanders, Dick Stanley
and Bob Banta contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
