<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-22 22:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5911 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-GULF-HURRICANE-HNS &LR;      08-22 1174
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GULF-HURRICANE-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
TEXAS COAST ESCAPES WORST OF POWERFUL HURRICANE
<TEXT>
<P>
   By T.J. MILLING &QL; 
and ARMANDO VILLAFRANCA &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
c. 1999 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CORPUS CHRISTI _ The state's most powerful hurricane in nearly
20 years spent most of its sound and fury Sunday on rural coastal
ranch land between Brownsville and Corpus Christi, sparing the
urban centers it had been menacing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's still a very dangerous storm,'' National Weather Service
meteorologist Gene Hafele said, ``but if there's something good to
say about Bret, at least it picked one of the most uninhabited
areas of our coastline to make landfall.''
</P>
<P>
   Early forecasts had the eye of the storm headed for this resort
city, which led to the evacuation of nearly 30,000 people, Mayor
Loyd Neal said. After a day of traffic jams and the frantic
clearing of grocery store shelves and lumber yards, the city of
300,000 breathed a little easier.
</P>
<P>
   Late Sunday, authorities reported no injuries or major
destruction from the storm. The National Weather Service issued a
flash flood warning for Nueces, San Patricio and Kleberg counties,
where 2 to 3 inches of rain fell hourly. People in low-lying areas
were ordered to evacuate immediately.
</P>
<P>
   By 8 a.m. today, officials said they will take a closer look at
the damage and decide whether to recommend that people return to
the city. Meteorologists were predicting 10 inches to 15 inches of
rain, however, that could cause delays.
</P>
<P>
   The compact, slow-moving storm, packing 145 mph winds and the
threat of tornados to come, lumbered inland near Baffin Bay, 75
miles south of Corpus Christi, about 6:15 p.m. Its winds cut a
50-mile wide swath, narrow for a hurricane, through ranch land
populated by more cattle than people.
</P>
<P>
   Within two hours, the Category 4 storm had been downgraded to a
Category 3, with sustained winds of 120 mph.
</P>
<P>
   By noon today, the weakening storm was expected to be heading
toward Laredo with less than 50 mph winds, but flooding remained a
concern.
</P>
<P>
   ``Quite often these storms will continue to wreak havoc for
several days just because of rain,'' Hafele said. ``It's just kind
of hard to forecast that though.''
</P>
<P>
   What officials feared was a scenario like last year. Tropical
Storm Charley, which brought a deluge to the Rio Grande Valley city
of Del Rio last August, resulted in flooding that killed nine
people. About a month later, remnants of Tropical Storm Frances
caused floods in the Houston area killing three people $300 million
in damage.
</P>
<P>
   By Sunday afternoon, Gov. George W. Bush had declared a
preemptive state of disaster in seven counties, Aransas, Cameron,
Kenedy, Kleberg, Nueces, San Patricio and Willacy. The governor
also sent a request to President Clinton to speed help to coastal
residents.
</P>
<P>
   The state emergency operations center in a large bunker under
the Department of Public Safety headquarters in Austin housed
representatives from 29 state agencies from the National Guard to
the Health Department, all prepared for a deadly outcome. Medical
teams, mobile hospitals and rescue workers were on standby, but
Bret was shaping up a lot more like Hurricane Allen of 1980 than
Charley or Frances.
</P>
<P>
   Allen, packing even stronger winds than Bret, roared across the
Caribbean headed straight for Brownsville but stalled, lost
strength and eventually made land north of the city. It caused $55
million damage and killed two people.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday night, as Bret surged inland from the remote coastline
south of Corpus Christi, more than 100 area residents huddled
inside a sturdy brick elementary school in the tiny town of Sarita.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the winds were knocking down trees and limbs and rocking
cars. Yet there seemed to be a surreal calm in the building, with
children playing in classrooms where floors were covered with
mattresses.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're getting the worst of it right now,'' said Nito Serna, a
security guard at a local ranch, taking shelter in the school.
``About half the town is here.''
</P>
<P>
   Another seeking shelter in the building was John Cordaway of
Houston. Cordaway said he had come down to help board up his
mother's home and had to stay.
</P>
<P>
   ``It (the storm) caught me off guard. I tried to go back north
but I had to turn around,'' he said .
</P>
<P>
   ``Among an estimated 120 people at a shelter set up in the
Riviera High School gym in Kleberg County, to the north of Sarita,
were Lupita Mendez, 44, and her 14-year-old son, Michael and her
elderly parents.
</P>
<P>
   Mendez had expected the storm to be a rough one. ``That's why I
got my parents who live in the trailer park to come. I live in a
small house in Riviera, and I didn't want to stay by myself. I
think we`ll be OK here.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Corpus Christi officials tried to look ahead. ``What
we're preparing for is the aftermath,'' said Police Chief Pete
Alvarez.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've done all we can to deal with the evacuations,'' said
City Manager David Garcia. ``The storm is upon us now and there's
not much we can do but wait to see what effects the wind and the
rain will have. We are now active in planning for the recovery once
the rain and the wind pass us.''
</P>
<P>
   Garcia said the city positioned emergency and road crews to
clear debris and open roads once winds have subsided.
</P>
<P>
   Officials with Central Power &AMP; Light were optimistic that
conditions were improving Sunday night. They hoped to be able to
cross the causeway to Mustang Island where half the homes in the
resort town of Port Aransas were without electricity.
</P>
<P>
   Alvarez said South Padre Island was mainly deserted Sunday after
most of that island's 15,000 residents heeded the warning to
evacuate and began leaving their beachfront homes. Eastbound lanes
on the John F. Kennedy Causeway, linking the city to the island,
were closed at 11 a.m. Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Interstate 37, the main artery out of Corpus Christi, was packed
with evacuees streaming out of the city Saturday night and Sunday
morning.
</P>
<P>
   Shelters in San Antonio were brimming with refugees from coastal
regions. The Red Cross, with four shelters full and a fifth
filling, was ready to accommodate them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll open more as we need them,'' spokeswoman Cindi Wright
said, noting the Red Cross has agreements with 109 locations for
shelters in Bexar County alone. ``We've been practicing and
preparing for this for a long time.... This is what we do.''
</P>
<P>
   Alvarez said some flooding was expected in the Corpus Christi's
low-lying areas such as Flower Bluff, on the city's south side.
</P>
<P>
   Another concern was structural damage caused by the storm. City
officials, however, said all new construction along the Corpus
Christi bayfront after Hurricane Allen was in compliance with
building codes requiring structures to withstand hurricane-strength
winds.
</P>
<P>
   ``The building codes have been strictly enforced,'' the police
chief said, ``but anytime you have a hurricane of this category you
have to be concerned. I don't care how secure your building is,
you're still subject to damage.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
