</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990822.0218 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-22 22:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5913 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-BRET-COLOR-COX     08-22 0673
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRET-COLOR-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Coastal Texans buzz into action before Bret's arrival
 &HT;    (EDS: Loyd is cq.)
 &HT;    By Suzanne Gamboa
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   KINGSVILLE, Texas _ First, there's the prayer _ that Hurricane
Bret passes over this town's stucco-covered Laundry Maid
Laundromat. Amen.
</P>
<P>
   Then _ if that doesn't work as well as owners Randy Nielsen, 43,
and his brother-in-law Randy Kell, 45, hope _ there's always
insurance.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is our bread and butter,'' Neilsen said as he boarded up
the windows and doors Sunday morning to protect the coin-operated
washers and dryers. ``I expect the worse.''
</P>
<P>
   As the most powerful hurricane in decades arrived on the lower
Texas coast, Nielsen and Kell spent the day like most of the 28,000
residents in this town located 30 miles southwest of Corpus
Christi: getting ready for the storm and, in many cases, preparing
to evacuate.
</P>
<P>
   Expecting that the area would take a beating, Kingsville Mayor
Phil Esquivel said he held off until about 2:30 p.m. from opening
shelters in this city so residents who could evacuate would.
</P>
<P>
   An hour later, some 65 people were in the Memorial Middle School
shelter and traffic was picking up with residents carrying blankets
and other belongings in plastic laundry baskets, canvas totes and
trash bags.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't think it was this serious,'' said LeRoy Velasquez,
24, explaining why he didn't evacuate. ``We thought it was going
somewhere else.''
</P>
<P>
   That's what Lydia Silva thought, too. She was in Harlingen,
where the storm was first expected to hit, and headed to her
mother's home in Kingsville Saturday, right with Bret's path. ``Now
I'm trying to turn around and go home,'' Silva said.
</P>
<P>
   At the Kingsville H-E-B on King Highway, shoppers whizzed
through aisles, filling their carts Sunday morning. Produce bins,
bread and canned-food shelves were cleaned out and residents
pounced on cases of bottled water when workers wheeled a
just-arrived shipment to the front of the store.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been like this since yesterday. We got wiped out at 6
p.m.'' said H-E-B employee Mike Garcia, 27, whose hair dripped from
the downpour that was pounding the parking lot outside.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of these people are going to ride it out. I'm getting out
of here. As soon as I'm off, I'm going to San Antonio,'' Garcia
said.
</P>
<P>
   South of Kingsville in Corpus Christi, Mayor Loyd Neal had
called Gov. George W. Bush by 8 a.m. and asked him to declare the
coast a disaster area to speed assistance. The early call
demonstrated that officials were not expecting to be spared by
Bret.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was here during Celia, with 140-mile-an-hour winds, and it
was a giant urban renewal project,'' Neal said. Celia hit Corpus
Christi in 1970 and caused $50 million in damage. Neal said the
city enforces windstorm building codes, but they have not been
effectively tested since 1970.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every so often you need to find out if you are doing the right
things by the way. It's a hard way to do it, but we're ready.''
</P>
<P>
   The busiest spot in Corpus Christi Sunday was the downtown
marina and Corpus Christi yacht club. Boat owners worked their way
through a lengthy waiting list to use heavy equipment to bring
their boats onto land.
</P>
<P>
   By about 11:30 a.m., Douglas Beck's Moonspinner was in a
shorefront parking lot. but the chore had left him with little time
to do much for himself. He would stay put in Corpus Christi, he
said. ``I was thinking yesterday it was going into Brownsville. Now
it's too late to do anything,'' said Beck, 75.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Rudy Benavides and Paul Lara, 35, were helping
Phillip Lara, 29, bring his shrimping boat, dubbed Bay King,
ashore. ``If it goes down, I go down too,'' said Benavides. ``My
family left and went to San Antonio. They wanted me to go with
them, but I think this is one of my priorities.''
</P>
<P>
   Suzanne Gamboa writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas. Diana Dworin contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
