<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-22 22:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5914 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-GAY-PARENTS-CAMP-ART-     08-22 0785
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAY-PARENTS-CAMP-ART-605&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A PLACE FOR FRIENDS, NOT FOR PREJUDICE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.J., N.Y., Pa., Mass.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By RANDY BANNER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWFIELD, N.J. _ To 10-year-old Bryan Corley, Camp Mountain
Meadow is a place to make friends without being judged.
</P>
<P>
   ``At home, almost nobody likes me, because I'm different,'' he
said. ``They say I'm weird and they're just mean. The kids here
accept me.''
</P>
<P>
   Bryan's parents, Marie Corley and Tara Klein, are lesbians and
say they have suffered from prejudice and discrimination. Because
of a stalker, they have had to move several times.
</P>
<P>
   Camp Mountain Meadow, which operates for two weeks every August,
was created in 1992 to give children like Bryan whose parents are
gay, lesbian or transsexual a place where they can be themselves
without fear.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get to know people who are like you, or at least have
parents like you,'' said Bryan, one of 67 campers this year. ``You
get to have friends.''
</P>
<P>
   Mountain Meadow offers daily forums where the children can
discuss common problems, as well as more typical summer camp
activities like athletics, crafts and theater.
</P>
<P>
   With its tents and wooden shacks, the camp at first glance seems
much like any other. But on closer examination, its particular
character becomes more apparent. While there is laughter, it rarely
has the abandon typical of elementary school children. Hellos are
easy to come by, even for a stranger, but smiles are much less
frequent. A seriousness infuses every action, no matter how
fanciful, with analysis.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because they've been through these ordeals with all of the
hatred toward them, a lot of these kids have been forced to grow up
too soon,'' said Andre Cruz, 20, a camp counselor from New York.
``They'll say things like `People don't understand me and don't
know enough about me to know that I'm just like them.' And I sit
there and think: While it's great that they know how to express
themselves in such a way, I wonder how many talks did they have to
have with their parents to finally understand this, and how much of
it really sinks through.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked about how their parents' lifestyles had affected
their own lives, the campers' initial responses were guarded and
stoic: Their parents' lives posed no problems for them. In the
course of conversation, however, bits and pieces of private agonies
emerged.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would never tell any of my friends about my mother,'' said
11-year-old Evan of Pennsylvania, whose mother is bisexual. ``They
would humiliate me. It's her life and that's fine with me. But I
know that I'm not going to be bisexual or something like that when
I grow up. I want to get married and have children.''
</P>
<P>
   Coming from such families, many of the campers have been
encouraged to express their individuality. Bryan said that
classmates jeer at him because he wears funny hats, and shorts with
hearts on them, and because he will not make fun of a retarded
friend.
</P>
<P>
   Reuben Jacobs, 11, of Amherst, Mass, will transfer from a
private day school to a public school in the fall because the day
school principal objected to his appearance and dress on several
occasions. The principal would not allow him to wear dreadlocks,
saying they ``were a disfigurement to the image of the school.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He said that it might catch on as a fad or something, and he
didn't want his son braiding his hair,'' said Reuben, who also said
he suspected that racism, as well as homophobia, was a factor in
his difficulties at the school.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly all the campers define themselves as bisexual. The camp
physician, Dr. Alexis Lieberman, said that while it was unlikely
that more than 10 percent of the campers were homosexual or
bisexual, their self-identification as such was a personal and
political statement.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``It's strange to hear a 7-year-old say `I'm bisexual,''' said
Dr. Lieberman, a pediatrician. ``But that's how they feel. They see
sexuality in broad terms because of their parents, and feel
comfortable with it. Eventually, they'll choose one way or the
other.''
</P>
<P>
   Many campers said they believed their presence at the camp and
Mountain Meadow's very existence had reaffirmed the validity of
their lives and those of their parents.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have to hide who my family is, that my mom's a
lesbian,'' said Krista, 11, of northern New York state, who is in
her second year at the camp. ``I'm really shy and I don't usually
tell people that. But it would be nice if I could.''
</P>
</TEXT>
