r s BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN     08-22 0687
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHEFFIELD TURNED OUT JUST GRAND
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Cal Ripken proved a big guy can play shortstop,
but it took Alex Rodriguez, Derek Jeter and Nomar Garciaparra to
revolutionize the position. They hit .325 or club 40 homers or
drive in 120 runs a season, and in the process prove a
defense-oriented position can produce offense in a big way.
</P>
<P>
   A decade ago, when A-Rod and the gang were mere high schoolers,
Gary Sheffield figured he'd be the one to do all that. Before that
could happen, though, Milwaukee turned him into a third baseman.
Then Florida made him an outfielder.
</P>
<P>
   Now, having endured his third position change, he's the Dodgers
left fielder having another solid, if not splendid, season. He hit
his sixth career grand slam and drove in six runs in Sunday's 9-7
win against Philadelphia in the series finale at Veterans Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Sheffield is hitting .310 with 21 homers and 66 RBI and has a
.413 on-base percentage. Nice numbers for an outfielder, but if he
were a shortstop they would be groundbreaking.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the time when I came up, there wasn't a power-hitting
shortstop like Cal Ripken or Barry Larkin,'' said Sheffield, a
five-time all-star. ``That was the thing I was thinking about,
changing the whole attitude of the position.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the Brewers drafted a young, hotshot prospect named
Billy Spiers to be their shortstop for the next decade. Sheffield,
who returns to Milwaukee today as the Dodgers open a three-game
series, was moved to third. He replaced Paul Molitor, who was being
switched to designated hitter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anybody (knew) what he would be like in the
major leagues. Maybe in the minor leagues they knew,'' said Dodgers
center fielder Devon White, who played with the Angels during
Sheffield's Milwaukee days. ``He was always known for his bat.
That's what people knew.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Shortstop was THE position. I fell in love with the spot,''
Sheffield said. ``My range was there, the glove was there. I made
some errors, but it was because I believed in my arm and thought I
could throw anyone out when I didn't have a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers manager Davey Johnson lamented earlier this season that,
when he managed in New York, the Mets tried to acquire Sheffield
but failed. Johnson, who loves offense, said he would have kept
Sheffield at shortstop, understanding the huge potential.
</P>
<P>
   Sheffield was traded to San Diego before the 1992 season and
that's where he blossomed offensively. Spiers, a journeyman now
with Houston, has 38 career homers. Sheffield has topped that in
one season.
</P>
<P>
   A year after being traded to the Padres, he hit .330 with 33
homers and 100 RBI. Playing for the Marlins in 1996, he hit .314
with 42 homers and 120 RBI.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, despite missing what amounts to a full season due to
injuries, Sheffield has averaged 26 homers and 80 RBI over the last
five years. He's hit .291 in that span and stolen 80 bases.
</P>
<P>
   Would Sheffield's name be mentioned in the same way as
Rodrigeuz, Jeter and Garciaparra are had he remained in the
infield? ``No doubt,'' Johnson said. ``He had a great arm, great
hands. Had the offense.''
</P>
<P>
   On a team marred with inconsistency this season, Sheffield has
not only become a voice of reason, he's been the Dodgers' most
consistent player. It was his double in the first that gave Chan Ho
Park the first two runs of what would become a 5-1 lead after two
innings. And when the Phillies scored three times during a Park
meltdown in the fifth to pull within a run, Sheffield smashed his
sixth career grand slam off reliever Steve Montgomery an inning
later to give the Dodgers a 9-4 lead.
</P>
<P>
   It came an inning after Montgomery knocked down Sheffield with
an inside pitch. The two exchanged barbs before Sheffield and
catcher Gary Bennett engaged in a conversation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole series they threw close to my head four times,''
Sheffield said. ``I was telling him how well he was wearing his
uniform. He told me my cleats were nice, with the No. 10 on them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
