<HEADER>
A6021 &Cx1f; tth-z
u a BC-DISASTERS-GOVERNMENT-     08-22 1064
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DISASTERS-GOVERNMENT-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLANNING FOR DISASTERS PITTED AGAINST NATIONAL SECURITY CONCERNS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ANDREW SCHNEIDER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Congress insists that citizens have a right to know the dangers
they face from nearby factories or chemical plants, but the CIA,
FBI and other security agencies want to keep secret exactly how bad
things can get if there are catastrophic leaks or explosions.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton signed an order on Aug. 5 that authorized
criminal sentences and fines of $1 million a day against anyone who
releases parts of that type of information to an unauthorized
person.
</P>
<P>
   The information on potential hazards can be vital, even
lifesaving, to firefighters, police, rescue workers and others
responding to a disaster, but some of those officials are reluctant
to take the information.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some are clearly concerned at the size of penalties and made
it clear they did not want the responsibility for the data,'' said
Lisa McArthur, EPA clean air coordinator for the Pacific Northwest.
McArthur, who is orchestrating the release of chemical data, has
been meeting with emergency planners for weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The 3,000 deaths from a leaking chemical plant in Bhopal, India,
in 1984 got the attention of Congress. Lawmakers feared that local
and state emergency teams in this country might not know exactly
what was behind the factory doors or in the huge storage tanks in
their communities.
</P>
<P>
   In 1990, Congress amended the Clean Air Act and gave the EPA the
job of determining the potential for disaster at companies that use
or store large quantities of any of 132 toxic or flammable
chemicals. June 21st of this year was the deadline for the nation's
36,000 bulk chemical users to submit their information. Only about
14,000 complied.
</P>
<P>
   The required information included:
</P>
<P>
   _A breakdown of the type and amount of hazardous chemicals
stored or used in the facility.
</P>
<P>
   _A risk-management plan that is revised every five years.
</P>
<P>
   _The company's plan for responding to emergencies
</P>
<P>
   _A history of accidental chemical releases during the past five
years.
</P>
<P>
   _The off-site consequences of the worst-case scenario from a
major release of hazardous material.
</P>
<P>
   It is this last category that has worried security experts.
</P>
<P>
   Neither the FBI nor other security agencies involved in
evaluating the dangers of the information getting into the wrong
hands were willing to discuss, for publication, their specific
concerns in the release of worst-case scenarios.
</P>
<P>
   However, an executive summary prepared by the security experts
call the worst-case scenarios ``a blueprint for terrorists'' and a
``nationwide guide of what to blow up.''
</P>
<P>
   The precise information that will tell those wishing to do harm
where to place their explosives will also tell those who must
control the catastrophe how to best plan for it.
</P>
<P>
   The EPA is caught in the middle.
</P>
<P>
   ``EPA fully supports the public's right to know about local
environmental threats,'' said a position paper from headquarters,
``but we are also committed to addressing all national security
concerns raised by the FBI, CIA and other security agencies.''
</P>
<P>
   Initial plans called for all the data but the worst-case
scenarios to be placed on the Internet. The public, citizen groups
or other interested parties would have to request the restricted
data by filing a Freedom of Information Act request. However, the
legislation signed by Clinton exempts the scenarios from being
released to the public for at least the next year.
</P>
<P>
   For some industries, such as nuclear power plants, worst-case
scenarios have always been a key part of the licensing process.
Somewhere in the hundreds of volumes of reports and studies the
utility prepares for government licensers are calculations of how
much radiation might escape in the most severe release, how far
will it go and in which direction. Medical experts are also
required to calculate the most likely immediate and long-term
health effects to the public from this exposure.
</P>
<P>
   This information allows emergency planners to determine such
things as the best evacuation routes, the number and placement of
alert sirens and whether the risks are so high that the public
should not try to outrun the toxic plume but seal up their houses
and stay inside.
</P>
<P>
   But, most important, knowledge of precisely how dangerous the
chemical hazards could be will make it easier for the public to
respond to evacuation orders.
</P>
<P>
   The EPA data will be the first time a worst-case scenario has
been prepared, let alone released to public officials, by many of
the country's chemical plants.
</P>
<P>
   ``The piece of information most useful for the public is the
off-site consequences and EPA's program makes far less sense than
was intended if we can't use that data,'' said Robert Koster, an
air pollution compliance specialist for Oregon's Department of
Environmental Quality.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see how we can alert people living near these
facilities, give them advance notice that they might get a midnight
call and what they should do when the sirens go off.''
</P>
<P>
   Bob Johnson, Auburn's fire chief and the chairman of the
Washington State Emergency Response Committee, also believes the
risk data is important and will allow emergency workers to do a
better job protecting the public. And he says the threat of the
million-dollar fine comes with the job.
</P>
<P>
   ``If most appointed or elected officials looked hard at the
liability they take with the job, they wouldn't get out of bed in
the morning,'' Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do understand the potential danger of certain information
getting into the wrong hands, but I don't understand exactly what
EPA expects us to do.''
</P>
<P>
   EPA's McArthur said it is not her agency, but rather Congress
that is restricting the information.
</P>
<P>
   ``Congress is trying to balance the public's right to know with
concern about terrorist access to data,'' she said. ``You can
definitely see the pendulum swing between when Congress was very
concerned about the public's right to know, when the law was
proposed in 1990 and now to where the Congress is concerned about
terrorists getting the data.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do feel this is very useful information for emergency
responders to have. It's very important and we will do all we can,
but we cannot force them to take it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
