u f BC-POWER-DEAL-NYT     08-22 0299
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POWER-DEAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAROLINA POWER TO ACQUIRE FLORIDA PROGRESS FOR $5.3 BILLION
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a move that will create a Southeastern utility with 2.5
million customers, the Carolina Power and Light Co. agreed Sunday
to acquire the Florida Progress Corp. for $5.3 billion in cash and
stock.
</P>
<P>
   The boards of both companies approved the deal Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Under the terms of the agreement, shareholders of Florida
Progress, based in St. Petersburg, will receive $54 a share in cash
or a new share of common stock in a Carolina Power and Light
holding company. The cash and stock components will be adjusted if
more than 65 percent of Florida Progress shareholders choose cash
or more than 35 percent pick stock. The price is a 21 percent
premium based on Florida Progress' closing price of $44.625 on
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   William Cavanaugh, the chairman and chief executive of Carolina
Power and Light, who will have those posts in the merged company,
said the holding company structure would be in place by the end of
the year.
</P>
<P>
   He said he expected the transaction, which is subject to
approval by shareholders and state and Federal regulators, to be
completed within the next year.
</P>
<P>
   After the deal is completed, the combined company will need to
cut about 7 percent of its work force, the companies said, leaving
about 16,000 employees.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Korpan, the chairman and chief executive of Florida
Progress, will retire from his current posts once the transaction
is completed and will join the Carolina Power board.
</P>
<P>
   Florida Progress, which began as the St. Petersburg Electric
Light and Power Co., has its headquarters in St. Petersburg.
</P>
<P>
   The combined company will be based in Raleigh, N.C., where
Carolina Power and Light has its headquarters.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
