<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-22 23:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6043 &Cx1f; tth-z
u a BC-GATES-CHARITY-SPI &LR;      08-22 1043
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GATES-CHARITY-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GATESES COMBINE FAMILY FOUNDATIONS TO CREATE GIANT CHARITABLE
OUTFIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By NEIL MODIE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The world's richest man has created America's richest
charitable foundation.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft founder Bill Gates and his wife, Melinda, have
consolidated two family philanthropic entities into a $17.1 billion
powerhouse, fueled by three quarterly contributions that added a
total of $15.1 billion in assets this year alone.
</P>
<P>
   The most recent contribution, occurring this month, was a
Microsoft stock transfer that enlarged the Bill and Melinda Gates
Foundation by $6 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The newly formed organization combines the William H. Gates
Foundation and the Gates Learning Foundation and will maintain
their focus on global health and education, foundation
co-chairwoman Patty Stonesifer said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   At the Gateses' current rate of giving, the couple, whose worth
is valued at $71 billion, soon could have the world's wealthiest
foundation in terms of assets. According to the Chronicle of
Philanthropy, a newspaper that reports on non-profits, the
London-based Wellcome Trust has assets of $19.2 billion.
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone interview from New York Sunday, Stonesifer said
she didn't know whether the Gateses intend to add a
multibillion-dollar donation in the fourth quarter of 1999 as they
have in each of the first three quarters.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know what their timing is,'' she said. ``But they
have made a firm commitment to return the majority of their wealth
to society, and the foundation is their vehicle for doing so.''
</P>
<P>
   The 1999 donations vaulted the Gates Foundation past the $13
billion David and Lucile Packard Foundation, now the nation's
second largest, and the $11.4 billion Ford Foundation, now in third
place.
</P>
<P>
   The Chronicle of Philanthropy said that with the latest
donations, ``the Gateses have given far more money than any other
living American.''
</P>
<P>
   The publication compared the Gateses' giving to the $4.1 billion
donated by duty-free store entrepreneur Charles F. Feeney, more
than $2 billion given away by former ambassador and publishing
magnate Walter H. Annenberg; a comparable sum donated by financier
George Soros, and $1.3 billion given or promised by CNN founder Ted
Turner.
</P>
<P>
   Heading the newly consolidated Gates Foundation are Stonesifer,
a former Microsoft senior vice president who is co-chairwoman and
president, and Gates' father, William H. Gates Jr., a retired
Seattle attorney who is co-chairman and chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   Next week the foundation is moving into new headquarters, 60,000
square feet of leased space in Seattle's Eastlake neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   The senior Gates has operated the William H. Gates Foundation
largely out of his home office in Seattle's Laurelhurst
neighborhood. Stonesifer has run the learning foundation out of a
small office above a Redmond, Wash., pizza parlor.
</P>
<P>
   The combined organization has about 130 employees, of whom more
than 100 work with the Gates Center for Technology Access. It
provides training to bring Internet access and other technology to
libraries in urban and rural communities across the country.
</P>
<P>
   Stonesifer said much of the Eastlake office space will be taken
up with classroom space where librarians and educators will work
with the Gates Center staff to increase public access to technology
programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The increase in endowment and the merger really just allows us
to sharpen the foundation's work in global health and learning,''
Stonesifer said. ``It allows us to identify and fund additional
programs in both of those areas'' and to eliminate overlap.
</P>
<P>
   The merging of the two foundations and the quantum increase in
their assets were disclosed by Newsweek magazine Sunday in
announcing a cover story about Gates in its Aug. 30 issue, which
reaches newsstands today.
</P>
<P>
   The article tells about the Gateses' charitable giving and
portrays the Microsoft boss as a fun-loving, good-humored family
man delighted with his role as a father of two young children.
</P>
<P>
   An accompanying story describes Melinda Gates as very much his
equal partner.
</P>
<P>
   The cover story's title: ``Bill Just Wants to Have Fun.''
</P>
<P>
   The articles could substantially soften Gates' reputation for
ruthlessness, a characterization exacerbated by negative publicity
from the Justice Department's ongoing antitrust suit against
Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   From the inception of the first of the two Gates foundations in
1997, they have spent or committed $707.4 million, including $322.1
million for global health projects, $300.7 million for education,
$54.7 million for programs in the Pacific Northwest and $29.9
million for other philanthropic efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Northwest projects have included donations to build new
libraries, to help buy the Loomis Forest, an important
North-Central Washington wildlife habitat, to save it from logging
and road building; and to help finance a public sculpture garden in
the downtown Seattle waterfront area.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will continue to give to a wide range of civic and social
efforts across the Pacific Northwest,'' Stonesifer said.
</P>
<P>
   The foundation's global health initiatives have included $50
million to accelerate development of a new malaria vaccine; $100
million to speed the delivery of lifesaving vaccines to children in
developing countries; money to a Columbia University program to
prevent maternal death in pregnancy and childbirth in poor
countries, and $1 million to help develop an AIDS vaccine.
</P>
<P>
   Recent grants in the learning field have included $200 million
to bring computers, Internet access and training to libraries in
low-income communities in the United States and Canada.
</P>
<P>
   Other grants have gone to the Teacher Leadership Project and
Smart Tools Academy in Washington state to improve access to
technology and training throughout the K-12 system at the
administrative level.
</P>
<P>
   Stonesifer said she and the senior Gates are meeting in New York
this week with representatives of other large foundations to
discuss how charitable programs among groups with common interests
might complement each other. The meeting was arranged by Dr. Vartan
Gregorian, president of the Carnegie Corporation.
</P>
</TEXT>
